<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: Inside Your Head and Counting the Minutes  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An AdOutlet.com survey in which 150 people were asked to keep
daily diaries of their thoughts for a week found that women think
twice as long as men per day about political issues (12 minutes to
6 minutes) and 25 times as long about their hair (75 minutes to 3
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Where men have women beaten is in thinking about themselves (men
five times as often as women) and about food (120 minutes per day
to 80 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Turning from what's in your head to what's on it, Elle
reports that the latest beauty products contain maple syrup, based
on the following logic: If trees can survive in cold weather, can't
the products of those trees help dry skin and hair? Next on the
horizon: Did you ever notice that rocks don't get wrinkles?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sting &LR;  told BBC radio that he has given up tantric sex and is
trying to get his wife,  &UR; Trudie Styler &LR; , ``into tantric shopping
now. That's where you shop for five hours and don't buy anything.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Meshulam Riklis &LR; , not  &UR; Menahem Golan &LR; , was married to  &UR; Pia &LR; 
 &UR; Zadora &LR; , and more power to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marlin Fitzwater &LR; , former press secretary to  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR; 
and  &UR; George Bush &LR; , has sold a novel to Public Affairs Books. It's
based on a true story about an 18-year-old schoolteacher in Kansas
who was accused of having an affair with a 14-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty works of graphic art by San Francisco poet  &UR; Lawrence &LR; 
 &UR; Ferlinghetti &LR;  will be shown at the National Gallery of Prague next
month. Ferlinghetti told ARTnews that he likes Prague because ``The
people who were in jail under the dictatorship are now running the
cultural scene. They haven't had time to get disillusioned like the
French. It's like '68 just happened there.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gerald Nachman &LR;  went to see the dance musical ``Contact'' at
Lincoln Center in New York and saw a sign at the front door saying,
``At this performance, there will be smoke effects, gunshots,
strobe lights, cigarette smoking and fishnet stockings.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In the audience at Sunday night's Negativland
multimedia/live/puppet show _ an anti-consumerism extravaganza _ in
Palo Alto, Calif., was San Francisco filmmaker  &UR; Craig Baldwin &LR; , who
creates films out of snippets of footage from other sources and is
part of the 2000 Whitney Biennial. Despite the don't-buy message,
T-shirts reading ``Copyright infringement is your best
entertainment value'' were sold in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MAKING IT &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Saxophonists die younger than musicians who specialize in any
other instrument, says a British Medical Journal finding reported
in Metrosource. Studying 813 jazz saxophonists born between 1882
and 1974, the researchers discovered that half died before they
were 40; half of other musicians hung on until at least 60.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers thought that ``circular breathing technique,''
in which a player inhales through the nose while blowing out
through the mouth might reduce blood flow to the heart and brain
and contribute to a high a player feels; it also might facilitate
strokes and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Playing more than one instrument seemed to increase longevity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Ohio State University report that people with
high credit card balances have more health problems than those with
low balances. ``The higher your debt-to-income ratio,'' says a
Health magazine report on the research, ``the more your health is
apt to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chukka Sachs &LR;  saw a Corvair with a Darwin fish sticker on it,
which she describes as a case of ``Unsafe at Any Speed'' meeting
``Survival of the Fittest.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Berkeley Bark reports that  &UR; Sigmund Freud &LR;  had three dogs,
 &UR; Jofi &LR; ,  &UR; Lunyu &LR;  and  &UR; Wolf &LR; , and said he loved them because ``The
direct simplicity of their lives is free of the inner
contradictions of civilization that are so hard for us to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``You ain't seen nothing yet.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Jackson &LR;  using  &UR; Al Jolson &LR; 's favorite line at the
World Music Awards ceremony.  &UR; Matthew Surrence &LR;  points out that
this is the catchphrase of a white singer who performed in
blackface appropriated by a black singer who performs in whiteface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
