<HEADLINE>
TROJANS CONFIDENT DESPITE PLAYING NO. 1 TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC plays the No. 1 team in the nation at its own
ballpark, but the Trojans hardly sound intimidated heading into
this weekend's college baseball super regionals.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-ranked Trojans (41-18) are in Atlanta to face
top-ranked Georgia Tech (50-14) in a best-of-three series beginning
at 4 p.m. PDT today. The winner advances to the College World
Series next week in Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're the team to beat,'' USC pitcher Mark Prior
said. ``We don't think we're an underdog. If they do, that's fine.
We're right up there with them, if not better than them.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior's confidence could stem from the fact he beat Georgia Tech
9-2 when the teams faced each other March 3 in a tournament at Cal
State Fullerton. But the Yellow Jackets did not use their ace,
left-hander Cory Vance (13-2, 3.21 earned-run average), who is 6-1
this season against ranked opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 50 games ago. We didn't see their No. 1 or No. 2
pitcher in that game,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie said. ``I thought
coming away from there they were a good club.''
</P>
<P>
   USC enters the series on a 13-game winning streak, the nation's
longest, and will start All-America second-team selection Rik
Currier (13-3, 3.27 ERA) tonight with Prior (9-6, 3.62) pitching
game three on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident. There's no question about it,'' Prior
said. ``The feeling on the team is we can come in and take two and
get out of here. I don't feel many people across the country feel
we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both teams feature quality pitching, the cramped
dimensions of Russ Chandler Stadium (320 feet down the foul lines)
could lead to high-scoring games. Tech third baseman Mark Teixeira,
who Thursday was named The Sporting News' College Baseball Player
of the Year, has hit 18 home runs and left fielder Jason Basil has
added 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the size of the ballpark, I'd love it if
we hit a couple cheap ones,'' Gillespie said. ``Our pitchers will
be ordered to throw only ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the Trojans' offense figures to be shortstop
Seth Davidson, who was named the most outstanding player of last
week's regional at Cal State Fullerton. Davidson went 10 for 14
with a double, home run and six RBI last week and has hit safely in
23 of the past 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most significant difference on our team,'' Gillespie
said. ``For about a month, he's been on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have been resilient during their winning streak.
They overcame a 3-1 deficit in the ninth inning to defeat
Washington 4-3 on May 21 and allowed Virginia Tech, Loyola
Marymount and Cal State Fullerton to build 2-0 leads before
defeating those teams in regional contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think anything is going to stop us,'' Prior said.
``We want to send a team home on their home field, just like last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   USC will be the visiting team tonight and the home team
Saturday. A coin flip determines the home team for Sunday, if a
game is necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
