<SLUG> BC-NY-BID-RIGGING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VENDORS CHARGED WITH PRICE FIXING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Justice Department Thursday charged more than a
dozen food vendors that supply New York City schools with rigging
prices on multimillion dollar contracts for produce and frozen
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors charged that 13 contractors conspired to fix
prices for more than $210 million in food contracts for the city
schools. They said that part of the price-fixing arrangement lasted
nearly a decade. Six of the 13 companies have agreed to plead
guilty and cooperate with the investigation, prosecutors said. They
said 22 officers and employees of the companies have also been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors estimated that the vendors inflated prices of the
food contracts by about 10 percent, or roughly $21 million for the
entire scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money should have been spent on the schoolchildren of New
York, not to line the pockets of greedy vendors,'' Joel L. Klein,
assistant attorney general for the antitrust division, said in a
statement on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said that some of the vendors were
also charged in another bid-rigging conspiracy involving other city
agencies, including city hospitals, jails and homeless shelters.
City contracting officials said Thursday that four of the companies
accused in the Board of Education case also sold to those city
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Manhattan Thursday afternoon, Klein said
that as a graduate of Brooklyn public schools, he was personally
offended by the evidence of ``despicable behavior'' uncovered by
federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see people come in and rip off these schools that are
trying to do a good job really tugs at one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the companies charged with the bid rigging
included almost all of the Board of Education's suppliers of frozen
food, like fish sticks, meats and french fries, as well as most
suppliers of fresh produce.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education has known about the investigation for
nearly six months, and has been working on a contingency plan to
ensure that food delivery to the schools would not be interrupted,
board officials said Thursday. The board has also hired an
independent monitor to oversee the operations of all food vendors.
Chad Vignola, general counsel to the chancellor, said the board
would continue to do business with some of the companies ``as we
attempt to work our way through this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the reason we would continue to do business with a
company is that it is under an independent monitor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Thursday that they have not uncovered any
incidents of bribery or public corruption in the case. Instead,
they said, the conspiracy involved vendors agreeing to submit false
bids to stifle competition for the food contracts. The prosecutors
said that vendors would designate one company as the low bidder for
a particular contract and would arrange their bids so that the
designated company would win.
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Mawn, the assistant director in charge of the FBI in
New York, said the investigation, which began about 18 months ago,
established that the vendors secretly controlled the prices on many
of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had secret meetings,'' he said. ``They had secret
agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said in a statement that the companies
charged included: the Nick Penachio Co.; Irving Libertoff Inc.;
West Side Foods Inc.; M &AMP;F Meat Products Inc.; DiCarlo Distributors
Inc.; FHR Inc.; the Landmark Food Corp.; Loeb &AMP; Mayer Inc.; Food
Service Purchasing Agency Inc.; A. Bohrer Inc.; Kanowitz Fruit &AMP;
Produce; Clifton Fruit &AMP; Produce; and the Baiardi Chain Food Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the lawyer for one of the companies, the Nick Penachio
Co., said the firm would work to resolve the suit in a responsible
way. Gerald Shargel, the lawyer, said the company holds a contract
with the city's Board of Education and expects to retain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick Penachio Corp. has been a responsible corporate citizen
for 63 years,'' he said. ``The company will survive and the
business will continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
