<SLUG> BC-IKE-MISSILES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARE MISSILE-SHIELD IDEA WITH RUSSIANS, JOINT CHIEFS LEADER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITEMAN AIR FORCE BASE, Mo. _ The administration's top military
adviser backed President Clinton's offer Thursday to share missile
defense technology with the Russians as a way to show that it poses
no threat to them.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry ``Hugh'' Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said during a visit to this home of the country's most
sophisticated bomber force that sharing the workings of the missile
defense system could ease Russian fears of the still-developing
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, who came to Missouri to speak at a conference of
prospective defense contractors in Warrensburg, repeated the
Pentagon's position that a missile defense would be geared only to
stop a nation with a few nuclear missiles, not the thousands Russia
could rain on U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is designed against a rogue nation, against a limited
threat, not anything like what the Russians have available to
them,'' Shelton told reporters in a hangar holding a B-2 stealth
bomber. ``We never will have that capability.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the two countries have helped stave off nuclear war
with the principle of so-called mutually assured destruction. It
promises that any nuclear launch would be suicidal because it would
trigger a retaliation leaving both nations, and perhaps the world,
in ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians see a missile defense as threat to that precarious
balance by giving the United States the ability to obliterate
targets without suffering similar losses. Clinton's statement this
week that he would share the know-how intended to ease those
worries, but there remains the question of whether the
cash-strapped Russians could afford to deploy a missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   Recent scientific efforts suggest that it would be easy to foil
a missile defense by filling the skies with scores of dummy
missiles. Tests of the system _ its task is compared with striking
one bullet with another in flight _ have been mixed at best. And
Shelton noted that a full-blown attack of thousands of Russian
missiles would pose too many difficult targets for any system
currently imagined by defense planners.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the procurement conference organized by U.S. Rep.
Ike Skelton, a Democrat from Lexington and ranking minority member
of the House Armed Services Committee, Shelton said American
relations with the Russians, ``despite some bumps in the road...is
coming along.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his forces, however, were being stretched ever thinner
by peacekeeping operations and other long-term deployments around
the globe. And the general called for increased spending to outfit
America's military to ensure the country's invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't plan to settle for a fair fight...or `just good
enough.'... That's not the American way,'' Shelton said. ``We've
got to transform our military...in order to assure an unfair
advantage over any potential adversary....an advantage so great
that our enemies dare not challenge us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
