<SLUG> BC-FBN-HELMET-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PLANNING EXPERIMENT TO PLACE CAMERAS IN HELMETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Football League is planning to let its
four television partners wire its players with microphones and put
miniature cameras inside their helmets during preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to experiment in the preseason and see how it
works,'' Greg Aiello, a spokesman for the league, said on Thursday.
If the plan works out, the technological toys could be used in the
regular season. ``But it may not be likely for this season,''
Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the most likely player to wear a ``HelmetCam'' or
a microphone would be the quarterback so viewers could hear him
barking signals. ``But it could be done for the free safety or the
middle linebacker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials may also be outfitted with miniature cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS, Fox and ESPN have wanted to use such enhancements for
years, but the league resisted. Last season, cameras were allowed
into locker rooms before games, and one player per team could wear
a microphone in pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, the producer of ABC's ``Monday Night Football,''
asked owners last month to expand the use of cameras and sound this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL may be reacting to the wishes of networks paying a
combined $2.2 billion a year for the rights to show games _ as well
as to the announced plans of the XFL, the football league created
by the World Wrestling Federation and NBC, which starts play next
February. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
