</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS STILL HEARING THE EWING QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Just after the New York Knicks lost Game 5
Wednesday night, the door to the locker room swung open. Slumped
forward in a chair, his face weary from exhaustion, Patrick Ewing
was decorated in ice bags like purple hearts.
</P>
<P>
   He was a vision of valor, but also a figure cursed by longevity.
At age 37, Ewing's aching body has the dents and rust of an
appliance placed curbside even as he continues to push forward. As
he nears the end of his 15th season with the Knicks, he has amassed
wealth and an historic place, but his extended stay in New York
City has yet to turn up a title or public affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the legacy has already been written for Patrick
here,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said Thursday after practice. ``He is
the best Knick ever, but he's not the most popular one.''
</P>
<P>
   He limps, but he is not Willis Reed. Thursday, on the eve of
Game 6 at Madison Square Garden, with his team one game from
elimination, down 3-2 to Indiana, Ewing was forced to confront an
issue that has only cemented his status as a tragic figure: are the
Knicks better without him? Just the question must sting even the
callous skin Ewing has developed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to it,'' said Ewing, who expects to play in Game 6
after his Game 5 comeback from a two-game absence due to tendinitis
in his right foot. ``I don't worry about it. I'm hurt. But I feel
like I can step on the court and help the team. I've got to come
out and try to play.''
</P>
<P>
   And play effectively _ or else the season could end. The Knicks
are in a dire situation, similar to the one they were in when they
fell behind Miami, 3-2 , in the conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest difference is, Indiana's a better team''
than Miami, Van Gundy said. ``Again, we have to find a way to play
one great home game to get the season down to one game back there
in Indiana. That's all we should be thinking about, making the
necessary corrections to be ready mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   They were at their prepared best against Miami. In that series,
Ewing came through with critical free throws and timely offense to
help remove the team from harm's way. But the Heat series seems so
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, Ewing's teammates seem to have had their
consciousness pierced by the repeated quote of a glaring statistic:
over the last two years in the playoffs, the Knicks are 5-1 without
Ewing against Indiana. Privately, one player uttered his
frustration with the way the pace of Game 5 bogged down once the
offense started to go through Ewing. It was certainly not his
fault, but an 18-point Knicks lead in the second quarter began to
vanish once Ewing, among others, began lofting up jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did nothing better in the first quarter other than we made
shots,'' Van Gundy said. ``We didn't guard any better. We didn't
rebound better. We didn't make hustle plays. It's fool's gold
thinking you're going to shoot your way to a win.''
</P>
<P>
   In Games 3 and 4, the Knicks were a penetrating team that
created open shots. And they also rebounded, which they didn't do
with a bigger lineup in Game 5. This lack of aggressiveness with
Ewing on the floor in Game 5 puzzled Latrell Sprewell, for one. Was
it Ewing, the Pacers' assertiveness, or something else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's the case or not, with Patrick on the
floor, whether we're better or not,'' Sprewell said Thursday. `'I
just don't know. I feel in my heart that we need Patrick and need
him to play well. We need everyone to play well if we expect to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look just at the numbers, the numbers definitely say
we're better without him. We've won five and lost one without him.
If you look at that, that's probably the case. That's what the
numbers say.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Ewing partially tore his Achilles' tendon against
Indiana during Game 2 of the conference finals and missed the rest
of the playoffs. In his absence, a liberated Knicks team used an
up-tempo style as it went on a journey to the NBA finals. With a
boot cast on his foot, and despair in his mood, Ewing watched from
the bench in a suit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the scene was revisited when Ewing pulled up six
minutes into Game 2. Unlike last year, Ewing is back _ whether his
teammates welcome it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point of the year, to me, it's an overanalyzed
issue,'' Van Gundy said. ``We had no problem winning with Patrick
on the floor against Miami. And this has nothing to do with
Latrell, but when you lose at this time of the year, when the
stakes are higher, there's not enough reflection on what each
person can do differently by the individual. And there's more
reflection on what others should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, the players have been asked about it so often. Once
you've been given this stat all the time, you start to believe it a
little. I don't think our strong-willed guys will believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
