<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOO-DOTCOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONMALL.COM SWOOPS IN FOR THE BOO.COM FIRE SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The remnants of Boo.com, the fashion Web retailer that
sought bankruptcy here last week when investors refused to give it
more cash, were acquired Thursday by Fashionmall.com, a New York
Internet company, for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   The deal opens a new chapter in the troubled life of Boo.com,
which was originally backed by the French luxury-goods magnate
Bernard Arnault, the Benneton family of Italy, J.P. Morgan and
Goldman Sachs, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by two 29-year-old Swedish entrepreneurs, the company
burned through 125 million pounds, or about $188 million, in just
six months in an attempt to create a worldwide fashion e-tailer
selling goods in multiple languages and currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Boo.com's rapid expansion and its staff's spending on luxury
offices, first-class plane travel and five-star hotels came to
symbolize the excesses of the Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   Although its Internet technology won raves for an ability to let
users view clothes in three dimensions from all angles, the company
utterly failed to generate the kind of business it had envisioned.
Boo.com's demise was Europe's biggest Internet collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Boo.com's remains Thursday to Fashionmall.com
includes the Boo.com brand, Web address, advertising materials and
online content. The deal does not include any of Boo.com's back-end
technology, distribution and fulfillment systems or physical
assets. Boo.com's back-end technology was sold earlier this week to
Bright Station PLC, a British Internet company, for 250,000 pounds
_ a fraction of the reported 70 million pounds Boo.com was said to
have paid for it. KPMG, the consulting and advisory firm, is
handling the liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Nasarin, chief executive of Fashionmall.com, declined
to say how much he spent, but said it was more than what Bright
Station paid.
</P>
<P>
   Fashionmall.com opened in 1994 as one of the first Internet
fashion sites. It plans to use the Boo.com brand to create a
high-end site similar to its existing one rather than continue to
run the company as an online retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a phenomenal job building their brand,'' Nasarin
said. ``They were probably ahead of their time, but such is life.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashionmall.com is hoping to migrate Boo.com's existing
customers to a new site using the same name that will act as a
virtual mall, selling goods through separate vendors and charging a
commission for each sale.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Boo.com's troubles, it attracted more visitors than
Fashionmall.com. According to Media Metrix, a research firm that
tracks Internet site visits, Boo.com recorded 558,000 visitors in
April, versus 208,000 for Fashionmall.com.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts questioned the rationale for buying a brand that has
the taint of failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been much maligned,'' Ken Cassar, senior retail analyst
at Jupiter Communications, said of Boo.com's brand. ``It's an open
question if it's an asset or liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasarin asserted, ``The brand has not been tarnished.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's business plan may have been tarnished,'' he
added, ``but I'm not buying their business plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
