<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-STRAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG_GONE DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an effort to spruce up Los Angeles for the
Democratic National Convention in August, city animal officials
have ordered a roundup of stray dogs and plan to euthanize more
dogs to relieve crowded kennels, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge we're facing is severe overcrowding,'' said Dan
Knapp, general manager of the Los Angeles Department of Animal
Services. ``Point A, and the catalyst for this change, is the
Democratic National Convention. Point B is the City Council ...
emphasizing getting these stray dogs off the streets to make the
streets safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activists are outraged by the plan, saying the
aggressive push to reduce overcrowding is inhumane and does nothing
to solve the problem of unwanted dogs in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is slaughter,'' said Laura Heisen of Agoura, a volunteer
at the Los Angeles Animal Services East Valley kennel. ``I believe
that we do have a big problem with pack dogs in some parts of the
city, but what they're doing is not going to solve the problem.
They just want to make things nice for the reporters and the
politicians for the Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, animal-control officials put up for adoption about
200 dogs every day at each of the city's six kennels. Under the new
plan, which could begin the second week of July, workers will hold
for adoption only about 61 dogs a day at each shelter, Knapp said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Strays not suitable for adoption will be kept separately and
euthanized after five to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Knapp said he does not know how many more dogs will be
euthanized under the new plan, but that about 40 percent are put to
sleep now because of illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in grief, and we're depressed. This is a hard decision
to make. We exist to provide life, and we've all struggled with the
reality,'' he said. ``The casualties will be that we will be
euthanizing more dogs that would have been available for adoption.
We don't know how many.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is so severe that Knapp estimates the kennels are
nearly 200 percent over capacity.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most cramped kennel is in South Central -- a
1920s-vintage temporary shelter with a population of 7,845 dogs as
of January. The second most crowded kennel is in the Northeast
Valley, with 5,183 dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Animal Control Department, with a nearly $13 million budget
and approximately 50 animal-control officers, has struggled over
how to deal with the severe crowding for several years.
Animal-control officers catch nearly 8,000 stray dogs a year and
receive an additional 27,000 dogs as dropoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Adding pressure is a law that took effect in January 1999 that
forces cities and counties to provide more care for sick and
injured animals rather than euthanize them. It extended the
mandatory hold period from three to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski recommended that
officials approve a $140 million bond measure on the November 2000
ballot to pay for five more kennels in the city and to refurbish
the other six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached a period where the animal population is simply
out of control in the city,'' according to Miscikowski's deputy,
Glenn Barr. ``Nobody likes to enhance the collection and
euthanization of animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with attacks by pit bulls and other stray dogs citywide,
the City Council has pushed aggressive spay-and-neutering programs,
including a new, higher fee for unaltered dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacoima and the Northeast Valley have always been the highest
ranked areas (for) stray dogs, unfortunately,'' said Councilman
Alex Padilla's spokesman, David Gershwin. ``There are far too many
stray dogs on the street. We need to beef up and provide additional
funding, greater coverage for this chronic problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers also established a Web site devoted to displaying
pictures of dogs offered for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Tia Maria Torres of the Villalobos Rescue Center, a Los Angeles
pit bull rescue group, believes there are other, longer-term
solutions to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many humane groups (that) offer help fostering
these animals with aggressive adoption programs and volunteering to
help train owners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is like the major talk of the town right now.
Pit bulls are going to be the first to go. I understand (the
shelters') dilemma. They're filled up. But stop running with the
problem and get with these humane groups to solve the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Teri Austin, president of Amanda Foundation, an organization
that rescues dogs and cats from city animal shelters, is critical
of the plan, calling it a ``cold and inhumane way to handle the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a numbers game,'' she said. ``It's about looking good. If
you make less animals adoptable then you should have a higher rate
of adoption. The result is that more animals are going to die
because they're not going to get a chance to be adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
