<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DIMAGGIO-ESTATE-SFCHR     06-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-ESTATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO TRUSTEE SUES SAN FRANCISCO TO KEEP NAME OF BASEBALL 
 GREAT OFF CITY PLAYGROUND
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By EDWARD EPSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The trustee of Joe DiMaggio's estate declared war on San
Francisco Thursday, suing to prevent the city from renaming the
North Beach Playground in honor of the baseball great.
<P>
   The action by longtime DiMaggio attorney and friend Morris
Engelberg of Hollywood, Fla., was greeted with disbelief and anger
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, filed in Miami, Engelberg charged that San
Francisco's plan was not a suitable honor for someone of the
stature of DiMaggio, the North Beach sandlot star who went on to
Hall of Fame greatness with the New York Yankees and then earned a
place in America's celebrity pantheon through his marriage to
Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco ``should not be given carte blanche to name the
city junk yard, the city waste dump, in this case the North Beach
Playground, or any other such facility after Joe DiMaggio, without
consent,'' says the lawsuit filed in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to forcing the city not to rename the playground
where DiMaggio and his brothers played ball as kids, Engelberg
sought unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiff doesn't believe that it's a fitting park or
place that should carry the DiMaggio name,'' said Miami attorney
Jeffrey Herman, who worked on the suit for the estate.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg, who has been feuding with San Francisco since shortly
after DiMaggio died at age 84 in March 1999, said naming the
playground after DiMaggio ``is both morally and legally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised Joe, not only during the years I was with him but
also on his deathbed, to protect his name at whatever sacrifice to
myself,'' Engelberg said.
</P>
<P>
   When Supervisor Gavin Newsom, who has worked to find a suitable
honor for the longtime Marine District resident, sent Engelberg a
long list of possible honors for DiMaggio, the attorney selected
either the Bay Bridge or San Francisco International Airport. But
Mayor Willie Brown and Newsom later said those were unworkable,
too-grand ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, Newsom thought he had heard the last of
Engelberg. In April, when Brown and Newsom announced plans to
finally act on a 20-year-old city plan to name the playground for
DiMaggio, Engelberg told The Chronicle that his earlier comments
threatening legal action had been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had never threatened a lawsuit. ``I'm not going to
take money from (DiMaggio's) grandchildren'' to go to court, said
Engelberg, who is trustee for an estate in which the grandchildren
are heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's consistent here is Mr. Engelberg's
inconsistency,'' Newsom said Thursday. ``Once again, he's
contradicting his own statements.''
</P>
<P>
   He charged that Engelberg had commercial motives for the
lawsuit. ``Mr. Engelberg's got a book deal and hired a personal
manager. I hear he's looking for $2 million for his book and that
magazines are doing articles about him and Mr. DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsom also said it was a slap in the face for Engelberg to
compare the playground to a garbage dump. ``That's an insult to
every San Franciscan, to North Beach and to tens of thousands of
kids who use that playground every year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said $3.5 million of renovations will begin next month at the
2.5-acre park, which includes blacktop ball diamonds, tennis and
bocce courts, a swimming pool and a playground. No signs honoring
DiMaggio have yet been erected.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said private local attorneys, including Iran-contra
prosecutor John Keker, have written to him offering to handle for
free any suit filed by Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Slavin, an assistant to City Attorney Louise Renne, said
the city will fight Engelberg's suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the playground was renamed recently, it was our opinion
that it was a legally sound action,'' Slavin said. ``That's still
our opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, it's a frivolous lawsuit and an
insult to San Francisco and a great American who we are trying to
honor,'' Slavin added. ``It's hard to fathom any opposition to such
a human gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Slavin said the city's first step probably will be to try to get
the suit moved from Florida to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, Engelberg said he he was trying to protect the
commercial value of the DiMaggio name. Allowing use of the name
without permission dilutes that value, causing financial problems
for the estate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city attorney's office has said Engelberg's concern can
extend only to the commercial use of the name and not to the city
naming a public site after someone.
</P>
<P>
   In North Beach, an old DiMaggio friend, 81-year-old Dante
Benedetti, said Engelberg was being a bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anyone ever have the guts to ask him where he comes
from?'' Benedetti said. ``He should stay in Florida and mind his
own business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe DiMaggio spent most of his young life at the North Beach
Playground,'' recalled Benedetti, the owner of the New Pisa
Restaurant and former University of San Francisco baseball coach,
who was there with DiMaggio and his brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, Engelberg also went after Joe DiMaggio's younger
brother, Dom, who has endorsed the playground plan.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint said Dom DiMaggio, a major league star in his own
right, does not speak for the estate and ``was not even included in
the will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominic DiMaggio owns real estate in the North Beach
Playground area which would benefit from the use of the Joe
DiMaggio name in the neighborhood,'' the complaint read.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio could not be reached for comment Thursday. In
April, he said, ``I am personally extremely pleased'' by the
planned honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know deep down in my heart that Joe would be very thrilled
as deeply as I am,'' added Dom DiMaggio, who has rarely had
anything good to say about Engelberg during the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was in New Orleans Thursday for a one-day civic trip. His
spokesman Ron Vinson said, ``Our efforts to honor one of our most
accomplished athletes will withstand any self-serving legal
challenge from Mr. Engelberg.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
