<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WILL TRY TO LAND KNOCKOUT PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The avenues surrounding Staples Center are
newly resurfaced, as if some overly eager public-works official got
a little ahead of himself and ordered up a downtown preening in
anticipation of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   So the streets of L.A. appear ready for the party. But its
basketball team appeared otherwise earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could have had their finals invitations in hand by
now, but the Portland Trail Blazers denied them that honor Tuesday
night by winning Game 5 of the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the Lakers weren't quite ready for prime time. Their
coach said as much when he called the loss ``good for us,'' musing
once again that they had lessons to learn.
</P>
<P>
   They'll get another chance to show progress, and wrap up this
series, tonight in Game 6 at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to understand there's a certain sense of carriage
that you have as a basketball team, there's a certain sense of how
you go about taking care of business when you have an opportunity
to close out a series like this,'' coach Phil Jackson said
Thursday. ``That you make adjustments during the course of a game,
you don't stay rigid, denied.''
</P>
<P>
   That happened when the Lakers failed to cope with early foul
trouble to guards Kobe Bryant, Ron Harper and Brian Shaw, or adjust
to the Blazers' pressure defense.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers could face their greatest adjustment of all _
playing with a hobbled Kobe, and perhaps no Kobe at all.
</P>
<P>
   Though listed as probable for tonight's game, Bryant is bothered
by a sprained right foot, and Jackson called him a ``game-time
decision.'' So a team that seems to play its best under duress has
an added source of stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're already on edge, with or without having to deal
with the fact that Kobe's injured right now a little bit,'' said
teammate Derek Fisher. ``We recognize that we let another
postseason opportunity to close out a series get by us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And dealing with that is sometimes tough and disappointing,
but we've just talked about the fact that it's still part of this
learning process we've been going through all season long, trying
to learn how to be the best team in this league. And we have
accomplished more this season than we ever have. And this is
another step in trying to reach that potential and reach that
plateau that people want us to r know that we're capable of
reaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland has the momentum and the home court tonight, but
neither concept has meant much in this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won convincingly in Game 1 but stumbled in Game 2.
They put together an impressive two-game sweep in Portland last
weekend but couldn't deliver that energy in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   As for home-court advantage, there has been none. The road team
has won the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's down to a battle of sports truisms: On one side,
there's the challenge of beating a team three straight games on its
home floor (the Lakers' task tonight); on the other side, the
challenge of beating a top-rated team three straight games period
(the Blazers' task if they can stretch this to a seventh game).
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that it's tough to beat a good team three times in a
row, it's a challenge for us to beat Portland three times in a row,
and a good enough team to understand that,'' Jackson said. ``In the
same regard, they have to beat us three times in a row. So we know
that we' driver's seat of this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   To close it out, the Lakers will try to regain the poise and
precision their offense lacked in Tuesday's loss. That will mean
finding Shaquille O'Neal early and often, but it will also require
finding a shooting rhythm for everyone else to avoid another 38
percent shooting night.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game, you know,'' said Robert Horry, who made 3 of 11
shots in Game 5. ``So we've got a lot of opportunities for guys to
come out there and just keep shooting. I just hope nobody's
hesitant, because that's going to make your shot really off, to be
hesitant.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Lakers have the mathematical advantage _ they
have two chances to get a win, while the Blazers have zero room for
a slip-up. Not that anyone is counting on coming home for a Game 7
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our eyes we have no cushion,'' Horry said, ``because we
want to go out and take care of the next game. People always say
you've got a cushion because you've got two games. That's not an
option. Yo go out there and play hard for the game you got, because
you never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
