<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-EXLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA AND OTHER EX-DODGERS TO FACE OLD CLUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Almost from the moment he was announced as the
Anaheim Angels' new manager, Mike Scioscia has had to answer
questions about his past.
</P>
<P>
   His Los Angeles Dodgers past.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when one spends 22 years in one
organization. He spent 17 seasons as a player in the organization
and five as a coach/manager. He credits all-time greats like Roy
Campanella and John Roseboro, among others, for being his mentors.
</P>
<P>
   But when his Angels take on the Dodgers tonight to begin a
three-game series at Edison Field, Scioscia says the Dodgers might
as well be from Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned with the 25 guys in this clubhouse than
about any other club,'' he said. ``As far as playing the Dodgers,
honestly, it's just another ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Mike. Just another ballclub?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's a strong connection to where I am now in my
baseball career and what I did with the Dodgers,'' he said. ``All
of my foundation was laid with the Dodgers. There are a lot of
people over there who took time to work with me. I have a lot of
great memories and a lot of great friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't change my commitment to this club. (The
Dodgers) are just another club we're trying to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia has the Angels over .500 (27-26) and in the middle of
the AL West race, despite predications of doom and gloom. Scioscia
talked confidently of his club from the start of spring training
and his players have backed him up both on the field and in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   He is a manager who preaches to his players the importance of
``turning the page'' from one game to the next. And he practices
his approach with his own career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about where I am now, to be here with the
Angels,'' he said, ``helping lay down the building blocks to get
this organization to be the perennial contender everybody thinks it
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia's coaching staff is made up primarily of ex-Dodgers.
Hitting coach Mickey Hatcher, third-base coach Ron Roenicke and
first-base coach Alfredo Griffin all spent time with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Roenicke played for the Dodgers only three seasons (1981-83),
but he coached and managed in the organization from 1992-98,
including managing Triple-A Albuquerque for the last half of the
1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any way to block that out,'' Roenicke
said. ``When I was a player, I went to so many other teams that
coming back to face them then wasn't really a big deal. But now
after going back to coach for them, I can't block that out. I can't
say I want to beat up on them, but the games are more meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenicke left the Dodgers after the 1998 season to manage at
Fresno, the Giants' Triple-A club. After spending so much time in
the Dodgers organization, particularly working with the players in
the minor leagues, one might think Roenicke wishes he could have
stayed there. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the same people were still running the club there, that
would have been great,'' he said. ``But (Peter) O'Malley left,
(Fred) Claire left. With all those changes over there, no, I'm much
happier where I am because of the people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher became a fan favorite with the Dodgers for his hustle
and goofy demeanor. He also coached from the low minors up to the
major-league club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place I thought I'd spend the rest of my life,''
Hatcher said. ``There's going to be emotion because of the fans.
The fans meant a lot for me. They motivated me and were behind me.
That part's going to be good. In Anaheim we see a lot of people
that went to Dodger games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's changed so much over there now, a lot of people I was
close to have gone somewhere else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
