<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     06-02 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE CITY OF THE RUDE AND CRUDE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
I'll tell you where I stand on dog poop.
<P>
   I am opposed to it as lawn sculpture in public parks.
</P>
<P>
   I fully support Mayor Willie Brown's plan to assign two park
patrol cops to full-time duty citing dog owners who don't clean up.
The city has a SWAT team, it should also have a SQUAT team.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani launched a campaign
to promote common courtesy, and it's about time San Francisco did
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Civility is on the decline. We've got road hogs, jaywalkers,
jaybikers, jayboarders, stereo blasters, cell-phone yellers,
litterbugs, rude Muni and taxi drivers, rude Muni and taxi riders.
</P>
<P>
   The city is brimming with selfish oafs who wouldn't give up
their seat on the bus to a 90-year-old pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   High on my list of the rude &AMP; crude: dog owners who don't scoop.
Disgusting. They should be ordered to do community service, given a
glove and assigned to fill a 10-gallon receptacle.
</P>
<P>
   That said, how would you like to draw this patrol assignment
right out of the Police Academy?
</P>
<P>
   Reader Steve Abney is worried about possible snags in the
mayor's plan. Establishing guilt could be difficult, he notes,
because this isn't like ballistics, where you match the bullet to
the gun barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what if you snitched on a negligent pet owner?'' Abney
wonders. ``Would you be a stool pigeon?''
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the Pooper Troopers.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW Chrysler PT Cruiser is hot, because a lot of Boomer men
have always secretly lusted for a hip, customized '40s delivery
van. It's a Boomer guy thing. You wouldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter Rapp phoned John Irish Chrysler in San Rafael to arrange
for a test drive. Sorry, the salesman said, no demos. Go rent a
Cruiser from Thrifty, then come in and place your order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee,'' said Dieter, ``that's not the way I envisioned buying a
new car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working for us,'' the salesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp phoned Chrysler, was told if he ordered right away, he
might get his Cruiser within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wow, a delivery van that takes a year to be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   CONCRETE JUNGLE: Steve Wall has noticed something missing at SFO
over the years _ landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a single plant alive anywhere near SFO?'' Steve asks,
rhetorically. ``Nope. Which is amazing, in a state with such a
great gardening climate. Maybe they could use that shot-up Muni bus
as a huge flower pot, to get things started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns, police, buses and flowers. Add some music (and drugs?),
and the summer of eLove has just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they're going to use that bus for street cleaning.
Fill it with water (driver in scuba gear, of course) and drive it
around town.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T BOTHER to try to get a cab or dinner reservation next week
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   JavaOne is in town Monday through Thursday with its high-tech
show and 20,000 javaheads. It's probably San Francisco's
second-biggest show-convention of the year (Seybold brings in about
36,000).
</P>
<P>
   Twenty thousand human search engines in search of a high-tech
old time. Is that a mouse in your pocket, or a roll of venture
capital?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what JavaOne is, but if these people are searching
for java, they're coming to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS have found an ozone hole above the North Pole much
like the one above the South Pole, which proves what Randy Alfred
has suspected _ ``The planet is suffering from a bipolar
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what the ozone holes looks like above the heads of TV
news people and country singers who use too much hair spray?
</P>
<P>
   And I wonder what Rush Limbaugh has to say about the latest
scientific discovery above the North Pole. I forgot to listen to
his show today.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his best-selling books, Rush devoted a lot of space to
debunking the laughably baseless claims of fear-mongering
environmentalists who are trying to deprive captains of industry of
their divine right to pollute for profit.
</P>
<P>
   As scientific evidence piles up against Rush's arguments, we
await his best-selling mea culpa and pledge to help rescue Earth.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, a recent reference here to the Rushster as blimp had
nothing to do with his size. Give the man credit, he has trimmed
his jib, now consumes a far smaller share of the world's oxygen and
dead-animal treats.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's a svelte bag of hot gas.
</P>
<P>
   THE BANDITO in ``Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' for those
hoping to fill crucial gaps in their educations in anticipation of
cashing in on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' was Alfonso
Bedoya.
</P>
<P>
   He's the grinning Mexican bad guy who made the famous ``stinking
badges'' speech to Humphrey Bogart. Bedoya was born in Mexico, was
a character in more than 40 movies in the U.S. and Mexico, and died
in Mexico in '57, at age 53, his health destroyed by drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports that Bedoya is buried in Hollister, the three
cemeteries in that city say they have no record of him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he didn't need no stinking headstone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NEWDEMS-TECH-SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWDEMS-TECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH MAVENS MEET CONGRESSIONAL DEMOCRATS AT 3-DAY RETREAT  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ About 20 House and Senate Democrats will meet
with Silicon Valley business leaders Friday and Saturday in a
get-together that's as much about old-time politics as it is about
the nation's high-tech future.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth annual Bay Area New Economy Retreat, which began
Thursday, features three days of workshops on such issues as
``Biotechnology and Genomics'' and ``Emerging Issues in E-Commerce
and the Internet.'' But between the high-powered seminars, there's
plenty of time built-in for the technology mavens to chat quietly
with members of Congress about what Silicon Valley needs from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just an opportunity for (scheduled) discussion,''
said Gabriela Prado, a spokeswoman for TechNet, the Silicon Valley
business group co-sponsoring the San Francisco retreat. ``There are
also receptions scheduled and places where our members can get
together with the political people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with the event's other sponsor, the New
Democrat Network. Linking politicians with high-tech leaders _ and
their money _ is an important part of what the group does.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the premier gathering of New Economy leaders in
Northern California,'' said Simon Rosenberg, president of the New
Democrat Network. ``We want to be a force for a more modern
Democratic Party, but we also want to influence the agenda for the
entire Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that likely agenda is going to be important to Silicon
Valley. The so-called ``New Democrats'' helped pass the Internet
tax ban and provided most of the Democratic votes for the China
trade bill that passed last week, both measures strongly backed by
the high-tech community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Democrats are just a modern version of the traditional
Democrats,'' Rosenberg said. ``They're usually more
internationalist and trade-oriented, but tolerant on social
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   With 65 members, the New Democratic Coalition is now the largest
caucus in the House, and their centrist agenda plays well in the
moderate swing districts that are going to be the battlegrounds in
the Democrats' efforts to grab control of the House from
Republicans in November. The NDN is a political action committee
that raises money to get more of those New Democrats elected,
Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a venture capital fund for the Democratic Party,
investing in a new generation of leaders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the reasons Assemblyman Mike Honda, state Sen.
Adam Schiff, Assemblywoman Susan Davis and former Rep. Jane Harmon
_ all Democratic candidates in California's four most hotly
contested congressional races _ will be at the retreat, rubbing
shoulders with the high-tech leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Even the technology seminars have their political side. The
topics, which include privacy, education and the digital divide,
cybersecurity and intellectual property protection, are all issues
important to the high-tech world and likely to come before the
Congress soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to design an agenda that covers issues that not only
the Valley is focused on, but that members of Congress might have
questions about,'' Prado said. ``Often the politicians aren't as
well-versed as they would like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Bob Graham of Florida and John Kerry of Massachusetts top
the list of attendees, while California Reps. Anna Eshoo of
Atherton, Cal Dooley of Visalia and Mike Thompson of Napa are among
those expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important gathering, because it brings members (of
Congress) into the place where ideas are created,'' said Eshoo,
whose district includes strongholds of the computer and biotech
industry. ``When Congress is in session, we have very little time
to meet with people who are part of this (high-tech industry) to
have discussions and ask questions. This is a very important
tutorial.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150 members of TechNet, which works with both Democratic
and Republican groups, are expected at the retreat, which began
Thursday afternoon with a seminar at a Palo Alto biotech firm and
continues through tomorrow with meetings at the Metreon in downtown
San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
