r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-02 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ A BIGGER HIT THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alex Rodriguez remembers the exact situation when he
realized Edgar Martinez was in the middle of something special.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third inning on May 15 vs. the Twins at Safeco Field.
Rodriguez was on first base after a leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had been demolishing baseballs with consistency for a
couple of weeks already, but in this at-bat he surprised even his
long-time teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits a ball (foul) out to left field,'' Rodriguez said.
``Then he hits a ball (again) foul out to right field. Then he hits
the ball out to center (for a home run).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching this and going, `What's up? That not fair.'
Nobody's supposed to be able to do that. I've been Edgar's teammate
for six or seven years now, and I thought I'd seen everything he
could do, good and bad. But he still surprises me. He's been
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez continues to amaze and surprise American League
pitchers, too, although it's unlikely they are as jazzed about it
as Rodriguez. For the month, Martinez hit, as he did in the May 15
at-bat against Minnesota's Eric Milton, line drives to left, right
and center.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez owned May. He hit .441 (45-for-102). He hit 10 homers
and drove in 32 runs. He scored 24 runs. He was a machine. The
batting average and RBI total were the best in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Now here comes June, and here come the San Diego Padres. And
here comes Tony Gwynn. To many people, Gwynn (begin italic) is (end
italic) the Padres. To Martinez, Gwynn is hitting. Although
Martinez is regarded as one of the best right-handed hitters of his
generation, he looks to the left-handed Gwynn, an eight-time
National League batting champ, the way a Catholic looks to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's one of my favorite hitters,'' Martinez said. ``I'd love
the chance to just sit down and talk hitting with him. I never have
had the chance, but I watch his every at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   As the designated hitter, Martinez generally leaves the dugout
when the other side is hitting. He'll go do some stretching or take
some swings _ anything to stay loose. But if you're among the
Safeco crowd this weekend, watch the Mariners' dugout when Gwynn is
at the plate. You'll see Martinez, soaking up every nuance of the
master. Michelangelo honing his craft in Da Vinci's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make sure I watch all of Tony's at-bats,'' Martinez said.
``His swing is amazing. He is so aware of what he's doing right and
of what he's doing wrong. He studies his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a career .320 hitter, also studies Gwynn's swing, even
though the Padres legend, a career .339 hitter, is left-handed and
Martinez is right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always anxious to learn what he does at the plate, to
adapt it to what I do,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   And what Martinez does, simply, is what Gwynn does. He hits.
They both hit. Against right-handers. Against left-handers. Against
flame-throwers. Against marshmallow tossers. What has made both men
special over the years is an ability to hit against anyone at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that amazes me about Edgar,'' said teammate Jamie
Moyer, Friday night's starting pitcher, ``is the way he can control
an at-bat. Normally, as a pitcher you always feel you control the
at-bat. You have the ball, you know what pitch you want to make,
and where.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Edgar, he takes that away from you. He controls the
at-bat. ... As long as he's got one pitch left, he's in control. If
you're pitching to him, it's scary to see how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   For left fielder Rickey Henderson, now playing with Martinez
after years on the other side of the field, Martinez is simply
``the best right-handed hitter around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just watch what he does,'' Henderson said. ``He studies
hitters. He studies pitchers. He learns from both of them. I've
been watching him for 10 or 12 years now, and he still has the same
habits, the same bat speed and the same bat control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always a tough out.''
</P>
<P>
   For manager Lou Piniella, who has the pleasure of writing
Martinez's name into the lineup 150 or so times a year, Martinez's
special skill is his ability to make the good times roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched Edgar for a lot of years now (eight), and the
thing that separates him from just about every other hitter is his
ability to stay locked in,'' Piniella said. ``If a normal batter
will get in a zone for a week, he'll get in it for two weeks. If a
normal batter will get in a zone for two weeks, Edgar will get
there for three or four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to extend things when he's going good, and he
knows how to keep the bad times, the slumps, to a minimum. That's
what makes him so dangerous. He's a threat to get a hit or drive in
a run almost every time he's at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella and Rodriguez both mention Martinez in terms of the
Hall of Fame. Martinez says he is flattered by the nominations, but
quickly adds, ``I don't have the numbers yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He does have two batting titles (1992, '95), and he leads the AL
in hitting (.376), so a third title is within reach. At 37, he has
three or four years ahead of him. One more batting title would
strengthen his case considerably. Two more would make him a major
contender.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, no player who has mostly been a DH has ever
made it to Cooperstown, although by the time Martinez is eligible
for consideration, current Baltimore DH Harold Baines may have
broken through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about the Hall, I know I have a long way to
go,'' Martinez said. ``When you compare my (power) numbers to the
Hall of Fame guys, I'm short. The hits and the average are good,
but I don't have the homers and RBIs.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be changing this year. He's among the league leaders
in both categories, and shows no sign of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit for this kind of power before, but I'm seeing
the ball good, and my bat speed is as good as ever,'' Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers beware.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
