r s BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     06-02 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS GRACIOUS GUESTS _ UNTIL TIP-OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Comets sat on the visitors' bench, their game
faces firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time reigning champions of the WNBA weren't exactly
patient, but during the long and winding pregame ceremony, they did
their best to endure the hype and hoopla surrounding the unveiling
of the Storm.
</P>
<P>
   Houston coach Van Chancellor paced like a lion, just for the
effect, as the public address announcer bellowed out the starting
five of Seattle's newest pro sports franchise:
</P>
<P>
   Edna Campbell, Charmin Smith, Kamila Vodichkova, Quacy Barnes
and Sonja Henning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cool-as-a-cucumber Sheryl Swoopes spread her long
arms over the back of two chairs, feigning serious boredom with a
cold stare that made you think twice about meeting up with her in a
dark alley.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time league MVP Cynthia Cooper studied the top of her
sneakers, as if they might sprout hair.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson applied another layer of plum-red lipstick, just
to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   In a league starting its fourth season, the reigning queens of
the WNBA understand they have to be somewhat gracious toward their
newest peers, so they let the new girls have their moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to see the growth of the new league, new faces,
new talent, new teams and their fans and the excitment generated
around the new franchises,'' said Cooper, a star whose attitude and
professionalism is somehow even greater than her stalwart game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to see growth, especially in a very young
league,'' Cooper said, being nice.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the niceness and patience ended.
</P>
<P>
   The second the warm and fuzzy pre-game ceremonies were wrapped
up, the Comets went to work.
</P>
<P>
   They brought their finesse game and their lunchbuckets and their
ornery determination, showing the Storm and their eager fans the
meaning of hardwood excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm had not even broken a sweat and there was Thompson,
dropping a moon-shot 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Next came Swoopes, picking up a loose ball in the backcourt and
heaving a bomb to Thompson for an easy layup.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper drove the lane for a layup, Thompson followed with
another 3-pointer, and that was how it started. An 11-point Houston
lead swelled to 18, then to 22, and then, well, the outcome was
pretty much as expected, with the reigning champs clamping down a
monster win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd be fired up,'' said Storm coach Lin Dunn. ``I
think they were embarassed by going to double overtime (Thursday
night at Portland), but give credit to Swoopes and Cooper. They got
us down early on.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't fair _ it couldn't be against this WNBA dynasty _ but
at least it was exciting.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking about watching Sonics star Gary Payton hug
Sonics owner Barry Ackerley's wife Ginger during a time out.
</P>
<P>
   No, Thursday night at KeyArena was about the women.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm held their coming-out party, and the WNBA production
seemed a reasonable facsimile of the NBA game, with all the good
and bad that sort of entertainment juggernaut entails.
</P>
<P>
   The swirling laser lights played havoc with retinas. The sound
system shook the very depths of your inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   And there were games and giveaways and the unveiling of the new
mascot, Doppler _ a fuzzy, red Barney-like creature, who thankfully
is a much better dancer than Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is a much better dancer than Barney, too. Another bonus.
</P>
<P>
   While the real, live Dunn could be seen patrolling the sideline,
extolling her Storm to get after the Comets, a videotaped version
of Dunn could be seen during timeouts on the JumboTron, leading the
KeyArena crowd in the ``Fan Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere at the heart of all this lightheartedness was a
basketball game _ and the first look in Seattle at a women's pro
basketball league whose future depends upon how long it takes for
the expansion teams to be competitive, for a more national audience
to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   While the Comets have every intention of hammering the expansion
franchises, they are not unaware of the importance of being good
ambassadors, about doing all the right things _ other than going
easy on the new girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the players that's well-known in the league, and
hopefully, I'll do what I have to do to keep the league healthy and
exciting, and will motivate other players to do exactly the same
thing,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the fortune of having to be the opener for two
expansion teams, and they're very motivated, very focused. We
already knew that we were going to have to play our best
basketball. The expansion teams have veteran players. They know
what it takes to play in the WNBA. When we come to town, they give
it a little extra.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets came and cleaned the Storm's clock, but at least the
champs said all the right things.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at
</P>
<P>
   206-448-8011 or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
