r a BC-CONTROLLER-WASTE-LADN     06-02 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTROLLER-WASTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. IS LOSING MILLIONS IN REVENUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ City Controller Rick Tuttle has accused Los
Angeles of mishandling taxpayer dollars, saying the city could save
more than $100 million a year with better management.
</P>
<P>
   In his report that city revenue growth was sluggish despite a
flourishing economy, a frustrated Tuttle identified eight areas
where the city wasted millions of dollars yearly. They include
allowing permit and license fee payment checks to sit uncashed for
months and neglecting to collect hundreds of thousands in tax
credits from the county and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over and over again, my office issues audit reports or makes
other recommendations to improve revenue collections, only to see
the recommendations get bogged down in bureaucracy,'' Tuttle wrote
in a report released Thursday. ``The buck-passing has got to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle issued the report with a letter urging City Council to
revive a plan to create a city finance director position to oversee
revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor proposed forming the new post in July, but the council
excluded it from the 2000-2001 budget, saying the job could be done
by the city treasurer. The mayor vetoed the item in the budget that
reflected the council's view, and said his proposal would do more
to strengthen the city's financial management.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the city collected $2.26 billion in revenue from
various sources -- including property, business and sales taxes and
license and permit fees, according to Tuttle's report.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, the city projects revenues of $2.79 billion, which
equals $2.18 billion in 1990 dollars -- a decline from 10 years
prior, after inflation is factored in, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even reached the level of 10 years ago, despite a
booming, vibrant economy and many more city fees at higher rates,''
Tuttle wrote. ``Something is wrong here.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer, chairman of the council's Budget and
Finance Committee, said the city needs to improve its revenue
collection, but he disagreed that creating a director of finance
would accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about the fact these things need to be
pursued,'' Feuer said. ``But it's not necessarily the job of a
single individual nor is it even possible for that to be the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   City Clerk Michael Carey, whose department oversees several of
the areas mentioned in Tuttle's report, agreed the city could save
money in certain areas. But he took issue with the report's
assertion that the City Clerk's Office fails to process checks fast
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city controller doesn't know what he is talking about,''
Carey said. ``We hire our own employees to quickly deposit money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association, questioned that the city's revenues could decline when
those of cities and counties statewide are soaring. But he said he
agrees the city could improve many of its systems, perhaps by
contracting more services out to private businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been study after study telling the city of Los
Angeles how to be more efficient and they haven't followed
through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle made the following eight recommendations, saying they
would save the city millions of dollars:
</P>
<P>
   --Better use of discounts in city contracts. The city should
make it a habit to use discounts already negotiated with vendors,
and negotiate discounts for paying early or on time. The report
estimates the city could immediately save $250,000, and eventually
up to $20 million a year, by changing its practices in this area.
</P>
<P>
   --Curb overtime. Overtime surged $18 million, or 15 percent last
year over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   --Process checks faster. The city should use lock boxes -- or
outside contractors -- to process checks for taxes, permits and
license fees. According to Tuttle's report, checks sit for days and
even months before being cashed. The report estimates the city
could collect millions in interest by depositing the checks more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   --Improve business tax collection enforcement. City officials
estimate some 60,000 businesses operating in Los Angeles do not pay
the city's business tax. The city now is advocating state
legislation that officials say will help identify those scofflaws,
which could mean up to $60 million more in the city's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   --Enforce collections. More than $75 million in the city's
accounts receivable -- including money owed to the city for fees --
is more than three months in arrears. A 1 percent improvement would
boost city revenue by $750,000, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   --Increase police fees. The city now collects police fees from
certain types of businesses -- such as firearms vendors,
pawnbrokers and carnivals. But the report says the cost of
providing the services is almost $4 million greater than the amount
the city collects in those fees, and that other political
jurisdictions charge more than the city does.
</P>
<P>
   --Recoup state and county tax credits. Now, the report states,
no single department is responsible for ensuring the city receives
reimbursements from the state and county for certain items such as
lab fees and tax credits. In 1998, the city identified $1.5 million
in reimbursements owed from the county.
</P>
<P>
   --Secure a users tax permit, which would increase the city's
revenues by some $170,000 annually, based on the city's purchases
from out-of-state vendors.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
