<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN ATHLETIC PROGRAM PUT ON PROBATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Further damaging Cal State Northridge's
beleaguered football team, the NCAA on Thursday put CSUN's ath on
three years' probation and imposed a number of other serious
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it had ``no doubt the institution failed in its
obligations,'' the NCAA also barred the football team from
postseason eligibility for the coming season and limited the number
of scholarship players to 75, 10 below the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   With the athletic program's move in 2001 to the Big West
Conference, which does not have football, CSUN interim President
Louanne Kennedy acknowledged the sport will be de-emphasized. While
remaining steadfast in her support of football and a new stadium,
Kennedy said CSUN is in negotiations with Los Angeles Pierce
College to play football there as a Division I-AA independent in
the future and that ``there are a lot of other facilities issues
ahead of the (football) stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The football program will be different,'' Kennedy said. ``I
can assure your readers that it was not my intention to become
involved in the death of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to continue to play football. How it's going to
pan out with the teams that we play and how many scholarships we
offer and so forth, those are issues that (will be worked out).
There is a coming in. She may have other ideas and interests that
she hasn't shared with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolene Koester, formerly of Sacramento State, will take over at
CSUN on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA released its findings in a 27-page report following a
lengthy review of an internal CSUN investigation that was completed
nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge fired football coach Ron Ponciano last summer after
discovering recruiting and other rules violations rampant in the
football program. CSUN's investigation was prompted by an anonymous
letter.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA found that Ponciano and two assistants had improper
contact with a pair of recruits following a high school basketball
game, despite being advised ahead of time that it could be in
violation of NCAA rules. The infractions committee also said
Ponciano arranged air transportation for one recruit to be flown to
California at no cost as well as arranging for local
transportation, lodging, meals, telephone calls and cash for
tuition to enroll at a local junior college.
</P>
<P>
   Other violations included improper recruiting of players
enrolled at other schools, payments to players, supplemental pay
for an assistant coach and granting too many football scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said Northridge failed to maintain control of and
conduct financial audits of the Quarterback Club, an independent
booster club. In 1998, a Northridge athletic representative who was
a member of the club used club funds to pay for 10 weekly barbecues
for the football team. The committee said there was no clear
guidance from Northridge athletic officials about whether the
barbecues were improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institution on a number of occasions had the opportunity
to control the situation,'' said Jack Friedenthal, the chairman of
the NCAA's Division I Committee on Infractions. ``They did not give
adequate instructions to the head coach, who was new. It was really
a failure to educate.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee said some of the violations could be attributed to
Ponciano's inexperience. It also decided, however, that some
violations appeared to demonstrate ``willful and blatant disregard
for basic NCAA legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano, who now is an assistant coach at Los Angeles Valley
College and has demanded a settlement from CSUN, also was punished
further by the NCAA. The organization limited his ability to be
hired by any NCAA-member school until July 15, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano, in Utah for a football clinic, was unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano's lawyer, Scott Campbell, said his client disputes that
his behavior was unethical, that he never made any call to arrange
a flight and that neither he nor any booster gave the recruit cash.
CSUN has not responded to Ponciano's demand for a settlement and
ignored his threat to file a wrongful-termination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult to take personnel action against
someone, knowing that it will affect their life profoundly,''
Kennedy said in reference to Ponciano's dismissal. ``But a year ago
I did what I felt was right, and the NCAA has now agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   Following its internal investigation last year, CSUN imposed a
number of penalties upon itself _ common in such matters, as the
NCAA considers how a university censures itself in determining
final punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the additional sanctions, Kennedy expressed satisfaction
with her school's handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we strongly support the (NCAA) report,'' Kennedy
said. ``The football program has had problems in the past. We have
taken actions to remedy them. This is in the past. This report is
about the past. We believe we have the people in place now (for a
successful future).''
</P>
<P>
   Among them is a new fund-raising officer, who is embarking on a
major campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The penalties are in line with what we anticipated,'' said Tom
Shannon, CSUN's NCAA faculty representative. ``They have other
penalties they could have imposed and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the actions CSUN has taken has been to hire a new
compliance officer, dissolving the Quarterback Club, educating the
staff its football scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic director at the time of the rules violations was
Paul Bubb, who was forced to resign in the aftermath of the arrest
of former women's basketball coach Michael Abraham on federal
drug-trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   Football coach Jeff Kearin reacted with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our recruiting's done,'' he said. ``Our team's in place, for
the most part. We'll play at Pierce if we have to. The president
has been clear the stadium issue will take care of itself after the
fund-raising campaign. . . . We haven't lost players I know because
of the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge has set a goal of raising $150,000 by July.
</P>
<P>
   As for a lack of conference affiliation, Kearin said as long as
Northridge plays a strong Division I-AA schedule, it will be
nationally ranked and a postseason contender.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
