<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC COLLEGE STUDIED FOR VALLEY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Valley could have its first Catholic university in as soon
as two years, serving a growing number of students who now must
leave the state for a Catholic college degree.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Brothers, a Catholic order that already runs seven
universities across the nation, has been studying the Phoenix area
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have been meeting with Valley leaders monthly. This
summer, they will look for money and land to build a four-year
liberal arts university, which also would offer professional and
graduate programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's started a school like this for quite a few years,''
said Mike Waters, chairman of the board of Lewis University, a
Christian Brothers school south of Chicago. ``You've got the
growth. It's a great spot to have a new university.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not say when a final decision would be made or
where the university would be located. But local Catholic leaders
are thrilled by the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is far and away the largest city in the country
without a Catholic university,'' said Monsignor Edward Ryle,
director of the Arizona Catholic Conference. ``We've got grammar
schools and high schools, but we don't have any Catholic
higher-education institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona school would be similar to Lewis University, which
enrolls almost 5,000 students studying nursing, education,
business, justice studies and aviation. Tuition runs about $13,000
a year. About 70 percent of its students are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Arizona's university could open in rented space
while the campus is built.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has about 780,000 Catholics. In the Phoenix Diocese,
13,000 students attend 14 Catholic preschools, 24 elementaries and
five high schools. And their numbers are growing.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic enrollment jumped 18 percent in the past five years. In
1998, a $25 million fund-raising campaign was launched to build the
Valley's first new Catholic schools in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   St. John Bosco, a kindergarten-through-eighth-grade &QL; 
school, will open next fall at Chandler Boulevard and 48th Street.
Catholic leaders expect others to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Already, families are clamoring to attend St. John Bosco, even
though it's still too early for even a waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Brothers, which also operates schools in Latin
America, is a teaching order that originated 300 years ago in
France. Observers say it is a sound group.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Lawless, president of the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, met
with Waters and sees the importance of keeping Catholic students in
the state after high school.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Catholic colleges now are in Los Angeles, San Diego,
San Francisco and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have open arms, and we should be encouraging it,''
Lawless said. ``That diversity is positive for Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   Local Catholic school officials also welcome a local Catholic
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives our graduates that opportunity to go to a university
without having to leave the state,'' said Sister Joan Fitzgerald,
principal of Xavier College Preparatory in Phoenix, a Catholic high
school. ``It will enrich the whole education system.''
</P>
<P>
   Remi McLean's 13-year-old daughter, Brianna Vasquez, is an
incoming Xavier freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see her stay here (after high school),''
McLean said. ``We believe values and morals should be adjacent to
your regular learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Brianna likes the idea, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could live in the dorms and still be close to my family and
carry on my beliefs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Kim Joyce is thinking about college for her 2-year-old
daughter, who will go to a Catholic elementary school when the time
comes and then, hopefully, a Catholic university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a Catholic education is very important,'' the Phoenix
resident said. ``It provides a little bit of shelter from
society.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kelly.Pearce(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8979. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
