<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL SIGNING BOOSTS VERO'S CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The city of Vero Beach, Fla., and Indian River
County took an enormous, and possibly final, step in keeping the
Los Angeles Dodgers in Dodgertown for the next 20 years thanks to
the long-awaited signature of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush on a funding
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed a bill late Thursday that will allocate between $7
and $8 million toward the effort to keep the Dodgers'
spring-training site in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach and Indian River County already had secured $12.5
million, boosting the financial package to about $20 million, which
should be enough to keep the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials low-keyed Bush signing the bill because they
are also negotiating with Las Vegas officials about a four- to
six-team spring-training complex, but the increased funding puts
Florida in a favorable position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of relief but also excitement, for Dodgertown
and all the facilities in Florida,'' Dodgers vice president Derrick
Hall said. ``It enables us to pursue our negotiations more speedily
with the city and county (in Florida) and Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said a soft deadline of mid-June was in place to make a
final decision. Dodgers officials will travel to Florida next week
to meet with city and county officials to discuss a deal, which is
expected to be for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision needs to be made quickly because of stipulations
in the newly signed bill. A private enterprise isn't eligible for
the funding through the bill, so Indian River County needs to buy
the land from the Dodgers before they can apply for the money. The
application deadline is Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are the only major-league club that owns its spring-
training facility, but under a proposed agreement with the Florida
municipalities, the land would be bought by Indian River County.
The Dodgers are also asking for renovations to the complex, where
the Dodgers have trained since 1948. Among the improvements are the
additions of practice fields and a better weight facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to move ahead and start going quickly,'' said
Dodgertown managing director Craig Callan. ``We need to look at
Indian River County and Vero Beach and Las Vegas. And Vegas is
still involved. Vegas is still a viable contender with Indian River
County and Vero Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also relief since Bush decided not to fund a similar
bill last year that would have provided $7.5 million in funding. In
the months after that, several Dodgers officials said the
organization would have signed a long-term deal with Vero Beach and
Indian River County if Bush funded that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas officials are expected to make their offer to the
Dodgers, and the five other teams interested in moving there, by
the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   However, given the Dodgers' history at Dodgertown and managing
general partner and CEO Bob Daly's affinity for it, Las Vegas will
have to knock the Dodgers over to lure the organization to the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can Florida offer an economically attractive package
with the additional funding, but Las Vegas has other elements
working against it. The Dodgers are concerned about the gaming
factor and the weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Studies indicate the weather is cooler than that in Florida
during the spring-training months, and the heat becomes an issue
for players in extended spring training and for minor leaguers in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Brown OK: Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said
right-hander Kevin Brown's injured right shin wouldn't keep the
staff ace from making his Monday start in Texas. Brown had
stiffness in the leg Thursday but no other problems after getting
hit with a line drive in his Wednesday start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
