<HEADLINE>
FALLING STAR: SWAYZE MAKES FORCED LANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS AND JUDI VILLA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT VALLEY - Actor Patrick Swayze was piloting a
twin-engine Cessna that made an emergency landing Thursday on a
half-mile-long paved road in an undeveloped subdivision near here,
the Federal Aviation Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   He was not seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Swayze, who was flying with his two dogs, brought the plane down
along Buckshot Road, shearing off part of his right wing on a
street light and felling a stop sign before he apparently taxied
the plane into a dirt lot, said John Bolstad, sales manager at the
Mingus West subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Swayze made a series of sharp turns and narrowly
missed several electrical cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed if he was a foot lower, he would have hung
himself,'' said Marty Zalucki, who was working at a con struction
site about a mile from the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Swayze walked away from the plane and hitch-hiked a ride from a
motorist on Arizona 89A, Prescott Valley police Sgt. P.J. Janik
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was ``shaken up but not injured,'' said John Clabes, an FAA
spokesman in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Clabes said Swayze, 47, was flying on instruments from Van Nuys,
Calif., to Las Vegas, a town near Santa Fe, N.M., when he
disappeared from radar and radio contact about 11 a.m. He was
flying at 13,000 feet and was 38 miles northeast of Flagstaff at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Janik said the plane experienced a pressurization problem that
forced Swayze to land. When FAA authorities lost contact with the
plane, they notified Prescott area law enforcement agencies, who
first found the plane in the dirt. Two homes were under
construction on the two-lane street, but neither was hit, Bolstad
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Road is off Arizona 89A, on the eastern outskirts of
Prescott Valley, near Mingus Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 feet of the plane's right wing was shorn off, but its
three wheels were still intact, chalk blocks placed behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fabulous landing job,'' said Chuck Skowronek, a
former pilot and nearby resident. ``He was fortunate to have that
street there. To put a plane that size in that space available says
a lot about his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd fly with him anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Janik said Swayze called the FAA from a private residence in the
Prescott area to report the landing. FAA officials were at the
scene Thursday; the plane was to be dismantled and brought to
Phoenix today.
</P>
<P>
   A steady stream of gawkers also pulled up to the scene
throughout the evening. As many as 10 cars arrived each minute to
check out the plane and inquire whether anyone knew where Swayze
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very quiet here, and you rarely hear anything. And when
something like this happens, it makes it more exciting,'' said Kory
Reuna, who moved to the area about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Swayze is best known for the 1987 film`` Dirty Dancing'' and the
1990 film ``Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   He was ``the talk of the town'' Thursday, said Robert Hamill,
owner of Robert's Marketplace, about six miles from the landing
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking for Patrick Swayze,'' Hamill said. ``It's
crazy around here.'' &QL; 
Reporters David Madrid and Kristin Koch contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
