A2586 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PARKS-DIVERTED-LADN     06-02 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-DIVERTED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE FUNDS SHIFTED AMONG L.A.'S PARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A state Senate budget subcommittee has taken $8.75
million promised for parkland in the Greater San Fernando Valley
and shifted it to inner-city parks and other projects from South
Pasadena to Maywood.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate action has infuriated backers of Propositions 12 and
13, but when the Daily News challenged the move, state Sen. Tom
Hayden, a member of the committee that shifted the funds, said it
was a ``mistake'' and would be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Unconvinced, Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who
campaigned for the $2.1 billion parks bond approved in March, said
he's concerned about the fate of the Valley's share.
</P>
<P>
   ``How this got siphoned off is quite a mystery,'' Yaroslavsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ought to know what is going on so they can keep an eye
on this. Unless you are doggedly watching every move the
bureaucrats make up there, you can find yourself with your pockets
picked.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved the proposition after being told the money was
earmarked for the Santa Monica Mountains and the Rim of the Valley
Trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you tell people if they vote yes on Proposition 12,
they'll get $35 million for the Santa Monica Mountains Conservancy
and Rim of the Valley, you owe it to them, legally and morally, to
keep your word,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Valley's share was shifted during a budget
subcommittee hearing May 22, when $5 million of the $24 million
appropriated for the conservancy was set aside for the Arroyo
Seco-Confluence Park, $1 million for the Compton-Slauson Natural
Park, $2.5 million for the city of Maywood's Los Angeles River
Parkway and $250,000 for a South Pasadena Park. The committee
deferred the remaining $11 million that is earmarked for the
conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said he has assured Yaroslavsky the mistakes will be
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake made at the staff level against my explicit
memo to the staff,'' said Hayden. ``I'm not asking anybody for any
special understanding, but these staff are up for 100 hours
straight putting together the final subcommittee reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said the Conference Committee on the Budget will be asked
to fix the mistakes when it meets over the next two weeks. ``The
two houses have to reconcile the different versions of the budget
in the Conference Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other projects, they also will receive funding from
other parts of Proposition 12, Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, is concerned about
the funding mix-up because much of the Valley project is within his
district, said his spokesman, Paul Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker is a supporter of the conservancy, and the Rim of
the Valley Trail, and he is working to ensure the legislative plan
for park expenditures reflects the Valley's needs as well as the
rest of the needs of the state,'' Hefner said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Subcommittee Chairman Byron Sher, D-Redwood City, said
the projects were ``incorrectly charged.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're correcting that as the budget moves forward,'' Sher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, the author of
the park bond, said he understands that mistakes are made. ``They
are trying to balance the budget items in the different categories
so they sometimes identify a pot of money that is not the
appropriate pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Edmiston, executive director of the Santa Monica
Mountains Conservancy, blamed the mistakes on a ``lot of
confusion'' at the subcommittee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was anything intentional. I'm 100 percent
sure these things will get changed. If things are different next
week, I'll be the first one to say we've got a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Safe Neighborhood Parks, Clean Water, Clean Air and Coastal
Protection Bond Act of 2000 -- or Proposition 12 -- is supposed to
invest in neighborhood parks and state parks, coastal beaches and
scenic areas.
</P>
<P>
   The $35 million for the conservancy was intended to buy land in
the conservancy zone and for the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to ring the San Fernando Valley with a string of parks,''
Edmiston said. ``We call it the emerald necklace around the San
Fernando Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy has received hundreds of nominations for land
acquisitions and other uses of the money. The conservancy is
expected to decide this month which ones are the most important,
said Rorie Skei, deputy director for natural resources and planning
at the conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potential purchases include 1,700 acres in the Santa
Susana Mountains above Granada Hills and Chatsworth called the
Joughin Ranch, a key wildlife corridor linked to other public
lands.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy is also looking at the 6,000-acre Big Sky Ranch
between Moorpark and Simi Valley where ``Little House on the
Prairie'' was filmed, property along the unpaved portion of
Mulholland Drive, restoration of a portion of the Tujunga Wash in
the Van Nuys area and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   The money will also be used to buy land to help complete the Rim
of the Valley Trail, a trail that when completed would run along
the Santa Monica, Santa Susana, Angeles and San Gabriel mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the trail and parks can be found on the
Internet at www.smmc.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Marco Antonio Firebaugh, D-Cudahy, said he learned
recently that the subcommittee had ``inadvertently'' funded the
Maywood River Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the action taken in the Senate was technically in
error in the sense that they inadvertently funded it out of a pot
of money that can't be spent on Maywood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the $2.5 million for his district's park will be taken
out of the Murray-Hayden Urban Parks portion of the bond so the
conservancy will get its full $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
