r s BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX     06-02 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL SCORES TWICE AS STARS EVEN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Dallas Stars captain Derian Hatcher
waited by his locker for Game 2 to begin, surrounded by silence.
Only occasional sounds invaded an otherwise quiet locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it was more quiet than normal,'' Hatcher said.
``I guess everybody had their own things to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Each player waded through his own thoughts about what he
personally could do to make up for the collective embarrassment
that had been Game 1. The Stars then went out and did exactly that
in a 2-1 victory against the New Jersey Devils on Thursday night in
Game 2 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The victory not only made up for the humiliating 7-3 loss in
Game 1, but allowed the Stars to return to Dallas with the split
they originally came to Jersey in search of.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are simple. Stars winger Brett Hull did what he does
best, scoring, not once, but twice. Stars goalie Ed Belfour bounced
back from his worst performance of the playoffs with one of his
best. And mostly, the Stars did what they do best: Dust themselves
off after a butt-kicking.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 9-0 after their past nine playoff losses,
including 6-0 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to be embarrassed in the Stanley Cup Finals when
everybody is watching,'' Stars forward Guy Carbonneau said. ``We
got our butt kicked the first game. Everybody knew it. We talked
about it. We wanted to come back tonight and play a lot better.
This team seems to be in trouble, and we come out of it and play a
great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Great will probably be debated by those in the NHL who prefer
more scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars played the game they need to play if they're going
to repeat as Stanley Cup champions. They were patient. They clogged
up the neutral zone. They negated the Devils' speed. They didn't
take a lot of chances. They scored on the ones they had.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, they got a great game from their goalie.
</P>
<P>
   They proved in Game 1 they're in a heap of trouble when they
don't. Belfour stopped only 12 of the 18 Devils shots in the series
opener after a prescription decongestant he took left him feeling
lightheaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something you try and do is forget about nights when you don't
have such a good night,'' Belfour said. ``It's definitely hard, but
I didn't have any problems sleeping. I knew it wasn't a good night
for myself. It's happened to me before, and I knew what to do to
get ready for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   And ready he was.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stopped 27 of the Devils' 28 shots, making a number of
spectacular saves to keep the Stars in the game until Hull scored
his game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Belfour) was a step late in the first game,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``But he was much more energized tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that surprise you?'' Hatcher asked. ``I'm not surprised
at all. I don't think anyone should be surprised. He's been that
way all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, because Hull has played exactly like he didn't all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off his worst regular season in terms of goals, Hull has
had his best postseason in that regard. He just keeps scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had talked of the importance of having a strong,
energetic start, and Hull obliged. His snap wrist shot beat Martin
Brodeur high, glove side, at 4:25 of the first period after Mike
Modano had done the dirty work to pry the puck free from along the
boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars needed a game-winner, and Hull obliged on that, too.
He deflected a shot by Jere Lehtinen with four minutes and 16
seconds remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say, `They don't make $6-7 million a year for
nothing,''' Carbonneau said. ``They have a knack to score the big
goals. They seem to be out of the game for 56 minutes then reappear
and score the big goals. That's something you can't teach.
Obviously, Brett and Mike have that knack.''
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson said that he thought Lehtinen had
been offside for Hull's winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey blamed itself for losing Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played absolutely terrible, and we still had our chances to
win the game,'' Devils forward John Madden said. ``We turned the
puck over time and time again, and it wasn't just one line. It was
every line.''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey looked to be in good shape after responding almost
immediately to Hull's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Like in any series, tempers soon flared, leading to a couple of
coincidental minors. Not good for Dallas. Four-on-four proved once
again to be a burr in the Stars' behinds as New Jersey forward
Alexander Mogilny answered Dallas' early goal with his shot at
12:42 of the first period. His wrister beat Belfour high, glove
side, on a four-on-four.
</P>
<P>
   Only Dallas didn't panic, retreating quickly to the game that
some would call boring but the Stars can count on to win. They
stuck with it, not one or two players, but all 20, to get
themselves to late in the third period with the score still tied.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and Modano simply put the icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and I talked,'' Hull said. ``Things had to change, and
everybody pulled up their pants and went at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the Finals are tied. The 7-3 loss is gone,
although not quite forgotten. They were tested, slapped in the face
they said, and they responded the way a winner should.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about being an athlete,'' Stars winger Blake Sloan
said. ``If someone punches you in the face, you got to dust
yourself off, get back up, realize it's a new day, a new
opportunity. We try to, what's that phrase, `''carpe diem''.' '' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
