r f BC-IPOS-MARKET-LADN     06-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPOS-MARKET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPS DELAYED BY INSTABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ Despite a couple of good days of recovery, the
stock markets remain sharply lower than their March peaks, a
scenario that is putting the brakes on the market for stock
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   As stock prices drop, so does the number of proposed initial or
secondary offerings that actually go through.
</P>
<P>
   Three local companies are among those that have chosen to delay
or cancel their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Canoga Park-based Qualstar, which had made it as close to an IPO
as being placed on the weekly offering schedule, has now postponed
its offering, said David Menlow, president of IPOFinancial.com,
which tracks the IPO market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Qualstar, Westlake Village-based Rightstart.com
has withdrawn a planned IPO, and Camarillo-based Interlink
Electronics on Thursday withdrew a secondary stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many deals in the system waiting to come public
and too many of them will find out over the next few months they
have missed their opportunity,'' Menlow said. ``Many of them may
just find it's relatively impossible to get back in the market for
the near term.''
</P>
<P>
   The market's harshness, however, isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ultimately is a good thing because there's a culling
process that will shake out the deadwood,'' Menlow said.
</P>
<P>
   In Qualstar's case, the offering has not officially been
withdrawn, but it hasn't taken place despite being ready to price
for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, a company sets its IPO price the night before it goes
public.
</P>
<P>
   Qualstar has revised its price range downward from a $10 to $12
range to $7 to $9 and reduced the number of shares it plans to
issue from 3.25 million to 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the stock is being viewed ... as having a
problem,'' Menlow said. ``That is something that's difficult for
any stock to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   For Interlink Electronics, which filed its registration
statement when the company's stock was around $60 a share, a
secondary stock offering just isn't worth it anymore, Menlow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount they were expecting to raise at the price was close
to $150 million,'' Menlow said. ``When they say `due to market
conditions,' what they're really saying is `we really needed all of
the money.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's market price, Interlink's take would have been
closer to $55 million, Menlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials at Interlink were not available Thursday.
Officials at Qualstar declined to comment, citing Securities and
Exchange Commission restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, companies involved in stock offerings are prevented
from discussing the stock -- SEC rules require a silent period
before and after the offering.
</P>
<P>
   Rightstart.com's withdrawal is symptomatic of a broader loss of
interest in consumer-based e-commerce sites, Menlow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone that's trying to bring a deal into this space had
better do it in a very pristine fashion,'' Menlow said. ``We have a
very difficult market right now, and it's not nearly as forgiving
as it was a few months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are looking for top-tier underwriters, he said. Only
the big-name brokerages will do in this market. And a company had
better be healthy. Companies without actual products or revenue
streams are not so revered as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a buyer's market, there's no question about it,'' Menlow
said. ``The market wants the better deals and they've clearly
spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that withdraw their offerings lose more than the money
they would have raised selling the stock, said Allen Sussman, an
attorney with the law firm of Brobeck Phleger Harrison who
specializes in IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   The expenses of preparing and filing the documents required to
hold a stock offering are steep, typically more than $1 million,
Sussman said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is not recoverable once an IPO is withdrawn, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The further along a company gets in the IPO process before
withdrawing, the deeper the stigma, Sussman said. ``I've been
involved in deals where they've gone on the road and it hasn't
sold,'' he said, alluding to the road show company executives
typically engage in to drum up interest in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   A company that withdraws its registration statement can expect
to sit out for a while before it tries again, Sussman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common wisdom has been that you have to wait a good amount
of time -- usually at least a year -- in order to distance yourself
from the perception that you're somehow troubled or tainted,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that time period, the companies often pursue other options,
such as a purchase or securing private financing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
