<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, May 18.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Vologda, Russia) _ This is Russia's not-quite-open
secret: the crash of 1998, the great financial meltdown that wiped
out Russia's middle class and turned the Kremlin into a global
deadbeat, is over. The Kremlin casts it as real, if still shaky,
and its numbers look promising. By Michael Wines. (ART ADV: Graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-REFUGEES (Asmara) _ A few weeks ago, Abrehet Amdimeskel
was simply a student, who happened to be in English class when the
war with Ethiopia came to her town in southern Eritrea. Now, at 14,
she is the head of her uprooted household, caring for her
grandmother and four younger siblings in a small tent in a huge
refugee camp. The refugee crisis could make the food shortages in
Eritrea far worse. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-BIDS (Undated) _ When eBay, the Internet auction company,
suspended the seller and voided the sale of a vivid abstract
painting whose price shot from $.25 to $135,805 last month, his
offense had nothing to do with the authenticity of the painting.
Rather, Kenneth Walton had entered a bid of $4,500 on his own
offering _ a practice known as shill bidding that violates eBay's
rules _ on the second day of a 10-day auction, long before
speculation that the painting might be by the renowned painter
Richard Diebenkorn sent the price soaring. But an analysis of that
and other eBay art auctions reveals that the flourishing
cyberauction world faces a deeper problem: rings of shill-bidders
that may include self-bidding. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-PUENTE (New York) _ Bandleader and percussionist Tito
Puente, who rode to fame on the heels of the 1950s mambo craze and
for the next five decades helped define Latin jazz, has died. He
was 77. By Joyce Wadler.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STROKE-RECOVER (Undated) _ Using a new kind of stroke
rehabilitation therapy, scientists have shown for the first time
that the brain can be coaxed into reorganizing its circuitry so
that people can regain nearly full use of their paralyzed limbs in
just two to three weeks, even if the stroke happened years ago. The
rehabilitation, called constraint-induced-movement therapy,
involves immobilizing a good arm or leg so that the patient is
forced to use the paralyzed arm or leg for familiar tasks. By
Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-FUEL-ECONOMY (Detroit) _ A soon-to-be released government
report calculates that the average fuel economy of new family
vehicles has improved slightly in the 2000 model year, but the
numbers would look much worse if automakers had not begun producing
huge numbers of vehicles that can run on either gasoline or
ethanol. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVORS (Undated) _ Last summer, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be A
Millionaire'' turned the television world on its head by defying
every expectation and seizing huge audiences, eventually
catapulting ABC to overall network ratings leadership. Now a new
CBS series, about a group of people forced to live together in
primitive circumstances on an island off Borneo, has had a
similarly stunning start, and television executives are already
wondering whether it can do for CBS what ``Millionaire'' did for
ABC. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The market for
million-dollar homes in Florida and Texas has long been stimulated
by the fact that such houses appeal to one particular class of
wealthy people: those who are about to file for bankruptcy. Now
Congress is about to increase the appeal of such homes to rich
people who may not face imminent bankruptcy, but see it as a
possibility if they lose a big lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Advertisers and media magnates are
celebrating the concept of good fortune with a lengthening list of
products, publications and pitches centered on the word ``lucky.''
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
