<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-ON-BROADWAY (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: Presenting
difficult concepts is always risky for a playwright, but it is
particularly so in an era when audiences have been conditioned by
lowbrow entertainment to have their senses tickled but not to have
their brains massaged. But science and scientists have been onstage
all over the place this season. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TONY-AWARDS (New York) _ Unless there are some major surprises _
and there always are _ on Sunday night, Tony voters will declare
that Broadway's best musical is ``Contact,'' which many people say
is not a musical, and that its best play is ``Copenhagen,'' which
many people say they simply don't understand. Confused? You should
be. It has been that kind of year on Broadway, an odd mishmash of
daring new work and lukewarm fare that has left theater
professionals searching for a cohesive theme. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-IMPRESSIONISTS (Washington) _ ``The Impressionists at
Argenteuil'' at the National Gallery of Art, is the umpteenth
repackaging of an evergreen late-19th-century painting style. But
scolding this art for being popular is a cliche; better to give it
a fresh squint, admiring its manifest beauties but also suggesting
what made it daring in its day. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GREENWICH-VILLAGE (New York) _ Some time around 1910, a company
of malcontents, political radicals, writers, theater people and
artists began to settle in Greenwich Village and declare their
down-at-the-heels neighborhood a bohemia in the European mode.
Tracing the bohemian life below 14th Street. By Christine Stansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BAUHAUS-TEXTILES (New York) _ The Jewish Museum's illuminating,
densely packed survey of the life and art of Anni Albers, one of
the most significant members of Bauhaus Weaving Workshop, is part
art exhibition, part weaving seminar, part biography and altogether
fascinating. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MOMMA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Big Momma's House'': Raja
Gosnell, director; with Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Paul Giamatti.
Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Live Virgin'': Katrina
Bartoloti, director; with Bob Hoskins, Mena Suvari, Robert Loggia,
Gabriel Mann. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Running Free'': Sergei Bodrov,
director; with Chase Moore. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   THIRTEEN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Thirteen'': David Williams,
director. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOM-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Not so long ago, it would have
seemed preposterous for a serious scholar to bother writing a book
titled ``How to Read and Why,'' but in our digital, image-driven
age, the eminent teacher and critic Harold Bloom apparently feels
it is necessary to reiterate the reasons why we read. Reviewed by
Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Ron Wertheimer spotlights the weekend
television fare: Sunday on Showtime, ``Harlan County War.''
</P>
