<SLUG> BC-FARMERS-MALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBAN MALL WILL HOST FARMERS MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tapping into a growing trend in the San Fernando
Valley, The Westfield Shoppingtown Promenade in Woodland Hills will
host its first farmers market today.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers markets have been credited with helping local shopping
malls increase foot traffic and provide a boost in store sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Promenade market's target clientele will be workers from the
Warner Center area just blocks from the mall, organizers say. It
will start out with about 40 vendors, including artists and local
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   This week's market will last from 11:30 a.m. to 4:40 p.m., but
organizers say they may extend hours to 7 p.m. next week if there's
sufficient demand.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers markets have been popular at other local shopping
centers, including the Northridge Fashion Center, and The
Promenade's market manager, Jennifer McColm, said she expects the
weekly event will offer customers a change of pace from the workday
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a fast-paced community, especially one like the Warner
Center, (a farmers market) slows the pace down and takes you back
in time a little bit to when things were easier,'' McColm said.
</P>
<P>
   McColm -- a Bell Canyon resident, writer and mother of three --
said customers from her 6-month-old Westlake Village market asked
her to open a location near the Warner Center area. And considering
the interest from customers and vendors, she said, The Promenade
market should do well.
</P>
<P>
   Mall officials said they believe the market will complement the
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're popping up all over the place, so we thought we would
try it,'' said Karla Hubbell, general manager for The Promenade.
``It's a nice amenity for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers markets can also bring new customers to shopping
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Char, marketing director for the Northridge Fashion Center,
said his mall's year-old Farmers' Market and Family Festival has
boosted foot traffic and store sales at the center. The Wednesday
evening market includes about 30 farmers and 30 to 40 food vendors,
crafts sellers and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our foot traffic in April was up 36 percent over April '99,''
Char said. ``I'm sure the market had a lot to do with that
number.''
</P>
<P>
   The Promenade's market will be held in the parking lot at
Topanga Canyon Boulevard and Erwin Street.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
