<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE CLICKS, BUT ONLY BECAUSE BELFOUR DOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This one looked very familiar. This one
was the Stars doing what the Stars do, as opposed to that mile-long
list of whatever the heck that was 48 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And what the Stars do best is play positional, defensive hockey,
which some call boring. And this Stanley Cup Finals' Game 2 last
night did drag at times, which meant the strategy was working well.
</P>
<P>
   And what boring hockey does, based on strong positional play, is
force the opposition to press and ponder, leading to mistakes the
Stars hope to pounce on, particularly in that area of every man's
land known as the neutral zone.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, they pounced last night. Pounced twice with Brett
Hull, who scored early in the first period and late in the third
period, providing a 2-1 victory that gave this series a completely
different spin.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Devils won't sweep, which seemed to be a prominent New
York media theme after that 7-3 trashing of the Stars in Game 1.
The next stop is Reunion Arena for two games. Buckle up everyone,
particularly you New Jersey visitors. The bull ride has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   But ...
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are where they now are in this series, and where they
are in the playoffs, and where they are in the NHL's big picture _
meaning defending Stanley Cup champs _ because of one reason.
</P>
<P>
   That reason is Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   You can take all the positional defensive schemes, and all the
scoring heroics of a Hull throughout the playoffs, and all of it
fits into a certain pattern. None of it works, however, without
Belfour providing the ... well, the medication.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie was feeling much better last night, not drowsy or anything
from a bad dose of decongestant for a cold.
</P>
<P>
   When all's well with Eddie, then all's well with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Facing 28 shots, with about eight of them from right there on
his front porch, Belfour left the Devils sick and drowsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people have made a big deal of this,'' said
coach Ken Hitchcock, meaning Belfour revealing after the Game 1
beating that his medication had gone sour on him.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hitchcock, Belfour's illness went back to Game 7
against the Avalanche. His goalie was feeling so lousy the Stars
almost left him at home for a couple of days, instead of arriving
here with the team on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked up to him after the skate this morning, asked how he
felt, and Eddie's answer was `good,' '' Hitchcock said. ``I think
anybody who knows what it's like to play goal understands that if
you don't have energy and you are a step late, you are going to get
scored on. He was a step late in that first game, but he was much
more energized today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils felt that Belfour energy last night. And it drained
them. The Devils walked out of Continental Airlines' Arena thinking
they had played the stronger game, and at least as far as good
scoring chances went, they would certainly be right.
</P>
<P>
   But the good chances stopped at Belfour. At one point, midway
through the third period in a 1-1 game, New Jersey's Randy McKay
screamed something unprintable after Belfour had stoned him from
right in front. Eddie got McKay twice in the third period when
McKay only had the goalie to beat. It was the same with Claude
Lemieux, who also thought he had the go-ahead goal in his cross
hairs _ twice in the final period _ only to have Belfour stop the
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie at his best again is a worry the Devils hadn't considered
after such easy pickings in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had anything to prove tonight; I just
tried to forget about \RGame 1\S,'' said Belfour, who sounded like
an excuse-maker when he mentioned the ``drowsy'' stuff after the
Tuesday night beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew I didn't feel well for the first game, and I knew I
felt a lot better for this game,'' added Belfour with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 followed the same trend Belfour and the Stars have used
throughout the playoffs. Play lousy _ so lousy there is no logical
explanation _ and then rebound in the next game. The only question
about rebounding last night was that Game 1 had reached the lowest
postseason point for this team in the past two playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, however, allowed the U-turn to happen, and the Stars'
commitment to defensive positioning followed his lead.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Devils were trigger-happy in this one, probably
an unavoidable reaction to the scoring-at-will fun of Game 1. The
good shots on Belfour mainly resulted from strong forechecking by
New Jersey. Almost no offensive threat came as a result of battles
won in the neutral zone or at the Stars' blue line. This, of
course, was a major change from Game 1 when the Devils used
superior speed to turn those areas into the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils kept trying the puck-rush again last night from
center ice, and were repeatedly turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had four men across the blue line and we continually
wanted to carry the puck in there,'' Devils' coach Larry Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Devils' took the medicine, while Eddie felt just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
