r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-02 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL DISCOVERS SCORING TOUCH AT RIGHT TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Well, dad, how is he doing now?
</P>
<P>
   By his own silent admission, Brett Hull had a bleak regular
season. Between a goal drought as he pursued his famous father and
a plus-minus tattoo that seemed to grow like the national debt, the
Dallas Stars' most prolific career goal scorer languished in his
mediocre results.
</P>
<P>
   But blessed be the mute. In the playoffs, Hull has taught us,
they shall have plenty to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hull's two goals, including the game-winner with 4:16 to
play, that breathed new life into the defending champion Stars on
Thursday night at Continental Airlines Arena. After the schoolyard
spanking that the New Jersey Devils had administered Tuesday night,
the Stars' 2-1 victory was yet another example of this team's
uncanny ability to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   And the postseason Lazarus of the bunch has to be Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things weren't going good the whole season,'' Hull said after
the series-knotting victory. ``But now things are.''
</P>
<P>
   In 79 regular-season games, Hull scored the fewest goals (24) of
his 15-year NHL career. His quest to equal dad Bobby Hull's mark of
610 career goals seemed to linger over several major American and
Canadian holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the playoffs, he no longer chases his father. The
attainable goal is named Conn Smythe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so focused on making a change from the way things were
in the regular season,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It was a very
difficult regular season for Brett Hull.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hull was on the ice during the season, the Stars were
minus-21. The number branded Hull as a noncontributor.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock was quick to remind Thursday night that that
wasn't necessarily the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seemed to go wrong,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think he
was on the ice for 11 or 12 empty-net goals against.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's just made so many believers of all of us in the
playoffs. It's great to see.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight months, Stars watchers finally see it again, too.
</P>
<P>
   He shoots, he scores. It is why Brett Hull wears a Stars jersey
in the first place. It is what Bobby Hull's kid does best.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, it was a good time for teammate Mike Keane
to break out the cap, the navy blue ballcap with ``Shut Up Hull''
stitched onto it. Keane first broke it out when Hull was in the
midst of his longest season scoring drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we have to play,'' Keane said, reciting the
Stars' ode to selfless teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before, but our star players deserve a lot of
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   What Keane was lauding is how Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk and
Hull _ especially Hull _ have sacrificed the scoring flash and Ice
Capades dash to play at both ends of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Hull is no longer any one-trick pony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hully deserves a lot of credit,'' Hitchcock said.
``It's tough when you're an older player, when you've played when
the league was a little more wide open. It's a difficult decision
that you have to make in your career when you know that the game is
so closed off now. There's not a lot of open space. You've got to
be able to go out and fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Hull has fought more tenaciously and found his room
to blossom in this postseason. With his two goals Thursday night,
he remains the NHL playoffs' leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hull is prepared to fight for it now,'' Hitchcock said. ``He
is a committed guy. He's committed to this team. He's committed to
the organization. He deserves an awful lot of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hull's first goal, a huge weight seemed to lift off the
defending champs' shoulders. It came on the Stars' first shot of
the night and spoke volumes. New Jersey goaltender Martin Brodeur
would not be a stone wall on this night.
</P>
<P>
   On his second one, Hull said, ``I just threw my stick out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you're hot, you're hot. The puck finds you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just keep hoping they do,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   In the winners' locker room Thursday night, they talked about
pride. They talked about resurrection. They talked about how it
stung after the 7-3 embarrassment in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the kinds of things that kept Brett Hull so
silent for much of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   As Keane, wearing his cap, said, ``I hope he's here talking till
three in the morning.''
nn
</P>
