<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-HOME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS LOSE HOME ADVANTAGE WITH GAME 2 LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Seven goals. Ten goals. Twelve goals.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter what the New Jersey Devils did in Game 1 of
the Stanley Cup Finals or how many goals they scored on Ed Belfour.
What the Devils didn't do in Game 2 was hold on to the
ever-precious home-ice advantage, and as the two teams return to
Dallas, the only numbers that really matter are 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Translation? Advantage Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you can go two games up on anybody and don't it's an
opportunity missed,'' New Jersey center John Madden said. ``Now
we've gotta do this the hard way. We knew we weren't going to win
this thing in four straight, but we had all intentions of taking
the first two games.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't, and that could turn out to be bigger than the
optimistic Devils realize.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, after all, are a league-best 9-1 at home during the
2000 playoffs, the only loss coming to Colorado in Game 1 of the
Western Conference Finals. Dallas has also outscored its postseason
opponents by a 26-12 margin in Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And last night, when the Devils handed the Stars a turnover that
resulted in the game-winning goal by Brett Hull, they also handed
the Stars home-ice advantage. All the Stars have to do is win every
home game and the Cup stays in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was certainly there for us,'' Devils defenseman Ken
Daneyko said. ``That's the disappointing part. We had opportunities
to win but we had too many defensive mistakes. There's a fine line
there between winning and losing.''
</P>
<P>
   That fine line just became a tightrope for the Devils, who
seemed to have the world in their hands after the 7-3 blowout in
Game 1. They kept saying the score of the opener didn't matter
unless they took care of things in Game 2. They knew all along
Belfour was going to play better. And they knew there would be no
shooting gallery last night.
</P>
<P>
   They also knew they had to play better against a Stars team that
would obviously be better. And the Devils didn't.
</P>
<P>
   So for the Devils, the highs of Game 1 become the lows of Game
2. They just have to hope it's not a repeat of the Eastern
Conference Finals, when they won Game 1 against Philadelphia only
to lose the next three games and fall behind 3-1. Because against
the Stars, there might not be a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as they have to feel good about themselves, we don't
feel very good about ourselves because we didn't show them our best
game,'' Devils coach Larry Robinson said. ``So now we are 1-1. They
didn't play their best game; we didn't play our best game. So we
are going back to Dallas to see who is the best when we both play
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
