<HEADLINE>
LITTLE THINGS BECAME BIG WIN FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The NHL has awards for seemingly every
statistic it tracks. There is, however, no Jane M. Doe Little
Things Award for the team or player who does all the minutia _
checking, faceoffs, digging pucks _ better than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   If there were such a piece of hardware, the Stars would have won
it Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our game,'' Stars winger Blake Sloan said, ``is doing
those little things.''
</P>
<P>
   After not doing little things so well in Game 1, the Stars made
sure that lines one through four covered every angle, and it paid
off in a 2-1 victory against New Jersey in Game 2 of the Stanley
Cup Finals on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was winning the faceoffs when they had to, digging
out pucks, creating chances, clearing pucks out of the defensive
zone or beating the Devils to neutral-zone pucks, the Stars'
sometimes faceless players did all the things that got them to this
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's definitely a contributing factor,'' Sloan said.
``If you eliminate those things from the game, you might be looking
at a different score.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Joe Nieuwendyk's line didn't score. It didn't allow
one, either. Neither Jon Sim nor Sloan created waves of chances,
but they combined for five hits and were both primary reasons why
the Devils never scored in the second period despite outshooting
the Stars, 17-10, in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Stars junked their wide-open style in Game 1
that resulted in a 7-3 defeat. Thursday night, they played more of
their conservative style that often bores fans but wins games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win faceoffs, that's puck possession, and that's half
the battle of carrying the puck around,'' Stars winger Mike Keane
said. ``Our centers did a great job tonight controlling the puck
and getting the pucks back. Once again, we had four strong lines
going.''
</P>
<P>
   They blocked 13 shots, won 31 of 63 faceoffs, dished out 31 hits
and absorbed the same amount and had 23 takeaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last game, we got caught trying to play an easy game,''
Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``We got beat off the wall, beat
in front of our net. That's what we talked about after Game 1 and
(Wednesday) in our meeting. Tonight, it showed a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have any easy pucks in the neutral zone, they
didn't hit that blue-line with a lot of speed too often and every
time they did they had to battle with one guy and (another) guy was
coming back so they didn't have much time to make their plays.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils made plays, they were quickly shut down, cleared
out of the zone or stopped by Stars goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   To win the Cup, the Stars likely must continue to excel in the
sometimes invisible-to-the-naked-eye tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's going to come down to,'' Stars captain Derian
Hatcher said, ``is all the little things.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
