<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE MOVE BY MOGILNY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. Think Alexander Mogilny's first-period
step around Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk, which left Mogilny
one-on-one with Ed Belfour and resulted in a goal, was a great move
by the Devils? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well it never would have happened without a big move by the
Devils' front office this spring. Every team tries to make a great
addition near the trade deadline that will spark a deep postseason
run, and New Jersey might have made the best when it traded Brendan
Morrison and Denis Pederson to Vancouver on March 14 to get
Mogilny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the postseason, Mogilny has been the man mentioned
when anyone speaks of New Jersey's more potent offense. He might
have been forgotten after Game 1 because of the great play by the
first line of Jason Arnott, Petr Sykora and Patrik Elias, but he
showed last night he's still dangerous in the open ice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And should the Devils get him and that first line going at the
same time, they could give the Stars' stifling defense a big test
for the rest of the series. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:End of a streak &QL; 
 &LR; agatea:Last night's 2-1 loss was the first in Stanley Cup Finals
competition for New Jersey goaltender Martin Brodeur. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was with the Devils when they swept Detroit in 1995, and
he's now 5-1 in Finals games. His career playoff record is 47-32. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Case for defense &QL; 
To no one's surprise, Devils coach Larry Robinson said he did not
believe the 10 combined goals scored in Game 1 would be indicative
of the rest of the series. Well, he was right. Game 2 was a titanic
defensive struggle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Each game is a series in itself, and so once that game is over
with, let's forget about it and go on to the next one,'' Robinson
said. ``We have to be prepared to meet a Dallas team at its
best.'' &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Stevens' milestone &QL; 
Devils defenseman Scott Stevens notched his 100th career playoff
point with his first-period assist on Alexander Mogilny's goal that
tied the score 1-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who is being regarded as the Devils' playoff MVP if
they win the Stanley Cup, has 10 points (three goals, seven
assists) in the playoffs. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:Open Devil denied &QL; 
Devils winger Randy McKay had three solid scoring opportunities
squashed by Stars goalie Ed Belfour. Two came in the second period,
and a golden chance got away with a little more than 13 minutes
left in the third period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The play started with Stars center Guy Carbonneau's winning the
draw against John Madden to the left of Belfour, but the puck
squirted into the slot. McKay was all alone, but he couldn't get
off a strong shot, and Belfour made the save. Had McKay been a
left-handed shot, he might have gotten more on it. &QL; 
\Nsubheds:The kid is back &QL; 
New Jersey center Scott Gomez broke a streak of seven games without
a point with his assist on Alexander Mogilny's first period goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, a finalist for the Calder Trophy (league's top rookie),
last registered a point on May 16, in Game 2 of the Eastern
Conference Finals. In that game, a 4-3 loss to Philadelphia, Gomez
had a goal and an assist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by staff writers Jeff Caplan, J. Douglas Foster and Mac
Engel. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
