<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WIN SECOND ROUND IN BATTLE OF TOP LINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils and Stars are hunkering down
for a battle of whatever you can do, I can do better.
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson initiated the matchup of top-line
supremacy by pitting center Jason Arnott, Petr Sykora and Patrik
Elias against Stars center Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Two games down, the lines have gone tit-for-tat, and Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock is apparently ready to let this series come down to a
battle of big guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it yesterday. We made the decision that our
line is going to play against Jason's the rest of the series,''
Modano said. ``He \RRobinson\S didn't really seem too interested in
getting away from that \Rlast night\S with the last change. We were
a little more responsible with the matchup. It is something that we
didn't have in Game 1, but I think that will be the way it is the
rest of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   With the advantage of last change, Hitchcock could change the
matchup when the Stars return home for Games 3 and 4 beginning
Saturday. That apparently won't be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Awakened by a Game 1 in which the Devils' line tattooed Modano
and mates for four goals and 11 points, the Modano line retaliated
with suffocating defense and two Brett Hull goals for a 2-1 victory
in Game 2 at sold-out Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Arnott line was held scoreless and was a minus-2, victimized
on both Hull goals, the game-winner coming at the 15:44 mark of the
third period on a redirect on Lehtinen's shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a specific job to do,'' Hitchcock said, ``and they
got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock started the line the way it finished Game 1, with
Lehtinen, a two-time Selke Trophy winner as the league's top
defensive forward, playing left wing in place of rookie Brenden
Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's game-winner was a result of hard work. The Stars got the
turn over, Lehtinen put the puck on net and Hull redirected it past
Devils goalie Martin Brodeur. Hull's first-period goal, which put
the Stars up 1-0, was again set up by outworking the Devils' top
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano can create his own space out there,'' Robinson said.
``He is such a skilled player when he gets the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen and Modano dug the puck out of the corner. Modano
gained possession and fed Hull, who seemed to lurk into the right
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal was just a lot of hard work by Jere and Mike as
usual,'' Hull said. ``I was just trying to stay in good position as
the third man. Mike got it to me, and I just hurled it and shot it
as quick and hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arnott line still managed to throw 10 shots on Stars goalie
Ed Belfour, butits space was severely limited compared to Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we talked about was our quickness and our position as far
as defensively in our own zone,'' Modano said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
