<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BELFOUR-REBOUND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR REBOUNDS IN STYLE AFTER GAME 1 MISERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Goalie Ed Belfour was feeling a lot
better Thursday night and so were the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 of the Stanley Cup Finals was just what the doctor
ordered for the Stars. Belfour, with a little help from his
friends, saved 27 of 28 shots as Dallas rebounded with a 2-1
victory against the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had to (prove anything),'' Belfour said.
``I knew I didn't feel good the first game. I just tried to forget
about it and get ready for tonight and prepare the same way and
just go out there and try to do my best. I feel a lot better today,
a lot stronger definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour allowed six goals on 18 shots before being pulled in the
third period of the Stars' 7-3 loss Tuesday night. He blamed his
poor performance on a decongestant prescribed for cold symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, there were no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something you try and do is forget about nights when you don't
have such a good night,'' Belfour said. ``You do the best you can
to just try and forget about it. It's definitely hard, but I didn't
have any problems sleeping. I knew it wasn't a good night for
myself. That's happened to me before, and I knew what to do to get
ready for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was back to normal in Game 2. In his past nine starts
after a loss, Belfour is 9-0 and has allowed less than two goals
per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was anyone in here concerned with Eddie,''
Stars forward Kirk Muller said. ``You know he's human, and we
didn't play well in front of him the other night. Everyone looks at
Eddie, but we have to play better for him, and we did (Thursday
night). He responded like he has all year. We felt like we let him
down the other night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars made it up to Belfour on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Either defenseman Darryl Sydor or his defensive partner, Sergei
Zubov, were on the ice for all 10 goals in Game 1. They had two
hits and three shots Thursday night, and neither was on the ice for
the Devils' only goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 1 was a big slap in the face,'' Sydor said. ``We talked
to each other. We told each other we need to pick it up
defensively, and I think it was a little better. Obviously, I think
it was a lot better than Game 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was feeling like himself again Thursday night. He said
he did not take any medication before Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot stronger,'' Belfour said. ``I felt a lot better.
Naturally, I saw the puck move well.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 of the third period, Belfour dropped his stick when he
left the crease to try to clear a shot by Claude Lemieux. It's the
only thing he lost all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to poke the puck, and I dropped my stick and when I
tried to cover, obviously, I was way behind on the play,'' Belfour
said. ``They got it back to the point there, and I just tried to
get back to the net as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was back in a big way in Game 2, and so were the Stars,
who come home with the series even at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Eddie was going to bounce back,'' Stars forward Mike
Keane said. ``We had no concern with Eddie. We know he is very
strong. We know he is a very proud person. If we want to win, we
have to have him playing good hockey.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
