<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' LANGENBRUNNER A SCRATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner was a
scratch last night as he continues suffering from a sprained right
knee. He has now missed four consecutive games dating to Game 5 of
the Western Conference Finals against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is better,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``But he's not
a player.'' Sloan sighting Stars winger Blake Sloan played for the
first time in the Stanley Cup Finals last night, moving Grant
Marshall out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was put on the line with Guy Carbonneau and Kirk Muller
and played 10 minutes, 17 seconds on 17 shifts. He had one hit and
one penalty for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan hadn't played since Game 6 at Colorado of the Western
Conference Finals. Struggles continue The Stars have struggled all
season on four-on-four situations, and it bit them again last
night. With Devils defenseman Brian Rafalski and Stars winger Blake
Sloan in the penalty box for roughing, the Devils' Alexander
Mogilny used his speed to tie the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up the loose puck, skated deep into the Stars' zone
and outskated Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk to the slot.
Mogilny beat Belfour high to the glove side at the 12:42 mark of
the first period. Penalty kill is back The Stars' penalty kill is
back at the high level it was at during the regular season. They
killed two more Devils power plays last night and have killed 22 of
the past 23 penalties.
</P>
<P>
   For the playoffs, they have killed 81 of 92 penalties. Hull
milestone Stars winger Brett Hull's playoff-leading 10th goal early
in the first period last night was No. 86 of his career, moving him
out of a fifth-place tie with former New York Islanders forward
Mike Bossy on the all-time playoff goals-scored list. He added No.
87, the game-winner, late in the third period. The game-winner tied
him with his father for sixth all-time with 15 career multi-goal
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Anderson (93), Jari Kurri (106), Mark Messier (109) and
Wayne Gretzky (122) rank ahead of Hull. Feeling good Stars
defenseman Derian Hatcher played with a hyperextended right knee.
He had three shots and two hits and survived a nasty check from
Jason Arnott at 4:23 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all right,'' said Hatcher, who was injured in the third
period of Game 1. ``I think there were a lot of questions in my
mind to be honest with you, but it felt great throughout the
night.'' Fewest shots The Stars' penchant for low shot totals
bordered on the ridiculous in the first period. They had three
shots, a team-low for this season's playoffs. Hull scored the
Stars' first goal at 4:25 on their first shot. The Stars' next shot
didn't come until 13:39 on Sylvain Cote's shot from the left
circle. Derian Hatcher had the other on a soft wrister from the
left circle at 14:12.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' previous low was four shots. They did that twice,
both coming during second periods against Colorado in the Western
Conference Finals. The Stars had four shots in the second period of
Game 1 and Game 3, both Dallas losses. Lehtinen's conditioning
Stars winger Jere Lehtinen waited patiently, sometimes impatiently,
to finally return after playing all of 17 regular-season games due
to a fractured right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it finally feels good,'' Lehtinen said. ``It's kind of
lucky that I am back for the Stanley Cup Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, who has scored one goal with four assists since
returning to the playoffs for Game 1 of the Western Conference
Finals, said that his ankle is mostly pain free and that his
conditioning is improving every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I would get tired \Rat the end of games\S,''
Lehtinen said. ``Now, it's getting better. I feel better and I am
not getting tired as much.'' Shattered glass Stars winger Mike
Keane is known to be a checker, but his hit on Devils winger Jay
Pandolfo at the 4:10 mark of the first period was no average check.
It shattered the glass between the team's benches.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player was injured, and the glass was replaced in five
minutes. Hey, that's quick; the crew in Colorado that replaced the
shattered board from a Ray Bourque pass took eight minutes.
Home-change advantage In Games 3 and 4 at Reunion Arena, the Stars
will have the advantage of last change in determining matchups. If
checking center Guy Carbonneau has his way, his line will match up
against the Devils' top line of Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and
Patrik Elias, who burned the Stars for four goals and 11 points in
Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we've talked a lot about,'' Carbonneau said.
``That's one thing about Hitch \RStars coach Ken Hitchcock\S: He
listens to what we say. He's still the one that makes the decision.
When you are on the road, it is kind of tough to \Rto get a good
matchup\S. We're going back home for two games, and I'm sure we'll
try to match something.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau's line in Game 2 included Blake Sloan, who was a
scratch in Game 1, and Kirk Muller. Hitchcock has usual Carbonneau
partner Mike Keane playing on the fourth line to try to spread out
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   In both games, the Devils opted to match their first line
against the Stars' first line of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtinen. Cut-up Muller Stars winger Kirk Muller suffered a cut to
his upper and lower lip after being hit with a deflected puck
during yesterday's morning skate. Muller left the ice and did not
return to practice. He had the cuts glued together instead of
receiving stitches, he said. The injury did not keep him out of
Game 2. Yankee approval Stars winger Mike Keane has a New York
Yankees tattoo on his shoulder. He's that big of a fan. Yet his
trip to Yankee Stadium for a game against the Oakland A's on
Wednesday was his first despite formerly playing for the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   So what did he think?
</P>
<P>
   ``Very nice, very nice stadium for being as old as it is,''
Keane said. Upset friends, eh? Stars winger Brenden Morrow's
friends aren't too happy with him, and they called to let him know.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, folks have Stanley Cup pools a lot like the Final
Four pools in the United States. Morrow's friends took the Stars
because that's whom he plays for. The Stars' lack of scoring didn't
exactly help their chances in the pool. ``They were a little upset
because the New Jersey guys got all the points and none of the
Dallas guys did,'' Morrow said. ``Their playoff pools aren't doing
too good.''
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by staff writers Jeff Caplan, Mac Engel, Jennifer Floyd
and Charean Williams.
nn
</P>
