<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARFIELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING GARFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, the Garfield neighborhood near the heart of
Phoenix was dying, struck down by the classic urban ills of
poverty, gangs, crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 1-mile-square area is still battered and blighted but
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't come cheap: The price tag has been at least $10
million in taxpayer dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves some officials and residents asking whether
Garfield's history showcases government's ability to rescue
troubled neighborhoods or shows the limits even the best intentions
can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have accomplished quite a bit,'' said Douglas Fox, a
longtime resident of the area bounded by Seventh and 16th streets,
Van Buren Street and the Papago Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I sometimes wonder if we spent twice the money if we could
finally clean this area up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been very expensive, and we have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with residents, police, city officials and others
suggest several lessons from Garfield's experience:
</P>
<P>
   _Only years of targeted efforts and millions of dollars can even
begin to rescue neighborhoods so far lost to urban blight.
</P>
<P>
   _Participation by neighbors themselves is essential for even
moderate success.
</P>
<P>
   _The forces affecting urban neighborhoods often involve broad
social and economic forces outside anyone's control.
</P>
<P>
   _``Saving'' one neighborhood can mean transferring its problems
to others.
</P>
<P>
   _The years and money spent on Garfield may preserve it only
until the rising downtown housing market arrives for the real
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   _But if such gentrification does bring new upscale residents to
Garfield, it may also drive poorer residents out. &QL; 
Definitely worth saving
</P>
<P>
   ``Neighborhood redevelopment is never cost-effective,'' said
Terry Goddard, a former Phoenix mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But is the neighborhood worth saving? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime resident Helen Trujillo remembers when Garfield was a
lower-middle-income community of well-kept homes and friendly
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the downtown started to die in the 1960s, our
neighborhood started to die,'' Trujillo said.
</P>
<P>
   As residents moved, she said, investors bought the houses for
rentals, bringing in tenants who ``didn't care as much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars were in yards,'' Trujillo said, ``old furniture was left
out. Gangs got started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crept up on us.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, gunfire was the nightly music in Garfield. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Army of occupation'
</P>
<P>
   ``The gangs were like an army of occupation,'' Phoenix police
Lt. Robert Settembre said. ``They terrorized the old people, shook
them down for money.
</P>
<P>
   Settembre said criminals sold drugs openly, shot each other in
broad daylight and sexually assaulted women too frightened to
report it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And it looked it. City officials found that three out of four
homes and apartment buildings needed significant repairs, often
equaling half the structure's value.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, residents and police say, Garfield had become a
``community of first arrival'' for illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of undocumented workers still occupy apartments in the
area until they obtain documents necessary to get work. Police say
the illegals are easy prey for drug dealers and slumlords.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our problems, from drugs to the market in selling
illegal documents, are rooted in the folks from other countries who
move into here,'' Fox said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
10 million fight
</P>
<P>
   To stem this tide of urban woes, taxpayers have poured more than
$10 million into Garfield since 1995 to fight crime, repair streets
and sidewalks, plant trees, rebuild homes and fund social programs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Phoenix brought the first of several programs to
Garfield. Neighborhood Fight Back carried an $80,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our department and the police helped get Block Watches
started, a newsletter printed and some improvements done in the
area,'' said Tom Boling of Phoenix's Neighborhood Services
Department.
</P>
<P>
   And the locals began to buy in. Douglas Fox said a neighbor,
Lupe Sisneros, talked him into joining the FightBack program.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``She founded the Garfield Organization,'' Fox said of
Sisneros, whom many neighbors credit with saving their community.
She died four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had meetings, got advice from the police, had some
neighborhood cleanups,'' Fox said. ``There was an increased police
presence, and that helped some, but it still was a tough place.''
</P>
<P>
   Settembre said that about 150 drug houses have been closed since
increased enforcement began in 1995. Hundreds of gang members, drug
dealers and prostitutes have been arrested. &QL; 
`Less shooting'
</P>
<P>
   ``We've almost broken the power of the gangs,'' Settembre said.
``There is less shooting. The streets are safer at night.''
</P>
<P>
   However, police still count Garfield in the top 100 of the 1,600
Phoenix crime grids.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Garfield Neighborhood Organization and the city
sought and received a federal ``Weed and Seed'' grant for $727,523.
In the next four years, an additional $2 million in Weed and Seed
money and about $7 million in Community Development Block Grant
money poured into the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Weed and Seed programs seek to weed out the criminal element
while planting the seeds of home improvement, education and social
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the best things Weed and Seed got us were a
bunch more street lights and a heck of a lot more trees,'' Fox
said. ``You felt a little safer at night, and the trees made the
place look a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued police pressure also helped. &QL; 
Gang influence down
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Since the police started hitting hard on the gangs, their
influence has gone way down,'' said Manuel Ramirez, principal of
Garfield Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, single-family home construction and rehabilitation
efforts began with federal funds. Social-service programs were
launched, including day care, job placement, remedial education, a
folk dance group, a youth crime watch, a teen council and others.
</P>
<P>
   The city began refurbishing buildings that could be saved and
demolishing the rest. In the past five years, 234 Garfield homes
have been rehabilitated or reconstructed, with neighbors using
low-interest block grant loans.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 new houses have been built by Neighborhood Housing
Services, a non-profit organization that promotes homeownership in
downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Central City Precinct Commander Joe Klima said that stings to
arrest prostitutes and their customers have begun, efforts against
slumlords will be boosted and that a special city prosecutor will
be assigned to the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Police statistics suggest a positive effect. Since 1994, violent
crimes in Garfield have dropped by about 10 percent while citywide,
there has been a 5 percent decrease. Property crimes and drug
crimes also have decreased. Calls for police service in Garfield
have declined by 22 percent since 1994 while increasing citywide. &QL; 
Yuppification ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Garfield remains tattered. Scores of buildings are
surrounded by trash, have peeling paint, broken windows and sagging
doors.
</P>
<P>
   But there is evidence that the years of work and money may have
set the stage for a further transformation. In December, Camden
Property Trust opened high-end apartments at Eighth and Van Buren
streets, across the street from the Garfield neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   There are more to come, according to urban planner John F.
McIntosh, who calls Garfield ``a prime area for `yuppification.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh, of Arizona State University, said young professionals
already have bought heavily in the nearby Roosevelt and Coronado
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The demand for nice places to live downtown will only
increase,'' McIntosh said. ``We're running out of available,
intact, historic neighborhoods. The Garfield neighborhood will see
more and more places like Camden.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the average Garfield home sold for $65,000. The
average price now is $90,000, according to real estate affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old houses will continue to gain in value, the slum
apartments will be bought up and demolished,'' McIntosh said. ``The
neighborhood should only get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Goddard notes, however, that yuppification of the
area, although good for homeowners, will not solve the problem of
the poorer folks, the mostly illegal immigrants who live in rentals
and likely will leave when upscale places are built.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will go somewhere else,'' Goddard said. ``The
neighborhood will get better, but part of its problem will just
move.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at William.Hermann(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-4875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
