<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-STORM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON COMETS SPOIL STORM'S HOME OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The celebration of the Seattle Storm's historic,
first-ever WNBA game in KeyArena began with fireworks and ended
just as abruptly after the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Comets, three-time league champions, were not in a
generous mood one night after nearly being upset by the expansion
Portland Fire, and took their frustration out Thursday night,
pounding the Storm, 77-47.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our worst nightmare was for them to have a close game in
Portland,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said of Houston's 93-89
double-OT victory over the Fire on Wednesday. ``They wanted to show
the world why they're the champs in Seattle _ we received their
wrath.''
</P>
<P>
   Comets forward Sheryl Swoopes, who scored 28 points in Portland,
led all scorers with 20 points, 13 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm were led by center Quacy Barnes' career-high 16
points, while forward Kamila Vodichkova grabbed seven rebounds.
Guard Edna Campbell, who led the league with 19.5 points per game
in the preseason, managed only 11 points on 5-for-17 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got good things from Kamila and Quacy, but needed
to get more points from our perimeter,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle won the opening tip and took a 5-2 lead on Vodichkova's
3-pointer. The good news ended there.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, game faces on and vengeance pumping in their veins,
went on a 22-3 run to take a 24-8 lead midway through the half.
Forward Tina Thompson hit two 3-pointers in the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we did a poor job of early was finding Tina Thompson
and contesting her 3-point shot,'' Dunn said. ``I don't think we
had enough respect for what she can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who missed her first seven shots, broke the Storm
scoring drought with a free throw. Barnes brought Seattle's offense
back to life with strong inside moves and soft outside shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quacy is our warrior,'' Dunn said. ``I think she arrived
tonight as a legitimate post player who can be forceful in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, facing the size and skill of Houston forwards Thompson
(6-foot-2), Tammy Jackson (6-2) and Tiffani Johnson (6-4), scored
seven of Seattle's final nine points before the break, narrowing
the deficit to 40-23 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough in there,'' Barnes said. ``I think I fight harder
since I'm only 180 pounds, but I tip my hat to Tina Thompson. She's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets picked up where they left off in the second half,
roaring out of the break with a 12-4 run in the first seven minutes
to extend the lead to 52-27.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm continued to struggle offensively, missing easy
baskets and committing turnovers in the face of relentless Houston
pressure. For the game, Seattle shot just 34 percent from the field
and only 57 percent from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just could not execute on anything,'' guard Robin Threatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn used her bench extensively, playing her entire roster and
resting starters Campbell, Vodichkova and Sonja Henning as time
wound down.
</P>
<P>
   Henning, who had two points and three assists, played just four
minutes in the second half as Dunn used Jamie Redd and Threatt at
the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonja wasn't scoring,'' Dunn said. ``We were down, and I
thought it was an opportune time to give Jamie and Robin some
minutes. We need to get scoring out of our backcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn also tinkered with her lineup facing the potent Comet
offense, starting defensive specialist Charmin Smith in place of
the slower Katrina Hibbert. Smith's best efforts were for naught,
however, as Swoopes showed no signs of playing 48 minutes in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swoopes came out on fire,'' Dunn said. ``She's world-class. I
think she's the premier player in the world. We've got nobody on
our team like her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn remained upbeat after her team's second loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me a team in this league that opened with a more
difficult and challenging schedule than the Seattle Storm,'' she
said. ``Portland is a bigger game for us _ we'll see where we are
Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland was supposed to be a break for the Storm after facing
Sacramento and Houston back-to-back, but with the Fire's surprising
performance vs. the Comets, the Storm has three tough games in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be nights like this,'' Threatt reflected
after the game. ``I just hope we got our worst one out now. I think
you'll see a different team (Saturday) against Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Dunn was pleased with the 10,840 fans who turned out for
the Storm's inaugural game in KeyArena. ``It was exciting ... to
see the crowd get into it. They were ready to erupt. I wish we'd
scored more points for them.'' ... The 17-member Storm Dance Troop
made its KeyArena debut and drew rave reviews from Sonics star Gary
Payton: ``Lavonte (Jackson, the youngest member of the squad at age
5) is the man. I can't do what he does.'' Payton, who sat
courtside, was impressed with the Storm's losing effort. ``I think
it's good the WNBA came to Seattle,'' he said. ``I like that
Campbell's game _ she gets her hands on the ball, plays defense and
goes to the hoop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
