<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-IAN-MCKELLEN-ON-     06-02 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-IAN-MCKELLEN-ON-X-MEN-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MAGNETIC ATTRACTION: IAN McKELLEN PREVIEWS `X-MEN'  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Sir Ian
McKellen with Patrick Stewart in a scene from ``X-Men.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    For a guy who didn't have a lot to do with science fiction or
fantasy for his first 60 years, Sir Ian McKellen is really making
up for lost time.
 &HT;    The 61-year-old Shakespearian actor is playing not one but two
iconic figures in four upcoming films, risking the wrath of
aficionados of two much-loved alternate universes by starring as
Magneto in Bryan Singer's ``X-Men'' and then as Gandalf in all
three parts of Peter Jackson's ``Lord of the Rings'' trilogy.
 &HT;    First up: ``X-Men,'' opening July 14.
 &HT;    Based on the phenomenally popular, 37-year-old Marvel Comics
series, ``X-Men'' follows the travails of a band of mutants who
fight the good fight on behalf of a mankind which fears and
despises them.
 &HT;    The story also pits mutant against mutant: The students of
Professor Xavier (Patrick Stewart) _ Cyclops (James Marsden), Jean
Grey (Famke Janssen), Storm (Halle Berry), Wolverine (Hugh Jackman)
and Rogue (Anna Paquin) _ face off against Erik Lehnsherr, a.k.a.
Magneto, and his disciples Toad (Ray Park), Sabretooth (Tyler Mane)
and Mystique (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos).
 &HT;    ``Magneto is a serious-minded, concerned citizen who believes,
as many people do in civil rights, that you only get to achieve
your ends through violence,'' McKellen says by telephone from his
Los Angeles hotel.
 &HT;    ``So that, I think, is the moral and political crux of the
comics and the movie,'' he says. ``Who do you agree with? Do you
agree with Magneto's view or with his old friend Xavier's view,
that integration and the soft, lobbying approach is the best way to
achieve your ends?''
 &HT;    Dramatic as that may sound, McKellen insists that ``X-Men''
never dips into the melodramatic. And, he promises, his Magneto
hews more to his Richard III than to Jack Nicholson's Joker.
 &HT;    ``If it were a melodrama, well, then one could play a
mustache-twirling villain,'' says McKellen, who portrayed an
elderly ex-Nazi in Singer's 1998 psychological thriller, ``Apt
Pupil.'' ``But Magneto is not of that sort.
 &HT;    ```Batman' is more simplistic in its storytelling than `X-Men,'
which is what I think has made `X-Men' so popular for 37 years,''
the actor says. ``Whoever writes to me about this film is always
very protective of the attitude that Magneto not just be a crude
villain.
 &HT;    ``I haven't intended to make him one.''
 &HT;    McKellen will take a turn to the good when he tackles ``Lord of
the Rings.'' Gandalf is the father figure in J.R.R. Tolkien's
``Ring'' novels, protector of the hobbits and mentor to Frodo
(Elijah Wood).
 &HT;    ``Gandalf is the wise wizard, the spirit from afar who is
concerned about preserving Middle Earth,'' McKellen says. ``From
the first time you meet him, you think he's a man to be trusted.
You feel that probably the hobbits will, somehow, come safely
through the dreadful adventure they have to endure.''
 &HT;    McKellen is enduring an adventure of his own in making ``Lord of
the Rings.'' Gandalf appears in all three films, first as Gandalf
the White and then as Gandalf the Grey. By the time production
ends, McKellen will have spent a year on location in New Zealand.
 &HT;    ``These films are a real curiosity,'' he says. ``Peter has said
this, but this is the biggest film ever made, in terms of logistics
and technology. Day by day, you get a sense of that. Sometimes
there are four different camera crews working on different scenes,
with Peter moving around from set to set.
 &HT;    ``The films are happening over 16 months,'' he adds, ``and
they're happening in New Zealand, away from any sense that there's
a world outside of Middle Earth.
 &HT;    ``We're all utterly absorbed in it.''
 &HT;    Expectations for both ``X-Men'' and the ``Rings'' trilogy are
sky-high and growing. McKellen understands the ardor, but asks fans
to temper their anticipation with a dollop of objectivity.
 &HT;    ``The most likely concern about `X-Men' is coming from people
who know the source material very well,'' McKellen says. ``They're
universally concerned that their image of the comic will be the one
that prevails on the screen.
 &HT;    ``My answer is always the same: We've been involved in an act of
translation from the page to the screen,'' the actor says. ``It is
Bryan Singer's `X-Men' that you are coming to see and Peter
Jackson's `Lord of the Rings.'
 &HT;    ``Once you appreciate that, you can perhaps be more open to what
you actually see on the screen,'' he says, ``and not dismiss it
because it doesn't totally accord with how you would have made the
film _ if you'd raised the money and committed an awfully big slice
of your life to bringing it off.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
