<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIC-FARMING (Schaghticoke, N.Y.) _ Like other new young
farmers, Shanti Nagel, 20, and Sebastian Meier, 25, are fighting
back against agribusiness with organics and kinship. And it's not
just about food. They want to preserve the land and the creatures
that occupy it. By KATE GURNETT. (For release Sunday, June 4.)
</P>
<P>
   PESTICIDES-TARGETS (San Antonio) _ Chemical pesticides and the
delicate green lacewing are most farmers' friends when it comes to
controlling crop-eating bugs _ but even carefully targeted
pesticides can wipe out the beneficial bugs, researchers have
found. By ELIZABETH ALLEN.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-EYES (San Antonio) _ Viagra has become firmly imbedded in
the American vocabulary since the drug debuted two years ago as a
treatment for men with sexual dysfunction. Now, researchers from
the University of Texas Health Science Center say their work
suggests Viagra, or sildenafil, should be studied as a potential
treatment for patients with macular degeneration, the leading cause
of blindness in older individuals. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONTRIBUTORS (Austin, Texas) _ Do corporate campaign
donations, coupled with access to high-ranking state officials and
favorable treatment of regulations, add up to influence peddling?
Absolutely not, say spokesmen for Gov. George W. Bush, state health
officials and a lawyer for Metabolife International, an herbal
dietary-supplement company whose contributions to Bush's 1998
re-election effort coincided with the company's attempts to avoid
stringent health regulations. By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Mamaroneck, N.Y.) _ Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican
opponent of Hillary Rodham Clinton for the New York Senate seat, is
moving away from key right-of-center stands on abortion and
education to position himself as a mainstream Republican. By LARA
JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ Clint Reilly says he has spent
close to $1 million so far on his legal attempt to stop the Hearst
Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle, and claims he turned
down a multimillion-dollar offer to settle the antitrust lawsuit.
By PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FORUM (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ In its inaugural year and
already stuffed with high-wattage events and filmmakers, next
week's Lake Placid Film Forum will include more than 40 films of
all types, panels and workshops, and a gala tribute to Czech-born
director Milos Forman. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MOMMA (Undated) _ Lest you make the same mistake I
did: ``Big Momma's House'' is not the name of the Shelley Winters
comeback vehicle. Nor is it the sequel to 1997's ``Soul Food,''
although it co-stars Nia Long, features a spread of good eats that
strikes the motherlode of fingerlickingoodness and provides ample
time to get acquainted with a plus-size woman. No, ``Big Momma's
House'' is a high-spirited, big-bottomed Polaroid of the comedian
in a fat suit. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GYPSY (Undated) _ As a girl living in England,
filmmaker Jasmine Dellal was told that if she misbehaved, Gypsies
would take her away. Haunted, in part, by that bizarre attempt to
straighten her out, Dellal set out to shoot a documentary about
Gypsy _ or, more correctly, Romany _ culture. To understand how the
result, ``American Gypsy: A Stranger in Everybody's Land,'' manages
to be something more than self indulgent, you'd have to meet Marks
first. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SEX (Undated) _ ``Sex and the City,'' (Sunday, 9 p.m., HBO)
is a the superb romantic comedy now entering its third season. In
the first year, with the quality as high as its been ever since,
this show couldn't get arrested. Certain critics _ most of them, in
fact _ flat out didn't get it. That's partly because many of them
were men and the thought of powerful, intelligent, shop-a-holic
women who talked frankly about sex just didn't register with them.
By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-WINSTON-CUP (Undated) _ For 24 of the next 27 weeks, the
NASCAR Winston Cup series will conduct a race somewhere in the
United States. That's three weeks off in the next six months. A
victory does wonders for the soul, but it doesn't provide sleep for
the weary. By LEE SCHEIDE.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JERRY-RICE (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ An agreement has been
reached that will keep Jerry Rice a San Francisco 49er this season
and next and all but assure he will retire in a San Francisco
uniform. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Last weekend, my wife and I were
riding the Larkspur Ferry, a $9.50 round trip (not counting Bloody
Marys) when we spotted a giant tanker bearing the name
``Condoleezza Rice.'' That's the name of the former provost of
Stanford, and foreign policy adviser to both President George Bush
and his son, the candidate for president. ``What's her name doing
on a tanker?'' asked my wife, who added ``Gross.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
