r s BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-HNS &LR;      06-02 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A BUSY SEASON FOR NASCAR DRIVERS AND CREWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LEE SCHEIDE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Bill France Jr.'s version of a forced march.
</P>
<P>
   For 24 of the next 27 weeks, the NASCAR Winston Cup series will
conduct a race somewhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's three weeks off in the next six months. Six months worth
of bent sheet metal and long, desolate drives back on Sunday night,
trying to get to the shop in time to turn the cars around for the
next race.
</P>
<P>
   A victory does wonders for the soul, but it doesn't provide
sleep for the weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point where we are going to have to hire
more people to run the shop while we have a crew on the road,''
team owner Richard Childress said. ``That's just going to make the
sport more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the marathon started May 20 in Charlotte,
N.C., when everyone tried to qualify for The Winston, a special
All-Star event.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, it was the Coca-Cola 600, which marked the start of a
march that won't end until July 9 in Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   After a week off, the crews load up for Pocono and then enjoy
another weekend off.
</P>
<P>
   When the teams arrive in Indianapolis for the Brickyard 400 on
Aug. 5, it will be the first of 12 consecutive weekends on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's can be a brutal schedule,'' Terry Labonte said in April
at the Texas Motor Speedway for the DirecTV 500, the eighth race in
a 10-week opening run for NASCAR 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that difficult on us (the drivers), because we get to
fly home and fly to the track. The crew guys, though, they are the
ones that are dead tired by the end of the season. I (have) more
and more respect for them each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the issue: When John Force beat Tony Pedregon in the
Funny Car final Sunday at the Castrol Nationals in Ennis, it tied
Force with Bob Glidden with 85 career victories.
</P>
<P>
   As Pedregon saw his chances of defeating his boss go up in smoke
at the starting line, Jerry Toliver watched his points lead
disappear just as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Force, a nine-time world champion who has won the past eight
titles consecutively, has 677 points to Toliver's 644. Ron Capps,
who Force has defeated in each of the past three events, is third
with 600 points and Pedregon is fourth with 557.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock at the top of the career-victory list could last
one week as Force looks to extend his winning streak to four when
the series stops at Route 66 Raceway in Joliet, Ill., this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Lyn St. James has been one of the top women drivers for years
and, for much of the past decade, she has competed at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But during the most recent ``Greatest Spectacle in Racing,'' St.
James was less than thrilled when all the questions directed her
way concerned 19-year-old Brickyard rookie Sarah Fisher and not St.
James' efforts to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   St. James' public-relations representative asked reporters to
make sure they asked her several questions about her effort before
bringing up Fisher's name in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   St. James made the field for her fourth Indianapolis 500,
qualifying 32nd in the 33-car field. But at 53, St. James' time in
the cockpit and spotlight at the Brickyard has passed, much like
the field just 10 laps into the race.
</P>
<P>
   She is no longer considered a Northern Lights Indy Racing
regular, and there is no bio for her in the media guide.
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 71, St. James reportedly had an ill-handling car, but
that didn't stop her from coming down on Fisher when the latter
made a pass going into Turn 1. The move put St. James into the Turn
1 wall and Fisher into the wall in the short chute, and left both
of them out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in the race Fisher had lapped her elder.
``It's not that difficult on us (the drivers), because we get to
fly home and fly to the track. The crew guys, though, they are the
ones that are dead tired by the end of the season. I (have) more
and more respect for them each year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
