<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOURDES0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The healing continues at Lourdes
 &HT;    By Katherine Ullmer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They prayed together, ate together, laughed and
cried together.
</P>
<P>
   Candles in hand, the dames and knights, malades (French for
``sick ones'') and caretakers filed in nightly procession through
the streets of Lourdes, France.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission: a spiritual healing in the place where in 1858 a
poor young French girl named Bernadette Soubirous began seeing
apparitions of the Virgin Mary. Mary told Bernadette to pray, do
penance and tell the priests to build a chapel, bathe in the cold
springs at the site and to have people come in processions.
</P>
<P>
   The sick, disabled and poor are honored guests at Lourdes, a
sacred place of pilgrimage in southwestern France, famed for
miraculous cures and spiritual healing. A village of 16,000
inhabitants, it has more than 5 million visitors a year and four
churches, including an underground one capable of holding 30,000
worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   Each May, members of the Order of Malta, also known as the
Knights of Malta, a 900-year-old lay religious order of the Roman
Catholic Church, make a pilgrimage to Lourdes. Their mission: to
take care of the sick and poor. Their insignia, the Maltese cross,
is worn on robes and capes.
</P>
<P>
   At Lourdes, the knights (male members), dames (female members)
and auxiliaries (younger members, often children of knights and
dames) of the order act as hosts or caretakers for the malades.
</P>
<P>
   Dionne Chanatry, 46, a member of Incarnation Church, who has
multiple sclerosis, was a malade or honored guest, from May 3-10.
</P>
<P>
   Her illness, which gradually weakened her left arm and leg,
struck at age 34, when she was a fitness instructor in California.
Now it has made even standing and moving with a four-wheeled walker
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   As a malade in Lourdes, her every need was catered to. She was
given preferential treatment, pulled to group events in a voiture
(blue metal cart), and surrounded by helpers _ a dame and a knight,
priests who prayed for her, and auxiliaries who saw to her needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty spiritually awesome experience,'' she said.
She said she went for the spiritual healing, though ``in the back
of your mind you hope that you're going to be the one person going
to be healed.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances are slim. Though millions have visited Lourdes, it
has only had 66 documented physical healings, said Dionne's
husband, Michael Chanatry, who accompanied her.
</P>
<P>
   The only physical healing in their group, Dionne Chanatry said,
was when a man with fingers paralyzed from a stroke found he could
move them. He walked with a cane and was not cured in that regard,
she said, ``though I observed an incredible spiritual healing in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dionne Chanatry was chosen in January by the American
Association of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta, based in New
York, as one of 45 malades, 13 of them children, to make the
pilgrimage this year.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association, with about 1,600 members, is the
largest of three Order of Malta associations in the United States,
the others being the Federal Association, based in Washington,
D.C., and the Western Association, in San Francisco, Calif. The
three U.S. groups total about 2,500 members, with around 10,000
members worldwide, according to Bill Burleigh, of Rabbit Hash, Ky.,
co-chairman with his wife, Anne, of the American Association's
pilgrimage this year.
</P>
<P>
   The group of pilgrims from the American Association, including
spouses, members and other volunteers, totaled around 300, the
biggest group they've ever had go, Burleigh said. It included many
cancer patients, but there were also people with paralysis, autism,
cerebral palsy and other disorders, including mental illness, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Order of Malta groups from around the world were also there
hosting malades, many on stretchers, and there were other pilgrims
and tourists, so the town had 30,000 to 40,000 pilgrims at times,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The malades travel free as guests of the order. Dionne
Chanatry's expenses were all paid for. Her husband paid his own
way.
</P>
<P>
   Chanatry's name was submitted by Albuquerque, N.M., artist Dan
Paulos, who does artwork for the American Association's Order of
Malta, and knew Chanatry's mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how people usually are selected to go,'' she said.
``They usually know somebody who knows somebody who recommends them
to go. Malades are not exclusively Catholic. They are invited from
all faiths.''
</P>
<P>
   A medical committee sorts through the applications to make sure
certain medical criteria are met to ensure the well-being of
everyone on the trip, Burleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   Knights and dames must be asked to join by current members. The
order includes lawyers, CEOs, doctors, and others in high
positions, though as members of the order, ``they are all very
humble,'' Dionne Chanatry said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the American Association pay about $2,500 dollars to
join, Burleigh said, and are expected to donate yearly to support
the order's charitable projects. The American Association supports
hospitals and schools in Haiti and has a number of volunteer
efforts in Latin America, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Lourdes, the group participated in a daily schedule of
events, from masses to processions, confessions, baths for
purification, vigils, visits to the grotto where the apparitions
took place, and a trip to the village of Pau in the French
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French, they're not afraid to reach out and help somebody,
whether it be in a wheelchair or whatever physical hang-up they
have,'' Dionne Chanatry said. ``They're eager to be there to
help.'' People in the United States often act afraid of someone
with a disability and don't offer help for fear of insulting them,
she said. Also, ``they're afraid they might catch what you have.
Over there, everyone was accepting of everyone else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly a life-changing experience,'' she said.
``People gain a lot of strength there _ maybe not physical healing
per se, but strength to deal with whatever it is they have to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chanatry said he gained more confidence and awareness as
a caregiver. One day, the caregivers shared their stories and
experiences. ``That was one of the most moving sessions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``this MS has been one of the biggest blessings,''
Dionne Chanatry said. ``It brought me back around to my faith and
into a deeper relationship with God. It has made me ask why am I
here and what do I need to do with my situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
