<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Sex and the City'': An educational experience
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Sex and the City'': Season premiere, 9-9:30
p.m. Sunday, HBO
</P>
<P>
   Why do I love ``Sex and the City'' so much?
</P>
<P>
   Is it because I get to see Kim Cattrall naked each week?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. But that certainly doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I'm fond of the chi-chi fashion _ you know, the elegant
Christian Dior dresses, vintage jeweled shows and Fendi embroidered
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Not particularly.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I just enjoy watching four pouty-mouthed women gabbing
about men and sex. And sex and men.
</P>
<P>
   That's it!
</P>
<P>
   I've always found ``Sex and the City,'' which kicks off its
18-episode third season tonight, funny and scathingly clever. And
the writing is always blade sharp. For instance, when Carrie (Sarah
Jessica Parker) finds herself dancing to disco tunes at a Staten
Island club in tonight's episode, she cracks that New York's
forgotten borough ``is like a quaint European country. The American
music was 20 years behind and you could smoke wherever you
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most men, I find women fascinating. Just when you think you
have them figured out, they toss another curveball your way. Oh,
I'm sure women say the same thing about us.
</P>
<P>
   For me, ``Sex and the City `` has been both educational and
entertaining. This delightfully raunchy series lets me be that
proverbial fly on the wall when women are saying what they really
think about men and how they really feel about relationships. While
I don't think most women are as sex-obsessed as Carrie; Samantha
(Cattrall); Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) and, my personal favorite,
Charlotte (Kristin Davis), I still believe these are realistic
characters who are often trapped in all too familiar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty certain women could relate to Charlotte's partner
falling asleep during sex. Or Carrie's torturous on-and-off
relationship with Big (Chris Noth), which produced some of the
show's most achingly tender moments. Or Samantha sleeping with a
man who wasn't exactly, uh, that well endowed. Or Miranda's
reluctance to date an average-looking, blue-collar nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   So few TV shows are told from a strong female point of view.
When one as hilarious and thought-provoking as ``Sex and the City''
came along, I immediately embraced it. You don't see many TV series
in which guys are treated like disposable sex objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City's'' third season gets off to a fine start.
Carrie is mourning her breakup with Big. Charlotte is determined to
find Mr. Right. Samantha continues sleeping with Mr. Right Now and
Miranda learns that being rescued by a man doesn't mean she's weak.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, folks. ``Sex and the City `` is back. That means school's
in session. Wonder what I'll learn this year?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
