<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD03-COX     06-02 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Face-frame joinery method a matter of preference
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An individual self-described as ``VERY new to woodworking''
wants to know the best way to put together a face frame for a
built-in entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to decide on mortising the joints (or) using dowels
instead, or just finish nail the pieces so they look like they're
all attached together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If mortising is recommended, what would be the best and most
versatile piece of equipment to use _ a mortising machine, a drill
press with a mortising attachment or a router with a mortising
bit?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the answer is: It all depends. Mainly, it depends on
whether you want the finest possible construction, and I believe we
amateurs should always go for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Nails are out. Forget nails.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of commercial cabinetmakers use pocket screws, which are
quick and probably will do well enough if the frame is subject to
no stress or wracking at all. Still, though, they are a method of
expedience, not of quality.
</P>
<P>
   Dowel joinery is just about a thing of the past. It really isn't
a very good way to make joints, despite the fact that some very
fine craftsmen have relied upon it over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the useful glue surface is quite small, and
the dowels themselves are not very strong unless you get into
half-inch dowels or larger.
</P>
<P>
   Dowel joinery has been largely supplanted by biscuit joinery.
The hand-held biscuit joiners make aligning the work far easier,
and their shape gives a great deal more glue surface than dowels.
They share with dowels the problem of expansion when moistened by
the glue. This can sometimes result in telegraphing or
print-through of the dowels or biscuits to the surface of the work.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are better ways than biscuit joinery, if you're
working with solid wood. If plywood, then biscuits are as good a
way to go as any.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to make up a face frame, or any kind of frame, is
any of the several variations on the mortise and tenon. The method
to use depends on the strength required and whether visible end
grain bothers you.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest of all these is, of course, the ordinary mortise
and tenon, with a tenon cut on the end of one piece fitting snugly
into a pocket, or mortise, in the other.The result is two broad
areas of side grain for the glue. The mortise helps keep it in
place. Cutting a shoulder on the tenon makes it even better.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that the ``loose'' mortise and tenon, which
involves mortises in both pieces joined by a tenon cut from another
piece of wood, is even stronger. It would, however, involve
mortising into end grain, which can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you insist on mitered corners, it's the method I
would use.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have the half-lap and the bridle joint, both of which
are easily cut on the table saw. Neither has the mechanical
strength of the standard mortise and tenon, and end grain will be
visible on the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as to the best tool for cutting the mortise, the mortise
milling machine wins hands down. However, you don't find many of
these within the reach of the ordinary amateur unless they are
included as part of another tool. The mortising attachment for a
drill press seems to be enjoying a revival, but I'm leery of them.
</P>
<P>
   Absent a mortise miller, I'd use a router with a good homemade
jig to keep everything in alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Tenons generally are best cut on the table saw using a tenoning
jig, although they can also be cut on the band saw. Heck, you can
waste the wood off with a router if you build a jig for it.
</P>
<P>
   You can e-mail Jack Warner at jwarner(at)ajc.com. We want to
hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
