<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-FORUM-HNS &LR;      06-02 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FORUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAKE PLACID TO STAGE IMPRESSIVE FILM FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Tributes to the past, nods to the future and
a whole mess of movies are on the slate at the Lake Placid Film
Forum next week, when films converge with filmmakers over a long
weekend in the Adirondack Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Adirondack Film Society, the forum will run
June 8 through June 11, at sundry locations throughout the bustling
Olympic town. Fittingly, its first event is ski jumping (with
water-soaked plastic substituting for snow).
</P>
<P>
   In its inaugural year and already stuffed with high-wattage
events and filmmakers, the Lake Placid Film Forum will include:
more than 40 films (old and new, domestic and foreign, features,
shorts and documentaries); a baker's dozen of panels and workshops;
and a gala, Saturday-night tribute to Czech-born director Milos
Forman.
</P>
<P>
   All told, more than 100 filmmakers and pundits _ directors,
screenwriters, actors, critics, studio executives and experts in
digital technologies _ are scheduled to take part in the festival
as panelists and presenters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fest's many prominent participants are actors Jill
Hennessy, Chris Noth (both known from ``Law and Order'') and Cliff
Robertson; authors Russell Banks (``The Sweet Hereafter''), Michael
Ondaatje (``The English Patient'') and Donald Westlake (``The Hot
Rock''); and directors Paul Schrader (who made ``Affliction,''
based on a Banks novel), Jay Craven (``Where Rivers Flow North''),
Terry George (``Some Mother's Son''), Robert Downey Sr. (``Putney
Swope'') and Richard Rush (``Color of Night''). Sony Classics
co-president Michael Barker, Shooting Gallery president Eamon Bowls
and Hallmark Entertainment vice president Lynn Holst are also
scheduled to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep (describing) this event as a microbrewery _ it's a
really yeasty event,'' said Naj Wikoff, executive director and
co-founder of the Film Forum. ``It's regional, it has quality, and
it has character. And the yeasty bit is, we have a lot of people
with a lot of strong personalities coming to talk about film. It
should be very entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have people who are passionate about film, and people
who are passionate about digital technologies, and people who are
passionate about screenwriting, and we'll have all these passionate
people here to show their wares. ... It's a great opportunity to
get behind the scenes and see how a movie is made, and see what the
issues are.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend is a mad weave of films, forums and special events.
Workshops on the art of collaboration and how-to sessions on ``the
perfect pitch'' overlap with screenings that run virtually nonstop,
morning to midnight, throughout the festival's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One forum, ``From Novel to Screen,'' will address the serpentine
path of a creative project and will feature as panelists Banks,
Schrader, Ondaatje, Forman and critic/screenwriter Stephen Schiff.
Another, ``Role Models: Finding Inspiration in the Work of the
World's Great Filmmakers,'' boasts Downey (discussing Preston
Sturges), Westlake (on Alfred Hitchcock) and screenwriter Greer
Goodman (giving John Cassavetes his due).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievably auspicious for a first event,'' said Wikoff
of the Film Forum's packed schedule and burgeoning profile. ``We've
really caught people's eye in the industry. They cannot believe
it's the first (year) because of the depth. So I think it bodes
well for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Programmed for screening next week are numerous area premieres
and a smattering of oldies but goodies. Among the older films are
one silent classic (``Peter Pan'') and three by Forman:
``Amadeus,'' ``Loves of a Blonde'' (a 1965 Czech work) and last
year's unsettling ode to Andy Kaufman, ``Man on the Moon.'' An
early favorite by black-humorists Joel and Ethan Coen, ``Blood
Simple,'' will reappear, as will Richard Rush's 1980 tour-de-force,
``The Stunt Man'' _ along with Rush's newly unveiled DVD
documentary, ``The Sinister Saga of Making the Stunt Man.''
</P>
<P>
   A staged reading of a screenplay, Tom Mercer's ``Choice of the
Cross,'' has also been wedged into the Film Forum's crowded
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Shorts abound _ several programs' worth, of varying lengths and
from around the world. One program is devoted to shorts by film
students at Columbia and New York universities; another,
``Fledgling Films/Ten by Teens,'' features work by adolescents. In
addition, the forum will screen a 28-minute documentary,
``Conversations in World Cinema: Atom Egoyan,'' about the filmmaker
who directed 1997's profound Russell Banks adaptation, ``The Sweet
Hereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   Included among the new and new-to-upstate releases being
screened at the festival:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Acting Class,'' about a hellish acting coach and his
browbeaten minions; directed by Jill Hennessy and Elizabeth Holder;
starring Hennessy, Holder, Jerry Orbach, Chris Noth, Benjamin
Bratt, Austin Pendleton and Courtney B. Vance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Saving Grace,'' a British comedy that looks at a financially
strapped widow who helps her Scottish gardener raise marijuana
plants; directed by Nigel Cole; starring Brenda Blethyn, Craig
Ferguson, Martin Clunes and Tcheky Karyo.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``George Washington,'' which follows an African-American boy
in poor North Carolina; directed by David Gordon Green; starring
Candace Evanofsky, Donald Holden, Eddie Rouse and Curtis Cotton
III.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Diary of a City Priest,'' a shortish (60-minute) feature
about an inner-city man of the cloth; directed by Eugene Martin;
starring David Morse, John Ryan and Ana Reeder.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shower (Xizao),'' A Chinese comedy about the aging
proprietor of a Beijing bathhouse and his business-minded son;
directed by Zhang Yang; starring Zhu Xu, Pu Cun Xin, Jiang Wu and
He Zheng.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Other Voices,'' which takes an offbeat look at an alienated,
upscale New Yorker who hires a private eye to spy on his wife;
directed by Dan McCormack; starring David Aaron Baker, Stockard
Channing, Peter Gallagher, Mary McCormack, Rob Morrow and Campbell
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Poles Apart,'' a documentary following the first all-female
trek across Antarctica; directed by Greg Stiever; featuring
expedition leader Ann Bancroft.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Tao of Steve,'' a romantic comedy involving a pudgy Don
Juan and a Santa Fe set designer; directed by Jennifer Goodman;
starring Donal Logue, Greer Goodman, Kimo Wells and Ayelet
Kaznelson.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Affair of Love,'' a French film about a lusty woman in
search of a no-frills relationship; directed by Frederic Fonteyne;
starring Natalie Baye and Sergei Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
