<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ The best way to make up a face frame,
or any kind of frame, is any of the several variations on the
mortise and tenon. The method to use depends on the strength
required and whether visible end grain bothers you. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-RIVERROAD _ On the famous River Road between Baton
Rouge and the Big Easy, the once-grand houses of the old sugar cane
plantations flank the Mississippi. Some are pristine and
refurbished; others are sagging and fading, forgotten beauty
queens. All sit in the shadow of the petrochemical empire. ``The
striking juxtaposition is what the modern age has supplied, a
reflection of ourselves and what we find important,'' photographer
Richard Sexton says. Sexton, an Atlanta native, grew up in
Georgia's Miller County. His latest book, ``Vestiges of Grandeur,''
is artistic documentation of one of the strangest, haunting
corridors in America, the so-called River Road. The geography is
specific, the debate universal. The River Road is many roads ...
(Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY,
JUNE 3
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ART _ HAVANA _ It's Sunday afternoon in a sweaty Havana
barrio called ``Callejon de Hamel,'' and curious tourists mingle
with dark-skinned Cubans as drummers pound out an Afro-Caribbean
beat and dancers sway to the hypnotic rhythm. Strolling through the
crowd, looking cool despite the sweltering heat, bearded, dark-eyed
Salvador Gonzalez greets friends, visitors and devotees to his
secluded, chic corner of Havana. Gonzalez has earned a world-wide
reputation as one of Cuba's most important mural painters. His
subject is Santeria, the mystical Afro-Cuban religion filled with
superstitions, animal sacrifices and frightening spirits that
correspond with Catholic saints. We profile Gonzalez and his work.
(MWilliams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
