<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HBO'S `SEX' IS NOW HIP STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Would Sarah Jessica Parker be hosting the
upcoming MTV Movie Awards if she weren't in HBO's ``Sex and the
City''?
</P>
<P>
   Even the MTV crowd is now aware of ``Sex and the City,''
(Sunday, 9 p.m., HBO), the superb romantic comedy now entering its
third season. In the first year, with the quality as high as its
been ever since, this show couldn't get arrested. Most critics flat
out didn't get it. That's partly because many of them were men and
the thought of powerful, intelligent, shop-a-holic women who talked
frankly about sex just didn't register with them. There was no show
like it on the networks, so nowhere to pigeonhole it.
</P>
<P>
   By the second season, the show moved firmly out of the cult
arena and women around the country were having ``Sex and the City''
parties, inviting their best friends over for 30 minutes of
well-written, often funny, often sad and almost always dead-on
realism about how four thirtysomething women in New York deal with
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The hip cachet that ``Sex'' brought with it has now blossomed
into full-blown must-see TV. It helps that more people get HBO now
(thanks largely to ``The Sopranos,'' although that show airs at
opposite ends of the year and attracts different viewers). But now
that the pay cable is hooked in, more people are realizing what
massive holes there are in network shows that try to deal with
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   If ABC's angst-filled fortysomething ``Once and Again'' captured
people's attention (then lost it) because it tried to be grown up,
think of how much better that show would be if it were on HBO,
where adults can have their lives reflected back at them without a
laugh track or through a censorship filter.
</P>
<P>
   In the third year of ``Sex and the City,'' viewers should be
just giddy: it has lost none of its luster, nor its lust. None of
the off-season hype or the loss of several key behind-the-scenes
players has hurt this series. It comes out of the gate on Sunday as
saucy and cerebral as ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie (Parker) is still rocked emotionally by her involvement
with Mr. Big (Chris Noth), and it manifests when she starts dating
an almost perfect politician (John Slattery). While he rushes
things, the open-to-almost-anything Carrie moves along hesitatingly
until one little sexual quirk makes her realize she needn't worry
about whether she's ready for another long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prudish Charlotte (Kristin Davis) has an epiphany
while drunk on Staten Island, which leads to The Question _ posed
in each episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dating since I was 15,'' Charlotte says. `I'm
exhausted. Where is he?''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha (Kim Cattrall), the sexual adventurist in the bunch,
thinks she may have found something in a dumb hunk of a fireman _
not that she's looking for anything long-term. And Miranda (Cynthia
Nixon) battles her indecision over looking for Mr. Right or
settling with bartender Steve (David Eigenberg), who's nice and
seems to love her. In a later episode, she ponders talking to Steve
_ who wants to be monogamous _ about not committing because ``what
if someone better comes along?'' To which Carrie counsels, ``You've
gotta put a better spin on it than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' is not just about sex, although that seems
to be all anyone points to when reducing the show to its basic
merits. The show has always been brilliantly about life. Yes, sex
plays a major part. But how these four women look at love, being
friends and surviving day-to-day has always been the heart of the
show.
</P>
<P>
   That and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   We welcome these four cool women back into our living rooms for
season three. And it doesn't matter now that everybody's on the
``Sex and the City'' bandwagon. It'll just make the water cooler
more crowded on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
