<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-02 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE SLOW BOAT TO NOWHERE IN PARTICULAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last weekend, my wife and I were riding the
Larkspur Ferry, a $9.50 round trip (not counting Bloody Marys) that
beats anything offered by the grand old trans-Atlantic ocean
liners.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunard Line used to say that getting there is half the fun.
On the Golden Gate ferries, getting nowhere is all the fun.
</P>
<P>
   So there we were sitting in the sun on the fantail enjoying the
view of Gatsby-esque homes on the back side of Tiburon. Suddenly
the bow of a giant tanker loomed over us. On the side of the bow
was the tanker's name, the Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   That's the name of the former provost of Stanford, and foreign
policy adviser to both President George Bush and his son, the
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's her name doing on a tanker?'' asked my wife, who added
``Gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is on the board of directors of the Chevron Corp. Sure
enough, as the tanker passed, we saw it had the Chevron emblem on
its funnel.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of honor is this to give a distinguished member of
your board of directors? They're putting the name of this highly
intelligent, uncommonly beautiful woman on a smelly tub of a
tanker, and not even a supertanker.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron didn't think this one through. If the tanker Condoleezza
Rice runs aground on Angel Island and spills oil all over the San
Francisco Bay, it will forever be known as ``the Condoleezza Rice
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of oily ducks, and her boss George W. Bush is one dead
duck.
</P>
<P>
   That same ferry ride can offer more uplifting moments, such as
the sight of people enjoying some happy mission on the old Liberty
ship Jeremiah O'Brien, and the view of the towers of the Golden
Gate Bridge poking above the fog like giant crowns fit for the
split-personality egos of San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But this sight beat all. As we made the slow passage past San
Quentin, the inmates were in the yard getting some midday sun and
shooting hoops.
</P>
<P>
   They turned and started waving to the ferry. The passengers all
waved back. It was a great human moment, one best savored without
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   We tried analyzing it, but it led us to stupid talk about crime
and punishment and whether the cons were conning the yokels on the
boat. Sometimes a wave means exactly what it means.
</P>
<P>
   Other nice moments, walking down the spiffed-up waterfront of
San Francisco to the new ballpark:
</P>
<P>
   Rollerbladers were rolling along Herb Caen Way, talking about
Chris Isaak. You don't get that in Cleveland, not even near the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The Boondocks, the Java House and Red's Java House are
surrounded by acres of new plaza, and yet they're still there, fine
waterfront dives that somehow survived the great uplift.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Japanese training ship Kojima, complete with a
forward 3-inch gun, was docked in the city that once sent hundreds
of ships across the Pacific to fight the Japanese. San Franciscans
of all ethnic backgrounds, including Japanese-American, were
walking down the pier to view the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Again, these are moments to appreciate, no analysis necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
