<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES INTEGRATION OF RUSSIA INTO EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the eve of his arrival in Moscow, President Clinton on Friday
urged European countries to do more to make Russia ``fully part of
Europe'' by encouraging its stability and democracy and promoting
its integration into international institutions like the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doors can be sealed shut to Russia, not NATO's, not the
EU's,'' Clinton said in a speech on the fifth day of his weeklong
trip to Europe. ``The alternative would be a future of harmful
competition between Russia and the West and the end of our vision
of an undivided continent.''
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke in Aachen, Germany, where he was awarded the
International Charlemagne Prize for contributing to peace and
European unity. Clinton is the first U.S. president and the third
American to receive the 50-year-old award, after former secretaries
of state George Marshall and Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the prestigious gold medal on a yellow ribbon placed
around his neck, the president addressed an admiring audience in a
sunny courtyard outside the cathedral where the body of
Charlemagne, the eighth-century ruler of the Holy Roman Empire, is
interred.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed out that Europe has become ``more united, more
successful and more peaceful than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president said, ``The job of building a united Europe is
certainly not finished, and it is important not to take all of this
self-congratulation too far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must work to build a partnership with Russia that
encourages stability, democracy and cooperative engagements with
the West and full integration with global institutions,'' Clinton
told his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not yet know if Russia's hard-won democratic freedoms
will endure,'' he said. ``We don't know yet whether it will define
its greatness in yesterday's terms or tomorrow's.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton criticized Russia's ongoing war in Chechnya as a
self-defeating tragedy that has caused heavy loss of civilian
lives, he also stressed that Russians were hewing to the democratic
path despite severe economic hardship and political and criminal
violence.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Though Russia's transformation is incomplete, there clearly is
reason for hope in Russia's remarkable journey over these last few
years,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his week-long trip to Europe, the last scheduled
for his presidency, in Portugal, where his schedule included a
meeting with EU officials. He flew Thursday to Berlin, where he
discussed Russia and the issue of anti-missile defense as well as
some bilateral child custody cases with German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the president will travel to Moscow, where he is
expected to hold talks with Russian President Vladimir Putin and
visit the Duma, Russia's lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's interest in building a new anti-missile shield to
protect the United States from attacks by rogue states could
dominate the meeting with Putin, who adamantly opposes changing the
missile defense treaty that Moscow and Washington signed in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the president will fly home via Ukraine, where he is
scheduled to meet its president, Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-'N-SYNC-PREVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-02 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-'N-SYNC-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS NO FLUKE FOR YOUNG TALENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. FOR USE AFTER JUNE 5, 2000) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes you can't hear the boy band for the squealing.
</P>
<P>
   While you know about the record-breaking album sales, the
millions in concert grosses, the court cases and dating gossip, it
might come as a surprise that there could be genuine talent in the
teen-pop phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people get a bad rap but these kids can really
sing,'' says songwriter Diane Warren, who has penned hits for
Christina Aguilera, 'N Sync and Britney Spears. ``I was in the
studio with 'N Sync and they sing their (heads) off. I was there
for every second of the process and there's no endless fine-tuning
and retakes. And Christina sings as good as anybody. These are
really professional artists who work really hard and they've been
working that hard since they were even smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about teens having hits and chalking up mad
airplay. You can trace the craze back to the early '50s when
13-year-old Frankie Lymon stood on street corners, harmonizing
``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' with friends. A little later came
the Monkees, Debbie Gibson and New Kids on the Block. Today's
mega-selling teens who rule the charts and your preteen's bedroom
walls include Spears, Aguilera, 'N Sync, Westlife, Jessica Simpson,
the Backstreet Boys, ATeens, Five, LFO, 98 Degrees and Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone's taking the whole thing a little wrong,'' 'N
Sync's Lance Bass, 22, said. ``As much as there are teen bands,
there's the same amount of rock bands, r&AMP;b groups, solo acts. A lot
of older people in the music industry are a little jealous it's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Working isn't the half of it. Since its release, 'N Sync's
sophomore effort, ``No Strings Attached,'' clung onto the No. 1
spot in the albums chart for more than two months only to be
knocked off by Spears' just-issued second album, ``Oops!...I Did It
Again,'' which recently broke all records for the largest
first-week sales of a female solo album at 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In its first week, ``No Strings Attached'' sold more than 2.4
million copies, the strongest week of sales by any artist in
history _ almost double the total of the previous record holder
(Backstreet Boys).
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync appears Friday at the Rose Bowl with Sisqo (``Thong
Song'') and Pink (``There You Go''). More than 1 million tickets
worth about $40 million were sold across the country the day tour
dates went on sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't dream of having a goal like that,'' 'N Sync's Joey
Fatone, 23, said. ``The fans broke the record. A lot of people are
interested because of what we're about and the music we stand for.
It's not like we're just trying to throw something together to sell
the album. We really do put our blood, sweat and tears into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest differences between the likes of Lymon and
today's teen stars, apparently, is control. 'N Sync, at least,
claims to have it. Lymon clearly did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know who controls your business and that's you,'' Bass said.
``And we didn't realize that until this last year _ that we are in
control. And without us five guys, nothing could happen. We finally
realized that and took control of our own business.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. 'N Sync fought a messy legal battle to extricate
themselves from a record contract designed by the quintet's former
promoter, Lou Pearlman, that was settled late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman, incidentally, could be seen in action as he tries to
create another teen sensation on the recently canceled ABC-TV
series, ``Making the Band.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of 'N Sync were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it was made by one of the guys that put money behind us
in the beginning, you know, they flip it around and make it look
like he's out there, he's the one that's putting the group
together,'' 'N Sync's Chris Kirkpatrick, 28, said. ``He's the one
sitting in choreography rehearsals, putting in his input. He's the
one in vocal rehearsals when, in actuality, we didn't talk to him
for months at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all those sales, older pop fans often grumble that
teen-pop is a manufactured phenomenon where moderately talented but
good-looking singers have little say in the final product. The word
on 'N Sync, for example, is they're merely clones of the Backstreet
Boys, who themselves are copies of late '80s/early '90s boy act New
Kids on the Block.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not true,'' insists Warren, who wrote Aguilera's
latest smash, ``I Turn to You,'' as well as tracks on the new 'N
Sync and Spears albums, adding that pure pop has always been
popular and will continue that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always want to write off pop music,'' she said. ``But
it always survives. You can't kill it. Girls will always want cute
boys singing romantic songs to them _ and there's nothing wrong
with that. For a long time you had this anti-rock star thing with
sloppy clothes and this attitude of, `I don't want to be famous.'
Then, why don't you just quit your major label deal and give tapes
to your friends? That attitude got tiresome. The new singers really
want to do it and be stars. And why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync got started in the teen-pop
factory town of Orlando, Fla., where they shared the same manager
as Backstreet. Sound fishy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't go through a boot camp or audition,'' Bass says,
arguing that 'N Sync wasn't assembled in the same way as some other
boy groups. ``Nobody trained us. You can't put a group together
like that from scratch and expect it to last.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was, the group grew out of Joshua ``JC'' Chasez
and 19-year-old Justin Timberlake's work on TV's ``Mickey Mouse
Club,'' where they appeared at the same time as Spears. The two 'N
Syncs tried to make it in Nashville, failed, and returned to
Orlando where they hooked up with the three other members _
Kirkpatrick, Fatone and Bass.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, they were gigantic in Europe and thanks to a Disney
Channel special, found a home on the U.S. charts. It didn't hurt
that there were now nearly 22 million American aged 13 to 19 with a
reported disposable income of $140 billion a year waiting to
pounce.
</P>
<P>
   Bass, however, believes 'N Sync's massive first-week sales were
due to a heavy promotion schedule. ''We did, like, 50 million
television appearances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, the sophomore disc was delayed; the group's
self-titled debut came out in 1998. ``The fans were so hungry for
something out there,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chasez contributed four songs on the new album, ``No
Strings Attached'' follows a tried-and-true boy-group formula of
light r&AMP;b grooves and romantic ballads. The first single, ``Bye Bye
Bye,'' rivaled Celine Dion's ``My Heart Will Go On'' for
wall-to-wall airplay earlier this year, especially on such
syndicated outlets as Radio Disney, which targets preteens and
broadcasts a steady diet of teen acts in 46 cities.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just radio. MTV's ``Total Request Live'' and music
shows on the Disney Channel, Nickelodeon and HBO also support the
teen pop scene.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it seems like the kiddie-pop field is overflowing
and there are no more records to be broken, a new crop of stars
from all over the world is heading down the pike. Britain's Five,
Ireland's Westlife and Sweden's ATeens, for example, are beginning
to see chart action.
</P>
<P>
   The squealing has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of only one possible period where you didn't have
teen acts and that was the mid-'80s,'' said Rob Durkee, author of
``American Top 40: The Countdown of the Century,'' a book about the
the pop charts and radio. ``Record labels just weren't in the mood
to take chances. Then, a couple years later, Debbie Gibson and New
Kids on the Block came along. So, you'll always have these acts.
The name of the game now is to get a vocal harmony sound and the
songwriting and production will take care of itself. The question I
always ask is, are they writing their own material? Because the
ones that sound good and can write will stick around into their 20s
and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I'm asked how a young singer can break into the
business, I always say, `Get yourself a killer ballad preferably by
Diane Warren and get it into a movie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ____ &QL; 
Who: 'N Sync with Sisqo and Pink. &QL; 
Where: Rose Bowl, 1001 Rose Bowl Drive, Pasadena. &QL; 
When: 7:30 p.m. Friday. &QL; 
Tickets: $39.75 to $65. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
