<SLUG> BC-ANGLOPHILE-FREETOWN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOST OF GRAHAM GREENE HAUNTS SIERRA LEONE CAPITAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 875-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ALEX DUVAL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   FREETOWN, SIERRA LEONE _ Unnoticed amid the turmoil of events in
Freetown, the world has lost one of its most supremely seedy
literary landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   As the pride of the British fleet sailed into view of Graham
Greene's ``world of tin roofs, of vultures clanging down,'' the
cockroaches of The Bedford Hotel _ immortalized in ``The Heart of
the Matter'' _ were frying alive.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tragedy for Shaika Kabie, who sells secondhand socks
for 500 Leones outside the burned-out building on Lightfoot Boston
Street. In common with most people in Sierra Leone, he has never
heard of Greene. But Kabie lost his entire business.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my socks were burned. It happened in the early hours of
May 2, but the fire kept on for several days. I stored about 500
pairs in the basement of the hotel,'' said the 18-year-old, as he
carefully hung out his colorful new stock, sock by sock, over a
pole.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Rahim, 31, a stationery seller who is Kabie's pavement
neighbor, said he is ashamed of his current selection _ a pot of
blue Bic pens and a dozen notebooks laid out on a rickety wooden
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This used to be a really big stationery stall. I had millions
of Leones worth of stock in that cellar. Now, this does not even
look like a serious business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as anyone knows, the fire earlier this month at the City
Hotel (its real name) was unrelated to Sierra Leone's nine years of
war and butchery or to the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
whose captive leader, Foday Sankoh, wants to run the country. The
blaze was started by a paraffin lamp or an electrical failure,
police believe.
</P>
<P>
   But the seedy hotel with its $3.50 room price was the reminder _
for those who knew _ of the Freetown that Greene knew when he
served here as a Colonial Officer in the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   The capital is still ``an impression of heat and damp'' where
``nature, conventionally grand, rises in tree-covered hills above
the sea, powerless to carry off the shabby town.''
</P>
<P>
   And Freetown's Anglican cathedral, ``laterite bricks and tin
with a square tower,'' its Norman Church, ``sticking up out of the
early morning fog'' are still, as Greene wrote, a reminder that
``one was back in home waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Brigadier David Richards, heading the current British operation
to secure Freetown, the airport at Lungi and to aid the
pro-government offensive against the RUF, says he has never before
so often been asked to recolonize a place.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Parkinson, a customer at the sock stand, was 12 years old
when the Queen of England came here on April 27, 1961, to declare
Sierra Leone independent after 153 years of British rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day,'' he said. ``We had parades all over town
and a great celebration at the `Recre' (sports field). We had a man
we called Father Christmas who gave us all presents that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we want our colonial masters to come back. They gave
us back our country but we mismanaged it because of envy and greed
for material things.
</P>
<P>
   ``After independence, the ruling elite _ the Krios who came back
from slavery when British philanthropists established this Free
Town _ wanted to be like the white man. Our leaders have not
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be superior, they want to have all the wealth
like the white man and to send their children to schools overseas.
If we get rid of Sankoh, another one like him will come along and
want all the diamond wealth,'' said Parkinson, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was critical of the colonizers because ``everything ugly
in Freetown was European.'' He said: ``England had planted this
town, the tin shacks and the Remembrance Day posters and then
withdrawn up the hillside to smart bungalows with wide windows and
electric fans and perfect service.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, from Hill Station, where the Presidential Lodge is now
situated, President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah looks down on a town in the
throes of recolonization.
</P>
<P>
   The police chief, Keith Biddall, is British. The finance
ministry is run by the British and the armed forces are about to
be, thanks to a (pounds sterling)20 million ($35 million)
``training program.''
</P>
<P>
   The favorite football team in this city, which Leo Blair
(British Prime Minister Tony Blair's father) visited as a law
examiner, is Manchester United. The mobile phone company and the
ferry to Lungi are run by Britons.
</P>
<P>
   So popular is the presence of the Royal Marines, who man the
roadblock leading to the British operations center at Aberdeen
Point, that the locals joke: ``You are now entering London,
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the good feeling towards Britain was consolidated by
Peter Penfold, the popular former British High Commissioner, who
when he left Freetown for the last time in April was treated to an
impromptu motorcade through the capital.
</P>
<P>
   His successor, Alan Jones, has not had time to grow into the
role yet. But he will, said Rahim: ``Britain is our friend. We want
the British soldiers to stay for as long as possible. It is so
important for us to know that they care.'' &QL; 
