r k BC-`TOILET-TO-TAP'-CALIF     06-02 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`TOILET-TO-TAP'-CALIF-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOILET-TO-TAP WATER SCHEME RAISES A STINK IN CALIFORNIA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a scare going around the San Fernando
Valley in Los Angeles. In this tract of suburban communities laid
out between the mountains and the desert, the authorities are so
short of water _ or so the breathless rumor goes _ that they are
seriously considering recycling human excrement and plunging it
straight back into the drinking supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toilet to tap'' is what the scheme is being called. The local
newspaper, the Los Angeles Daily News, is up in arms already (``Can
Valley overcome `yuck' factor?'' it asked in a headline), as are
quite a few residents worried about their property values and the
mutterings of unkind neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   So-called experts have been brought in from the other side of
the country to drown the health assurances of public authorities in
a cold shower of skepticism. Both the Department of Water and Power
and the Los Angeles City Council have called special sessions to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Could the rumors possibly be true? At least on the surface, it
certainly seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are enacting something called the East Valley
Water Recycling Project, which will take waste water, purify it,
reintroduce it into the ground and let it seep back into the
household supply over a five-year cycle. Some of this waste water
will indeed come from toilets.
</P>
<P>
   But is this any cause for alarm? This is where things _ pardon
the expression _ become somewhat murkier. The Daily News reported
excitedly how the scheme risked exposing tens of thousands of
households to chemicals whose long-term effects and detectability
were unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is human waste,'' the Daily News quoted Lori Dinkin,
president of the Valley Village Homeowners Association, as
exclaiming. ``I'm very uneasy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a similar scheme was proposed in San Diego, 120
miles south of Los Angeles, but was scrapped last year after
protests from residents.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a tussle in the San Gabriel Mountains in 1995
when the Miller brewing company worried that a recycling scheme
upriver from the source of its beer water would give its products a
bad name. The yuck factor thus appears to be genuine.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, every water expert in Los Angeles swears that
the process is safe. All water is recycled eventually, they argue;
this is merely a scientific method for speeding up the process and
sparing precious groundwater resources into the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really toilet to tap, anyway, it's more like washing
machine to tap. There's nothing unusual about it,'' said Lynne
Plambeck, a former water official and environmental activist in
north Los Angeles county. ``When you build houses all over
everywhere, as they have in this city, then you have to recycle
water. There is no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Recycling has, in fact, gone on at two locations in Southern
California since the 1960s, and there has not been a single health
problem reported.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, plenty of other communities treat sewage water and
then dump it in river beds, where it eventually seeps into aquifers
feeding into households. Again, there seem to be no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the San Fernando Valley getting so upset? Could it be
something to do with the area's peculiar historical dependence on
water (the Valley was only built thanks to a giant scam by the Los
Angeles city fathers, who drained a whole farming valley in the
Sierra Nevada foothills and pumped the water 250 miles south)?
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled historical scores might have something to do with it,
since the recycling scheme has virtually been forced onto Los
Angeles as a result of a court settlement with the descendants of
those unlucky farmers who saw their livelihoods sucked away at the
beginning of the twentieth century.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also another sneaky agenda at work.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley is lobbying to secede from Los Angeles,
arguing that the only things the city authorities ever bring are
urban blight, crime and mismanaged schools. The Daily News, in
particular, has been in the forefront of efforts to denigrate the
city of Los Angeles at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that, without Los Angeles, the Valley would have
almost no water at all. What better way to lobby for independence
than to tell prospective voters that L.A.'s Department of Water and
Power is trying to poison them with recycled excrement from someone
else's toilet? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
