<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEMICAL-WEAPON-CLEANUP-STALLED-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESTRUCTION OF CHEMICAL WEAPONS IS DEADLY SLOW  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF JUNE 5, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By DEBORA MacKENZIE  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cash cuts and a lack of clean disposal technology look likely to
prevent Russia and the United States from keeping promises to
destroy their chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Countries signed up to the Chemical Weapons Convention are meant
to destroy their chemical weapons arsenals by April 29, 2007. But
officials from Russia and the United States told delegates in The
Hague that they will not make the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Russia simply hasn't enough cash for the task, says Valery Semin
of the Russian foreign ministry. Money has become even tighter
since the United States stopped funding Russia's chemical weapons
destruction program last year after Russia failed to fund its share
of the work.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, weapons destruction has been stymied by
local opposition to incinerators. The U.S. Army insists it can burn
its 32,000 tons of nerve agents and mustard gas safely, and on
time. But environmentalists in the towns of Pueblo, Colo., and Blue
Grass, Ky., where 3,130 tons of mustard and nerve gas are stored,
have convinced Congress to halt incinerator construction and look
for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Braun, head of military technology at the National
Research Council, told the conference that no alternative is likely
to be available for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to working toward the 2007 deadline,'' says
Gloria Patten, deputy assistant secretary of the army, in charge of
chemical demilitarization. ``That's not saying we're going to make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Army officials say it is riskier to store the chemical weapons
than burn them. But objectors point to two releases in May of the
nerve gas sarin at the army's incinerator in Tooele, Utah _
apparently after some weapons got stuck in the plant's input
chutes.
</P>
<P>
   The two most promising alternatives to incineration start by
cutting the weapons up and stewing them in water at 40 degrees
Celsius until most of the chemicals decompose. This is effective
for mustard and nerve agents, but tricky for the propellants and
explosives in the weapons, says Braun, some of which can recombine
and explode.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical agents themselves are broken down into chemicals
which could be used to make more chemical weapons, and under the
convention, these too must be destroyed. One promising treatment is
to use soil bacteria immobilized in a foam. Astonishingly, these
bacteria, which come from soil near army chemical testing ranges,
thrive on mustard gas. These are partnered with nematode worms that
eat surplus bacteria, reducing waste.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the technique works better for mustard than for nerve
gas. But Johnson says that with the right bugs, it could work for
nerve gas, and for PCBs and pesticides too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
