<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Letter of the law often needs a lick of common sense
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Georgia _ Charles Stith, U.S. ambassador to
Tanzania recently chronicled the story of his son's arrest by the
Atlanta subway police.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, the young man, a star student at Morehouse
College, after buying a token, got on a train with his bicycle.
Maneuvering his bike through the gate with help from an elderly
passenger, he forgot to drop the token.
</P>
<P>
   After boarding the train, he was approached by a transit
policeman who inquired why he hadn't paid his fare. The young man
apologized and offered the token to the officer. Rather than
accept, the officer took him off the train at the next stop. He was
handcuffed and carried to jail, where he was booked and put through
the criminal routine. His personal belongings were confiscated, and
his mug shot taken in the eight hours he was incarcerated. His
father suspects racism was involved.
</P>
<P>
   It may be of little comfort to the Stiths, but occasional cop
stupidity isn't totally confined to citizens of color, or even
young black men.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Massengale, organist at Fayetteville's First Methodist
Church, is a native-born lifelong resident of Fayette County,
middle-age, white. He plays piano at a popular Italian restaurant.
He cheerfully lends his musical talents to charitable and civic
events.
</P>
<P>
   This was a busy day for Rick. He had to go to the church to
practice a piece the choir was doing on Sunday. He was doing dinner
music at Baci's and before that, playing for the christening of a
new grand piano at the Fayetteville library.
</P>
<P>
   He happened to be driving his wife's car instead of his own. He
parked it on the curb next to church, across from the courthouse.
It was about 3 in the afternoon when he finished practicing on the
church organ and began to load the instruments he would use that
evening at the restaurant _ an electronic keyboard and all the
paraphernalia that goes with modern music-making.
</P>
<P>
   While loading the car, he noticed a city police cruiser parked
behind him. He wondered why a cop would be sitting in his car on a
side street next to the church on such a hot afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The police cruiser followed as he drove away from the church and
turned left on Ga. 54. Just after he crossed Ga. 85 at the
courthouse intersection, the cruiser turned on the blue lights.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled, Rick pulled into the driveway of the former Farmer's
and Merchant's bank. When he started to get out of his car, the
policeman made a motion toward his gun and instructed him to stay
in the car. Rick produced his driver's license and proof of
insurance, and then asked the officer what it was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're driving with an expired tag,'' he was informed. He was
surprised. He had purchased a tag for his own car about two weeks
earlier. ``I guess my wife thought I had taken care of her tag, and
I thought she had,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tag office is right across the street,'' he said to the
officer. ``I can go over there and get the tag right now.'' He was
unlikely to become a fugitive from justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' replied the officer. ``I've got to impound your car.
I've already called a tow truck.'' By this time, a second police
cruiser had arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Rick asked the officer to cancel the tow truck, offering to pay
whatever the wrecker company might have charged. He really needed
to be on his way. He explained his tight schedule, including
playing at the fund-raiser for the city library. He asked to drive
his instruments to the restaurant before the tow truck took his
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the officer. ``We'll take care of that.'' So right
there in the middle of Fayetteville, in sight of the tag office,
they loaded Rick's keyboard and other stuff into the two police
cruisers. Off went his wife's car to the pound, at a fee of 80
bucks. Patrice, Baci's proprietor, was stunned to see her piano
player arrive with a two-cruiser police escort.
</P>
<P>
   After calling his wife for a ride, Rick barely managed to get
home for supper, make it to the library, and back to Baci's for his
dinner performance. Now all he has to do is go to court and see how
much he owes for the crime of forgetting to buy a tag for his
wife's car.
</P>
<P>
   I sympathize. I forget things. About two years ago, late at
night, my wife and I encountered a road-block license check in the
little town of Gray. To my surprise, my license was three-months
expired. I figured I was in for a hard time from a small town cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better let your wife drive until you get a new license,'' said
the young officer, and we were on our way. I'm glad I wasn't
apprehended in Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   We have the case of the 20-year-old bride headed for a honeymoon
in Cancun being taken into custody at Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport
after discovering and reporting a .22-caliber pistol in a carry-on
bag borrowed from her mother.
</P>
<P>
   One Atlanta police officer is in trouble for ignoring an order
to arrest the young lady. Clayton County Magistrate Judge John
Campbell had the good sense to refuse a warrant that would have
sent her to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a dab of common sense beats the letter of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
