<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2869 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's $20 mil obesity study a prime example of fiscal
gluttony
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to spend $20 million on a study to find
out why so many Americans eat food that makes them fat.
</P>
<P>
   That's a waste of tax dollars. Americans are fat, not stupid.
</P>
<P>
   A group of nutritionists and dietary nannies at a White House
conference on nutrition want to raise taxes to fund new government
programs that will brainwash Americans into eating broccoli, tofu
and bulgur wheat chaff.
</P>
<P>
   The last White House Conference on Food Nutrition and Health
called for new taxes and government programs to combat hunger. That
was 31 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Professional worriers at the 1969 nutrition conference must have
done a good job. Today, 55 percent of adult Americans are fat or
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of U.S. children are overweight. Another 25
percent of American youngsters are likely to become fatties when
they grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government began issuing dietary guidelines 20 years
ago, the number of overweight Americans has ballooned 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two decades of government dietary warnings, officials at
the U.S. Department of Agriculture estimate that only 12 percent of
Americans follow their dietary advice to eat balanced diets with
plenty of fruits, veggies and grains.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 25 percent of Americans know the government's ``five
a day'' slogan, agonize our tax-paid protectors.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know the ``five a day'' slogan, but I know about Wendy's
new steak sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem, according to government nutrition officials.
The Ag Department spends a mere $350 million tax dollars every year
to nag citizens about their ``five a day'' nutrition needs compared
to $7 billion spent each year on advertising by Wendy's and the
rest of the food industry.
</P>
<P>
   If the government tries to outspend the food industry in an
attempt to get citizens to eat their peas, Americans will lose
weight from being overtaxed. No one could afford an order of super
fries, much less a Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   A White House conference nutritionist called for a new tax on
candy bars and other food products with high sugar content. He said
the taxes could be used to convince Americans to eat healthier
food.
</P>
<P>
   Bless his heart, the man simply doesn't understand how
Washington works, much less why so many Americans choose to eat
junk food.
</P>
<P>
   A raw deal for consumers
</P>
<P>
   Despite congressional chest thumping about the glories of free
trade, Congress gives U.S. sugar producers a $1.6 billion annual
gift in the form of a federal sugar program. Subsidies for the U.S.
sugar industry come out of the pockets of American consumers. To
keep sugar prices propped artificially high, the government buys
and stores sugar with no plans to ever use the stored commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar industry officials turn around and give big contributions
out of their guaranteed profits back to Congress. It's a sweet deal
for everyone except American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition bureaucrats should not count on a tax on candy bars to
fund their ``five a day'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the argument that Americans should have the right to
choose to get fat, government nutritionists say overweight people
are at greater risk to be afflicted with diabetes, high blood
pressure, strokes, heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Health problems can end up costing the taxpayers, which is why
government nutritionists need to raise taxes and spend more money
to convince Americans to heed the warnings in their ``five a day''
campaign, whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: Rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
