<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONSERVATIVE PARTY POISED TO ENDORSE LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMARONECK, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio has moved away from key
right-of-center stands on abortion and education even as the state
Conservative Party prepares to endorse his bid for the U.S. Senate
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is positioning himself as a mainstream Republican in hopes
of capturing bipartisan support in his race against First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Democratic candidate. They are dueling
to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was the beneficiary of a Conservative-sponsored television
advertisement touting his candidacy that began airing Thursday in
New York City and Albany. The party hopes to raise $1 million over
the next five months for Lazio's campaign and ``party building.''
</P>
<P>
   At a ``Mainstream Express'' campaign bus stop outside Mamaroneck
Avenue Elementary in this leafy Westchester County town, Lazio
indicated he is uneasy about the blanket use of vouchers and said
he has ``yet to see a plan'' for teachers' merit pay ``that I am
really comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   He also defended his abortion platform after criticism Wednesday
from anti-abortion activists at a rally in Binghamton. He generally
favors abortion rights, but opposes late-term abortions and federal
funding for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on the far end with both sides of the issue
who only define your position if you're 100 percent with them,'' he
said Thursday. ``I just don't think that's where New Yorkers are. I
try to make these decisions and respect both sides of the argument
without necessarily having to agree with both sides of the
argument.''
</P>
<P>
   On private school vouchers, Lazio said he favors them in cases
of ``schools that are failing, and there's no opportunity for
children to learn, or if they're not safe.'' On merit pay, Lazio
said he would need to ``make sure there is objective criteria, not
subjective criteria. ... I am concerned about that part of merit
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lazio has all but officially accepted the Conservative
endorsement, expected to come Saturday at the party's convention in
Albany. Party Chairman Mike Long suggested that Lazio may be more
open to those core conservative issues later in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't have the whole loaf, we have a pretty good
slice here in Rick Lazio,'' Long said. ``He's more open to more of
those key issues than Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton favors abortion rights unconditionally and would reject
proposals for school vouchers and merit pay for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Conservative Party should tell New Yorkers why they are
really endorsing Rick Lazio this weekend _ he supports restrictions
on a woman's right to choose and opposes common-sense gun control
measures,'' said Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
