<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOMMA-HNS     06-02 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOMMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `BIG MOMMA' IS HEAVY WITH STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lest you make the same mistake I did: ``Big Momma's House'' is
not the name of the Shelley Winters comeback vehicle. Nor is it the
sequel to ``Soul Food'' (1997), although it co-stars Nia Long,
features a spread of good eats that strikes the mother lode of
fingerlickingoodness and provides ample time to get acquainted with
a plus-size woman. No, ``Big Momma's House'' is a high-spirited,
big-bottomed Polaroid of the comedian in a fat suit.
</P>
<P>
   The clown in question happens to be Martin Lawrence. So it's no
wonder that when his FBI agent goes undercover donning what we're
to believe is a homemade get-up, ``Big Momma's'' feels like a
slap-happy throwback to the salad days of Lawrence's Fox sitcom.
Ahh, the days when the ghost of Flip Wilson seemed to come over
Lawrence and inspire him to lose himself inside an variety pack of
African-American grotesques. Shanaynay would be Wilson's Geraldine.
And when ``Martin's'' Tichina Arnold shows up to have Lawrence's
Big Momma deliver her baby, it's a bit too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Also too close for comfort is the film's naive courtship of dumb
black stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence plays Malcolm, the agent trying to catch an escaped
robber and murderer named Trent (a dangerous Terrence Howard, who
appears to have strolled off the set of the new ``Shaft'' movie),
who is looking for the $20 million left in the possession of his
ex-girlfriend Sherry (Long). Expecting Sherry, who's on the lam
from her ex-con ex-man, to unwittingly lead the feds to her man,
they stake out the most remote place possible the California girl
could flee: the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm is sent to a small town in Georgia where Sherry will
probably look up Hattie Mae Pierce, a k a Big Momma (Ella
Mitchell), that neighborhood force with girth that merely indicates
the size of her love. Before Sherry even arrives, Hattie Mae leaves
town to care for an ill friend, and to keep Sherry around long
enough to lure Trent, Malcolm becomes Big Momma.
</P>
<P>
   He builds a fat suit and rubber masks, presumably using the
``M:I-2,'' at-home kit, with the help of his partner, John, played
by Paul Giamatti, whose hangdog face and gruffly congested manner
of speaking evoke an entire bygone era of black-and-white
television sitcoms. When the mayhem, which includes a rump-shake
with the real Big Momma to Rick James' ``Give It to Me, Baby,''
comes his way, Giamatti faces it like an exemplary good sport. If
he's on the receiving end of the shenanigans, Lawrence, of course,
is doing the giving.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Big Momma'' doesn't get turned out until the home stretch.
Before that, the film is just a vulgar-looking shot at ``Mrs.
Doubtfire.'' Though with Lawrence impersonating an ersatz domestic,
Momma often seems like an invocation of real dignified big mommas
like Esther Rolle and Mabel King.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a man in a muumuu _ and it's not good.
The same can also be said for the costumes and makeup techniques
used on both Lawrence's Big Momma and Mitchell's. It usually looks
like an eclair went off on someone in a housecoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma'' is at its most unimpeachable when it just lets
Lawrence rip in the costume, which must be made of down. He goes
ballistic in a game of roughhouse. He gets his karate on in a
self-defense class. He brings down the tabernacle when he testifies
in church. He speaks in hip-hop terms, at some point using ``wobble
wobble'' to the delight of many a No Limit Records fan.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Raja Gosnell, a guy who showed a gift for
featherweight screwball last spring in ``Never Been Kissed.'' He's
clearly more content supervising one-man shows the way he did with
Drew Barrymore in that film and with Lawrence here, just grabbing
reaction shots to the implausible bits.
</P>
<P>
   But when is the last time anybody ever went to a Martin Lawrence
movie for the realism. Good God, you go to see him keep it real,
and he does. Even so, ``Big Momma'' plays like a lower-budget
warmup for Eddie Murphy's eminent ``Nutty Professor'' sequel, which
begs the question of whether summer is big enough for two black
comedians in obese drag?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Lawrence isn't the artist Murphy is. He's funny here only
because it's an exercise in breaking character. And to put it
politely, this is not a phatic movie, just big-boned.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
