<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-     06-02 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds, adds detail on photos for first article; changes to show that
we now expect to file articles in advance, sted day before
publication.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, and continuing for six weeks, The New York
Times will publish a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Two generations after the end of legal discrimination, race
still ignites political debates _ over Civil War flags, for
example, or police profiling. But the wider public discussion of
race relations seems muted by a full-employment economy and by a
sense, particularly among many whites, that the time of large
social remedies is past. Race relations are being defined less by
political action than by daily experience, in schools, in sports
arenas, in pop culture and at worship, and especially in the
workplace. These encounters _ relations in the most literal,
everyday sense _ make up this series of reports.
</P>
<P>
   The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort by a team of
Times reporters to capture some of the troubling issues that
Americans continue to face and the voices of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   These articles, two or three each week, are long, at 6,000 words
and up. They will move on the News Service wire a day or more in
advance of publication _ where possible _ and will carry a slug of
the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. In addition, the News Service will file
an abridged version of each article, approximately half the length
of the original. All of the articles will be accompanied by photos
for photo clients and be available for separate purchase by other
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief description of the first three articles.
</P>
<P>
   For release Sunday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH (Decatur, Ga.) _ Nearly 50 years after the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. scolded Christians for making 11 a.m. Sunday
the most segregated hour of the week, the Assembly of God
Tabernacle here is the rarest of religious institutions: a truly
integrated church in the heart of the South. And yet, the
Tabernacle is deeply conservative, socially and theologically. What
draws its members is the intensity of their Pentacostal faith,
which teaches that the Holy Spirit can move in the lives of all
believers, regardless of background. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, NYT101,102,103,104,105,106 were sent to NYT photo
clients on Friday, June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story will be filed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For release Monday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS (Miami) _ Before they left Cuba for America in
1994 Joel Ruiz, who is black, and Achmed Valdes, who is white, were
the best of friends. Today, in Miami, the two men live only four
miles apart, not even 15 minutes by car. Yet they are separated by
a far greater distance, one they say they never envisioned back in
Cuba. In ways that are obvious to the black man but far less so to
the white one, they have grown apart in the U.S. because of race.
For the first time, they inhabit a place where the color of their
skin defines the outlines of their lives _ where they live, the
friends they make, how they speak, what they wear, even what they
eat. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   For release Wednesday, June 7:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MILITARY (Fort Knox, Ky.) _ On a chill December morning,
two soldiers _ one black, one white, both part of an institution
portrayed as a model of race relations _ stood only yards apart in
the middle of this sprawling base, each believing himself the
victim of racism; one because of an award, the other because of a
transfer. The Army is not supposed to harbor racial resentment
anymore. Its work force is integrated. The Army is one of the few
institutions in America in which blacks routinely boss around
whites, and supposedly no one gives it a second thought. But that
is an idealized image. The Pentagon has found that two-thirds of
its men and women had experienced a racially offensive encounter in
the previous 12 months. And those findings are more or less
mirrored here at Fort Knox. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Paul is executive editor.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Perlman is deputy editor.
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Gary McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   The evening supervisor is Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor is Ray Krueger.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend editor is Lynn Hoogenboom.
</P>
