<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-GYPSY-HNS     06-02 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GYPSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOCUMENTARY FOCUSES ON ROMANY CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a girl living in Britain, filmmaker Jasmine Dellal was told
that if she misbehaved, Gypsies would take her away. Haunted, in
part, by that bizarre attempt to straighten her out, Dellal set out
to shoot a documentary about Gypsy _ or, more correctly, Romany _
culture.
</P>
<P>
   She made telephone calls all over the United States looking for
Gypsy immigrants to share with her details about their heritage for
her film. Jimmy Marks was the only man who called back, telling her
a story ripe for a movie.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how the result, ``American Gypsy: A Stranger in
Everybody's Land,'' manages to be something more than self
indulgent, you'd have to meet Marks first. He is a rotund
loudmouth, running a used-car business in Spokane, Wash. Then you'd
have to meet his kin, a warm, volatile extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Marks entered the public eye after he went on campaign to clear
his family's _ and by extension, his people's _ name after the
police descended upon his home 10 years ago looking to confiscate
what they wrongly believed was a slew of stolen property. He
returned Dellal's call, presumably to try, after a insidiously
judgmental piece on ``Eye to Eye,'' the defunct Connie Chung news
mag, to find a more sympathetic eye. And unquestionably, Dellal's
is it.
</P>
<P>
   After a cursory, but enlightening overview of Romany life,
Dellal shows her five-year immersion in the substantial Marks
household, practically disappearing into the ruins of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Her many months with the Markses are distilled into 80 fraught
minutes, and what must have been hours of Jimmy talking to her
answering machine form a journal that provides the film with the
hearty relationship at the film's core. The salesman in him lies to
her. She calls him on it. For her, Marks completes a perfect,
eloquent circle: Maybe a Gypsy walked off with a little piece of
her soul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-MISSILE-BOS &LR;      06-02 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSILE PLAN IS CALLED UNLIKELY IN CLINTON TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Technical problems and political opposition make it
unlikely that President Clinton will decide on a national defense
system before his term expires, US officials and defense analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Even inside the Pentagon, which is overseeing the tests,
ballistic-missile specialists have expressed strong doubts in
meetings that they will have enough information to recommend
whether a system is technologically feasible, two senior Defense
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and top Pentagon officials had vowed to decide late this
summer whether to start building a national missile defense, a
costly and controversial system that would theoretically safeguard
the United States against a limited attack by long-range ballistic
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit to Moscow this weekend, Clinton will try to
sell the idea of a US missile shield to Russian President Vladimir
V. Putin, who has objected to any such broad defense because it
could further shift the balance of power away from Russia as well
as break the terms of the countries' key nuclear arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
   If Putin continues to voice strong objections, say
administration officials, Clinton could very well eventually decide
that is reason enough not to proceed now.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton were to persuade Putin to renegotiate the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty _ which White House aides admit is
unlikely _ he would face a growing array of obstacles back home.
Many legislators, both Democrats and Republicans, have threatened
in recent weeks to reject the Clinton plan, variously calling it
too far-reaching or too narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Two former Clinton aides, Deputy Defense secretaries John Deutch
and John P. White, are now criticizing the administration plan as
diplomatically unwise, in an article to be published next week in
Foreign Policy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, prominent scientists are increasingly
skeptical that the technology for such a system is ready to move to
the next phase, in which the military would begin building a
missile defense center in Alaska. One senior Pentagon official said
Thursday the project's viability still ``looks very iffy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has little evidence to the contrary: Of
the two missile tests it has conducted, only one successfully
intercepted a decoy in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   A third test, which was supposed to take place this spring and
could have bolstered the Defense Department's case, has been
postponed at least twice because of technical problems. Now
scheduled for the first week in July, the test may not satisfy
military officials even if it succeeds. According to the Pentagon
official, ``the feeling is there isn't enough time to make a good
recommendation'' to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And many in the nuclear weapons control community _ both doves
and hawks _ agree. ``What you now have is the increasing likelihood
that the decision won't be this year,'' said Joseph Cirincione,
director of the non-proliferation project at the Carnegie Endowment
for Peace. ``Political doubts are rising. I wouldn't say they're
determinate yet, but they are on the rise. The winds have shifted
on missile defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, nothing has changed. Clinton, in both public and
private, has said he still plans to make a determination before his
term ends next January, and he is proceeding apace. He spent the
last few days trying to soothe fears of European leaders who worry
that a US missile system might prompt a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen expects to make his
recommendation to the White House in August, when he hopes the
``technology has matured to the point'' where he could comfortably
advise the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't reached that point yet,'' Cohen said in an interview
Thursday. ``That's why I'm going to be looking very carefully at
the next test. I still have to take into account, not only the
technology, but the implications for the arms control
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But timing alone is raising doubts about reaching a decision
soon. Only a 10-day window exists in July for the military to
conduct the tests, in which an interceptor rocket is launched from
a test facility in the Pacific Ocean and tries to intercept a dummy
warhead mid-air. After July 10, the Pentagon cannot start up again
until mid-August, because of environmental agreements. Any further
delay could push Cohen's review back as far as September, forcing
Clinton to make an announcement in the heat of the presidential
campaign, muddying the project with politics further still.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are plenty of critics who already see Clinton's
determination as wholly political. Many Democrats believe he
pursued the missile-defense project simply to steal the issue from
Republicans (``a classic Clintonian triangulation,'' said one
missile specialist).
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, on the other hand, say he is pretending to
favor the missile shield to help Vice President Al Gore, but that
Clinton never intended to implement the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an administration that hasn't wanted anything to do
with missile defense from the day it took office. . . And they
certainly don't have any intention of having a missile defense
before Clinton leaves,'' said Frank Gaffney, director of the
conservative Center for Security Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by all appearances, the decision may be largely out of
Clinton's hands. Even though there is tremendous political will to
build a US missile defense of some sort, there appears to be
virtually none for getting it done according to Clinton
administration plans.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton can give his blessing to the project at any
time, setting in motion the building of the Alaska site sometime
next year, he has virtually no support in Congress, where any
alterations to the 1972 ABM treaty would have to be ratified.
Senator Jesse Helms, the North Carolina Republican who heads the
Foreign Relations Committee, has already promised to reject any
Clinton treaty deal.
</P>
<P>
   And although Clinton could proceed singlehandedly, with neither
the backing of Congress nor an ABM agreement with Russia, George
Shultz, a former US secretary of state and an adviser to Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush, offered this cautionary
note: ``I don't think he could make an effective decision. . .
because in order to spend money, you have to get it authorized and
appropriated.''
</P>
<P>
   In this election year, more than two dozen Republican senators
have said they would rather wait to approve an ABM treaty
alteration until after November, in the hope that a Republican
committed to a more robust missile defense would win the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, meanwhile, are fearful of any steps that would
undermine the ABM treaty. Others, such as Senator John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts, have expressed concerns about the technology, and
hope the administration would consider other proposals _ such as
one that intercepts enemy rockets when they are launched, instead
of as they near their targets _ before carving the current one into
stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that few people consider this the optimum approach,''
said former Defense Secretary Harold Brown, who worked in the
Carter administration. ``It really strikes most people, I think, as
a compromise that will satisfy neither the arms controllers nor the
defense hawkers. Now clearly, the Pentagon is at least going along,
and the State Department is going along. But I doubt this is the
preferred solution of anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Brown added: ``That is often the case in the US
government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
