<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAN THOSE BLOODY FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Million Mom Marchers want something concrete to do, I
have a suggestion. Get airlines to ban gun movies.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, I wrote about how one of my sons, then 9, and I
were subjected on a Sunday morning Northwest Airlines flight to
``True Lies,'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger. Northwest's idea of
family entertainment was seeing 85 people killed or wounded, many
with visible bullet holes and blood.
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed. In March I flew American Airlines from San
Juan to Boston. The route is often packed with children. The movie
was the James Bond thriller, ``The World is Not Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   This movie had a PG-13 rating. A quarter of the movie, 42
minutes, was devoted to scenes of deadly mayhem in which the gun is
the star and corpses are the supporting cast. Since James Bond has
two separate body counts, one for his copulations and one for his
corpses, Bond's allotted time to rack up corpses is not the same as
Schwarzenegger's. Still, Bond is quite a terminator in his own
right. By the time the movie was over, there were between 30 and 35
people killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens with three bad guys shot (one with a visible
bullet hole) or knifed to death. In the next violent scene, a man
is blown up by a bomb. A female assassin fails to kill Bond with
machine gun fire, then commits suicide by blowing up her hot air
balloon. Four assassins on snowmobiles not only fail to get Bond,
they crash and explode. Then Bond kills someone and throws him into
a garbage hopper.
</P>
<P>
   When he is not actually killing people, Bond negotiates with the
forces of evil by sticking guns in the backs of henchmen or
thrusting the barrel at their heads. Of all the killings, none was
more sick than when Bond shoots at point-blank range the villainess
with whom he had sex earlier in the film.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of violence and misogyny is not only twisted in its
own right, it shows how numb America is to guns compared to other
outrages. A few weeks after that flight, our family went to see
``Erin Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, we did not know whether to take our other son, now 9,
with us. The movie was rated R. As it turned out, ``Erin
Brockovich,'' a movie about a nearly destitute heroine who fights
against corporate greed, was rated R because of Brockovich's
profanity, words you can hear at Fenway Park. Deciding the message
was more important than some of the words from the messenger, we
took our son and had no second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, many children, especially girls, have missed out on
``Erin Brockovich'' because parents were scared off by the R rating
(there was only one other child in the theater the Friday evening
we went). But it apparently is just fine to subject children and
teens on an airplane to two hours of gun glorification, dead
bodies, and disposable sex partners.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The World is Not Enough'' opened last November, it was
No. 1 its first weekend, grossing $37.2 million. It was the best
opening in the history of MGM. It currently is at the top of the
home video charts.
</P>
<P>
   A huge reason for the movie's success was the PG-13 rating,
which, unlike R-rated films, allows adolescents to go without their
parents. The PG-13, instead of R, allowed MGM to heavily advertise
the Bond movie on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there ever was a statement on the strength of PG-13, it is
this movie,'' said Larry Gleason, the president of worldwide
distribution for MGM. ``Sixty percent of our male audience was
under 25. We are getting a very young audience. (They) have to be
credited for our increased business.''
</P>
<P>
   What people do for the personal entertainment is their business.
But this is also the post-Columbine age where we are urgently
telling children not to solve their problems _ as Bond does _ with
guns. We are suspending children in schools for even making the
motion of a gun with their fingers. Thus, the glorification of
guns, with the attendant blood splatter and perforated bodies,
should no longer be allowed in airplanes, where people have to
endure the visual carnage whether or not they choose to wear
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence to suggest that if people do not want these
kind of movies on flights, they do not have to have them. A few
months ago United Airlines dumped ``The General's Daughter'' after
customer complaints (it was rated R due to a graphic images
relating to sexual violence, including rape).
</P>
<P>
   That is a beginning. Much of last month's Million Mom March
rightfully focused on political pressure for gun restrictions. Just
as important is the cultural war, persuading Hollywood that guns
can no longer be thrust at the viewer's head. If we can create
smoke-free flights, we can work toward gun-free flights. American
Airlines obviously thought it was fine to show ``The World is Not
Enough.'' The message it should be hearing is ``enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
