<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN AT WORK, IT MAKES SENSE TO ... WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Recently, my company installed Websense. Now,
whenever I go to a site that is not work-related, I get a message
saying, ``Access to the desired Web page is not permitted.'' So, is
there any way around this?
</P>
<P>
   _ Senseless
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SENSELESS: I suppose you could go to work for some company
that actually trusts its employees not to spend all day booking
flights or downloading pictures of Christina Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   Websense is a commercial package that monitors what employees
are doing on the Internet and blocks certain activity. There are
only two reasons why a company would install it: Either the boss is
a killjoy and doesn't want you to have any fun, or there's been
some sort of abuse of Internet privileges.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe Websense's advertising, during a regular workday,
70 percent of all Internet porn traffic occurs, 30 percent to 40
percent of surfing is non-business-related and 60 percent of online
purchases are made.
</P>
<P>
   So, no, I'm not going to tell you how to beat Websense. You can
play when you're not at work.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did I mention that Websense logs all your attempts to get to
those off-limits sites? Think about that the next time the boss
calls you in for your performance review.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How do you type those Spanish letters like the
letter ``n'' with the tilde on top or the upside-down question
mark?
</P>
<P>
   _ Multilingual
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MULTI: It really depends on the word processor you use. In
DOS, you've got more than 200 characters available to you.
Obviously, that's a lot more than can fit on the standard English
keyboard, so programmers came up with a way to insert special
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, that involves pressing Alt and Shift while keying in
a character's value on the numeric keypad. For instance, that ``n''
with a tilde is 164 and the Spanish question mark is 168. Find
yourself an ASCII chart to get the rest. And don't worry about what
``ASCII'' stands for. You've got enough to worry about already.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Windows word processor, there are even more
special characters available. Most of the programs have some sort
of ``insert'' function that let you pick the character from an
on-screen chart. Good programs even have shortcut keys, although
they tend to be real finger-benders. In Word, for example, that
tilde thing is done by first pressing Control, Shift and the tilde
key simultaneously, then pressing the ``n'' key. The question mark
is done with Alt, Control, Shift and ? all at once. It takes some
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever program you have, all the info you need is tucked
somewhere deep within its help file.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is it possible to put Windows 95 on my
computer? It's an IBM PS/1 (486SX, 50-megabyte hard drive, four
megabytes of memory).
</P>
<P>
   _ Upgrader:
</P>
<P>
   DEAR UPGRADER: Well, I suppose anything is possible, as long as
you don't mind having a computer that has no storage space left and
runs slower than my two-buck Rolex knockoff.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Microsoft says you meet the minimum requirements,
here in the real world you need at least 16 megabytes of memory _
no, make that 32 _ and at least 55 megabytes of disk space. Unless
you want to do a major upgrade on a relatively obsolete machine,
avoid the headache.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay is also relatively obsolete. In fact, almost
all of his components need to be replaced. Write him at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: 390-7257. In the nonvirtual
world, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
