<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOST FOR AFFORDABLE HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Franklin Raines came east from Seattle as a teenage Harvard
freshman, he navigated around Boston on the subway.
</P>
<P>
   When he came back to the law school, he had a car. But he tried
to drive routes he had learned on the subway _ heading into Park
Street before taking a left or a right _ big mistake. Wednesday
morning he didn't have to drive himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was driven through Roxbury and Mission Hill in a big black
van filled with people who work for him, the chairman-CEO of the
world's largest financial company that isn't a bank _ Fannie Mae.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the nation's prime money men _ Raines ran the federal
budget for President Clinton as head of Office of Management and
Budget _ and now as boss of Fannie Mae, Raines literally moves
billions with a flick of a finger.
</P>
<P>
   He rode past Mission Main, a new low-rise development springing
up behind the Mission Church, with 535 new apartments up or coming,
thanks to $20 million from Raines. There are similar stories behind
Orchard Commons (76 units), Urban Edge (200), and Academy Homes I
(202).
</P>
<P>
   Alighting at Faneuil Hall for a ceremony that drew Senator
Edward Kennedy, US Representatives Joseph Moakley and Michael
Capuano, and Mayor Thomas Menino, Raines announced a new $15
billion expansion of a plan to put 115,000 more Massachusetts
families in affordable homes or rental units.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae has financed housing for 35,000 families in Boston
over the past five years with $1.7 billion from the outfit that
guarantees or otherwise makes happen one-fourth of all the home
mortages in the United States. With 4,000 employees and 365,000
shareholders (FNM on the New York Stock Exchange), Fannie Mae buys
mortgage bundles from lenders and issues securities to guarantee
the financial underpinning of more than 11 million mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stage at Faneuil Hall, on boards trod by ``patriots,
abolitionists, suffragists,'' Raines linked the principle of home
ownership to those other epochal causes. He challenged
Massachusetts, home of the first public school, university, public
library, and the computer, to set the standard for home ownership
and the family stability it confers: ``Our goal is to make
Massachusetts first in the nation in home ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking up the challenge, Kennedy said that for all of its
leadership in high-tech, medicine, education, and financial
services, ``Boston will not be Boston unless we have affordable
housing.'' Moakley ticked off the infrastructure improvements _
federal courthouse, Big Dig, convention center, harbor cleanup _
then placed affordable housing as the newest target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said for years that people form their world view by
looking out their kitchen window,'' said Moakley. And he wants more
kitchens, more windows.
</P>
<P>
   Menino put his stamp of approval on affordable housing as the
single most important need here. ``Housing is probably the No. 1
issue in our city,'' he told the 150 bankers, developers, and
housing advocates. Boston had more than 2,000 housing starts last
year, not bad for a city of less than 600,000 population, but ``we
don't want Boston to be a city only of the very rich and the very
poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino said the Fannie Mae mortgage aid rollout means ``other
cities and towns across the state can start building their share of
affordable housing. We'll show you how to do it _ maybe you don't
want to do it _ but we'll show you how.''
</P>
<P>
   Capuano hailed bankers such as Larry Fish of Citizens Bank for
``not looking to make a hit'' on every housing initiative. And
without Fannie Mae's muscle, said the rookie congressman from
Somerville, ``then virtually no project in the Boston area would
have been built.''
</P>
<P>
   Capuano complained that ``a lot of people in Washington don't
know what a three-decker is.'' He added, ``I live in a two-family;
my brother lives in a three-family; my mother's in senior housing _
anybody who gets in the way of affordable housing will be run
over!''
</P>
<P>
   Fish emphasized his bank's commitment to underserved markets.
Citizens and Fleet are major partners of Fannie Mae. Dick DeWolfe,
a realtor and developer, pointed to the gap ``between the haves and
have-nots'' in housing.
</P>
<P>
   Noting political declarations of war on drugs, war on crime, war
on poverty, DeWolfe said that all those efforts targeted inner
cities. ``We need to declare peace, not war,'' he said, and peace
for a family comes through home ownership, stability, neighborhood.
``Home ownership is the defining difference in America,'' he said,
and no one seemed to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
