<SLUG> BC-TV-SEXCITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEX AND THE CITY' IS BACK WITH WIT AND POIGNANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEX AND THE CITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Catrall, Kristin Davis,
Cynthia Nixon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On: HBO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: Sunday at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: TVMA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``Sex and the City'' is one of the few half-hour comedies
on TV that wasn't assembled at the punch-line factory.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than an incessant series of one-off jokes, punctuated by
the tin hysterics of a laugh track, it deals in the larger comic
ironies of single life and the quirky redemptions of friendship
among women. Sure, the ``Sex'' scripts can be laugh-out-loud funny,
as they pursue ripe topics like ``dating feng shui'' or as they
uncover the sexual fetishes of an army of Barney's-wearing
bachelors. But the show is also a more bittersweet study of
romantic yearning and straight female identity. One of the savviest
and sauciest comedies on TV right now, it returns for its third
season Sunday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and ``Seinfeld,'' the best part of
``Sex and the City'' is its four delightfully drawn characters _
five, if you include Manhattan. After a promising first season, the
series came into its own last year by turning the women into more
than just fashion-plate vehicles for sexual puns and dirty talk.
Charlotte (Kristin Davis), naive on the surface, turned out to be a
shark prowling cocktail parties for a wealthy man with a
circumcised penis. Brainy redhead Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) wanted to
fall in love, but her terror at the thought of losing
self-sufficiency always kept her at arm's length from her
boyfriends. Samantha (Kim Cattrall), with her tiger prints and her
fabulous beauty mark, was forever looking for sex, more sex, and
sex with men who have money, despite our persistent wish that she
would aim higher. And Carrie (Sarah Jessica Parker), the
chain-smoking journalist whose column forms the focus of the show,
became a sweet amalgamation of her three buddies _ searching for a
balance of security, independence, and uncomplicated sex. Her near
miss last year with Mr. Big (Chris Noth), which was steeped in
``The Way We Were'' allusions, was heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   This season opens with the four women resuming their mating
games aboard a ferry to Staten Island, where Carrie will judge men
for inclusion in a fire department calendar. It doesn't take long
to guess that water-hose quips will ensue and that Samantha will
make it with one of the firefighters. But, typical of the series,
the episode veers into a deeper, more provocative query about
Charlotte's hungover realization: ``Women really want to be
rescued.'' Do they? It's not the show's tightest half-hour, but by
next week ``Sex and the City'' is back in full force as Carrie, now
dating a politician, wonders, ``Can there be sex without
politics?''
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers have been offended by the show's bawdiness, and
others have frowned on the women's obsession with men. Like Elaine
Benes on ``Seinfeld,'' the ``Sex and the City'' women are
tough-minded and professionally empowered, but they are nonetheless
fixated on finding a member of the opposite sex to make them happy.
I can't say whether they should be looking elsewhere for the
meaning of life, just as I wouldn't want to warn Carrie about her
fashion sense, which, next week, brings her to ``a spin on Jackie
Kennedy, the early years.'' But until they turn their attentions to
trout fishing, or game shows, I will watch them, amused, touched,
cynical, and hopeful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BIG-BOS &LR;      06-02 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG MOMMA'S' PACKS THE LATEX LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Raja Gosnell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Darryl Quarles &AMP; Don Rhymer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Paul Giamatti, Jascha
Washington, Terrence Howard, Anthony Anderson, Ella Mitchell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 98 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's shaping up as a body-latex kind of summer. Next month Eddie
Murphy will return as the entire overstuffed Klump family in
``Nutty Professor II.'' Meanwhile, Martin Lawrence has beaten
Murphy to the fat suit in ``Big Momma's House.'' To the question of
whether ``Big Momma's House'' is a good film, the answer is that
it's good enough. It keeps its promise to throw an hour and a half
of lively entertainment at audiences. It's never slowed down by its
pseudo-poundage, and it manages a level of warmth that most of the
summer's other manufactures won't likely match.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence stars as an FBI agent and master of disguise, a talent
established in a prologue that shows him as an Asian man pretending
to be a bettor inside an illegal dogfight haven. His next
assignment sends him into silicone overdrive. When he and his nerdy
partner (Paul Giamatti) are sent to stake out a rural Georgia house
to nab a vicious escaped bank robber and his girlfriend, a single
mom played by Nia Long, Lawrence has to suit up fast when the
girlfriend's grandmother is called away to care for a sick friend.
</P>
<P>
   Because the bank robber's terrified ex-girlfriend hasn't seen
her grandmother for years, the agent is able to pull the latex over
her eyes and pass himself off as the corpulent septuagenarian, even
when his kitchen technique gives rise to a cloud of suspicion, not
to mention a cloud of smoke, when he tries to heat up a pork chop
in a sea of lard. Underneath all the rubber, his heart starts
beating faster as he predictably falls for the lovely woman he'd
like to believe is innocent and starts wooing whenever he can slip
out of the fat suit undetected.
</P>
<P>
   The plot line is pretty predictable, and so are the
complications. As the romance deepens, the young woman thinks she's
renewing what had been an estranged relationship with her
no-nonsense grandmother. Her young son sentimentally begins to bond
with the new guy in her mom's life and with the figure he thinks is
his grandmother, especially when he/she walks the boy back to a
playground where he had been humiliated and teaches his tormentors
a lesson. And of course we also know that the bank robber is going
to appear sooner or later, gun in hand, to say nothing of the real
Big Momma.
</P>
<P>
   Barely skirting offensiveness with its stereotypes, the film is
politically incorrect on a few counts. But the comedy and the sunny
tone sell it. ``Big Momma's House'' is action-packed without being
truly wild. It even puts a lid on its flatulence jokes. Actually,
it's more of a successful juggling act than it may seem, given its
prefab nature. More than a few movies have been sucked into their
own body makeup as if by quicksand. But farcical adroitness and
Martin's ablity to turn on the charm keep ``Big Momma's House''
perking along. It'll keep more than a few seats warm at the
multiplexes until the next blockbuster comes along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     06-02 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMMING FIVE LITTLE WORDS MAKES A BIG DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While declarations against homosexuality and women as pastors
have gotten the headlines, other expected changes in a Baptist
statement of faith are causing more of a furor among some members
of the giant denomination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, no explicit mention is made of the bedrock Baptist
tenet of ``the priesthood of the believer'' in the revised Baptist
Faith and Message Statement expected to be adopted this month at
the Southern Baptist Convention in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Revisers of the statement removed the words ``Baptists emphasize
the soul's competency before God, freedom in religion and the
priesthood of the believer'' from the document's preamble.
</P>
<P>
   It is a shocking omission.
</P>
<P>
   The individualistic principle that every Baptist is his or her
own ``priest'' goes back to 17th-century England when dissenters _
forerunners of modern Baptists _ risked prison and death by
rejecting the established church's practice of infant baptism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priesthood of the believer'' is a dangerous concept. It
means Baptists are competent through their own souls to decide
matters of faith for themselves without going through a priest or
pastor.
</P>
<P>
   The ``priesthood of the believer'' stance was adopted by Roger
Williams, who founded the first Baptist Church in America in
Providence, R.I., in 1639.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Baptists can believe anything they want. They
are bound by certain basic doctrines _ like the virgin birth of
Jesus, his sacrificial death on the cross to redeem sinners and his
bodily resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   But after much prayer and Bible study, all Baptists are supposed
to be free to decide for themselves _ based on their own
consciences _ most matters of faith. What's hazardous about that is
that it leaves a lot of room for disagreement. For example, women
who believe God has called them to be pastors might go against the
views of the denomination's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative committee members who revised the document issued a
news release this week declaring that the concept of the priesthood
of the believer is a ``cherished principle'' and is assured in
other sections of the faith document. It is included, they say, in
the sixth article of the report which says ``each member is
responsible and accountable to Christ as Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   But taking out any explicit reference to the priesthood of the
believer is pretty extreme. Even some conservatives might insist
that it be put back in.
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, though.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Baptist conservatives who took control of the nation's
largest Protestant group in the 1980s seem a little nervous about
the priesthood of the believer concept, even though they voice
support for it.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives believe some fellow Baptists have
misinterpreted the idea to mean that people may interpret the Bible
in any way they like.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives believed moderates, who formerly controlled the
15.7 million-member denomination, were drifting toward a liberal
interpretation of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   When conservatives gained power, they insisted that their
seminary presidents and professors affirm a more literal and
historical interpretation of the Scriptures. Also, some
conservative seminary presidents reject faculty who believe that
women should be allowed to serve as pastors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Baptist Faith and Message Statement _ first adopted
in 1925 _ is supposed to be used as a guideline and not as a creed,
it has teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty at all six Southern Baptist seminaries, including
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, are
required to affirm the Baptist Faith and Message Statement.
</P>
<P>
   When a controversial phrase was added to the faith statement in
1998 saying wives should submit to the servant leadership of their
husbands, some Southwestern Seminary professors refused to sign it
and left their teaching positions.
</P>
<P>
   With new changes coming up in the Baptist document, seminary
professors who disagree will have another hard decision to make.
And if they exert that old-time ``priesthood of the believer''
principle, they might be fired.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
