<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-EIGHT-BOS &LR;      06-02 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`8 1/2' ISN'T ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 8 1/2 WOMEN &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Written and directed by: Peter Greenaway &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Starring: Polly Walker, Amanda Plummer, Toni Collette, Vivian Wu,
John Standing, Matthew Delamere, Shizuka Inoh, Barbara Sarafian,
Kirina Mano, Natacha Amal, Manna Fujiwara &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Running time: 120 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Unrated &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The earth moves for Peter Greenaway in his new film, ``8 1/2
Women.'' How many others it will move for is seriously open to
question.
</P>
<P>
   As its title implies, the new film is indebted to Fellini's ``8
1/2,'' but the late Italian director liked women and was a little
afraid of them. Greenaway seems only afraid of them. Fellini's
films worked because his alter ego, Marcello Mastroianni, enjoyed
playing weakness and confusion when confronted with this or that
fantasized harem. With Greenaway, the harem situation is more
problematical. It arises when a Swiss banker played by John
Standing finds himself widowed, calls his grown son in Japan and,
bereft, goes about purging his grief.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to thumb their noses at death with a burst of shared
lust, they assemble a harem of consenting women, some brought back
from Osaka, in the family's Geneva mansion. Father and son take
turns bedding the women, or most of them. In Osaka, they experience
a few real earthquakes. Back in Geneva, the earthquakes are
figurative, jolting their egos. The reason, predictably, is that
they had fleetingly thought themselves in control. But of course
they learn they're not.
</P>
<P>
   Eight times over, they find themselves no more in charge of
their respective fates than the steel pachinko balls cascading
through the popular Japanese pinball-like machines in a chain of
arcades the banker owns.
</P>
<P>
   The pachinko addiction of one woman puts her in hock to the
banker and has led to her installment in the upmarket bordello,
which in any case is stuffed not with real women but with
stereotypical male fantasy projections. The Scandinavian nun (Toni
Collette), the adoring servant (Barbara Sarafian), the Madame
Butterfly figure (Kirina Mano), the pregnant woman (Natacha Amal),
the woman who not only loves to ride her horse but loves the horse
(Amanda Plummer), and a prostitute with the proverbial heart of
gold (Polly Walker) eager to play earth mother to the aging banker,
mark the film as an old man's dream world, dragged from the dusty
shelves of the most venerable of Soho sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   Standing has panache to go with his plummy voice, and he turns
``8 1/2 Women'' into Greenaway's most warm-blooded film, but he has
his work cut out for him, especially once the seraglio situation is
set up. At first, there's an interesting tension between wit and
uncertainty. Once the pieces are in place, however, Greenaway
starts spinning his wheels. The ensuing irony and turnabouts, and
sexual politics aren't enough to conceal the fact that the film
seems to decline into a series of noodlings and doodlings, many of
which recycle previous Greenaway preoccupations with nudity,
numbers, human destruction, and his favorite standby, architecture.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the exterior and interior shots of the banker's
Swiss mansion seem more lovingly photographed than the women. As
mere projections of male fantasies, they have little dimension or
character. They simply become soft sculpture, artfully arranged. As
usual, Greenaway deploys tableaux in lieu of narrative, but this
time they don't have the associative zing they had in ``Drowning by
Numbers'' or even ``The Pillow Book,'' which was a much more
densely and intriguingly loaded screenful of collisions between
East and West. (Vivian Wu, who plays a repressed secretary here,
starred in the earlier film.) There just isn't enough subterranean
energy in ``8 1/2 Women,'' libidinous or otherwise. The problem
with ``8 1/2 Women'' isn't that what you see is what you get; it's
that what you see is all you get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
