<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-PUENTE-COX     06-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUENTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even in death, `El Rey' will keep audiences dancing
 &HT;    By Michael Point
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He really wanted to be a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   He had to settle for being ``King of the Mambo.'' For a half
century Tito Puente, who died Wednesday at age 77, personified the
universal appeal of Latin jazz in its vast and varied dance-music
disguises. His cunningly crafted tunes and stylish showmanship
repeatedly ushered in new music crazes that reconfigured popular
entertainment. The timeless nature of those creations keeps them in
circulation today, as telling a tribute as any to a musician whose
exuberant embrace of his own culture expanded the parameters of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Puente didn't intend to be ``El Rey'' of the bandstand. He would
have preferred to have been on the dance floor practicing Fred
Astaire moves, but an ankle injury curtailed that career plan. So,
he decided to be the one who puts the dancers in motion. His
success in doing so spanned generations and cultures, uniting all
in joyous service to rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The celebratory physicality of Puente's supple music meant it
was best experienced live. But Puente was, nevertheless,
prodigiously prolific in the recording studio. When his 100th album
was released in 1991, he undermined the promotional campaign by
stating it was no big thing; he could almost make them in his
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He probably could have, but his approach to making music,
whether in the studio or on stage, was neither casual nor
unschooled. Puente, who studied composing and orchestration at
Juilliard, worked diligently to keep his sound fresh and
unexpected, while retaining its traditional roots. He incorporated
ideas from the big bands of Tommy Dorsey and Count Basie and kept
his ears open for what was happening on the street as well. His
orchestra was stocked with the best and brightest young talents on
the scene. His legacy has been established for decades through the
accomplishments of the illustrious alumni _ Mongo Santamaria,
Willie Bobo and Ray Barretto _ of his big band turned Latin jazz
academy.
</P>
<P>
   Puente loved the excitement of the big stage shows he had seen
in New York nightclubs and was determined to reproduce the
atmosphere of fun and wonder no matter where he played.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to give them something to see or they can just stay
home and listen to the records,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The image of Puente dancing around his timbales while hammering
home rhythms in front of his razor-sharp orchestra is a lasting
one. His shows were uniformly upbeat affairs, full of finely
focused energy and sophisticated rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   I last talked with Puente before his performance at Bass Concert
Hall last year. He was calling even though it was too late to use
the interview to advance the concert, so things were unusually
relaxed. I told him I'd seen him play here 15 years before at Sixth
Street Live and was looking forward to the show. ``I don't know
why,'' he joked. ``You've already seen the show, because I still do
the same one now.''
</P>
<P>
   That was, quite happily, somewhat true, because Puente felt
compelled to perform his hits in live action. He always played the
classic version of ``Oye Como Va'' and he always prefaced it with a
humorous thank you to Santana for bringing his original back into
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And, as usual, his humor disguised a significant insight. Puente
said, that to his ``poor, old ears,'' Santana's band was just ``too
loud, with too much guitar.'' Then he added with a satisfied
chuckle, ``But he's got people dancing again, so I guess we just do
the same thing in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
