<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-TEXANS-COX     06-02 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texans hear fightin' words from Bush critics
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because ``proud Texan'' is redundant, and because Texans get
their chaps in a knot when outsiders bad-mouth the state, this kind
of thing became inevitable when George W. Bush painted a target on
his beloved homeland by deciding he should be president.
</P>
<P>
   The war of words between Texans and outsiders who dare criticize
the state is underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Texan whose family settled in Texas in 1859,'' Austinite
Bill Hale said in a letter this week to a California politico who
demeaned Texas, ``I deeply resent your editorial commentary quoted
in the Austin American-Statesman on Sunday, May 21, 2000. At best,
your statement is totally void of enlightened facts and at worst a
belief grounded in the fictional fantasies of Hollywood `B'
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The target of Hale's statetriotic venom was Garry South, top
political adviser to California Democratic Gov. Gray Davis. South's
offending comments, as quoted in a story about the presidential
race in California: ``I'm sure in Texas (Bush) looks like a
compassionate conservative because Texas is so far to the right. In
that landscape he really does seem like a sensible moderate. In
California, the guy looks like a right-wing wacko.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hale, executive director of the Texas Human Rights
Commission, those are fightin' words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear you have zero comprehension of Texas history or
our way of life,'' he told South. ``It is beyond this short epistle
to give you any substantive lesson on Texas history and culture.
But, in brief, Texas was founded in revolution based on the
principles of equality, justice and fair dealing.'' ``The next time
you have the urge to make slanderous editorial comments about Texas
and its governor, get your facts straight. You owe Texas a public
apology,'' Hale concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, California boy. And there's plenty more where that
came from, ready to be dished out to anyone else _ be it probable
Democratic nominee Al Gore or his surrogates _ who dares to
implicate that the Great State of Texas is anything less than a
great state.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented way, Bush's race for the White House has put
the spotlight on Texas and Texans. Though Texans have been involved
in presidential politics in the past, Bush is the first contender
whose record rests solely within the state. Lyndon B. Johnson built
his career and reputation in Washington. The elder Bush never held
state office. Ex-Gov. John Connally had been out of office for 11
years when he made his unsuccessful 1980 bid for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Gore is putting Texas on trial. Though he doesn't mind
dipping into Texas to dip into Texans' pockets, Gore has called
Texas ``the most polluted state in America.'' He also has
criticized the state's low rankings, by some measures, in education
and social services.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that could explain why Gore is so cranky about Texas:
His 1988 presidential campaign ended here, days after a major loss
in the New York primary, when he was in Austin for a fund-raising
event.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family is intimately acquainted with the ins and outs
of running against a governor. Then-Vice President George Bush did
it successfully in 1988 when he defeated Democrat Michael Dukakis,
self-anointed architect of the ``Massachusetts miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the elder Bush was ousted by Bill Clinton,
governor of a state that ranked near the top only when you list the
states alphabetically. In that race, the Bush campaign _ in a
technique now echoed by the Gore campaign _ tried to show that a
governor's home state offered little evidence in support of a
promotion to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republic of Texas Museum in North Austin, museum
assistant Audrey Tyler doesn't cotton to Gore's criticism of her
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Texan from way back,'' she said. ``And it does upset me.
I do think that Texas is great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the desert. We have the trees and we have the lakes.
We have it all in Texas,'' said Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   In San Angelo, House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, a
Democrat who backs Bush, said the Gore theme has a familiar ring to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't President Bush say all that about Arkansas?'' said
Junell, who says he is a Texas Democrat, not a Democrat from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Texan way before I'm a Democrat,'' he said. ``I think
people believe Texas is the place to be, that we have less
government regulation, that we have good schools and that we have a
spirit of entrepreneurship other states wish they had.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol this week, tourist Bill Craft of Cleburne said
he, too, doesn't appreciate campaign stump bad-mouthing of Texas,
but he has figured out how to handle it: he ignores it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just negative politics. It's just throwing mud, as far
as I'm concerned,'' he said. ``If you look at Al Gore you're gong
to find stuff wrong with Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly Beth Malcolm, chair of the Texas Democratic Party and a
high-volume Bush critic, understands why Texans don't appreciate
Gore's criticism of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans are just like a big family,'' she said. ``We are loyal
to our state and we are sensitive when outsiders talk about it. I
can talk about my brothers and sisters or mama and daddy, but I
don't want somebody else doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm is confident that the Democratic National Convention
this summer in Los Angeles will not turn into a four-day Texas
bash-a-thon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not Bush-bashing if you are telling the truth about
some of the rankings. They are the truth. We just don't like to
hear someone else talk about them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texans are willing to talk about them. At the Center for
Public Policy Priorities in Austin, a non-profit policy research
organization that keeps an eye out for the less privileged, senior
fiscal analyst Dick Lavine says the presidential race is putting
needed focus on some of the state's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to keep people's attention on what could be better,''
said Lavine, a 20-year Texan. ``I'm not aware that Al Gore is
exaggerating any of these facts. They are facts that people
sometimes don't like to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are periodic reminders of how Texas can be heaven
to some and hell to others. This week, 17 years after he went to
prison for a rape he said he did not commit, A.B. Butler Jr. of
Tyler received a gubernatorial pardon after DNA evidence cleared
him.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Randy Shaeffer of Houston, said Texas is not a good
place for people who find themselves in Butler's predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a controversial situation like a black man given
the maximum sentence for savagely raping a white woman you don't
find people running up to the front of the line to set aside the
conviction and let him go. This is still Texas,'' said Shaeffer.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism from outside the state sometimes hangs on isolated
statistics and facts. In a recent letter to the editor of The New
York Times, New Yorker John Guthrow noted that corporal punishment
remains legal in Texas public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cruel form of child abuse has now been banned in most of
the civilized world,'' Guthrow wrote. ``The fact that George W.
Bush governs a state in which schoolchildren are still beaten every
day is something that voters should be aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sliver of a mega-state that tests the extremes. Texas is
both the unspoiled grandeur of Palo Duro Canyon and the industrial
grit of the Houston Ship Channel. It's www.zillionaires thriving on
free enterprise and people enduring persistent poverty in a state
whose idea of welfare is get a job.
</P>
<P>
   It's good schools and bad schools, wide-open spaces and almost
round-the-clock traffic. When it comes to a current stereotype,
it's downright confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any longer the cowboy image is the dominant
one,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a 25-year Texan who teaches politics at
the University of Texas. ``The mega-state image is coming to the
fore, coupled with attitude. The part of the old image that
survives is the attitude: We're tougher. We're bigger. We're
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it hurts George W. Bush at all,'' said Buchanan.
``And it clearly helps him that Texas is a long way from Washington
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1518EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-IDIOTS-BOS &LR;      06-02 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-IDIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VON TRIER'S `THE IDIOTS' IS BOTH LIVELY AND JUVENILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE IDIOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by: Lars von Trier &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Bodil Jorgensen, Jens Albinus, Louise Hassing, Troels
Lyby, Nikolaj Lie Kaas, Henrik Prip, Luis Mesonero, Louise Mieritz,
Knud Romwer Jorgensen, Trine Michelsen, Anne-Grethe Bjarup Riis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 115 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R (strong sexuality and nudity, and for language) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots'' is a sometimes infuriating film that comes close
to being Lars von Trier's first real flub. But there's also a
genuine provocativeness about it that charges it with vitality and
outruns its sometimes fascist juvenilia.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense it lives up to the ideal of renewal animating von
Trier and his fun-loving Dogme 95 filmmaking colleagues from
Denmark. Be prepared to hang on for a while, however, until its
virtues emerge from beneath what for a long time seems a replay of
'60s indulgence. It's offensive in several ways, starting with the
discovery by a sad, timid woman in a restaurant that some fellow
diners who have been causing pervasive uneasiness are not the
mentally challenged individuals they appear to be. They're a band
of so-called normal people who, they assure her once off the
premises, are trying to make contact with their inner idiots.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing loftily Dostoyevskyan about their search. They
spout off a lot about how superior they are to bourgeois culture
while having it both ways, behaving selfishly and squatting in the
comfortable house belonging to the uncle of the ringleader, Jens
Albinus's Stoffer. He's supposed to be selling the place for his
uncle, but he scares away potential buyers by telling them the
house is next door to an institution. He's arrogant, and something
of a fascist, bullying the others in the name of liberating them
from their hangups. Karin, the newcomer from the restaurant, who
certainly looks as if she's shouldering more than her share of
troubles, seems to need the collective support they offer. But you
can't help feeling she's on target when she asks Stoffer why
there's so much getting at people.
</P>
<P>
   The smugness and self-righteousness pervading the quasi-commune
at times grows insufferable, and the talk about transcending
barriers gets pretty fuzzy and self-justifying. When the group
indulges itself, it's with champagne and caviar, bought with a
credit card that one of the women shames out of one of the men _
the one who briefly returns to his job in an ad agency. Some of the
men seem benign and most of the women seem pleasant and
good-natured. But their submerged personalities make the film seem
short on content, much less the genuine idealism that would have
been a much more effective motor. Better, certainly, than Stoffer's
admission that there's no real justification for the group
play-acting at being retarded and that they may in fact be
inexcusably patronizing to those they are impersonating. They even
flaunt a callous name for their pastime _ ``spassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Their gratifications seldom exceed the level of the most
rudimentary creature comforts, including a group sex scene in which
male genitalia are concealed with black opaque rectangles
strategically placed. The self-styled idiots, playing at their
version of the noble savage fallacy, which holds that that which is
simple is morally pure and that the way to spiritually cleanse
yourself is to pretend to be simple, deliberately live in a
provisional moment-to-moment world ideally suited to von Trier's
anarchic hand-held camera. The inhibition-shedding is too
self-servingly mindless to be taken seriously. Certainly none of
this film's airing of the idea of abandoning control is on the
level of tightrope-walking undertaken by Emily Watson's character
in ``Breaking the Waves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots'' is as kinetic as that other deliberately
disruptive Dogme 95 film, Thomas Vinterberg's ``The Celebration.''
It has an improvised feel, especially as conflicts surface and the
group dynamic undergoes a seismic shift. There's more than one
section where von Trier's claim to have written ``The Idiots'' in
four days makes you wish there had been time for a rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots'' is messy and miles too uncritical of itself. It
wears sanctimoniousness like a halo. But there's also no question
that its rampant ids fly off the screen and engage us. ``The
Idiots'' isn't easy to take. It doesn't succeed in achieving Dogme
95's Holy Grail _ the recapturing of lost innocence. What could? It
plays more like the recapture of Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, it does shake some of the dust off
filmmaking in its slapdash rambunctiousness. For better or worse _
and it does give us both _ it's always alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
