</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KNIPFEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUDY IN SELF-DESTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITTING THE NAIROBI TRIO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Knipfel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy R. Tarcher/Putnam, 285 pp., $23.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When readers last encountered Jim Knipfel, he was giving up a
life of petty crime, punk rock, and paranoia for a career as a
writer. (Well, maybe not the paranoia.) He was also coming to terms
with retinitis pigmentosa, an eye disease that left him in a world
of dimming light and terrifying stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Slackjaw,'' was a jaggedly charming collection
of essays that documented his progress from graduate school in the
Midwest to a job as columnist for The New York Press, an
alternative weekly in New York City. His new work, ``Quitting the
Nairobi Trio,'' probes more deeply into one stop on that trip, a
suicide attempt that landed him in a locked psych ward in
Minneapolis. It is also a masterful leap forward in style and
control. While some of the searing heat of ``Slackjaw'' is missing,
Knipfel introduces more nuance and continuity. He seems to be
trying to get some distance, to mediate his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people get creepy and nervous when I offhandedly mention
that I've spent a goodly amount of time in the bughouse,'' Knipfel
offers at the outset. But the food was OK, the bed was comfortable,
and the world was muted.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide attempt that landed him in the locked ward _ done
with a rainbow overdose of over-the-counter pills _ wasn't his
first. In fact, he writes, he had been trying to kill himself since
he was 14. ``No matter how I had tried, nothing worked. I threw
myself down flights of stairs, drank bleach, cut my wrists, stepped
in front of buses, all to no avail.'' If Nietzsche were having a
really bad day, he'd be Jim Knipfel.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't too many clues as to cause in this book. He
provides a glimpse of his childhood in Green Bay, where he tried to
dream an adventurous life for himself. His description of scuba
lessons at a local pool is as telling an anecdote as any about his
shamefaced struggle for independence. Knipfel seems to come from a
stolid, Sears-catalogue type of Midwestern family, but his life
devolves into throttled anger and self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   When the doors slide shut in the psych ward, Knipfel takes stock
of his fellow heretics in the Dante-esque environment. This is
where his storytelling instincts take hold: there's Cartwright, the
social worker with the sclerotic soul of a bureaucrat; Gus, the
manic bicyclist; the TV room, where patients watch the Ernie Kovacs
reruns that give the book its title; and Joey, the erstwhile
roommate who is whisked away one night, leaving a welter of blood
and a mystery that pervades the rest of the story.
</P>
<P>
   The ward teaches him lessons about lying in wait. And watching.
Attendants take his shoelaces and belt. The stuff of daily life
gets doled out in dribs: psychotropic drugs, cigarettes, meals,
information. Knipfel cracks his only book _ ``Ecrits,'' by French
psychoanalyst Jacques Lacan, and offers ``A Half-Assed Guide'' for
the uninitiated. Lacan makes as much sense to Knipfel as his
10-minute weekly visits with Dr. Spellman, his assigned
psychiatrist. Soon, the patients begin making more sense than the
paid professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clearer the hopelessness of my situation with Spellman,
the clearer it was that I really was on my own here, almost to the
point that I could be my own therapist. I guess I had Lacan with me
_ however ludicrous he could be at times _ and thought I had some
simple common sense. That was a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Knipfel later obtained his medical records, and found that he
had been diagnosed with a mixed personality disorder: ``an enduring
pattern of inner experience and behavior which persists over
several years and deviates markedly from the expectations of one's
home culture.'' Like many perfectly sane people, he finds some
comfort in not fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nairobi Trio'' takes one structural leap that falls flat,
however. The book alternates descriptions of real events with
descriptions of hallucinations, presumably brought on by Knipfel's
overdose. Personal hallucinations, like dreams, are difficult to
pass judgment on: They're important to the beholder but don't
always translate in the wider world. These chapters never resonate.
</P>
<P>
   Knipfel doesn't need hallucinations. He is inventive and
outrageous enough to make the mundane details of his real life
weirdly compelling (just check out his disquisition on cat sputum
on the Web). But this is only his second book, and sophomore
efforts are just that. If Knipfel is willing to let readers
continue to devour the details of his life, there's room for a
third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
