<HEADER>
A2953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SKOLSHOOT-C     06-02 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SKOLSHOOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All CNN imitators, all the time
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an insatiable national craving for news that comes like
lobsters _ live and ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Car chases in California, trial verdicts, hostage standoffs and
army invasions _ it is imperative that we see the pictures as they
happen. Later may be too late. Information is delivered with the
thrill of an electronic high-wire act. At any second, the speeding
car may crash, the building may explode, the defendant may crack
and the army may do battle. To wait is to run the unbearable risk
of not being there.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner gave us CNN two decades ago, and a passion for
immediacy was ignited. We could watch live as bombing was shaking
downtown Baghdad or the people in Oklahoma City. We could mark the
exact moment and place we were when O.J. got off the hook. At its
best, CNN took us to Berlin as the Wall was being torn down, a
moment of pure history. At its worst, CNN wallowed in the tragedy
of fallen celebrity as the network did last year in its continuous
coverage _ what network news president Richard Kaplan proudly
termed ``wall-to-wall coverage'' _ of the plane crash of John F.
Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall how the poor anchors were sentenced to provide
dialogue for the wall-to-wall coverage when there was nothing to
cover. From the Atlanta studio, they watched live aerial video as
the Coast Guard cutter made its long journey, its very, very long
journey, to the crash site. They had to fill the air with words
during this interminable voyage. They were live. So they discussed
depths of Atlantic waters, how choppy the seas were, how Mr.
Kennedy had a father who had been president, how he was Irish, how
the Coast Guard was founded in 1790, etc. The walls were way too
far apart.
</P>
<P>
   CNN feeds our national obsession for live news, and it also
inspires followers at the local level. All stations must have at
least a remote van, if not a remote truck, equipped with a huge
logo and a satellite tower to go live from anywhere. Because live
is what we all want.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday afternoon, when a teacher was shot dead in Lake
Worth, the mobile TV towers went up outside the middle school
campus, and three West Palm Beach stations battled each other for
the first details of the killing. WPTV-Channel 5 was first to
report the name of the teacher, Barry Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   The station got the identity by interviewing 12- and 13-year-old
students live on the air _ kids the reporter sometimes addressed as
``sweetie.'' Two of them mentioned Mr. Grunow's name. Neither
police nor school officials released or confirmed the name. But
Channel 5 was live, and this was what was said, and so this is what
was broadcast. Never mind that the kids, young and shaken, might
have been wrong, or that the victim's family might be getting the
horrible news by television. Being live and first, being there and
linked to the instant. That's what mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind, too, that a reporter sought to allay fears of a
wider tragedy by telling viewers ``just a teacher'' had been shot.
Live TV is a messy business, the station says, and it is essential
to beat all comers on the story. Channel 5 was first, Channel 5 was
right, and Channel 5 thanks you for watching.
</P>
<P>
   Editing has become the most prominent casualty of live TV's rush
to transmit. Considering content and context of information takes
time. How much easier it is to vomit words and images through a
screen and take your chances. Sources don't need to be reliable
because the medium is live, and the message is whatever comes out.
The lowest standard applies because of how very difficult it is
just to get there, put the tower up and pull anything at all from
the chaotic scene. Stick a microphone in a kid's face and maybe
what comes out will be _ news.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 5 might have chosen to interview students off-camera.
The station might have videotaped interviews, listened, edited them
and aired them a few minutes later. Only a few minutes. But, then,
that would have been responsible, but it wouldn't have been live.
That would only be almost live. Getting it live is what matters.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett is an editorial writer for The Palm Beach Post. His
e-mail address is danmoffett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
