<HEADLINE>
BON JOVI STILL ROCKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jon Bon Jovi was the ultimate arena-rock star of the 1980s,
belting out guilty-pleasure hits ``You Give Love a Bad Name'' and
``Living on a Prayer.'' Today, however, Bon Jovi may indeed be
living on a prayer, since he's an outsider in a fiercer, more
alternative, youth-oriented rock scene. Yet Bon Jovi is not going
down without a struggle. As he sings in the new song, ``The Next
100 Years'': ``If it should all end tonight, I'll know it will have
been worth the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bon Jovi and his group of the same name issue ``Crush,'' the
band's first CD in five years, on June 13, and play Saturday in
Mansfield, Mass..
</P>
<P>
   These days, Bon Jovi is known more for his movies than his music
_ exemplified by roles in the new submarine film, ``U-571'' and six
previous flicks, including ``Moonlight and Valentino,'' ``No
Looking Back,'' and ``Row Your Boat.'' He will also appear in ``Pay
It Forward'' with Helen Hunt and Kevin Spacey, due in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Crush,'' Bon Jovi and his reunited mates, including Richie
Sambora and Tico Torres, crank out a ``classic'' Bon Jovi sound of
big guitars, big backbeats, gushy love songs, and uncomplicated,
working-class anthems.
</P>
<P>
   The album doesn't hop on any bandwagons _ don't look for any
hip-hop/rock crossovers here _ but Bon Jovi deserves credit for
writing honest, adult lyrics that reflect where he is today.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey rocker, who has been called a poor man's Bruce
Springsteen, gets right to the task with ``Older,'' a virtual
position paper of Bon Jovi 2000: ``All these years of memories, I'm
still chasing dreams, but I'm not looking over my shoulder . . .
Like a favorite pair of torn bluejeans, the skin I'm in is all
right with me/ I like the bed I'm sleeping in/ It's just like me,
it's broken in/ It's not old, just older.''
</P>
<P>
   The new single, ``It's My Life,'' should score on Top 40 radio,
even if rock radio shuns it. Although the band has become a bit of
an anachronism, it's still a guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walden Woods update: Eagles singer/solo act Don Henley headlines
FleetBoston Pavilion on Monday. It's a benefit for the Walden Woods
Project, which Henley has championed for 10 years, as he's helped
keep Henry David Thoreau's Walden Pond retreat out of the hands of
developers.
</P>
<P>
   So what's up with the project on its 10th anniversary?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trucking along,'' says Henley. ``Our Web site is up
and running at www.walden.org. We are still struggling to get
funding to refurbish the building that houses the institute. We're
still struggling to raise a $15 million endowment so that the
project and the institute can survive after I'm gone. And we have
some wonderful education programs out there for schoolchildren of
all ages. We have seminars and lectures. We have visiting scholars
from all over the world. We're still cataloging our Thoreau
collections and digitizing those collections.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
