<HEADER>
A2957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CLINTON-CAREER-$ADV04     06-02 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CAREER-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEN. WILLIAM JEFFERSON CLINTON, D-ARK.? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     For release Sunday, June 4)   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton, U.S. Senator from Arkansas?
</P>
<P>
   Some people who know President Clinton think that's the next job
for him after he leaves the White House in January.
</P>
<P>
   At age 54, Clinton will be the youngest former U.S. president
since Teddy Roosevelt in 1915. Given his life-long career in
politics, a run for the seat now held by Sen. Tim Hutchinson,
R-Ark., could be in Clinton's future, according to these Clinton
watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., a long-time acquaintance of
Clinton's who served as one of his chief defenders during the
president's impeachment trial, thinks a Senate seat would be the
logical continuation of Clinton's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that's an option for him,'' Bumpers said in a recent
interview. ``He's not constrained by age and I think there's plenty
of time (for him) to serve in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   David Maraniss, who wrote the best-selling Clinton biography
``First in His Class,'' noted that Clinton has long been interested
in a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the time he was governor of Arkansas he wanted to be
senator,'' Maraniss said, referring to Clinton's 10_year occupancy
of the governor's mansion in Little Rock. ``He always wanted to run
for Bumper's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   But the senator was popular and a member of Clinton's party. The
other Senate seat was held by another Clinton ally, Sen. David
Pryor, D-Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Bumpers' seat opened up in 1998 when the four-term senator
retired and was succeeded by Democratic Sen. Blanche Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, a first-term senator who voted last year to convict
Clinton in his impeachment trial, is up for re-election in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While the Constitution bars Clinton from seeking a third term in
the White House, there's no similar obstacle to a run for the
Senate. And he would be following the precedent set by former
President Andrew Johnson, the only other president besides Clinton
to be impeached, who joined the Senate after leaving the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   John Quincy Adams had a long career in the House of
Representatives after he left the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, ``I would eliminate the House,'' Bumpers
said. He said Clinton would prefer to be a senator or secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become very good with foreign affairs,'' Bumpers
explained of Clinton's qualifications for the Cabinet position.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn McQuary, chairman of the Arkansas Democratic Party, said
Clinton would ``be welcome back here He certainly has an open
invitation from me as chairman to act (in Arkansas politics) in any
way he feels comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the president's future career has been renewed by
the move to disbar him from practicing law because he gave
misleading testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case.
That issue will be decided soon by a judge in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris, Clinton's former top political adviser, thinks the
president should skip law practice anyway and set up his own think
tank to study public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading a think tank that would probe new ideas would be good
for him (and) it would give him some visibility,'' said Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Other Clinton watchers expect him to work in the private sector,
taking time to help raise money for Democrats or to serve as an
international peacekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution think
tank in Washington, predicts Clinton will ``go back to making some
real money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess said Clinton, like most other modern presidents, could earn
a large sum writing his memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing every ex-president does is write his
memoirs,'' Hess said. ``For a president who has cared so much about
his legacy, he'll want to tell it as he remembers it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some top corporate headhunters agree Clinton's business
opportunities are vast.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Pfieffer, a partner in the Washington office of the
executive search firm of Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, said Clinton comes
across as ``an extremely smart, personable executive I see him as a
deal-doer, but not just a glad-hander.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ryan, a consultant at the outplacement firm of Drake Beam
Morin, said Clinton could become a corporate CEO if he chose to
work only with one company. But Ryan said Clinton is ``more likely
to serve on many'' boards because he would then collect several
director's fees and could work in different fields.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could also make large amounts of money quickly by making
speeches to corporate executives, like George Bush and Ronald
Reagan did when they left office.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Morris, Reagan's official biographer and author of
``Dutch,'' recalled that Reagan made ``extremely lucrative public
speeches for fat-cat corporations'' after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   He said the speech circuit is an option for any ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   John Challenger, chief executive officer of the international
outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas said, ``I don't
think he'll go back and practice law'' regardless of the outcome of
the disbarment proceedings. ``He'll do something more
presidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenger suggested Clinton might end up secretary-general of
the United Nations or as the head of the Americorps volunteer
program that he established.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger said Clinton might go ``out and work in the
non-profit arena like Jimmy Carter with Habitat for Humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kranz, an American historian specializing in the
presidency at the Library of Congress, said Clinton could follow in
the footsteps of Harry Truman, who spoke on numerous college
campuses about the presidency after he left office. Kranz also
suggested that future presidents take advantage of Clinton's
speaking skills and ask him to speak at funerals for foreign
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one better at delivering eulogies,'' Kranz said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Ornstein, a resident scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute think tank in Washington, suggested Clinton ``will
develop a relationship with some kind of investment house for a day
or two a week.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Washington fundraiser, Clinton said he would like to
teach at least a semester a year. Clinton last taught at the
University of Arkansas law school in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Mort Gitelman, a fellow law school faculty member, recalls that
Clinton was ``a very engaging instructor'' who had ``lively
conversations with the students.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has told reporters on several occasions that he plans to
spend time in Arkansas working on his $80-million-$125 million
presidential library in Little Rock. He said he would live with
mother-in-law Dorothy Rodham until his planned apartment at the
library is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for Clinton is to join his many friends in
California and go into show business.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent White House Correspondents Dinner, Clinton starred
in a short spoof video about being a lame-duck president. Many said
he performed better than the evening's featured entertainer,
``Tonight Show'' Host Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   While Ronald Reagan went from acting to politics, Clinton could
do the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be at all surprised if (Clinton) went into the
movie business,'' said Morris, the Reagan biographer. Reagan didn't
return to acting because he was too old when he left office, Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, chairman of the California Democratic Party, said he
hopes Clinton will come to his state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so loved out here,'' Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
