<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONLINE-PORN-ART-BOS &LR;      06-02 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-PORN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WEB PORN BUSINESS FINDS NICHE IN SUBURBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The four-bedroom brick colonial seems to be the very model of
mainstream suburbia: two cars in the driveway, friendly dogs at the
door, a pool in the backyard, a grand piano in the
climate-controlled library. The owners are Internet entrepreneurs.
In their spare time, they like to garden, rock climb, and sail.
</P>
<P>
   And down in the basement, they run a profitable online
pornography business that specializes in bondage and domination.
</P>
<P>
   When the neighbors ask what they do, the owners say, ``We're in
e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Located in southern New Hampshire, the Phoenix Group (no
relation to the Boston Phoenix) is a multimillion-dollar operation
that employs a staff of seven, including a former middle school
teacher. ``We're not doing as well as Bill Gates, but we have a
nice nest egg,'' says Phoenix Group founder Colin Daniels (a
pseudonym), 45, a former professional musician. Daniels says his
business, which includes a flagship site, boasts a cumulative total
of 150,000 customers a year; he points out that many of these
customers sign on for the service for short periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when venture capitalists and business leaders are
falling all over themselves trying to figure out how to make money
on the Web, entrepreneurs in the online adult entertainment
industry are floating in profits. With its global reach, instant
accessibility, and anonymity, the Internet has brought pornography
into the mainstream, taking it out of the penthouses and mansions
of porn kings and placing it smack in the basements and garages of
middle America.
</P>
<P>
   Since virtually all of the companies are private and many of the
merchants tend to be cagey and circumspect, it's hard to determine
the exact size of the industry. Most analysts steer clear of the
trade, and ratings services like Media Metrix don't track adult
sites as a separate category. But according to a 1999 study by the
New York-based research firm Datamonitor, adult content accounts
for 69 percent of the $1.4 billion market for online services;
other estimates put the online porn business at between $1 billion
and $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In April, some 17.6 million users, or 22 percent of all Internet
users, visited an adult site, according to Nielsen/Net Ratings. And
the top-rated porn site in April received more traffic than such
popular mainstream sites as AskJeeves.com, Priceline.com, and
BarnesandNoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wide-ranging content
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources estimate that there are tens of thousands of
porn sites on the Internet, offering everything from still
photographs to live Webcams and streaming video. The content is all
over the map; virtual sex shops sport names like Lust Highway, Sex
on the Strip, Busty Amateurs, and Granny Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Run by amateurs and semi-pros all over the country, many of
these sites are turning a handsome profit. While the top few sites
are run by a handful of old-fashioned porn purveyors, there is a
brand-new group of proprietors that includes slick young computer
wizards, former porn stars, and suburban swingers. Young and old,
male and female, they pioneer new technologies and marketing
methods years before they are adopted by the mainstream corporate
world. Almost all of them use pseudonyms, and many of them defy
stereotypes, like the Cambridge programmer who runs a paid porn
site so he can afford to run free support groups for people with
HIV and other chronic disorders. ``A lot of these people are geeks
who obsess about code, not content,'' says Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the adult entertainment industry exists in its own
alternative universe on the Internet, independent of the vagaries
of venture capitalists and the Nasdaq market. It has its own
villains and heroines, ts own search engines and service
organizations, its own award ceremonies and trade shows. It has a
fair share of hucksters and rip-off artists, but it also has its
own self-appointed consumer watchdog, a former advertising
saleswoman named Jane Duvall who runs Jane's Guide, a popular Web
site that monitors industry fraud. And now it's part of a college
curriculum: Last month, San Francisco State University launched a
course that studies the online skin scene.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is: Sex sells.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Danni Ashe, a former centerfold who has become a sort
of poster girl for the flourishing industry. She started her
soft-core site, Danni's Hard Drive, for $8,000 in 1995; her
business now employs 38 people and grossed $5.2 million last year,
with projected earnings of $7 million this year. ``Obviously, we
are all genetically programmed to want to have sex and talk about
sex and look at sex,'' says Ashe, 32.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated technology
</P>
<P>
   But the success of the industry doesn't ride on hormonal
instinct alone. Porn has always driven the development of media
technology, from nickelodeon peep shows to videocassettes to
Webcams to live, streaming video. The next generation of Internet
add-ons is already in development; one company is marketing a line
of tactile devices called ``cyberdildonics,'' and Vivid
Entertainment Inc. invented a neoprene cybersex bodysuit with 36
built-in sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware manufacturers often test new high-end systems on porn
sites, which generate heavy traffic and require high bandwidth.
``It's all very confidential, but the major vendors do it all the
time,'' says Chris Buerger, manager of networking for Datamonitor.
</P>
<P>
   The online pornographers also pioneered marketing techniques
that have been adopted by mainstream merchants and publishers all
over the Internet. They were early adapters of pop-up windows and
exit consoles that invite users to visit affiliated Web sites; the
referring site gets a cut of any business conducted at the next
site. Amazon.com and other e-merchants now have similar referring
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The free porn sites, or ``farm'' sites, make decent money this
way; many of them are run by the same folks who operate the
subscription sites, which charge up to $25 a month. Cooperation is
the name of the game in the industry: Large or small, providers are
all involved in a complex web of partnerships and profit-sharing
deals.
</P>
<P>
   The adult sites also expertly monitor and filter traffic,
building demographic profiles of customers to target ads
specifically to users. ``You don't try to sell a lawnmower during
`Oprah,' '' explains Andrew Edmond, chief executive officer of
SexTracker, a Seattle-based service company that hosts porn sites
and markets statistical analysis tools.
</P>
<P>
   The porn industry has always been a few steps ahead of the
mainstream entertainment industry, which is embroiled in lawsuits
involving Internet piracy and hasn't figured out how to make money
of its own online. Likewise, none of the mega-hyped start-ups
offering mainstream online entertainment have been able to develop
a following, sustain a profit, or pay back their investors. Two
high-profile Net entertainment start-ups, DEN and Pixelon, are both
mired in scandal and headed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream attention
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Hollywood executives are watching the adult world,
but they're doing it quietly. ``It's not like they have big board
meetings and trot out the porn and say, `Get me some of that,' ''
says Mark Hardie, a former analyst with Forrester Research. ``But
they are looking at areas where money is being made and asking, `If
they're making money, why can't we?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, the question of the moment on Wall Street
and Main Street alike. But even the porn sites are seeing a drop in
profits these days, in part because the credit card companies are
putting the squeeze on shady operators, instituting higher fees and
penalties for merchant accounts. American Express recently
announced it was dropping all merchant accounts for online porn
sites. And the scams in the industry are notorious. Some sites are
rigged so that users trying to exit are bombarded by page after
page of smut; other sites offer ``free trial'' periods and then
bill customers before they can cancel. Late last year, Seth
Warshavsky, the Seattle wheeler-dealer infamous for selling the
Tommy Lee and Pamela Anderson Lee sex video online, was accused by
his employees of double-billing thousands of customers. And in
April, a scam artist duped Web users out of thousands of dollars by
using software that reset their modems to dial the African nation
of Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Some adult entertainment moguls turn a blind eye to such fraud,
but others in the business are trying to force the industry to
police itself. ``There is an attitude in the adult industry of
`Rah, rah, we're all in this together,' '' says Duvall of Jane's
Guide. ``But my big thing is that people should know what they're
getting and they shouldn't get ripped off.'' Her site crusades
against scams and evaluates porn sites on such consumer issues as
customer service and user agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has taken steps to clean up its business practices,
says Craig Tant of CCBill Inc., a third-party billing company in
Phoenix that handles merchant accounts for more than 10,000 porn
sites. He notes that about 95 percent of his customers run an
honest business. But, he admits, ``we have seen scams that are
outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Service companies like CCBill and SexTracker are reaping huge
profits, although their founders won't say exactly how much. The
real money in Internet pornography, some say, is being made by the
business-to-business companies that provide hardware and services
to Webmasters. ``The people who made the money in the gold rush
were the people selling the stuff to the miners, not the miners
themselves,'' says Duvall.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Edmond of SexTracker is riding high in Seattle these
days. At 26, he oversees a company with 100 employees and more than
29,000 clients. He fashions himself as a kind of sheriff bringing
order to the Wild, Wild West of the adult Internet. ``We take
professionalism very seriously,'' he says. ``This is not a
fly-by-night operation where there are a bunch of guys with
strippers sitting on their laps.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many virtual porn shops are run in makeshift home
offices where computer programmers type at keyboards and
customer-service operators take technical questions and complaints.
</P>
<P>
   At the offices of the New Hampshire Phoenix Group, for instance,
three women smoke cigarettes and field phone calls in a relaxed
suburban setting.
</P>
<P>
   Customer-service representative Mercedes Taylor (a pseudonym)
says she was attracted to the job because smoking is permitted and
casual dress is encouraged. A single mother, she makes more money
now than she did as a teacher. ``I'm not the morality police,'' she
says. ``This is not my lifestyle, but I love my job. It's creative.
It's cutting-edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would Daniels, a classically trained musician who still
conducts a local chorus, turn his basement into a porn shop as
opposed to, say, a Web business that sells sheet music? ``This
business makes money,'' he says simply. ``Others don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
