<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLINDED BY OUR LOVE AFFAIR WITH THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It should not be a great surprise that George W. Bush has
received a respectful hearing on his plan to let Americans invest a
portion of their Social Security money in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   We have become comfortable with the market. More than that, we
have become dependent on it. We use it to pay for college, save for
retirement, and pick the companies where we work.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The stock market, as measured by the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index, has returned an average of 18 percent for the
past 18 years. If you had invested a dollar in stocks when the bull
market began in 1982, it would be worth slightly more than $20
today. What's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   But imagine, hard as it is may be, that the party is over.
Imagine that we are entering a period where the stock market goes
into an extended funk, where every dip is not followed by an
immediate rebound (like Thursday's), where returns are mediocre,
rather than spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   In that kind of world, would we all be so enthusiastic about
taking risks and managing our own financial futures?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shiller probably doesn't think so. In his gloomy new
book, ``Irrational Exuberance,'' the Yale economist points out some
unpleasant historical realities. He notes that every time the
market has had a long runup, and price/earnings ratios have reached
new highs as they have recently, the subsequent 20-year period has
been characterized by miserable stock-market performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bad times followed good at the beginning of the century, after
the Crash of 1929 and after 1966, another high-water mark for
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with Barron's, Shiller said: ``It is
certainly plausible to me that the Dow could be trading at the
current level of 10,000 to 11,000 20 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wyss is nowhere near that gloomy. But the chief economist
at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI is forecasting a period of below average
stock-market returns for the next 10 years. Wyss's argument is
based largely on economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   He reasons that much of the bull market can be explained by the
gradual decline in interest rates and inflation over the past 20
years. That decline made stocks more attractive than other
investments and allowed price/earnings ratios to climb
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``That process is over,'' said Wyss. ``We have gone about as low
on rates and inflation as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Others make the case that high stock prices sow the seeds of
their own destruction. The logic goes something like this: When
stock prices are high, investors are already making the assumption
that there will be plenty of good news _ and good earnings _ in the
days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   If the news is merely as good as forecast, stocks will just
maintain their levels. If the news is worse than expected, stocks
will fall.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few numbers: When stocks are appreciating 18 percent
a year, an investor doubles his money every four years. If stocks
rise 6 percent a year _ an arbitary but not ridiculous number _
that same investor would double his money every 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   In an 18 percent environment, a $20,000 investment turns into
$160,000 after 12 years. In a 6 percent environment that $20,000
investment would be worth only $40,000 after 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   All of us have become accustomed to living in the 18 percent
world and we have made our decisions accordingly. We have embraced
401(k) plans enthusiastically, prefering to trust our fate to the
market, rather than a paternalistic employer. We have barely
complained or seemed to notice that traditional defined-benefit
retirement plans cover a smaller percentage of the work force every
year.
</P>
<P>
   We have put our children's college money in the market. Some of
us have jumped to new jobs on the expectation that our stock
options will soar in value. And now as a nation we are at least
considering the possibility of putting a portion of our Social
Security money in the same pot.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is we have fallen in love with investing in the
greatest period of stock-market performance in history. We are like
people who fall in love with New England on gorgeous days in the
fall when the leaves are changing color.
</P>
<P>
   Will we feel the same if the weather turns rotten and the winter
lasts a long time?
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (617-929-2918) and Charles Stein (617-929-2922) can
also be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
