<SLUG> BC-FBN-JERRY-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICE AGRESS TO STAY WITH 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Jerry Rice will remain with the San
Francisco 49ers for the next two seasons under an agreement between
the team and the wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The deal restructures the 2000 and 2001 seasons of Rice's
existing contract, which runs through the 2004 season, and will
save the 49ers ``a significant amount'' against the salary cap,
general manager Bill Walsh said Thursday. By significant he meant
more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Until the deal is approved by the NFL, Rice is on the books for
$5,490,423 in salary cap money this season. The 49ers and Rice's
agent, Jim Steiner, were in agreement on salary but were not able
to sign off on two incentive clauses in the new contract until late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league helped us with wording for two specific clauses in
the contract,'' Walsh said. ``That wording must go to the agent and
be OK'd. Then it's up for Jerry to sign it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GARDEN-FLOOR-BOS &LR;      06-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-FLOOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD STEPPED HERE: CELTIC PARQUET TO BE AUCTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On Monday morning, segments of the original Boston
Celtics' parquet floor will be auctioned, many of them bearing the
signature of the player whose most legendary move came on that
particular panel of varnished wood.
</P>
<P>
   Decades from now, when bits of the floor hang on the walls of
important places, a number of people can justly take credit for
assuring long life to 21 squares of Tennessee Red Oak.
</P>
<P>
   They will be men with names such as Cousy and Bird, Havlicek and
Russell, Cowens, Heinsohn and Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Mann?
</P>
<P>
   That would be Jeffrey Mann, 28, the guy who spent eight weeks
studying videos, films and photographs to figure out where
everyone's feet were planted when they performed heroic deeds with
a basketball. He's also the guy who has traveled some 12,000 miles
in the past few weeks for autographs of men who have moved far from
Boston, his carry-on baggage consisting of 25-pound, 2x2-foot
square slats and a box of Sharpie pens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I got tired, I kept reminding myself: This is a piece
of sports history you're responsible for,'' said Mann. He took no
chances when he was on the road. At a Holiday Inn on a dark stretch
of Pennsylvania highway, Mann slept with the wood within arm's
reach. He said that often people asked: What's in those carpet
sample boxes that look so heavy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pieces of flooring,'' he preferred to answer, figuring that
what they didn't know, wouldn't tempt them.
</P>
<P>
   For owners of famous basketball courts that need to be sliced,
diced, autographed and auctioned, Jeffrey Mann is probably the man
for the job.
</P>
<P>
   A recent graduate of Springfield College's master's program in
sports management, Mann went to work last fall for the FleetCenter
as a sales director. His first project: Sell the 54-year-old floor
of the Boston Garden. It comprises 264 panels, each 1 1/2 inches
thick and 5 feet square.
</P>
<P>
   When the Garden was razed, the flooring was moved to the new
FleetCenter for the 1995-96 basketball season. On Dec. 22 of last
year, the floor was retired with much fanfare and a few tears by
some of the greats who had played on it. All 16 Celtics titles were
won on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A new floor was laid down for the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, conducted online by Sotheby's
(www.sothebys.amazon.com), will run from June 5 to 15. The proceeds
will go to the FleetCenter, the Celtics and charity, though Mann
wouldn't specify who will get what.
</P>
<P>
   For most Celtic fans, the attachment to the floor is strong, a
reminder of a time when the team could be relied on to be a winner
every season. ``The secret of the parquet has always been the great
players who stood on it,'' Tom Heinsohn said at the floor's
retirement party. ``That's what made it so special.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the auction is the 20x20-foot leprechaun logo
that had been center court. Most other items are 24-inch squares of
flooring (cut down from the 5-foot panels so they would be suitable
for framing) where famous players performed famous feats.
</P>
<P>
   The squares carry the National Basketball Association's stamp of
authenticity because, as Mann put it, ``the last thing we wanted to
be selling something that claimed: `This is where we think John
Havlicek stole the ball,' '' in game 7 of the 1965 East Conference
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining panels will stay in storage. Some are slated to be
given away to longtime Celtics supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mann spoke from a seat in the otherwise empty FleetCenter arena,
recalling some of the challenges of his research to match famous
plays with the appropriate slice of parquet. In the old Garden, the
television cameras (and earlier movie cameras) were located on the
opposite side of the arena from where they were located in the
FleetCenter. The team benches were also flopped, as was the center
court leprechaun.
</P>
<P>
   ``So left was right, right was left, and it all got kind of
complicated,'' Mann recalled. Early films of the pivotal moments
old-timers recalled were hard to find, in one case the saving
factor was an arcane collection of Sports Illustrated photos. The
photographs helped Mann pinpoint the square from which Bill Russell
leaped to block a St. Louis Hawks' shot in 1957. The play won the
Celtics their first NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   He said it wasn't that hard to locate the players _ sometimes a
few years, sometimes decades _ after their plays made them legends.
Many are still in basketball, working in youth leagues. Hauling the
wood around to get their signatures, however, was another matter.
The trunks of rental cars sometimes weighed down to the point they
were almost scraping the road.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting his boyhood heroes also proved disappointing at times.
For example, he stood in awkward silence while Larry Bird, the
coach today of the Indiana Pacers, was signing autographs in
Indianapolis's new Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice fieldhouse,'' he told Bird, who looked up at him with a
``do-you-really-think-that's-relevant?'' expression. The session
concluded in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Mann is pretty sure he was able to canvass the country with his
squares without anyone noticing what he was doing. The exception
was a ticket saleswoman at Los Angeles International Airport. She
had asked, as many did, what was in the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pieces of flooring,'' he responded as usual.
</P>
<P>
   She looked at his office address written on a corner of the box.
It said FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness!'' she said. ``That must be part of the old
parquet floor!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
