<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SIMON-BOS &LR;      06-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SIMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLY SIMON FINDS TIME FOR THE PAIN _ AND LEARNS FROM IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, Carly Simon was sitting in a bar in Woods
Hole, waiting for the ferry to Martha's Vineyard. She was immersed
in a book, Sartre's ``Nausea,'' about a man who becomes ill
searching for the meaning of life. Simon herself had recently been
diagnosed with breast cancer. That night she was lost in thought _
dark, painful thoughts _ about the possibility that she would never
write music again.
</P>
<P>
   Just then a song came on the jukebox. As ``Embraceable You''
played, something in Simon snapped. She had a vision of George
Gershwin toiling at his piano, grappling with his muse, struggling
to write his song. At that moment she felt something she hadn't
felt in a long time: inspired. Later that night she came up with
the first piece of original music she had liked in five years and
wrote a letter to the late composer that would eventually become
``In Honor of You (George),'' one of 11 songs on Simon's new album,
``The Bedroom Tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All things conspired and came together in a moment that made
me feel as if I could go back again,'' says Simon, recalling that
transformational night during a phone interview from her business
office in New York. ``Even if I would feel tortured.'' As it turns
out, the process of writing and recording ``The Bedroom Tapes,''
Simon's first album of original music in half a decade, was
anything but torturous. Without a record label to suggest
directions, a manager pulling strings, or a producer to feed her
ideas, Simon _ at 54 _ had the freedom to find her way back to
music on her own terms.
</P>
<P>
   She taught herself how to operate the simplest equipment and
recorded songs on an eight-track console in her daughter Sally's
old bedroom (hence the album title) in her house on Martha's
Vineyard. Sometimes, Simon says, she would pick up an instrument
randomly to test a microphone and end up just leaving the cymbal
crash, or the tambourine shake, on the track.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of writing and recording that produced 20 songs, a
handful of musicians added additional parts. But much of Simon's
original, spontaneous work was left intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about choruses, or making them three minutes to
get on the radio,`` Simon says. ``It was so simple, because it was
the truth I wanted to express, via the medium of music, in as
unself-conscious a way as I could deliver it. I'm not a great
guitarist or pianist. I can't do anything fancy. I have always
relied on people who knew more than me. So it was all very new. But
there's something about relying on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bedroom Tapes'' emerged on the heels of a long creative
slump for Simon. ``Letter Never Sent,'' from 1994, was her last
album of originals (``Film Noir,'' released in 1997, was a
collection of classics), and her experience supporting that record
jump-started a major crisis of confidence. ``The album didn't quite
hang together. The label expected ``Like a River'' to be an
important single, and it didn't perform. It was my first tour in 14
years,'' says the famously performance-shy Simon, ``and it felt as
if there wasn't really a machinery that was properly operating.
Also, none of my albums were in stores. I felt a lack of belief in
me by the people who were supposed to sell my records. And I lost
faith in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Simon's two children, Sally and Ben, were both
preparing to leave home. ``I got into this feeling, this downward
spiral, when you start questioning _ especially as you start
getting older _ your validity as an artist. With the kids getting
ready to leave, the identity I'd been hanging on to for many years
was leaving me. So I was lost. I was alone. My husband (businessman
Jim Hart) was there, and was wonderful, but I was alone in a very
deep way. And scared.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, after being diagnosed with breast cancer, Simon
underwent a mastectomy and several rounds of chemotherapy. She says
that fighting cancer was the key to reclaiming her musical voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way you battle a life-threatening illness is with
life. The thing that had always been there in my life was music.
Even if I didn't have an audience for it, and maybe I never would
have an audience, at that point I thought, `it's up to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bedroom Tapes'' finds Simon candid as ever. On the song
``Scar,'' she examines her surgery in a poetic light: ``It's after
the knives and the sutures and needles/I'm left with an arrow that
points at my heart/I call it the seat of my sentimental sorrow/Gone
seems to be one of the sum of my parts.'' The album is a literate
and lovely return to contemporary confessional pop _ aptly
described by one of the singer's friends as the most Carly Simon of
Carly Simon albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I reconnected with that thing we call the stream, the
flow, the creative spirit. I guess I call it my art.'' However,
Fans shouldn't expect a tour any time soon. ``I would rather fast
for 150 days in the desert than tour,'' says Simon. ``I'm not that
comfortable in front of a lot of people. But I'll play a concert in
your town; I'll stop and stay for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Our town was, in fact, supposed to be her town. In 1998, Simon
bought a four-story townhouse on Beacon Hill, but after a more than
a year of renovations, she decided to sell it _ two weeks after
moving in. ``I wanted to live there so badly,'' says Simon. ``But I
also wanted to be anonymous, and found out that I wasn't. Some
neighbors didn't want me to live there. It started with a roof
deck, and then the acoustics, that's the words they used, weren't
worked out. I do play music, and the first night I was there the
neighbors wrote a letter saying `we're having a problem with your
acoustics.' I didn't need to live in a place that has ill will
toward me.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon had already given up her apartment on New York's Upper
West Side, and last year she moved lock, stock, and barrel to her
longtime second home on Martha's Vineyard. For the first time in
decades, Simon has consolidated under one roof, and she's happily
nesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know just where my nasal spray and cotton sheets are,'' she
marvels.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the future is concerned, Simon only will say, ``I have
so many things planned. A lot of it involves travel and playing
music in exotic places.'' And, yes, making another album of Carly
Simon songs.
</P>
<P>
   From her vantage point, Simon is sage about the trials and
tribulations she's endured. ``You don't get to grow older and not
have a little something happen to you. You have problems in
relationships, people lose faith in you, you get sick. It happens
to everybody. I don't feel singular. But I did feel I could tap
into the experience for other people. I realized, `Hey, I can put
notes together.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
