<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER OR NOT, THE ACTION IS HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last weekend was not exactly high summer on the Atlantic, with
high winds and low temperatures well below the traditional season
kickoff norm.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the weather, the fish are in. The spring mix
combines ground fish such as cod and tautog with market-sized
haddock, wolffish, plenty of mackerel, and striped bass in nearly
every area along the coast. Bluefish have been filling steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Area A: In the far north, from Saco River to Kittery, the
schoolie stripers are everywhere, with larger fish in the mix.
Herring in Great and Little Bay are forage, and live-lined herring
is the best bait. Plenty of stripers from Adams Point in Great Bay
downriver to the mouth of Little Harbor in Newcastle. Mackerel also
draw in the big stripers along these haunts. Plenty of striped bass
at Plum Island both along the oceanfront and well up the river, the
largest fish at Lawrence at the dam.
</P>
<P>
   Area B: Danvers River is full of schoolies and the waters of
Salem and Beverly. Saturday Night Ledge was the site of some good
striper catches, along with Newcombs and Kettle Ledge. Jeffries and
Tillies Ledge is still good cod water, while schools of mackerel
keep the stripers feeding around the waters of Gloucester and down
along the Marblehead rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Harbor is still ablaze with stripers, especially the
outer islands, according to Pete Santini of Fishing FINatics in
Everett. Lots of bass at Green Island, Brewster, and Deer Island.
Best bait is live mackerel and herring, but tube and worm rigs are
also working well with a slow retrieve through the watering tubes.
There are some flounder at Peddocks and Georges, with some cod
close to shore from 12-15 pounds. A 20-pounder was caught last
weekend at the B-Jigs with clams and worms. A couple of haddock are
rumored inside the B buoy.
</P>
<P>
   Area C: Plenty of cod and striper action along the South Shore,
from the rocks around North Cohasset to Minots, 3d and 4th Cliffs
at Scituate, and the North and South rivers. Lots of mackerel
busting in schools around Minots down to Green Harbor, and the
pollock that show up in spring along this shore are here in good
numbers. Some mackerel being jigged off the Gurnet with keeper cod
and pollock, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Area D: Both sides of the Canal are hot with bass and bluefish,
with leadheads taking big bass in the Canal. At the west end,
plenty of bluefish have been hitting top and midwater plugs, and
down into Buzzards Bay the scup fishing is in season. Cleveland
Ledge to the Falmouth side is where the action congregates. Also,
tautog over the Mattapoisett Rocks, and fluke moving into the
Mashnee area.
</P>
<P>
   Area E: The bass are small along the south Cape beaches, but the
bluefish are schooling in good numbers and size throughout Vineyard
Sound, including the regular Vineyard haunts _ South Beach, Wasque,
and all around the north side waters. Good bass around both
islands, with plenty of keepers at Sconset Surfside on Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Area F: Good-size bass at Provincetown, with plenty of blues in
the mix. Sand eels and mackerel are the bait of choice. Bluefish
are hitting the north side outer beaches, with some very good size
near shore. A few large bass in the mix, but most fish down around
Pleasant Bay are smallish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
