<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2974 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CBS EXEC STILL PASSING THE PUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neal Pilson is a self-proclaimed hockey guy. He played in high
school, coached a minor league team in suburban New York and, not
too long ago, was playing in an over-30 league.
</P>
<P>
   He is a fan to say the least, and can recall dressing his son in
a hockey uniform the night before an early-morning practice to
ensure ease of transport. ``I wouldn't even wake him up,'' Pilson
said. ``I'd just put him on my shoulder, carry him to the car, and
by the time he woke up, we were at practice.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many like Pilson. He played the game, understands
the game, and remains one of its ardent supporters. ``Most
television viewers don't appreciate the difficulties of the
sport,'' Pilson said. ``Most people see a guy flip the puck to a
linesman. They make it look easy. But try it sometime. Very few
have actually tried to skate, stick handle, shoot, and avoid some
guy trying to knock your socks off.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilson also knows how hard it is to sell hockey in this country.
He was the president of CBS Sports for 14 years and was never able
to convince the network bean counters to acquire the rights to NHL
games. CBS was flush with sports deals at the time, including the
NFL, the NBA, and Major League Baseball. ``The perception about the
NHL was that it didn't generate an economic model that worked for
CBS,'' said Pilson, who started his own media consulting business
after he left CBS in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   CBS did but one NHL telecast during his tenure _ a game between
the New York Islanders and Philadelphia Flyers. The NHL didn't have
a network home in the mid-1970s. ``Unfortunately, CBS never put the
NHL on its radar screen,'' said Pilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking smaller ratings numbers, but (hockey) remains a
secure, exciting national sport. They must make sure that their
level of expectation doesn't exceed reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' in this case means ESPN and ABC, the NHL's two main
television partners. The first Stanley Cup championship game on
ESPN earned just a 1.9 rating. By comparison, the Red Sox-Yankees
game last Sunday night drew a 14.4.
</P>
<P>
   While the ratings have not grown significantly in the first year
of ESPN's six-year, $600-million-a-year deal with NHL, the network
points out that the key advertising demographic _ males 18-34 _ has
increased as much as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN and ABC have made the most of their cross-promotional
platforms. Last Saturday, Peter Jennings did a historical report on
the Stanley Cup trophy. Last month, ABC news reporter Brian Rooney
also did a report on the trophy. And while the reports appear to
blur the lines between journalism and self-promotion, Pilson said
the public doesn't seem to care about separation of journalism's
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``An argument could be made that their numbers would not be as
good as they are without all of the cross-promotion,'' Pilson said.
``Promotion doesn't hurt, but it doesn't guarantee ratings
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilson said the numbers are determined by the matchups, quality
of play, time of day, and competition on the other networks.
Another important element is star power. Michael Jordan, Tiger
Woods, Muhammad Ali _ they had the ability to draw viewers. Wayne
Gretzky didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The quality and creativity of television coverage is not the
problem. Most everything has been tried, from Fox's blue puck to
ice-level cameras to enhanced audio. Both ESPN and ABC have great
access to players during intermissions, and they have installed
cameras in the goals and high above center ice.
</P>
<P>
   What television can't do is give viewers the understanding of
actually playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   As Pilson explains, most people have shot a free throw or thrown
a football or hit a tennis ball. Not so for shooting a hockey puck.
``Almost by definition, hockey is a unique sport,'' Pilson said.
``You need a rink. You need equipment. It's limited by its very
nature. Yes, there are a lot of rinks around the country. But they
are not as numerous as soccer fields or basketball courts.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Pilson said, most Americans ``just don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey will always have that fundamental handicap,'' Pilson
said. ``But it's all about positioning. As long as the NHL doesn't
anticipate ratings in the same neighborhood as baseball or the NBA,
then the networks will be all right. It's a breakthrough that the
games are even on network television.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2975 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-CHURCH-ART-2NDTA     06-02 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-CHURCH-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DECATUR: of background.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pastor Roger W. Brumbalow's mission statement, displayed
prominently in the lobby, challenges the congregation ``to be a
multiracial, multicultural maturing body of believers,'' and,
indeed, the church is blended in almost every way. Fifty-five
percent of the members are white, 43 percent are black and the rest
are Asian or racially mixed. Perhaps a third of the blacks are
foreign born, and the church flies 36 flags to honor their
homelands.
</P>
<P>
   The Tabernacle has had trouble integrating its eight-member
pastoral staff, a legacy of the Assemblies of God's history as a
white denomination. Its first black associate pastor resigned last
fall after two years. Over the last 13 months, Brumbalow, who is
white, filled two openings with white associate pastors before
finally hiring a black youth pastor in May. The board of deacons,
by contrast, has been integrated since 1994 and acquired a black
majority after elections in March.
</P>
<P>
   The choir is thoroughly mixed, and its praise-and-worship-style
music falls comfortably between the traditional country hymns of
white Pentecostalism and the thumping gospel funk of the modern
black church. Pastor Gary Smith, the music minister, jokes that his
choir would be faultless ``if we could just get the whites to clap
on time and just get the blacks to be on time.''
</P>
<P>
   The congregation does not mix only in the pews. Blacks and
whites visit each other in the hospital, share motel rooms at
retreats and attend potluck dinners at one another's homes. They
come together in kitchens and living rooms, forming circles of
prayer around an ailing old man or a hopeful young couple, then
laying hands on the supplicants' foreheads and shoulders. Visiting
one another's suburban homes, with their manicured lawns and
large-screen TVs, these accountants and teachers, nurses and
software consultants discover the common threads of their
middle-class lives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the utopian imagery, for all the hope and faith that
the congregation has moved beyond race, the life of the church is
still driven by race in countless ways.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone has made accommodations of some kind. The whites,
mostly native Southerners, have been forced to confront their
racial assumptions and cede some control over church governance and
liturgy. The blacks have ventured from the safe harbor of the
African-American church and, in many cases, have suppressed
lifetimes of racial resentment and distrust.
</P>
<P>
   The little compromises can be detected any Sunday. They show in
the frustration of some black members with the regimentation of the
morning service, which opens with exactly 30 minutes of singing and
usually lasts precisely two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when we're praising God and then they just cut
it off,'' complains Robert Lawson. ``You can't do that. You can't
put God in a box.''
</P>
<P>
   Some whites, meanwhile, dart glances at black churchgoers who
they feel may be worshiping too exuberantly. They search for
delicate words to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of cases, the blacks are really more committed,''
says John F. Kellerman, a former deacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``More outgoing,'' agrees his wife, Grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the whites are more reserved, you know,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Behind such concerns, though, is the question at the heart of
the Tabernacle's future: Is the church simply enjoying a fleeting
moment of integration on the way to becoming predominantly black?
With the church growing rapidly and blacks joining at twice the
rate of whites, the Tabernacle could tip, like those neighborhoods
where blacks move in and whites eventually flee.
</P>
<P>
   The Tabernacle is a work in progress. But how far is it willing
to go? And how much are the Burches, the Pughs and the others
willing to concede in order to realize St. Paul's declaration that
``you are all one in Christ Jesus''?
</P>
<P>
   MAKING `COLORED' FRIENDS
</P>
<P>
   On a chilly Saturday afternoon in January, a racially mixed
crowd gathers at Howard and Janice Pugh's house for a catfish
feast. They segregate quickly, of course. The men decamp to the
garage, handicapping the Super Bowl and admiring Pugh's skill with
the deep-fat fryer. The women settle in the sun room, swapping
tales about the cold snap and the flu bug.
</P>
<P>
   When the group comes together for dinner, everyone laughs
knowingly at Eugene Glenn's stories about his 16-year-old
daughter's interest in buying a car and lack of interest in finding
a job. Before long, the joshing turns to the male love affair with
the channel changer and, eventually, to Pugh's vigilance in the
church lobby. The guests tease their host about how he was spotted
letting the youth pastor's wife cross the carpet with an open can
of soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're slipping, Howard,'' taunts William Turner, a black
deacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he chuckles, ``I'm getting soft.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as anyone, the Pughs have been transformed by the
church's integration. Having lived most of their lives with little
exposure to blacks, and little interest in gaining any, they now
count blacks from the church among their closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling before I got to know them was that there really
wasn't that many good blacks out there,'' Howard Pugh explains.
``After being around them and working with them, shoot, I don't
even think about them as colored anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Pugh's ``colored'' friends would prefer he use a
synonym. But in his mind, his choice of words marks some progress.
``Hey, I've come a long way,'' he says. ``I don't say nigger
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' his wife chimes in, ``they should see where
you've come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Where they both came from were country churches in the piney
woods of northwest Florida. When Howard was an infant, his mother
would slide him under the bench so he wouldn't get trampled while
they danced in the spirit. Janice was abandoned by her parents and
raised by a grandmother who enforced a strict Pentecostal code: no
smoking, no drinking, no dancing, no makeup, no short pants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
