<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SONGWRITING-SENSATION     06-02 2503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONGWRITING-SENSATION-CENTERPIECE-ADV04-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 DIANE WARREN: THE LOVE MACHINE OF POPULAR MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, June 4, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By ROB TANNENBAUM  
 c.2000 Rob Tannenbaum  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you own a radio, you know her songs. In the lucrative field
of Top 40 songwriting, Diane Warren is like Michael Jordan, the New
York Yankees or Wal-Mart. One of the summer's most expensive
movies, ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' which opens Friday, features a new
Warren song, ``Painted on My Heart,'' recorded by the Cult.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, 43, is arguably the most successful songwriter in music:
three of her songs, Toni Braxton's ``Un-Break My Heart,'' Celine
Dion's ``Because You Loved Me'' and Aerosmith's ``I Don't Want to
Miss a Thing,'' were among the biggest hits of the '90s. Other
writers have had equal success for a year, or a few. But no one can
match Warren's sustained highs. Since the mid-1980s, she has
written more pop hits than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, pop music mostly maintained the Broadway division
of labor: writers wrote; singers sang. Then came Bob Dylan, whom
the great Brill Building songwriter Doc Pomus once called ``the
worst thing that ever happened'' to the trade because he inspired
mediocre talents to write, which put the veterans out of business.
Now, deep into the MTV era, labels favor artists who look good over
those who write, which has put songwriters back in business, and in
power.
</P>
<P>
   Songwriters usually remain anonymous, but as with all dynasties,
Warren's success has inspired hatred. A writer for an alternative
paper in Seattle called her ``the execrable Diane Warren.'' Even
artists who benefit from her songs express ambivalence; Aerosmith's
singer, Steven Tyler, has called Warren ``a genius,'' then moments
later said that a lot of her songs are ``'expletive' see-through.''
A deal with the group to record ``Painted on My Heart'' fell
through shortly before the final deadline, which Warren calls ``a
bit of a slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The company she owns, Realsongs, grossed $25 million from her
copyrights last year, according to an executive there. Warren has
even become a force in Hollywood; she wrote the title song for
``Music of the Heart,'' which earned an Oscar nomination for
original song, her fourth consecutive nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Her ``sync fee'' for use of a song in a film is among the
highest in the business, according to an executive who has worked
with her, at $150,000 to $175,000. The songs ``are worth every
penny,'' says Kathy Nelson, president of music at Buena Vista
Motion Picture Group, who hired Warren to customize songs for
``Armageddon'' and ``Con Air'' _ which, respectively, grossed $554
million and $224 million worldwide, the latter helped immeasurably
by Warren's smash ``How Do I Live,'' which was a simultaneous hit
for both LeAnn Rimes and Trisha Yearwood.
</P>
<P>
   Having a movie theme on the radio and MTV provides ``a constant
advertisement for the film,'' says Jerry Bruckheimer, who produced
both movies. Bruckheimer sends scripts to Warren before filming
starts ``to get her involved as soon as I can.'' She has become his
unofficial in-house writer; aside from her single for ``Gone in 60
Seconds,'' she wrote four songs for ``Coyote Ugly,'' about an
aspiring songwriter who works in a rowdy bar, to be released in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give people a hit, and they want to work with you,''
Warren says.
</P>
<P>
   In music and words, Warren's songs express epic sentiments with
unabashed fervor and describe the intense passions many people feel
but can't freely express. Yet the songwriter _ a funny, informal
woman who lives with two cats and four birds (including a cherished
parrot named Buttwings) _ is far more sarcastic than sentimental.
``People who know me well say, 'I can't believe you write these
songs,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She has a reputation, even in the music business, for being
vulgar. Her sense of humor, which she terms ``pretty twisted,''
focuses on body parts and body noises, and she swears like a
teen-ager in detention. She dislikes travel, has no hobbies and
rarely takes time out from a seven-day workweek, except for what
she laughingly calls ``much-needed therapy.'' And most
surprisingly, she hasn't had a relationship in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Even extremely successful people, accustomed to sacrifice and
ambition, worry about Warren's monomaniacal commitment. ``I urged
Diane a number of years ago to get into therapy,'' says her friend
David Geffen, ``because I think it's important to have balance in
life, and she did not have it. Diane simply works.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren once asked her therapist, ``Why am I in therapy?'' The
therapist, she says, answered: ``You're successful, you're
attractive, you're smart and your best friend's a parrot. That's
why you belong in therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren works in the established language of pop songwriting: she
rhymes ``heart'' with ``apart,'' ``pain'' with ``rain,'' ``baby''
with ``crazy.'' Her songs use elemental imagery: more rain than
Portland in April, more stars than a planetarium and frequent
references to fire, sun, rivers, tears and other cinematic cues.
The sentiments are broad enough to permit a wide appeal. This
vocabulary is unpremeditated, she says, the inevitable result of
her first and most enduring romance: the radio.
</P>
<P>
   She describes herself, with the relish of the vindicated, as the
worst music student in history. Diane Eve Warren grew up in Van
Nuys, Calif., ``beyond fanatical'' about songs even in adolescence.
A guitar teacher ``told my parents I had no future in music'' and
requested she not return. Her first professional income was
accompanied by an ignominious bruise: at 14, she was hired to sing
at a Venice restaurant, but after one song, the owner paid her $25
to stop. (Almost 30 years later, she still has crippling stage
fright. ``Even if I'm getting an award, I can't even breathe.'')
</P>
<P>
   Her two sisters are 11 and 14 years older, and partly as a
result, Warren spent much of her time alone. Her solace was the
radio, and extended listening infused her with a populist
aesthetic: the best songs are the ones people like. The writers she
grew up hearing _ Carole King and Gerry Goffin, Jerry Leiber and
Mike Stoller, Burt Bacharach and Hal David, Stevie Wonder, John
Lennon and Paul McCartney _ are still her favorites. The heyday of
pop, she says, was the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is good stuff now _ my stuff.'' She laughs. ``That's a
joke.'' Even at 15, she thought she was great. ``No one else did.
Except my dad.'' Her father, David Wolfberg, sold insurance and
``changed his name to make it more palatable to anti-Semitic
people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Although her mother ``would always yell at my dad and say, 'Why
did you get her that guitar?' '' he promised to support her writing
efforts as long as she stayed in college. She was indifferent to
the classes she took and plotted every action toward the goal of
writing hit songs. She briefly worked as a messenger but was fired
for giving tapes of her songs to music executives.
</P>
<P>
   By her early 20s, she was depressed and angry that she hadn't
yet written a hit, she says. Warren tells these stories while
sitting in a lounge off her writing office, nicknamed the Cave, a
small, claustrophobic pen, maybe 10 by 12 feet, with ``only room
for me and the cockroaches.'' Cassette tapes are stacked in towers
and piled precariously on every flat surface. A framed copy of her
first million-dollar check sits on the grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   It is said the room hasn't been cleaned in 15 years, and the
legend is believable. It is ``the most intimate place'' in her
life, Warren says, and company isn't welcome. When I trespass
inside to note the room's contents, she turns visibly anxious. She
sticks to sets of habits: she has pairs of lucky socks, and she
gets to the office at a certain time each day. Her therapist has
diagnosed a slight case of obsessive-compulsive disorder, she says.
``But whatever. Whatever gets the work done.''
</P>
<P>
   After Warren wrote her first hits in the mid-'80s, including
Laura Branigan's ``Solitaire'' and DeBarge's ``Rhythm of the
Night,'' she sued the publisher she worked for, charging nonpayment
of royalties. While the lawsuit was pending, no other publisher
would sign her, so she published her own songs, an incalculably
important factor in her success.
</P>
<P>
   Though its rules sometimes seem as secret as Masonry, song
publishing is a $6 billion annual business. A No. 1 single can
gross anywhere from $250,000 to $4 million. Not all of this money
goes to the songwriter. Publishers typically take 25 percent of
mechanical royalties, the money generated by albums sales; at the
current mechanical rate of 7.55 cents, one song on a record that
sells six million copies yields about $450,000. And performance
royalties, earned each time a song is heard on radio or TV, are
usually split equally between publishers and writers. Warren almost
never writes with anyone else, so publishing her own songs has
literally saved her millions of dollars in shared earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is renowned for her tenacity in ``plugging'' songs. When
Cher didn't want to record ``If I Could Turn Back Time,'' a song
that revived her career, Warren dropped to her knees and begged.
She calls programmers at key radio stations and asks them to play
her singles. And she regularly phones a small circle of top
executives, producers and artists, sings them a song that's only
half-finished and asks, ``Do you want to record it?'' _ a practice
one executive calls ``very unusual.'' Her doggedness is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call and say you're gonna record one of her songs, she
says, 'Why not record two?''' says Nancy Russell, Trisha Yearwood's
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Where other top writers specialize in one genre, Warren has had
hits on the pop, R&AMP;B, Latin, dance, country and even Christian
charts. (She occasionally withholds songs from people she doesn't
like; although, she says with a laugh, ``If they sell 10 million
records, I might change my mind.'') Her songs have been recorded by
Barbra Streisand, Aretha Franklin, Mary J. Blige, Mariah Carey,
Tina Turner, Patti LaBelle, Gloria Estefan, Reba McEntire, Whitney
Houston, Ricky Martin, 'N Sync, Christina Aguilera and Britney
Spears. All that success has had an effect on Warren. ``Maybe I'm
not as angry as I was before,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Warren paid close to $3 million to buy from
David Geffen a villa in the Hollywood Hills. An ascetic in a
hedonistic industry, Warren doesn't seem to own anything expensive,
aside from her house and a two-seat Aston Martin convertible, or to
enjoy her money. Her single-minded goal is validation, through
getting her songs on the radio. In her living room, which has a
view of Los Angeles from downtown to the mountains, hangs a signed
photograph of Irving Berlin, whom she calls ``kind of a hero of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   There are striking similarities between Warren and Berlin, a
hard-driving immigrant Jew who owned a publishing company and
rarely wrote personal songs. As Laurence Bergreen wrote in his
biography of the composer, Berlin ``was driven by the sublimation
of his erotic impulses. While his friends frolicked in bed, Irving
remained at his piano.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren says: ``I can relate to that. It's ironic that people are
falling in love to my songs, and maybe somewhere out there, the
person of my dreams is hearing it but can't really get to me.'' Her
last relationship was with Guy Roche, who is the producer and
co-writer of Aguilera's recent ``What a Girl Wants.''
</P>
<P>
   She likens the writing process to Method acting: she imagines a
character, in love or in misery, and then, ``For the whole week, or
however long I'm writing that song, I'm that person.'' Although she
has been single for a long time, she says, ``I know what it's like
to have a broken heart,'' even if the experiences she names are all
related to music: being turned down by publishers when she was 15,
or having record labels mishandle songs. ``I know what it's like to
love _ not that I do, much,'' she adds with a knowing laugh. ``I
love my parrots. There are some people I actually love, real
humans, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ``Because You Loved Me'' _ a tributary ballad she
wrote for the Michelle Pfeiffer-Robert Redford film ``Up Close and
Personal'' _ was inspired by thinking about her devoted father, who
died of heart failure in 1987. When Jerry Bruckheimer commissioned
her to write a ``Con Air'' theme, Warren watched the film and
decided to write a song in the voice of Nicolas Cage missing his
wife. Searching for a parallel in her life, she imagined how she
might feel if she couldn't write songs and wrote ``How Do I Live,''
which stuck on the charts for a record 69 weeks. She calls it ``my
love song to music,'' though most listeners never spot this
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Song ideas and titles occur to her constantly _ she writes them
on her hand and sings them into her answering machine or a Walkman
she keeps in the front seat of her car. She even thinks of songs
during therapy: ``I'll say, 'Wait, stop, I've got to write this
title down!''' During one session, Warren said, ``I don't really
get what you're talking about.'' Her therapist replied, ``One day
you will.'' Warren liked the phrase so much, she used it for a
song. (Deborah Cox recorded it.)
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday night, Warren was scheduled to meet with Les
Nubians, a pair of French-African sisters from Bordeaux whose last
album sold unremarkably in the United States. Some top writers
wouldn't deign to meet a struggling group, but Realsongs will be
the sisters' first stop; they will fly in from Paris, drop their
bags at a hotel, put on some lipstick (they are, after all, French)
and come straight to see Warren. But their flight is delayed, and
rain and lightning light up the L.A. sky as in one of Warren's
songs. Les Nubians' manager calls to say they will be late.
</P>
<P>
   As the rest of the Realsongs staff members leave to start their
weekends, Warren waits around the office. She says contentedly,
``I've got nothing else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Tannenbaum writes about popular culture.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
