<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-02 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORMER MAYORAL CANDIDATE SAYS HE TURNED DOWN HEARST SETTLEMENT
OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly says he
has spent close to $1 million so far on his legal attempt to stop
the Hearst Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle, and he
claims he turned down a multimillion-dollar offer to settle the
antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   His comments Thursday came a day after the end of the trial on
the lawsuit, which will determine the future of daily newspapers in
San Francisco. U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker said he will
issue his ruling as quickly as possible, but did not say when.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. attorney Gary Halling said Reilly's statement about
the settlement offer was ``off base,'' declining to comment further
on the settlement negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in the Reilly-owned Merchants Exchange
Building in San Francisco, the former candidate said the Hearst
Corp. was trying to reap profits at the expense of readers, who
would not have the benefit of other ``political viewpoints'' if the
deals were allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I have spent nearly a million dollars of my own
money on this public interest lawsuit and refused to settle for
many millions more,'' said Reilly, who spent almost $4 million last
year on his fourth-place finish in the mayor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly declined to say how much he had been offered to settle
his lawsuit, which was filed Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his office, Halling said Reilly's statement was
wrong. ``As usual, the plaintiff is off base,'' Halling said. ``And
that applies to everything he's saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial ended Wednesday after Walker listened to nearly five
hours of closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The judge asked pointed questions about both the proposed $660
million sale of the Chronicle to the Hearst Corp. and Hearst's plan
to hand the Examiner, along with a $66 million subsidy, over to the
Fang family, which now publishes a three-times-a-week newspaper
here.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims both deals are shams. His lawsuit sought a court
order blocking the sale of the Chronicle. Later, after Reilly lost
out to the Fang family in his bid to buy the Examiner, his
attorneys sought to stop that sale as well, claiming the Examiner
could never succeed with the subsidy Hearst offered over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said the lawsuit had cost more than $900,000 with
attorneys, witness and transcript fees among the largest costs.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a three-page statement, Reilly echoed several arguments
his lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto, made during trial, including claims
that other Hearst executives knew about alleged ``horse trading''
between Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White and Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   White testified on the first day of the trial last month that he
had offered Brown favorable editorials in exchange for Brown's
support of the Chronicle purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. placed White on an indefinite leave of absence,
then hired retired federal judge Charles Renfrew to lead an
internal investigation to determine whether journalistic ethics had
been violated.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst released a statement in which White said he had been
``tired and confused'' while testifying. White has said he expects
to be cleared of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly asserted that the investigation was being paid for by
Hearst, and would not restore credibility to the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editorial fairness of The Examiner's news coverage will
not be restored without a thorough housecleaning at the highest
levels of the paper,'' Reilly said. ``And since the Hearst
leadership in New York, including (Hearst Newspapers President)
George Irish himself, clearly participated in blatant violations of
journalistic ethics, that housecleaning should extend from San
Francisco to the boardrooms of the Hearst Corporation in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Bronstein, executive editor of the Examiner, said the
integrity of the paper's news pages, editors and reporters remained
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein said: ``The judge will decide the merits of the
lawsuit, but as far as Mr. Reilly's comments at the press
conference _ he knows very well that the editorial integrity of our
news coverage has never been questioned in this case. Not in Tim
White's testimony or anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish testified during trial that he had not known of the offer,
although he acknowledged that White had briefed him on at least two
meetings where the publisher sought the mayor's support for
Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Frank A. Bennack Jr., Hearst's president and chief executive
officer, testified that he had been horrified when he learned about
White's testimony, and hadn't heard about the offer until after the
publisher made the statements on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly also responded to criticism that he had filed the lawsuit
as revenge against his political enemies, claiming he had done it
for readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, owning a newspaper did hold some appeal to me
when that option was presented,'' he said. ``And obtaining a choice
piece of real estate is always enticing. And yes, they say revenge
is as sweet as hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no, for those who assume these have been my motives, I'll
have to disappoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein disagreed, saying, ``His statements are not about
public good or even personal grudges. They are about
manipulation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-0603-C     06-02 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RUSSIA-0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SUGGESTS NATO, EU MAY EMBRACE RUSSIA AS PARTNER
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AACHEN, Germany _ Reaching out to Moscow on the eve of his first
summit with the new Russian leader, President Clinton suggested
Friday that Russia might one day become part of both NATO and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were part of a larger call for the United States and
Europe to step up efforts to fold Russia into the global mainstream
as a way to help advance the uneven pace of democratic and economic
reforms in the former Communist superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must work to build a partnership with Russia that
encourages stability, democracy and cooperative engagement with the
West, and full integration with global institutions,'' said
Clinton, who travels to Moscow on Saturday for a weekend summit
with newly elected President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means no doors can be sealed shut to Russia _ not NATO's,
not the (European Union's),'' Clinton said. ``The alternative would
be a future of harmful competition between Russia and the rest, and
the end of our vision of an undivided continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has had an observation and consultative role within NATO
since 1994, and Russian troops have participated with NATO forces
in peacekeeping operations in Bosnia and Kosovo. Russia hasn't
sought full membership in the alliance that stood sentry against
Soviet divisions throughout the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed, though, since the Soviet Union's collapse in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borders built to stop tanks now manage invasions of tourists
and trucks,'' said Clinton, adding that the prospect of a fuller
embrace between Russia, and NATO and the EU _ the security and
economic institutions that bore the Western alliance through
decades of Cold War against the former Soviet Union _ should not be
ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to fly to Moscow Saturday night, local
time, after participating in a day-long conference on 21st Century
governance in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin plans to host Clinton for a working dinner at the Kremlin,
setting up a day of summitry and a joint press conference on
Sunday. On Monday, Clinton will become the first U.S. president to
address the State Duma, Russia's lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The first meeting between the two leaders since Putin's election
in March, the summit is expected to focus on a high stakes set of
nuclear arms and missile defense talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger,
has repeatedly cautioned reporters to expect no immediate
breakthroughs on those fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin are already scheduled to meet three more times
this year, and the two leaders are far apart over nuclear arms
reductions and the question of whether the United States should
deploy a national missile defense (NMD) system.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said, though, that the two men will likely ink an accord
calling for each side to dispose of 34 tons of weapons-grade
plutonium, enough to produce thousands of nuclear warheads, over an
agreed upon period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the agenda will be Putin's plans for shoring up the
Russian economy, improving but still beleaguered by high inflation,
rampant corruption, criminal activity and capital flight. Putin
needs to present a credible plan for addressing those ills before
American and other foreign investors will find Russia attractive,
and the United States and multinational banks will step up badly
needed aid.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton journeyed to here to Aachen, regarded by many
as the cradle of Europe, where he was awarded the prestigious
Charlemagne Prize, named for the conqueror who placed most of
present-day Europe under his rule 1,200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the occasion to try to allay concerns across Europe
about the growing dominance of U.S. might, paying tribute to his
own country's roots and casting the United States as a product of
European vision and drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had our differences,'' Clinton said. ``But the
simple fact is, since Europe is an idea as much as a place, America
also is a part of Europe, bound by ties of family, history and
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the New World explorations of Portuguese, Spanish,
French, British and others, Clinton said, ``without the longing for
a new Europe, there never would have been an America in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed, though, that European security remains
integral to U.S. strategic policy, vowing that there would be no
diminution in the American role as leader of the NATO alliance at
the core of Europe's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe's security remains tied to America's security,''
Clinton said. ``When it is threatened, as it has in Bosnia and
Kosovo, we, too, will respond. When it is being built, we, too,
will always take part.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he re-asserted U.S. strategic interests in the
continent, Clinton sought to assuage growing concerns in some
quarters of Europe over the growing influence the United States
enjoys as the world's last remaining economic and military
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns have been rekindled by a proposal Clinton is
weighing to build a missile defense system to protect the United
States from the threat of a inter-continental ballistic attack by a
rouge state, such as North Korea or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Russia opposes the project, saying it would upset the balance of
power between the world's two largest possessors of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered earlier this week to share information about the
system, and perhaps even some of its technology with Russia. In an
interview Thursday night on NBC-TV, Putin said that he would be
open to such discussions, but the White House has not made clear
what might be entailed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, leaders in France, Germany and elsewhere across the
continent have echoed Russia's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who raised the fear
Thursday that a U.S. missile defense shield could trigger a renewed
U.S.-Russian arms race, reiterated those concerns during Friday's
award ceremony. He added, further, that such a system could
threaten the U.S.-European unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, Bill, have always sought to bring about progress in
disarmament,'' said Schroeder. ``It is therefore good that you have
said that, in making a decision, when the time comes, the relevant
security and disarmament aspects in particular will be weighed.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued Schroeder, ``this includes considering the impact on
other important states, as well as possible consequences for the
cohesion of the Atlantic alliance. Our overriding objective must
remain to guarantee durable security and to carefully choose the
best means to this end in any given situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is weighing whether to build a limited NMD system that,
proponents claim, would be able to intercept and destroy one or a
few ballistic missiles fired at the United States from across the
Pacific ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon plans to test the system in July then advise
Clinton on its projected cost _ now between $26 billion and $60
billion _ and effectiveness. It would take four or five years to
put into place.
</P>
<P>
   A decision from Clinton isn't expected until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
