<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FREEDOM-COLUMN-$ADV04     06-02 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS AREN'T IN THE MARKET FOR FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn nowadays, somebody is trying to sell you
something. Why not? The American economy is churning out
unprecedented prosperity, and consumers (the creatures formerly
known as ``people'') are snapping up vacation houses, fancy cars
and other nifty appurtenances of the good life.
</P>
<P>
   Folks are entitled to enjoy their earnings, after all. And why
should anyone attend social critics who, from their tasteful
vacation houses in Amagansett, berate the masses for buying
his-and-hers Barcaloungers?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the one thing nobody is insisting you rush out
and buy is freedom. Ever hear of it? I don't mean freedom of speech
or religion, which we enjoy in spades. I mean the freedom to do
what you want _ including, if necessary, telling your boss to drop
dead. For non-lottery winners, it's the kind of freedom that comes
of thrift, and maybe also self-knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm suggesting, in other words, is to forget that big new
professional-quality range or $40,000 sport utility vehicle and buy
yourself some freedom; you really can, because it's a commodity
just like any other.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-earner household, for instance, maybe one of you can
quit and go back to school, or even see the kids once in awhile.
Save enough and perhaps live a little more modestly, and you might
be able to ditch that lucrative but unworthy gig you've been
slaving at all these years and do something you believe in _ teach
school, start a business, move to the country, join the Elks. Read
a book, for Pete's sake.
</P>
<P>
   The current boom comes at a steep price. Cell phones, pagers,
e-mail and other technological tethers keep us on our toes at all
hours. Those who hand out Internet freebies insist that you pay
with your privacy. Even the dot-com elite find themselves bound by
so-called golden handcuffs: They can't leave until their options
vest, and now that investors are showing signs of coming to their
senses about Internet valuations, it may all be for naught anyway.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when more people than ever have the opportunity to do
what they want in life, many lack the imagination to do anything
but accumulate possessions. Freedom is losing market share to
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Why? One possibility is that freedom has a marketing problem.
All the other stuff is hawked day and night in commercials
suggesting that a product will somehow make you more free rather
than less. Yet freedom itself goes unpromoted.
</P>
<P>
   This woeful lack of advertising for America's very best product
means relatively few people know about it, at least judging by
consumer behavior. Easy credit and record-high personal
indebtedness mean that, despite rising affluence, lots of people
still owe their souls to what amounts to the company store. ``Money
is coined liberty,'' Dostoyevski rightly observed long ago. People
who make pronouncements like that are usually well-fixed in the
things department; the poor regrettably don't have the option of
blithely giving up some of their income to change their lives.
Besides, Americans really like all the stuff they buy, even
deriving a sense of identity from it. Yet many of us are so rich
that we need not give up much material well-being to become a whole
lot freer to do what we want to do.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Americans aren't in the market for more freedom because
they already enjoy an extraordinary degree of personal liberty, by
global and historical standards. It's odd that we aren't any
happier, though. Maybe we have too much of some kinds of freedom
and too little of others.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that money buys freedom (if not love) might change
the way you look at all you make and spend. If you're smart, it
will induce you to save more. It might also challenge you to think
about what you're doing with your life. Then again, money has
always heavily taxed the imagination. In this day of unbacked
currency and electronic balances, the whole concept requires a leap
of collective faith.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the reason there's so little call for more material
freedom in this country. More than anything else you buy, freedom
demands that you do something with it. It's not something to tuck
away in the garage or unload a few years later on eBay. When
someone asks, ``Free to do what?'' the answer doesn't always come
easily. But when you're lucky enough to live in a time and place
like this one, perhaps that's your  &UR; real &LR;  job _ not making the
money, but figuring out what you ought to achieve with it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1559EDT &QL; 
