<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-GUIDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUIDE TO READING C.S LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies LEWIS-PILGRIMS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interested in investigating some of C.S. Lewis' writings? Here's
a review of a new guide to his work, plus a list of some of his
best-known books.
</P>
<P>
   _Colin Duriez's ``The C.S. Lewis Encyclopedia'' (Crossway,
$17.99) is subtitled ``A Complete Guide to His Life, Thought, and
Writings.'' Well, all right _ for a really complete guide to
``probably the greatest popularizer of the Christian faith in
recent times,'' you'd need a tome at least three or four times this
size. But you might be surprised at what Duriez is able to do in
240 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The entries include material on Lewis' books, background,
relatives, friends and philosophies. Distinguishing this volume
from Zondervan's ``The C.S. Lewis Reader's Encyclopedia'' (which is
otherwise more exhaustive _ and expensive) is Duriez's extensive
cataloging of Lewis' fictional characters and sites, although those
entries are rather abbreviated.
</P>
<P>
   Duriez, an editor with InterVarsity Press in the United Kingdom,
tends to write informally, although ordinary readers may find the
material on academic subjects a bit rarefied. ``The C.S. Lewis
Encyclopedia'' will be a handy reference work for those interested
in a long-popular writer.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Chronicles of Narnia,'' a seven-volume fantasy series for
children beginning with ``The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe.'' A
lion named Aslan is a Christlike figure.
</P>
<P>
   _''Mere Christianity,'' a classic discourse on Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Screwtape Letters,'' a satirical work about a devil's
advice to an apprentice demon.
</P>
<P>
   _''Surprised by Joy,'' Lewis' autobiography describing his
spiritual journey from atheist to thoughtful Christian.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
