r l BC-LEWIS-PILGRIMS-2ndTak     06-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-PILGRIMS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
OXFORD, England: by collectors. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tour buses have been banned from Lewis Close, the tree-lined
street leading to The Kilns, but small vans and taxis frequently
unload tourists who shoot pictures of The Kilns and wander in a
nearby forest that was owned by Lewis and his late brother, Warren
``Warnie'' Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The forest _ with a small lake and strangely shaped rocks and
tree trunks that sometimes resemble monsters _ is said to have
inspired many of Lewis' children's stories.
</P>
<P>
   At Magdalen College, where many famous people taught, there is
little information about Lewis. But many visitors gravitate toward
the chapel where Lewis often worshipped.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis frequently walked in the deer park and other wooded areas
behind Magdalen College. On a path called Addison's Walk is a
plaque displaying one of his last poems. Some believe that the
poem, ``What the Birds Said Earlier This Year,'' was a premonition
of his death. It includes the words:
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, this year, as all the flowers foretell,
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall escape the circle and undo the spell.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, an unlikely blend of tweedy intellectual and ardent
Christian who embraced the supernatural, was a gifted lecturer and
writer on many subjects _
</P>
<P>
   moral, philosophical and theological.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that one of the 20th century's greatest expounders of
the Christian faith is identified with a pub is only one of many
unexpected twists in the life of this brilliant Oxford don.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more popular now than when he died,'' said Walter Hooper,
a kindly North Carolina native who was Lewis' secretary when he
died. ``He still has a lot to say to a confused and complicated
world. He could take the great wisdom of the ages and make it
understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a member of the Church of England, died Nov. 22, 1963,
the same day President John F. Kennedy was assassinated in Dallas.
Few took note of Lewis' death then, but his fame has endured.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by reading Celtic and Norse mythology as a
14-year-old, Lewis was an atheist much of his adult life. His
conversion to Christianity in 1931 was heavily influenced by his
friend Tolkien. Lewis became convinced of the supernatural
existence of good and evil and believed Jesus was God's way of
rescuing humankind from sinfulness.
</P>
<P>
   He had a gift for explaining complex theological matters in
simple terms, demonstrated when he went on BBC radio during World
War II with comforting talks about his faith. Some of his major
Christian works include ``Miracles'' and ``Mere Christianity,'' a
remarkably down-to-earth account of how a skeptic came to embrace
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a splendid popularizer of the faith,'' said Barrington
White, well-known British church historian and retired principal,
or president, of Oxford's Regents Park College. ``I can remember
during World War II how much he did for the generation of my
parents. He won many of them back to faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' religious allegories, such as the ``The Screwtape
Letters'' _ fictional correspondence between a senior and junior
devil _ have been compared to those of John Bunyan, author of ``The
Pilgrim's Progress.''
</P>
<P>
   His children's stories are equally popular, including the
imaginative ``The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe,'' the first of
his chronicles of the fictional Land of Narnia.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper _ who has lived in Oxford most of his adult life and has
been named by Lewis' estate to edit his letters and other papers _
scoffs at critics who say Lewis oversimplified theological
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is part of his brilliance,'' Hooper said. ``He
has a double gift. He can be both profound and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of C.S. Lewis Societies in the United States
and around the world. How would C.S. Lewis feel about his
continuing popularity?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Lewis doesn't hear any of this,'' Hooper said.
``I think he is in purgatory, where he hoped and prayed he would be
after his death, so he could make up for some of his sins.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
