<HEADLINE>
SCHOLAR'S SPIRIT STILL LIVES IN WOODS, COUNTRY LANES AND PUBS OF
OXFORD
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by LEWIS-GUIDE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England _ One of the best places to find out about
atheist-turned-devout-Christian C.S. Lewis is in a pub.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the surprising things the droves of Lewis pilgrims
discover in Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Lewis' books are in print, and he has a cultlike
following. He accumulated more fans with the 1994 release of the
critically acclaimed movie ``Shadowlands,'' starring Anthony
Hopkins and Debra Winger, about Lewis' love for an American, Joy
Gresham.
</P>
<P>
   The fans of the scholar with the deep faith and the wonderful
way with words are so many that directing Lewis pilgrims is a minor
industry in this part of England.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Oxford visitors who are curious about Lewis are
directed to his favorite pub, the Eagle and the Child, nicknamed
the Bird and the Baby by Lewis and his literary cronies, including
fantasy writer J.R.R. Tolkien.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors treat the pub on St. Giles Street like a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Even on Friday nights, when students loudly revel on an outdoor
patio until after midnight, Lewis aficionados can be seen squinting
at plaques and pictures and discussing Lewis and his comrades, The
Inklings.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the many sites in Oxford connected with Lewis can be
challenging. But aids abound.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a hand-drawn map showing Lewis sites can be
obtained for a few pence at the old Registry Office where Lewis and
Gresham were married in a civil ceremony. The building is now the
Quaker Center, also on St. Giles, just two doors down from the
Eagle and the Child.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a recent development, the Oxford Information
Centre near the bus station distributes a commendable summary of
Lewis' life, with helpful information on how to reach sites
connected to Lewis. Local tour guides take groups on walks to the
Lewis sites for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   But zealous Lewis pilgrims can explore on their own, using the
map from the Quaker Center. The tireless can even tramp the five
miles or so to Lewis' home in Headington, The Kilns, following the
route often taken by the professor.
</P>
<P>
   Near his home is Holy Trinity Church, which he attended, and the
church cemetery where he is buried. The church has a stained-glass
window honoring him.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites to visit include University College, where Lewis
studied and received his degrees; University Church of St. Mary the
Virgin, where Lewis preached his first sermon in October 1939; and
10 Old High Street, where Joy lived with her two sons.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis pilgrim can also take a taxi. Peter Cousins, a taxi
driver recommended by Lewis scholars, has been conducting Lewis
tours for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   He not only shows visitors the sites but also offers anecdotes
that he has gleaned from interviews and biographies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got involved with C.S. Lewis quite by accident,'' Cousins
said. ``A woman hailed my cab outside Magdalen College and wanted
to visit Lewis' home. We couldn't find it, so I began learning all
I could about C.S. Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins, treasurer of Oxford's C.S. Lewis Society, drove a
visitor by Parsons' Pleasure, a pond where Lewis was fond of
swimming nude. He stopped at Lewis' first home, at No. 1 Mansfield
Drive, and pointed out a house with a red door as the place Gresham
lived before marrying Lewis. Cousins wended through heavy traffic
to the Eastgate Hotel near Magdalen College, where the couple met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadowlands,'' the movie, ``had so many errors,'' Cousins
said. ``It had Lewis and Joy being wed at the Registry Office in
London. But it happened right here in Oxford.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was a professor of literature at Oxford's Magdalen College
for 29 years. When he took a distinguished professor position at a
rival institution, Cambridge University, late in his career, he
maintained his residence in Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Now the red brick house, surrounded by plush gardens, is owned
by the C.S. Lewis Foundation of Redlands, Calif., and is being
developed as a study center. Volunteers from around the world live
for a time at the home, repair it, answer visitors'questions and
participate in conferences. A major symposium was held there in
1998 on the 100th anniversary of Lewis' birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about living in this house, it is very
humbling,'' said Ryan Hawkins of Arkadelphia, Ark., who is spending
a year as chief resident, or caretaker, of The Kilns. ``We have
about six people staying here now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and his wife, Meredith, showed a visitor around the home
and even opened the attic, which may have inspired Lewis' ``The
Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Gilnett of Seattle, who has been volunteering at The Kilns
since 1993, said that Gresham was responsible for remodeling the
home in the late 1950s. Much of the original furniture is gone,
including old wardrobes bought by collectors.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
