<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUSTY COMEDY AROUSES PASSIONATE FEELINGS IN BOTH FANS AND FOES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TV-SEX-WOMEN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ongoing quarrel over how trampy or edgy, cheap or deep,
artificial or genuine ``Sex and the City'' is broke out into a
range war along the sexual divide earlier this year. With the
show's unexpected Golden Globes win as best comedy producing both
cheers and jeers, the already-heated debate over the show's merits
(or lack thereof) leaped out of control, setting things up quite
nicely, as it turns out, for the show's third, friskier-than-ever
season.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the first of 18 new episodes Sunday on HBO, ``Sex
and the City,'' about four single women (Sarah Jessica Parker,
Cynthia Nixon, Kristin Davis and Kim Cattrall) navigating love,
lust and sexual liability in Manhattan, has now reached the point
where success definitely breeds contempt, which has girded the
show's passionate fans to take up arms to defend their show (and
usually, in the process, their gender as well).
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' scores such a deep response from its fans
because its endlessly chatty observations on sex of all kinds, sex
toys, wrinkled bottoms, flat chests, large chests, spanking, boy
toys, bisexuality and other such subjects are used as bridges to
serious and very real emotional issues. And while mining emotional
terrain that's familiar to anyone who's lived _ willfully or not _
the single life, it toys with and confounds its audience's
expectations in a way that no TV show has since ``Ally McBeal's''
first season, and does so with considerably more amusement and
poignancy _ and without any dancing babies.
</P>
<P>
   For insiders, that ``Sex and the City'' comes from
producer-writer Darren Star only adds to the unexpectedness of the
show's success. Star was creator of ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and
``Melrose Place,'' two series that, over the years, ground their
audiences to dust by elevating tales of shallow young
pretty-somethings to high drama. True to form, their recent demises
(''Melrose Place'' last season, ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' last
month) weren't graceful exits so much as mercy killings.
</P>
<P>
   Star vacated network television in disgust after his ``Central
Park West'' went belly up a couple years back, and it appeared his
reputation was headed the same way. You could say ``Sex''
represents the producer's sweet revenge, particularly now that the
broadcast networks have summoned him to duplicate ``Sex's'' success
with a drama about men working on Wall Street. (Good luck, pal.)
</P>
<P>
   Cattrall, whose performance as the cynical, sex-hungry Samantha
has revived her struggling career, has said Star's no-holds-barred
scripts have given her, finally, creative liberation.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Sex'' can be appreciated for its fearless,
dare-to-be-different writing, it is also easy to love because it's
eons removed from the typical sitcom format. In just about every
episode, a subject (usually about dating) is raised and debated
heatedly, usually over a meal or a drink at a nightclub. Adjustment
follows debate until the climax (often literally), after which the
women cut their losses and get together again to figure out just
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   What has made ``Sex'' so watchable is that the women, unlike
characters in most sitcoms, actually learn from their mistakes
sometimes, and in the process they have matured from stereotypes to
characters with hearts and real vulnerabilities. For example: The
way Parker's Carrie sets herself up for failure with Chris Noth's
Mr. Big, the quintessential ``Man Who Can't Commit,'' could not
have happened in the show's first year, but it's just right for
where her character is at in the second season.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Parker has been able to create a kinder, gentler
Carrie without losing the edge of the more morose, cynical
character in Candace Bushnell's book, on which ``Sex'' is loosely
based.
</P>
<P>
   None of which diminishes what I consider to be the truly
subversive part of the show. A number of women I know are already
so devoted to this show it's a little frightening, but the fact is
that these characters they relate to so passionately are no more
real than the tooth fairy. I can't help but wonder if these female
characters that women love so much are actually designed for men to
love, or at least for men to love to hate. I often wonder if the
tight-lipped pessimism of Nixon's Miranda, for example, is the
result of the show's male writers (most of the writing staff is
male, by the way) using a character to explain their own bitterness
toward women. And I wonder if the odd situations Davis' mousy
Charlotte always seems to get herself into result, again, from male
writers working out their own feelings toward a tease masquerading
as a good girl.
</P>
<P>
   And while I've found the foursome's coarse euphemisms for men's
body parts hilarious, a number of men have found it offensive and
shallow, which once again suggests the show has been designed as
much to salve male viewers' wounds as those of females.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie, Samantha, Miranda and Charlotte are, let's face it,
elitist snobs who care little about needs other than their own. Men
with money and standing and fame attract them, yet they whine when
the rich lugs turn out to be soulless jerks. (Did Carrie really
think she could change Mr. Big?)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's a testament to Star's talent that he's able to make
us feel for these woman, how, for instance, Miranda can seem like
such a, well, shallow witch, and yet pull us back on her side in a
subsequent episode in which she shows a warm heart.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, if the show's female fans have no problem with
the characters' superficial musings, who am I to suggest the show
strays far from the truth?
</P>
<P>
   As for future adventures, Sunday's premiere finds Carrie
attracted to a politician played by John Slattery while Samantha
has meaningless but, as she notes, ``pretty exquisite,'' sex with a
fireman up against his truck. Miranda gets laser eye surgery and
has to be led home by that ever-compromising Steve, played by David
Eigenberg, in the clingy role reserved for women on most shows.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent episodes include ``Politically Erect,'' which begs
the question, ``Can there be sex without politics?'' And, in ``Boy,
Girl, Boy, Girl ...'' Carrie is faced with the question, ``Does
gender really exist?''
</P>
<P>
   Although there's always the chance that the women could become
as peevishly insufferable as the squabbling malcontents of
``Melrose,'' right now the playful atmosphere of ``Sex'' provides a
joyful romp that is unlike anything else in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
