<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-WOMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX AND MY CITY: SINGLE WOMEN WHO KNOW WHAT THEY WANT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TV-SEX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hate that show.''
</P>
<P>
   Curious about how any twentysomething guy could not
automatically give his approval to something so obviously heavy on
the sex quotient, I turned my attention from the Dallas Stars
post-game wrap-up to his attractive young face and asked him to
explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's written for men,'' he said. ``The women on `Sex and the
City' aren't real. They act like sexual predators. Women aren't
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a thirtysomething single woman, I think I know exactly what
women are like _ certainly more so than this freshly minted man.
But never one to ruin a Memorial Day party with debate about the
politics of sex, I decided instead to agree with his next point: It
was definitely time to gather a group and head to a local bar for
some beer and darts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I give you a ride?'' he asked me, heading for a tiny,
black sports car. Climbing in, I couldn't help but wonder when I
had last been in a car with just two seats. Ten years ago? Fifteen?
There was no room for kids. No room for groceries. Barely room for
two shopping bags full of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And then it hit me. There's no way this Generation Next guy _
who spent his time in the company of twentysomething girls guilty
of faux pas involving tanning salons, fake nails and embarrassing
errors in fashion judgment _ could relate to my favorite show about
four single, independent women in their 30s. He was used to being
around twentysomething girls _ our youthful doppelgangers, as the
HBO show's heroine, Carrie Bradshaw, described them in one episode.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know anything about single, independent women in their
30s like me.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The first time I saw Carrie Bradshaw and her friends Miranda,
Samantha and Charlotte, I fell completely in love.
</P>
<P>
   It was last December, the end of the show's second season, and a
friend taped the finale for me. I watched it three times in two
days.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Carrie mustered up the courage to ask a newly engaged
Mr. Big _ her on again/off again boyfriend for two years _ why it
wasn't her he was marrying, I tried to answer the same question for
myself. I had an ex-boyfriend, too, who three or four nanoseconds
after our breakup decided commitment was OK after all _ so long as
it wasn't to me.
</P>
<P>
   As Carrie and her girlfriends, swilling cosmopolitans, analyzed
the Big situation, concluding that Big didn't have the capacity to
understand complicated Carrie and instead had settled for someone
simpler, Carrie felt better, stronger, wilder.
</P>
<P>
   I turned off the TV, drove directly to the headquarters of my
cable company and agreed to pay $18 more each month to add Home Box
Office to my viewing package.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Predators'' is a strong word. Predators steal. They plunder.
</P>
<P>
   When you're thirtysomething, and you're a single, independent
woman, it's not so much that you think of men as sexual remora,
it's just that you know more about what you want _ and don't want
ever again under any circumstances whatsoever _ in a relationship.
And you're not afraid to talk _ and laugh _ about it.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, as I watched Sunday night reruns of the second
``Sex'' season, often swilling wine with my girlfriends, I wondered
along with Carrie and her friends about a number of quirky,
quixotic but somehow essential relationship questions that are the
comedic foundations of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Can you be friends with an ex? My real-life friend Carrie
answered with an emphatic no, agreeing with the show's Miranda that
the best philosophy is ``we didn't work out as a couple; you need
to not exist'' and proving it by hiding behind a counter in Whole
Foods when her ex waltzed through the glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   Have we evolved past relationships? My personal example was a
clueless guy named Tony who called me back a full four weeks after
our wild first date and had the nerve to think I might like to go
out that very evening _ could we meet in an hour?
</P>
<P>
   And this one, a personal favorite: Are all men freaks? My
girlfriends' list of inexplicable behavior from men was longer than
the lists of what we bought each week at Target.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It's the age-old question. Which came first: women talking
openly about sex _ or ``Sex in the City,'' which encourages a
no-secrets dialogue among friends, pondering those questions that
single, independent women in their 30s are never supposed to think,
let alone say out loud (like this season's debut dilemma: ``Do
women just really want to be rescued?'').
</P>
<P>
   What I'm sure of is that lately I've been framing my own musings
about men into the kinds of questions Carrie punches into her
laptop each episode in her work as a columnist for a New York
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   _Voice mails, e-mails and Caller ID _ is electronic technology
heating up or destroying modern romance?
</P>
<P>
   _How can you tell if ``no'' really means ``maybe'' or ``yes''?
</P>
<P>
   _Does a guy deserve an official breakup after only one date?
</P>
<P>
   _And can a thirtysomething woman find any sort of happiness with
a twentysomething man?
</P>
<P>
   This last one came to mind after two games of darts, one game of
pool and several pitchers full of bad, bad beer when the
twentysomething guy asked for my phone number with all the
confidence of someone who has yet to have his dreams dashed and his
illusions shattered.
</P>
<P>
   So, I gave him my number.
</P>
<P>
   And I even let him think, for a while, that it was all his idea.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
