<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-02 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAW GRADS FIND CLERKING HAS APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By L.M. SIXEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Frenzied competition for lawyers from Internet
start-ups and investment banking companies have pushed first-year
associate salaries at Houston's blue chip firms to $115,000.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities such as Chicago and New York, starting salaries
are closer to $140,000.
</P>
<P>
   So how can federal judges find newly minted lawyers who graduate
at the top of their class who are willing to spend a year or two as
a clerk at an annual salary of $42,000?
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, the relatively low salaries don't appear to
be much of a problem in attracting top graduates. Which goes to
show money isn't everything.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Circuit Judge Jerry Smith of the Fifth Circuit Court of
Appeals in Houston said he hasn't noticed any falloff in
top-quality applications for the four, one-year clerkship positions
he offers each year. But, he added, the run-up in law firm salaries
is fairly recent so it could depress the next crop of applications.
</P>
<P>
   Other judges aren't seeing a decline in the number or quality of
the hundreds of applications they receive each year either.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that applications would dip but a clerkship is a
prestigious appointment, said U.S. District Judge Vanessa Gilmore,
who has two clerks at a time on two-year appointments.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, having a federal clerkship _ especially at the U.S.
Supreme Court _ is a real plum in any lawyer's rsum. It's so great
that many new lawyers are willing to accept the feudal lordship
system and work for the equivalent of slave wages.
</P>
<P>
   To make it work financially, Gilmore finds that many of the
clerks who come to work for her live at home with their parents to
save money.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Maya Raghu did to put a dent into her $55,000 of law
school loans. Raghu, who called her two years with Gilmore an
``absolutely amazing'' experience, said she doesn't regret the
sacrifice one bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the best legal job I will ever have,'' she said,
waxing on about her close-up view of the controversies in front of
the court.
</P>
<P>
   But the Georgetown University Law Center graduate is heading to
a law firm in New York this fall in which she'll start at $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty common phenomenon for Gilmore, who routinely
sees her clerks going into jobs that pay more than her $141,300
annual salary.
</P>
<P>
   Sorcha Landau has it better than most clerks. She worked for a
New York firm for a year before she arrived in Houston to clerk for
Gilmore and consequently received a special bump in pay that works
out to an extra $25,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her $67,000 pay packet is less than the $135,000 she'd be
earning if she were still in New York. However, it's enough to pay
the rent and her $700 a month in student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Landau said, her parents have a hard time with the fact
she accepted a lower-paying, two-year clerkship instead of taking
the big bucks at the law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand the honor _ in the abstract _ but they can't
wait for me to finish and get on with my career,'' she said. ``They
see me getting waylaid here in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   While many new lawyers can make the financial sacrifice, Gilmore
said she doesn't get enough minority applicants, especially from
students who are the first person in their family to go to college.
They can't afford to take a clerkship because of their heavy load
of student debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine taking a clerkship for $42,000 when you can get
$142,000 and have $70,000 in debt?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore said she set up an interview with a minority candidate
but before she could interview him, another judge hired him.
</P>
<P>
   To make it easier for students it has recruited to accept
clerkships before coming to work for the firm, Vinson &AMP; Elkins just
boosted its sign-on bonus to clerks from $10,000 to $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Reeder, the hiring partner at Vinson &AMP; Elkins, said the firm
wanted to encourage its lawyers to get what he calls a marvelous
up-close experience of how the judicial process works. He said the
firm also wanted to support what it sees as a good public service.
</P>
<P>
   Reeder said there was some concern at the firm that new lawyers
couldn't afford to take the clerkships without some special
financial help.
</P>
<P>
   It was all great news for Garrett Wotkyns, a first-year
associate, who is heading out for a one-year clerkship with a
federal appeals court judge in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Wotkyns said the money will come in handy so he can pay off a
chunk of his $100,000 in student loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
