<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-TELLER-$ADV04     06-02 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-TELLER-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAIT OF A DIRTY LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By now, many fashion photographers have had an
exhibition mounted or a book published to inform the world of their
artistic intentions. On Thursday, it was Juergen Teller's turn to
be an artist in New York. The German-born Londoner was in town for
his show at the Lehmann Maupin Gallery in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Teller is best known for discovering Kate Moss, and his images
of strung-out-looking models in unappealing settings (described as
everything from dirty realism to heroin chic) have helped to lower
the traditional standards of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't done much for the dress code at parties, either. For
his big night, the laid-back Teller, 36, was wearing ripped Levi's
with one button of his fly undone, a washed-out beige T-shirt and
canvas sneakers. In one pocket, he had stuffed a camera, in the
other, a pack of Marlboros. Never mind that the T-shirt was given
to him by Marc Jacobs and the camera was a limited-edition Olympus.
The effect was an oh-so-casual nonchalance that makes fashionable
people doubt themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about fashion at all,'' the unshaven Teller said
in his German accent, as he walked from the Mercer Hotel to his
opening. ``And I know it's kind of a dodgy thing to be a fashion
photographer, a kind of pathetic occupation, but I like it, even
though I question it.''
</P>
<P>
   SoHo's streets were glamour glutted with fashion statements,
from dirty denim to Sabrina heels. ``You can't get away from
fashion,'' said Teller, who had a hangover and whose hangdog hair
was greasy, not wet and squeaky-clean, he pointed out. ``The whole
beauty thing is everywhere. It's just really weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the gallery, fashion followers were flocking to celebrate
the pleasant and approachable Teller, and every one of them was far
better dressed than he was. Sofia Coppola, the director, for
instance, was in a flouncy denim skirt, and Dan Peres, the new
young editor of Details, wore a crisp white shirt and grown-up
slacks. The model Stephanie Seymour was in a pretty sundress, and
nearby, 5-year-old Troy Baker was drinking a Snapple in a
super-dapper blue suit.
</P>
<P>
   Even the usually low-key and pared-down Helmut Lang wore a natty
blazer, despite the oppressive heat. ``I wanted to make an effort
out of respect for the artist,'' he said, adding that he and Teller
share an interest in restraint. ``It's important to know when not
to do things.'' Like not dressing up for a fashionable,
high-profile party given in your honor? ``Juergen has to stay with
his trademark look,'' Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   As the opening continued to open, questions rose in the air with
the heat. Were Teller's Polaroid shots of aspiring supermodels in
one room and giant portraits of smiling Miss Universe contestants
in another raw or facile? Did Jackson Pollack permanently alter the
dress code for all artistic geniuses? Do Marc Jacobs (who designs
beautiful clothes but never dresses in them) and Teller trade
T-shirts sometimes?
</P>
<P>
   As the evening wound down, so did Teller's pants, which had
dropped just low enough to reveal a bit of his behind and his boxer
shorts. ``He's got a timeless grunge look,'' observed Stefano
Tonchi, the creative fashion director of Esquire, who was wearing a
Jil Sander suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all about unfashion,'' said Cary Leitzes, the photography
director of Harper's Bazaar. ``These days, the more powerful you
are, the schlumpier you are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless,'' added Stefan Campbell, a stylist, ``you're Anna
Wintour.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way out, someone asked the chain-smoking Teller how he
felt after his big evening. He shrugged. ``Not horrible,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-02 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POINTERS ON BUYING NEW GRAPHICS CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because you're not a hard-core game player, don't think
your computing experience won't benefit from a better graphics
card. You don't have to be a Quake III junkie to discover the joy
of state-of-the-art 3-D acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to pay a fortune, either. One of the benefits
of the torrid pace of development in the graphics card business is
that yesterday's top-of-the-line board is now a bargain. Cards
introduced just nine to 12 months ago have more than enough power
to run today's games comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   My father is an example of those who switch cards. At 70, he's a
big fan of flight simulators, and he was happy with the look he got
on his relatively new IBM Aptiva, which comes with a generic,
built-in graphics chip.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until he saw Microsoft's Flight Simulator 2000 running
on an Elsa Gladiac card, which uses nVidia's new GeForce 2 GTS
processor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he became interested in fill rates, gigatexels and
bump-mapping.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need a Gladiac, though, which would cost him about
$350. He would be happy with a 3dfx Voodoo3, or a card that uses
nVidia's older TNT2 chip, or ATI Technology's Rage 128 card. He
could find all of these in the $100 to $200 range.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for a video card can be confusing for many reasons.
There are multiple generations of cards on store shelves, so
picking the right one based on budget and needs is not easy. You
also need to know something about your PC, and the games or
graphics applications you plan to run.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a guide to the basics of video card shopping in May
1999, which you can read at www.chron.com/content/
chronicle/tech/99/05/14/compute.html. But there are now more
aspects to consider:
</P>
<P>
   The drop in PC prices means more people can afford a new
computer. But low-cost systems often have a serious graphics
drawback. Rather than using a replaceable video card for displays,
their displays are generated by a chip that's fixed to the main
system board. In modern PCs, the chip still communicates with the
rest of the computer though an Accelerated Graphics Port, or AGP,
connection, but there is no separate AGP slot.
</P>
<P>
   That means if you want to add a better card, you'll have to use
a PCI (Peripheral Component Interconnect) slot, which is a slower
connection.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the latest generation of cards is not available
in the older PCI format, though that may change. But older cards
unveiled in the last year should still provide enough speed and a
great look for most uses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest trend in graphics card design is moving functions
that previously were handled by the computer's main processor to
the graphics card itself. This allows the PC's chip to do other
work, which speeds both graphics and other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Different card manufacturers take different approaches to this.
For example, cards that use nVidia's GeForce 256 and GeForce 2 GTS
chips, as well as ATI's upcoming Radeon 256 card, handle transform
and lighting _ the way objects are drawn and then lit in a 3-D
world _ on the graphics card itself.
</P>
<P>
   3dfx has not included this feature. Instead, its pitch is that
its new Voodoo4 and Voodoo5 cards are better at smoothing out edges
in 3-D scenes, a process known as full-scene anti-aliasing. (The
nVidia chip does this as well.) It's difficult to cut through the
marketing hype on these features. Some features, such as transform
and lighting, require developers to write software that takes
advantage of them. Others, such as anti-aliasing, work
automatically with any game.
</P>
<P>
   Look for features that are supported by more than one
manufacturer. Both 3dfx and nVidia offer anti-aliasing; ATI and
nVidia support transform and lighting. You'll find that developers
are more prone to take advantage of features if more than one
graphics company supports them.
</P>
<P>
   A graphics card is only as good as its drivers, the software
that lets the hardware talk to the computer's operating system.
Graphic card drivers are notoriously buggy _ in fact, many problems
in Windows can be traced to this problem.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, older cards may actually be more stable and
work with more applications and games than newer cards. Most of the
graphics card vendors are good about releasing new drivers on a
regular basis, so many bugs get worked out in the first three to
six months of a card's life.
</P>
<P>
   State of the art graphics cards are so powerful that other
facets of a PC can become a performance bottleneck. If you've got
an older PC with a paltry amount of memory, a next-generation video
card may be unable to strut its stuff in your system. In this case,
an older card that's still better than what you have now may be a
more cost-effective choice.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a hard-core gamer, or anxious to drain every drop of
performance from a graphics card, you may want to look for one
that's friendly to overclocking. This involves forcing the card to
run at a slightly faster speed than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Overclocking can be risky. Graphics chips can get hot, and
making them run faster makes them hotter. This can cause game
lockups, or even damage the chip. But some cards are more amenable
to overclocking, and those that are often come with built-in
utilities that let you do this.
</P>
<P>
   Take it slow, increasing the chip's speed a little at a time,
then testing with your favorite game after each increment. If you
start seeing erratic behavior, shut the game down and back off on
the speed.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, I'll take a look at two state-of-the-art cards:
Elsa's GeForce 2 GTS-based Gladiac and 3dfx's Voodoo5 5500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
