<HEADER>
A3018 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GAVIN-PROFILE-$ADV04-     06-02 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAVIN-PROFILE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAME AND DISDAIN ON FAR WEST 15TH ST. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a spring Saturday night, a crowd reeking of grunge
and glamour choked the entrance to Gavin Brown's Enterprise, a
gallery in the meatpacking district. It had come to see
Fischerspooner, nine performance artists costumed like a hybrid of
the 1980s band Devo and the cast of ``The Rocky Horror Picture
Show.'' The artists sang and danced with the audience against a
backdrop of smoke, strobe lights and synthesized music.
Reservations for the five nights of performances were a must, but
many wheedled their way past the list-keepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mad,'' said Cecily Brown, the painter. ``No one wants to
be the one who hasn't seen it. Of course, it has to do with Gavin.
He has a consistently high batting average of art that is new and
lively.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavin is Gavin Brown, a British-born dealer, who represents a
roster of rising stars, the best known of whom is Chris Ofili,
whose creativity with elephant dung was the subject of the fuss
over the Brooklyn Museum's ``Sensation'' show last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown is more than an art dealer. He is also the proprietor
of Passerby, a bar adjacent to his gallery, which is a cliquish
rendezvous for art and fashion, attracting the likes of Moby, the
DJ; Chloe Sevigny, the actress; Terry Richardson, the fashion
photographer; and Jeffrey Kalinsky, the store owner.
</P>
<P>
   Right next door, Brown's wife, Lucy Barnes, runs a clothing
boutique, selling her own designs: slip dresses, A-line skirts and
halters with antique lace and crystal beads. She has a following
among well-heeled artists like Rachel Feinstein, who married the
painter John Currin in a Lucy Barnes gown inspired by Marie
Antoinette as a shepherdess. Her bridesmaids wore Barnes dresses
inspired by ``The Stepford Wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Art gallery, bar and clothing boutique _ all are part of a nexus
of cool on West 15th Street between Ninth and 10th Avenues. The
scene, as one dealer put it, is ``superhip, groovy artists, great
parties, a fashion-meets-the-art-world kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown insists that he and his Scottish-born wife never set out
to create a scene, that it is mere happenstance that their three
businesses are cheek by jowl on a block slightly off the beaten
path, making it a kind of demimonde destination.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the polished galleries of Chelsea, Brown's space, with a
concrete floor and only 900 square feet for exhibitions, is a
gritty showcase for emerging artists. Brown, 37, who favors jeans,
work boots and an unshaven look, is not like his slick,
Prada-suited colleagues on West 22nd Street. He cultivates an
anticommercial image and a prickly persona. When working for
another gallery, he faxed friends, asking them to nominate him for
most obnoxious gallery attendant for an art magazine. (He didn't
win. An employee of Mary Boone's did.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Gavin, but he's a rogue,'' said Richard Flood, the
chief curator of the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis. ``I value
him for his rudeness and his creativity within the marketplace.
Running a gallery has always seemed like an annoyance rather than a
privilege to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hort, a New York collector, said it took a long time
before Brown was enthusiastic about selling art to her. To prove
her support, she bought a broad range of his artists, rather than
just those who were hot. ``A collector who wants to collect with
him gets around the difficult part or deals with him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? With new and old galleries thriving, why buy
paintings from someone who acts like the Soup Nazi of the art
world?
</P>
<P>
   ``What raises Gavin above his degage attitude is the fact that
he's got some of the hottest artists of the moment,'' said Bruce
Wolmer, the editor of Art and Auction magazine. ``In addition, he's
got a kind of cool magnetism that makes the gallery work. He's the
anti-earnest art dealer. He mirrors the moment. He's not ironic.
He's beyond irony. He's beyond caring. That's what's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not care to be involved in this article. He declined
requests for an interview, then met briefly with this reporter. His
comments were mostly etched in acid.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he chose West 15th Street, rather than a spot among
other high-profile Chelsea galleries, he said, ``It's nearer to the
subways than the other ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the anticommercial bent of his and his wife's
businesses _ she sometimes doesn't let her friends pay for clothes,
and he made no profit from the 30 Fischerspooner performances _ he
replied, ``We're saints.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in suburban London, Brown attended a graduate-level art
program at the Whitney Museum of American Art before opening his
first gallery in 1994 on Broome Street. The space, which he
constructed himself, was minuscule, but it quickly became a place
where artists, dealers and curators gathered to argue aesthetics
over beers.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown moved to 436 West 15th Street in 1997 _ opening with
no sign, only an orange brick facade to mark the spot _ it was
logical that he would also import a bar. Passerby, a bare-bones
establishment, is only some benches and stools, with a disco floor
that lights up in response to music _ actually a work of art by
Piotr Uklanski.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, artists hung out at Spring Street Bar,''
said Ivy Shapiro, a daughter of Joel Shapiro, the sculptor. She is
with the Barbara Gladstone Gallery. ``Until Gavin's bar came
around, there wasn't a good place for artists to hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, 34, is unlike her cantankerous husband. Friendly,
easygoing and soft-spoken, she sometimes pads around her small,
light-filled storefront in flip-flops. The shop contains
cream-color sofas, a birch tree adorned with vintage silk flowers
and a couple of racks of Barnes' simple but quirky clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Because she uses vintage textiles or makes her own printed
fabrics, adding hand finishes like beaded trim or appliques, her
designs, which range from $50 to $1,500, are often one of a kind.
They are sought by artists who want to wear something more unusual
than the latest dress splashed across magazine ads. ``You can wear
Lucy's clothes head to toe and not look like you're dipped in a
designer,'' said Jessica Craig-Martin, a photographer whose work
appears in Vogue. ``You can get really dressed up, and there's
something still funky about them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Barneys New York will begin to carry Barnes'
collection. ``Her clothes are more artisanship than design,'' said
Julie Gilhart, the vice president for fashion merchandising at
Barneys. ``Everything in fashion is big and grand, and we have all
those designers doing major influential collections. It's so
refreshing to trip over someone doing something small and unique...
''
</P>
<P>
   The aura of selectivity that surrounds Barnes' clothes, as well
as her husband's gallery and bar, serves both well. Jack Bankowsky,
the editor of Artforum, said that Brown's detachment, along with
his stable of interesting artists, explains his attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their dealer's off-putting attitude, Brown's artists tend
to show work that is engaging and accessible. Elizabeth Peyton
paints lush portraits of pop stars like Kurt Cobain. (A Peyton work
was auctioned last month at Christie's for $70,500, more than
double the house's highest estimate.) Even the conceptual art that
Brown shows, like Rikrit Tiravanija's work _ in which the artist
offers food to people and displays the leftovers _ has benevolent,
even populist implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of dealers,'' said Flood, the Walker Art
Center curator. ``One is the kind that harvests when the crop is
mature. The other tends to the seedlings. That's Gavin. He's not an
opportunist. He's identified the talent and maintained it. In last
fall's Chris Ofili show, every painting but one _ that is, four out
of five _ sold to a major museum. That's a dealer who is really
doing his job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
