u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     06-02 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DID MARBLE GET CHIPPED? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 4, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My marble fireplace front (sides and top of the face) is a
beautiful dark green in the house built in 1969. Now it looks as if
someone hit it with an ice pick. Little chips are popping out,
making sharp dents. It is a sort of flaking, very small flakes
coming off. What's wrong? Is there a way to stop it or keep it from
recurring? Or is there a way of filling those chips? I don't think
heat was a cause because we have not used the fireplace very often.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN KENNEDY, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Beats the heck out of the handyman. Your first priority is
to show it to a marble man. It sounds as if water got into some
tiny, invisible cracks, and somehow eroded out those chips. This
would be more plausible if the marble were outside, where invading
water could freeze, popping off the chips. If anything like that
happened, it may mean that the marble was defective, that the chips
were already there, and loose, ready to be popped off.
</P>
<P>
   So now we'll put the question to everyone in the hopes that
someone will know why John Kennedy's great-looking marble chipped.
The handyman and Kennedy would love to hear from anyone who might
have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the chips occurred, there might be a way of
filling those holes. Carefully remove one of the slabs and sand the
back of it to create some marble dust. Mix this with clear glue and
fill the holes. Let set, sand smooth with very fine emory cloth. If
the patches show, polish the marble.
</P>
<P>
   As a P.S., Kennedy called Plymouth Quarries, a dealer in stone,
brick, and other masonry materials in Hingham, where one of the
specialists thought some movement behind the marble caused the
spalling. He said it was not a defect in the marble.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that movement behind the marble was a rather sharp blow,
knocking off a chip on the other side. It would be a little like a
BB shot that hits a window, knocking off a chip on the inside of
the glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I have a very nice birdbath but it does not work. The bowl
is square granite and very deep, too deep for the birds to bathe in
or drink. Putting in just a bit of water won't help because it is
too far down the bowl. How can I make it shallower? The bowl is 8
to 9 inches deep and 12 inches square. And, the water gets all
slimy and filled with gunk.
</P>
<P>
   ROZ EPSTEIN, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Some designer did not have the birds in mind when he
designed that thing. Birdbaths should be no more than 2 inches
deep. So, you could fill that bowl with concrete, to within 2
inches of the top. And you could taper the concrete so it is
shallower along the edges. Or, have a shallow copper tray molded by
a metalworker to fit on top of the bowl. The copper will weather to
that handsome green when it oxidizes, and should not hurt the
birds.
</P>
<P>
   Any water will get slimy and full of mold and algae, so on a
regular basis empty the bowl and treat it with bleach, but be sure
to rinse very thoroughly before adding water.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure no water gets under the copper bowl. In summer it will
get stagnant and in winter it could freeze and break the granite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  The man who serviced my oil burner in a house I own in
Lunenberg noticed that the copper pipes are turning green with
green spots, mostly at the joints. Is this something to worry
about?
</P>
<P>
   JOE LUCA, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Frankly, I don't think so, unless the joints start to leak.
The greening is actually oxidation, caused by water. It is the same
process as the greening of copper outdoors. The water is coming
from water vapor condensing on the cool pipes. The oxidation will
take a long time to make a hole in the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  We had all our windows replaced with vinyl windows, and are
surprised at the brightness of the white. It is a blazing white,
particularly in contrast with the colors in the room. And the
woodwork is dark, aggravating the situation. Can we paint the
windows? How else can we cover that over-bright white? We cannot
cover it with curtains.
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN SHAHID, Brockton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  What about draperies? They would cover most of the window,
even partially open. OK, you can paint vinyl if you sand heavily to
reduce gloss and roughen the finish (an old story). Apply one coat
of a latex enamel undercoater and finish off with any kind of latex
paint you like. Specify Muralo undercoater, which claims to adhere
to shiny surfaces. Sanding still is important. Make the paint
semigloss, or eggshell (neither flat nor shiny) to keep down the
glare.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to avoid the hassle of painting (three coats are needed),
cover the glare with Contact paper. Choose a matte finish color,
and remove it when you tire of it or it gets dirty. Unlike the old
Contact paper, the new version is easily stripped.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
