<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3021 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HYBRID-CARS-$ADV04-NY     06-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYBRID-CARS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCING HYBRIDS VS. ELECTRICS ON THE ENVIRONMENTAL SCALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hybrid gas-electric cars can be clean and very
fuel-efficient, and may, if automakers persuade regulators, be used
to fill the quota for battery-electric cars that California, New
York and Massachusetts plan to require. But engineers are learning
that hybrids cannot accomplish everything environmentalists want. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That point was demonstrated at the end of the 12th running of an
alternative-vehicle race, the American Tour de Sol, here on May 18,
when race organizers set out to rank the competing cars on a
variety of scales. One criterion was energy efficiency, which was
measured on a miles-per-gallon basis for the hybrid vehicles that
used gasoline or diesel fuel; for battery-electric vehicles,
organizers came up with an equivalent measure based on how much
fuel an electric utility would need at its power plant to make the
electricity the vehicle consumed. Another criterion was the cars'
potential contribution to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The race showed that all the cars were improving in many
aspects, like range, reliability and handling. The numbers also
showed that hybrids had better fuel economy than some electrics,
but emitted more gases believed to cause climate change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the race's ``production category,'' for vehicles
commercially available today, the overall winner was the Honda
Insight hybrid. It had a fuel economy average of 92 miles a gallon
in the race. In second place over all was General Motors' two-seat
EV1 electric car. It had the equivalent fuel economy of 68 mpg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the ``global warming potential'' of the Insight _ a number
that includes carbon dioxide and two much more potent tailpipe
gases, methane and nitrous oxide _ was roughly double the EV1's
level. A big reason is that even a very good gasoline engine is
only about 18 percent efficient in turning the gas into usable
energy; the rest of the fuel is consumed by friction or expelled as
exhaust. In contrast, an inefficient power station using the same
amount of fuel is closer to 33 percent effective at turning fuel
into electricity; an efficient one can reach 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tour de Sol organizers had the Argonne National Laboratory, part
of the Energy Department, perform the calculation using the mix of
power plants in the Northeast, since the race ran from New York
City to Washington. That includes nuclear and hydroelectric plants
that do not emit carbon dioxide and related gases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hazard, who organizes the race for the Northeast
Sustainable Energy Association, a nonprofit environmental group,
said the result was ``something that I was not actually
expecting.'' But even if the Insight gave off twice as much
greenhouse gas as the EV1, it was still a huge improvement over
most cars on the road. It had only a quarter of the emissions of a
conventional gasoline-powered Saturn driven on the same route. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, at least, hybrid cars are more likely than
battery-electrics to be a solution to the problems of air pollution
and dependence on imported oil. Toyota, which has produced both
types of vehicles, told California regulators last week that the
public was not ready to accept electrics; indeed, Toyota said it
could not sell the cars and would have to pay customers to take
them.
</P>
<P>
   Hybrid technology is second-best from a greenhouse-gas
standpoint, and hybrids have a brighter future than battery-powered
cars because they cost comparatively less and travel much farther
without needing to stop for recharging.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of trading off one environmental value against another
is not new. Controlling acid rain by taking sulfur out of
power-plant emissions means using some of the plants' electric
output for anti-pollution equipment, which means more carbon
dioxide for each kilowatt-hour delivered to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is belatedly trying to ban
methyl tertiary butyl ether, or MTBE, a gasoline additive it once
favored to clean the air. When gas leaks into the soil, MTBE
contaminates water supplies. Catalytic converters, the basic
pollution-control equipment of ordinary gasoline cars, have been
found to produce nitrous oxide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
