 NEW GRAND CHEROKEE IS GRANDER THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (repeating in l and f coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I lay hands on an SUV, one of the first things I like to do
is take it where most SUVs never go _ off road.
</P>
<P>
   In my neck of the New Hampshire woods, that means out where the
skidders have been, following the rutted, muddy, stony, log-strewn
paths of departed or ongoing logging operations. It's a good test
for these rigs because skidders do not pause for steep or sloshy,
stone or stump.
</P>
<P>
   So where better to start my week in the 2000 Jeep Grand Cherokee
Limited 4WD? It would be a good test to see if Daimler-Chrysler, in
its 1999 makeover of the Grand Cherokee, had pulled off the
Jekyll-and-Hyde feat of turning this Jeep into a luxurious and
smooth highway performer while at the same time saving its solid
off-road soul.
</P>
<P>
   I took it up steep grades where you could see only the sky
through the windshield. Plunged it through mud, walked it gingerly
over rocks and stumps one wheel at a time, pushed through a
streambed, across a thick scattering of old bark and wood chips,
