<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, June 3. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEFENSE (Moscow) _ In a bid to recast the debate over
missile defense, President Vladimir Putin has suggested a new
approach to protect against missile attack by nations like North
Korea. Instead of building a nationwide shield against incoming
warheads as the Clinton administration has proposed, Putin hinted
that the United States and Russia collaborate on new ways to shoot
down enemy missiles soon after they were launched. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Aachen, Germany) _ President Clinton Friday
called on America's European allies to invite Russia to join NATO
and the European Union. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR (Berlin) _ Five months after German industry
and the government agreed to pay Holocaust survivors nearly $5
billion, the deal became ensnarled here Friday in disagreements
with the United States over liability from future lawsuits. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-DEMOCRACY (Jakarta) _ Everything has changed in
Indonesia since its strongman, Suharto, was pushed from office just
two years ago. The clamor of democracy is everywhere, along with
the violence and instability that accompany a time of unfettered
transformation. And nothing has changed. Indonesia is still focused
on the ideas, the directives _ even the whims _ of one man, its new
president, Abdurrahman Wahid. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-GAYS (Rome) _ World Pride Roma, a global gay pride
festival, is expected to draw gay men and lesbians from all over
the world to Rome on July 1 for a week's worth of conferences,
fashion shows, a gay pride parade, and a concert featuring Gloria
Gaynor and The Village People. The Vatican, which is hosting a Holy
Year for religious pilgrims, is not amused. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AIR-CRASH (Washington) _ The Federal Aviation
Administration Friday threatened to shut down Alaska Airlines major
maintenance work, which would ground the airline within months. The
government said that the airline had a persistent problem in
keeping track of whether required maintenance had been done, and
the managers had not noticed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SUBURBS (Smyrna, Ga.) _ In state after state, a platform
of conservative social issues that once monopolized the
conversation of Southern suburbs _ lower taxes, welfare reform,
crackdowns on crime _ has been supplanted by a new agenda: managing
growth and transportation, bringing in high-tech jobs, and above
all improving public education. In a swath of states from the
Carolinas to Mississippi, Democratic governors have made these
issues their own, and Republicans are struggling to keep up. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks surge as the jobs report heightens
expectations that the Federal Reserve may soon halt raising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ In the strongest signal yet that the
booming American economy is finally slowing, the Labor Department
reported Friday that the nation's private sector employers, instead
of hiring, shed 116,000 jobs in May, the largest drop in more than
eight years and the first since the economy began to boom in the
mid 1990s. The stock market immediately celebrated. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
</TEXT>
