<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE MIAMI RELATIVES DOWN FOR THE COUNT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez have vowed to fight on.
These folks are goofy, but let's give them high marks for tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   They bring to mind the underdog in a boxing match I watched on
television a few weeks back. The guy was trying to wrest a title
from one of those big-deal champs who fires sledgehammer jabs and
hit-by-a-truck uppercuts; the challenger lost the fight but won
plaudits for his willingness to take a beating.
</P>
<P>
   So. Let's hear it for Lazaro Gonzalez, Marisleysis Gonzalez, et
al, who endure knockdown after knockdown and eagerly bounce up from
the canvas and stick out their collective chin as the U.S.
government winds up to throw one more devastating punch.
</P>
<P>
   The latest blow was Thursday's decision by a three-judge panel
in Atlanta that said the Immigration and Naturalization Service was
acting within the law when it ruled that Elian was not entitled to
an asylum hearing. The Miami relatives have been pushing for such a
hearing in hopes of keeping Elian in the United States over the
objections of his father, who wants to take him back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Perseverance has its merits. On the other hand, these Miami
relatives are fighting tooth and nail in defense of a point of view
that is just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If would be terrific if Juan Miguel Gonzalez decided to seek
asylum for himself and his whole family, but he has shown no
inclination to do so. Gonzalez says he wants to go home and he
wants to take Elian with him. That should be the end of the story.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who laid claim to Elian after he was fished out
of the ocean last November apparently have no interest in the bond
between a father and son _ just as they have no interest in
complying with the lawful dictates of the INS. The Miami relatives
are still whining about Attorney General Janet Reno's decision to
snatch Elian from their home and return him to his father, but Reno
had no choice; the relatives had defied the law by refusing to give
up the boy voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have consistently upheld the parental rights of
Elian's father and yet this band of distant relatives with no
standing whatsoever to claim custody of the boy persist in throwing
legal arguments at the courthouse wall.
</P>
<P>
   Why won't they do the right thing? Why won't they accept defeat?
Why won't they drop their futile and redundant legal challenges to
the government's reasonable, fair and morally pertinent decision
that a boy should live with his father _ even if some people don't
approve of the country that the father chooses to live in?
</P>
<P>
   If the Miami relatives truly cared about the best interests of
Elian _ and they have repeatedly insisted that those interests are
exactly what they care about _ wouldn't they call off their howling
pack of legal beagles and graciously allow the kid and his dad to
go home?
</P>
<P>
   Sure they would.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Miami relatives couldn't care less about
Elian's best interests at this stage of the game. For them, the
continuing legal battle is no longer about some noble desire to see
Elian grow up free in America _ if in fact it ever was about that.
</P>
<P>
   The battle now is about their own egos. It's about the Cuban
American community's seething hatred of Cuban President Fidel
Castro. It's about the perfectly natural human instinct to keep
fighting when the really sensible thing to do is to lie down and
take a 10-count.
</P>
<P>
   The judges gave the Miami relatives 14 days to file appeals.
Rest assured that if the courts would let them get away with it,
these people would appeal till the cows come home.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-day window is encouraging. It just might indicate that
the courts are as tired of this seemingly endless controversy as
the general public is _ maybe even as tired of it as Juan Miguel
Gonzalez must surely be.
</P>
<P>
   One of the TV newshounds said yesterday that Juan Miguel is
growing more impatient by the day, that he desperately wants to get
on with his life.
</P>
<P>
   And he could _ if only his bullheaded relatives would let him.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7787, or e-mail:
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
