<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0603-COX     06-02 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Nader's finger on the scale
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidential race is a virtual dead heat five months before
the election, according to
</P>
<P>
   a new Reuters/Zogby poll, with Ralph Nader showing as a possible
problem for Al Gore. The poll found George W. Bush barely ahead of
Gore, 42-41 percent, in a two-man match-up with 17 percent
undecided. Adding three minor candidates _ Nader of the Greens, Pat
Buchanan of the Reforms Harry Browne of the Libertarians _ resulted
in Bush stretching his lead to 42-39 percent. Nader drew 4 percent,
Buchanan 2 percent, Browne 1 percent, and the rest remained
undecided. In both cases, the Bush advantage was within the poll's
3.2 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   THAT OLD STATESMAN IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the focus on international affairs and making fresh
overtures to Hispanic voters, George W. Bush is sharing the stage
with eight other U.S. and Mexican border governors at a two-day
Border Governors Conference in Sacramento, Calif. The Texan joined
three other governors _ Gray Davis of California (D), Jane Hull of
Arizona (R) and Gary Johnson of New Mexico (R) _ and the leaders of
five Mexican states. They were focusing today on border issues
relating to the environment, education and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   NOPE, NEVER TALKED TO ANYONE
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the General Services Administration, Roger
Johnson, says he never talked to Al Gore or anyone else in the
Clinton administration about a proposed $400 million federal lease
for a Democratic fund-raiser and long-time Gore friend. Johnson was
responding to the public disclosure of a memo suggesting that
``Gore has called or is ready to call'' Johnson in an attempt to
help Tennessee developer Franklin Haney on a planned building
called the Portals. Gore denies haveing intervened. Justice
Department investigators have been unable to learn who wrote the
undated, unsigned and unaddressed memo, which was part of a grand
jury proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLITICS OF DEATH
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton pulled off the campaign
trail to oversee the execution of a cop killer. The decision drew
criticism from liberal groups, but allowing Clinton to put forth a
tough-on-crime image and move toward the political middle. Now,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's approval of a 30-day reprieve in a
death penalty case after allowing 131 executions is an act that
could be perceived as the opposite, allowing him to soften his
image and attract more moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   CAREFUL, GUN ISSUE COULD HURT SOMEBODY
</P>
<P>
   Democrats predict the debate over guns will rally voters,
especially women, to support Al Gore for president. But the polls
offer little evidence of that now, however. Gore is shown with no
clear advantage over George W. Bush on the issue. Polls show the
two about even when people are asked who they trust on guns. And
Republicans argue that the debate may actually help their candidate
because of Bush's call for tougher enforcement of existing gun
laws, instead of new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY REPUBS LYING LOW
</P>
<P>
   While their Democratic counterparts are capturing most of the
headlines in the race for New Jersey's open Senate seat, four
Republicans are campaigning away in relative obscurity. And many
say the attention focused on the primary battle between investment
banker Jon Corzine and ex-Gov. Jim Florio will work in their favor.
The Republicans _ state Sen. William Gormley, Essex County
Executive Jim Treffinger; U.S. Rep. Bob Franks and Ramapo College
professor Murray Sabrin _ are keeping relatively low profiles and
aiming their shots at Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   PICKING UP THE CONSERVATIVE NOD
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio has all but officially accepted the Conservative
Party endorsement for the Senate in New York, expected to come
Saturday at the party convention in Albany. A
Conservative-sponsored TV spot touting Lazio has begun airing in
New York City and Albany, and the party hopes to raise $1 million
over the next five months for his campaign and ``party building.''
</P>
<P>
   JUST CAN'T STOP TALKING ABOUT HER
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Rick Lazio set out from the Republican convention in
Buffalo, the immediate concern of his Senate campaign was not what
he said, but how he was photographed. Everywhere Lazio went _ a
vineyard here, a schoolyard there _ his staff members vigorously
stage-directed the candidate and the media, seeking the best
photographs of Lazio's inaugural bus tour. Most important, Lazio
was advised to refrain from attacks on Hillary Clinton, because
they might distract from these carefully arranged images. That
restraint, however, lasted for all of five hours.
</P>
<P>
   RAISING THE CEILING IN CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina has never elected a woman to any statewide office
higher than secretary of state, but is poised for something like a
breakthrough this year. Two women, both state senators, are the
major parties' nominees for lieutenant governor: Betsy L. Cochrane,
a Republican, was the first woman to hold a leadership position in
the General Assembly, and Beverly M. Perdue, a Democrat, has been
co-chair of the Senate Appropriations Committee since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   REACHING FOR THE BIG SKY
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will meet in Dayton, Ohio, and Billings, Mont., this
month to gather citizens' views for the platform the party will
approve at its national convention. The Dayton meeting, June 16,
will focus on Social Security, education and health care; the
Billings meeting, June 23, will cover welfare programs, national
security, foreign policy, natural resources and Western land
issues. Montana Gov. Marc Racicot said that with the national
convention being held in Philadelphia, the Bush people are ``trying
to reach as far as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW HONCHOS FOR DEM CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention Committee hired a new chief
operating officer and managing director. Rod O'Connor succeeds Dan
Foley, who resigned in late January. O'Connor, who has served on Al
Gore's staff, will be in charge of communications, production,
credentialing and media logistics for the convention committee. Tom
O'Donnell, a Washington lawyer, is the new managing director,
overseeing all administrative, external affairs and management
functions. The convention is Aug. 14-17 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS ALWAYS GOOD AT HOLDING OUT
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James P. Hoffa said his powerful labor union
may not endorse a presidential candidate this year, and is still
weighing its options. ``Maybe we won't make an endorsement at all,
that's a possibility. And there's a possibility we'll endorse
somebody, but we're just not in a position to make that
announcement now,'' Hoffa said. Last fall, the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, along with the United Auto Workers,
abstained when the AFL-CIO announced its early endorsement of Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
