<P>
   KOREAN PITCHERS ARE TURNING UP RED. Three Korean pitchers _
Sang-Hoon Lee, Jin Ho Cho and Sun-Woo Kim _ are hoping to make the
big leagues with the Boston Red Sox. Gary Gaetti, who broke into
the majors with the Twins in 1982 and is currently fighting for a
spot on the Red Sox roster, says Lee, Cho and Kim have become
welcome additions during the Grapefruit League season. ``Now there
are a lot more Latin players and a lot more Asian players. And I
guess that's good because we are trying to get global with
baseball,'' Gaetti says. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-KOREAN-PITCHERS-GO-MAJOR-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE AFTER ELIAN. This week, columnist James Garcia writes that,
nationally, the Elian Gonzalez affair exposed longstanding
divisions between Cuban-Americans and other Latinos. Most notably,
the saga highlighted the waning power of the once seemingly
indomitable community of Cuban exiles. ``It's time for Elian to go
home and for Cuban-Americans to let the country know that CANF (the
Cuban American National Foundation, which orchestrated a relentless
legal and public-relations crusade to keep Elian in the United
States) and its right-wing allies do not speak for the entire
community,'' he writes. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-LIFE-AFTER-ELIAN-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   SEEING WHAT'S AHEAD. What if the United States and the rest of
the world were at the beginning of a period of change _ an economic
expansion driven by technological progress that would literally
dwarf the magnitude of the Industrial Revolution? If this were
true, what would the implications be for African-Americans? In this
excerpt from Emerge magazine, contributing columnist Nat Irvin II
offers answers to these questions _ and asks African-Americans to
take advantage of the future they envision by reframing the
present. (slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-LOOKING-TO-FUTURE-NYTSF)
</P>
