<HEADER>
A3062 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NEW-AMERICA-LIFE-AFTE     06-02 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-LIFE-AFTER-ELIAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE AFTER ELIAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    In the weeks after she snatched a crying Elian Gonzalez from his
relatives' home in Miami's Little Havana, federal immigration agent
Betty A. Mills received repeated death threats.
 &HT;    Mills is the officer who fought her way through a gauntlet of
angry protesters as she struggled to reach a waiting government van
while carrying the 6-year-old boy.
 &HT;    The agent eventually made it to the van, but the raid led to
street riots later that day.
 &HT;    This chaotic and rebellious portrait of our nation's
Cuban-American community, as presented by the world's news media,
has since come to hurt Cuban-Americans.
 &HT;    In Florida, the Elian controversy exacerbated political and
racial rifts between Cuban-Americans and other local groups.
Nationally, the Elian affair exposed longstanding divisions between
Cuban-Americans and other Latinos.
 &HT;    Most notably, the months-long saga highlighted the waning power
of the once seemingly indomitable community of Cuban exiles.
 &HT;    Many Americans _ including a growing number of Cuban-Americans _
believe that conservative Cuban leaders went too far this time in
using Elian to wage their latest political assault against Fidel
Castro, Cuba's communist dictator.
 &HT;    Elena Freyre, director of the Miami office of the Cuban
Committee for Democracy, blames most of the negative publicity her
community has received on the Cuban American National Foundation
(CANF) and its hard-line stance against the Clinton administration.
 &HT;    ``It's been a PR disaster,'' she said. ``In Washington,
traditionally hard-line Cuban-Americans have certainly lost a lot
of power.''
 &HT;    Almost from the moment that immigration agents handed over the
child to his Miami relatives last November, CANF has orchestrated a
relentless legal and public-relations crusade to keep Elian in the
United States.
 &HT;    CANF's efforts have largely backfired, and its ability to shape
U.S. foreign policy toward Cuba has weakened.
 &HT;    But the cracks in the once-unshakable alliance between
conservative Cuban exiles and their supporters in Congress weren't
created by the fight over Elian, said Julia Sweig, deputy director
of Latin-American Studies at the Council on Foreign Relations.
 &HT;    She said the power of conservative exiles began to wane after
the death of CANF's former chairman, Jorge Mas Canosa, in 1997. And
the group's influence was further weakened by Pope John Paul II's
visit to Cuba in 1998. The pontiff's visit, analysts say, helped
soften Castro's international image.
 &HT;    Sweig noted that the Cuban exile lobby has almost always had its
way in Washington. Witness the nearly 40-year economic embargo
against Cuba.
 &HT;    Another powerful lobbying group, however, has been chipping away
at CANF's powerbase in Washington in recent years. A growing number
of U.S. business leaders, especially in the farm industry, now back
proposals to boost trade with Cuba.
 &HT;    Last month, House and Senate committees approved an easing of
the trade embargo, though conservatives and Cuban exile leaders vow
to block the measure's final passage.
 &HT;    Back in Miami, the Elian controversy rocked local politics.
 &HT;    Miami Mayor Joe Carollo fired City Manager Donald Warshaw for
refusing to fire Police Chief William O'Brien. Carollo was furious
that O'Brien did not tell him in advance that the raid was going
down. Carollo wants Elian to remain in the United States.
 &HT;    Tom Fiedler, editorial-page editor of the Miami Herald, says
Carollo's behavior during the Elian affair angered many in Miami.
As a result, the mayor may face a tough challenge if he seeks
reelection.
 &HT;    Many believe the Elian controversy did nothing to help improve
already strained relations between Cuban-Americans and other U.S.
Latinos.
 &HT;    A California group representing mostly Mexican and Central
American immigrants marched to protest the ``special treatment''
granted Cuban emigres. Unlike other immigrants, Cubans who reach
U.S. soil automatically receive permanent legal status.
 &HT;    Observers also note that the nation's leading Latino advocacy
organizations never publicly sided with CANF or the boy's Miami
relatives.
 &HT;    Lisa Navarette, a spokeswoman for the National Council of La
Raza, says her group did not get involved in CANF's battle with the
feds because the issue didn't resonate with NCLR's Latino
constituency.
 &HT;    The Elian dispute, she said, wasn't a ``Latino issue.''
 &HT;    Navarette also noted that conservative Cuban exile groups,
including CANF, have rarely supported NCLR's pan-Latino agenda,
including its stances on issues such as immigration or bilingual
education.
 &HT;    I asked Navarette if she thought CANF's power in Washington has
been waning. She said CANF and its allies continue to wield
substantial influence in Washington, though she believes the tide
has changed.
 &HT;    In Navarette's words: ``I think we are in a different time.''
 &HT;    She's right. It's time for Elian to go home and for
Cuban-Americans to let the country know that CANF and its
right-wing allies do not speak for the entire community.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James E. Garcia is editor-in-chief of Politico magazine, a
monthly publication covering U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1(at)aol.com or visit www.politicomagazine.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James E. Garcia 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NEW
AMERICA NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
