u f BC-IVILLAGE-STREET     06-02 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVILLAGE-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVILLAGE IN TALKS TO SELL IBABY TO BABYGEAR.COM
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVEN VAMES   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the going gets tough, the tough put the baby up for
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   That just might be the strategy for iVillage, the troubled
womens' Web site, which is in talks to sell its baby products
commerce site iBaby to privately held competitor BabyGear.com.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to ditch iBaby, which sells everything from
strollers to breast pumps, is seen as a significant shift in
strategy for iVillage, which has built an online community of 4.9
million women sharing common interests like parenthood and careers.
When iVillage acquired a $1.35 million majority stake in iBaby in
April 1998, it was widely heralded as a groundbreaking strategy in
which an online content provider could make customers out of its
users.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, New York-based iVillage has apparently
changed its mind about the tumultuous world of retailing after
dealing with the day-to-day annoyances of warehouses and product
returns, The Wall Street Journal reported Friday, saying that the
company confirmed it is in talks to sell the unit. An iVillage
spokesman confirmed Friday morning that the company is in talks
with BabyGear but declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Bealle, president and chief operating officer of
BabyGear.com, said in an interview that the talks have been ongoing
for ``a couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a deal yet,'' he said, but added that he hoped
to wrap up an agreement within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   iBaby's appeal lies in part in its affiliation with iVillage,
Bealle said. BabyGear.com hopes to embark on ``a longterm
relationship that really takes advantage of their huge user base,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face in iVillage's strategy comes at a time when the
company is ailing from a severely beaten stock value, high turnover
among its executives and employees, and growing quarterly losses.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which peaked at 113 3/4 following its April
1999 public offering, was at 8 7/16, up 33/36, or 7 percent, in
early trading Friday. The company posted a first-quarter operating
loss of $26.8 million, compared to a net loss of $17.9 million in
the first quarter of 1999, even as revenues nearly tripled to $20.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited people familiar with the situation who said
that iVillage is interested in pursuing more advertising and
sponsorship revenue from companies including baby-products
retailers, and its ownership of iBaby precluded it from that.
</P>
<P>
   BabyGear.com's Bealle noted the retail business is ``far
afield'' for iVillage, whose core business is based on content.
``From the beginning, we have been focused on being a retail
business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of iBaby would not severely affect the company's
revenue stream. The company's e-commerce revenue of $3.2 million in
the first quarter was dwarfed by its $17.6 million in revenue from
sponsorship and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of iVillage jumped in early trading Friday, rising 15/32,
or 6 percent, to 8 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
