<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PESTICIDES-TARGETS-HN     06-02 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESTICIDES-TARGETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS WARN OF UNINTENDED EFFECTS OF PESTICIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH ALLEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Chemical pesticides and the delicate green
lacewing are farmers' friends when it comes to controlling
crop-eating bugs. But even carefully targeted pesticides can wipe
out the beneficial bugs, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   While exploring the effects of insect growth regulators (IGRs),
which are supposed to kill specific pests like aphids and
whiteflies by preventing them from maturing to adulthood,
agricultural extension service entomologists found that two of them
kill the lacewing in its third larval stage.
</P>
<P>
   That raises concerns about their effect on the entire ecosystem,
said Andy Scott, research director at Rio Farms, a private
agricultural research foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question I would have is what's the effect on some of the
other beneficial species, such as the big-eyed bug, the lady
beetles (and) the serpent-fly larvae,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Extension researcher T.X. Liu plans to begin testing the IGRs'
effects on lady beetles in August.
</P>
<P>
   The two chemicals that have unintended consequences are
fenoxycarb and pyriproxyfen, approved by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture for use on some crops in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do when you spray insecticides is
to kill off beneficial insects,'' said Liu, a researcher at the
Texas A&AMP;M Agricultural Research and Extension Center at Weslaco.
Liu is trying to get IGRs approved for wider use in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Liu is also testing buprofezin, which does not appear to hurt
lacewings but is not licensed for use in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to avoiding such trouble is to apply the IGRs when the
lacewings are not in that vulnerable third stage, Liu said,
although he admits that the timing can be tough to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very careful when we use it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said the fact that the research station is looking
carefully at the IGRs' unintended effects is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line with any new compound, we really need to know what
we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many pesticides tend to take out all beneficial insects, Scott
noted, so IGRs present an advantage, but any change in the
ecosystem can throw it out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the 1995 boll weevil eradication project in the
Rio Grande Valley, where heavy spraying for boll weevils, drought
and an infestation of beet army worms combined to produce a
disastrous year for cotton farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers sued, and a judge ruled the program unconstitutional.
The Legislature revamped the program in 1997, but Valley farmers so
far have declined to opt back into it.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and many farmers contend the boll weevil spray also took
out the army worms' natural predators, giving the pests free rein
in the fields of the Valley's main crop.
</P>
<P>
   However, other chemicals will take out some pests but boost the
aphid population, creating a bountiful food supply for beneficial
insects, Scott pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're dealing with biological systems they're very
complex,'' he said. ``You do one thing, and it causes a chain
reaction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
