<P>
   TV-FASHION-SEX (New York) _ Times fashion critic Cathy Horyn
writes about the style on ``Sex and the City'' and comes away
disappointed in the clothes and the show. She raises the question:
Isn't the show ``just a swankier version of ``The Golden Girls''?
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STYLE-REGIS (New York) _ Monday Regis Philbin will introduce
Regis, by Van Heusen just in time for Father's Day June 18. Fashion
magazines say the ```millionaire look'' of monochromatic shirts and
tie sets is ``on trend.'' In fact, if the manufacturer's $50
million sales projection is accurate, then Philbin may have found a
licensing path to becoming a millionaire. By Rick Marin. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   GAVIN-PROFILE (New York) _ Gavin Brown, a British-born art
dealer, represents a roster of rising stars, the best known of whom
is Chris Ofili, whose creativity with elephant dung created a fuss
at the Brooklyn Museum. Brown is also the proprietor of Passerby, a
bar adjacent to his gallery. Next door, Brown's wife, Lucy Barnes,
runs a clothing boutique. All three are part of a nexus of cool in
Manhattan on West 15th Street. By Elizabeth Hayt. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOM-READING (Undated) _ Harold Bloom, the Yale professor whose
latest book is ``How to Read and Why,'' writes about the depressing
experience of reading the latest Michael Crichton thriller
downloaded onto a portable PC. ``Crichton's prose is as dead as the
14th century,'' he writes, ``and if you're reading it on a
hand-held computer, it is a double ordeal, physical and
stylistic.'' Information may be fine transmitted on a screen, he
concludes, but ``wisdom and beauty cry out'' for a book.
</P>
<P>
   NITE-OUT-TELLER (New York) _ A night on the town with Jurgen
Teller, the fashion photographer, who is best known for discovering
Kate Moss and creating a look that has been described as dirty
realism and heroin chic. Bob Morris, the reporter, says Teller's
images have helped lower the traditional standards of beauty. ``I
don't care about fashion at all,'' Teller says, and he adds that
being a fashion photograher is a ``kind of pathetic occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   EIGHTIES-RETURN (Undated) _ From her boutique in Beverly Hills,
Gale Hayman, had a front row seat for the lavish fashion of the
'80s. Now, she reports, furs, feathers, higher heels, pink
lipstick, pony skin and leopard boots, Chanel quilted chain belts
and big hair have all reappeared. The difference is that back then,
women wore it all together, head to toe. Now it's edited down to
one great piece at a time.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ This is the best time to order bulbs
for fall. The memory of the ones that worked is still in your mind,
and there are hefty discounts for orders placed before July 1. By
Anne Raver
</P>
