<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3087 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-EIGHTIES-RETURN-$ADV0     06-02 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIGHTIES-RETURN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION'S TIME MACHINE LANDS IN THE '80S 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on Sunday, June 4) 
 By GALE HAYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the 1980s? ``Dynasty,'' affluence, opulence, jewels,
high heels, designer labels and entirely new categories of luxury
goods, from foods to expensively scented candles to indulgent
accessories for the bath?
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designers remember. For fall, they are revisiting some
of the signature styles from the decade of dressing excessively.
Some of the most incendiary young talents, including Marc Jacobs at
Louis Vuitton and Nicolas Ghesquiere at Balenciaga, are again
pushing the shoulder-pad envelope and putting the power back in
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Before all this makes you run screaming in protest to the Gap,
take a deep breath. In style, there was a lot more to the '80s than
the linebacker shoulders of Claude Montana or the silly, desexed
string ties of women ``dressing for success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The '80s really got a bad rap,'' Buffy Cafritz, the venerable
Washington hostess, told a group of us the other day at a lunch for
Bob Colacello, who is writing a book about Ronald and Nancy Reagan.
``Luxury living is bigger than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right, of course. The wardrobe choices of Reagan that once
drew such scorn in the news are the essence of classic elegant
restraint. The china she chose for the White House, another target,
looks fabulous today. The way I see it, the '80s was a dress
rehearsal. This time around, we're getting the '80s right by doing
the original looks better, more stylishly and with greater
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   I had a front-row seat for the dress rehearsal decade. Back
then, I owned one of the quintessential stores for fashion, Giorgio
Beverly Hills, on Los Angeles' Rodeo Drive. We couldn't get enough
Kenneth Lane jewelry, Thierry Mugler, Claude Montana, Versace,
Oscar de la Renta, Karl Lagerfeld, Scaasi, Bill Blass, Calvin
Klein, Christian Dior, Valentino and Zandra Rhodes. Extravagance
walked out of the store. Christian Lacroix's poufs literally
floated out like parachutes. By the mid-'80s, Halston, who had been
enormously popular in the '70s, was all of a sudden too quiet for
the newly created glamour girl.
</P>
<P>
   By day, however, this glamour girl, who couldn't exactly float
into the office in a pouf, was in a fashion quandary. In
counterpoint to the shimmer of evening, there emerged the dress for
success look (and a book by the same name), which dictated dressing
like a man in order to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Two-piece gray, navy or tan suits with a high-buttoned white or
pale blue shirt, worn with a man's black tie. It became a uniform
in offices all across the country. (We sold it, too, except ours
was made by Brioni in Rome). To complement (or perhaps counteract)
the stiffness, I created Giorgio perfume: sexy, powerful, feminine
and effusive.
</P>
<P>
   Today the rigid office look is long gone. It has been stretched,
softened and made to skim the body. Even by night, fit is
everything. Perhaps the biggest revolution in fashion over the last
two decades has been in fabric technology.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to go back to a 100-pound beaded gown (I kid you not)
when you've worn one weighing six ounces, like those Richard Tyler
designs for the stars. Skinny capris now have stretch and give to
them. The famous Jax capris of the '80s would split almost without
fail whenever you sat down. Jeans in the '80s were so tight and
uncomfortable they required you to lie down when you zipped them
up. Now we have slim cuts but wearable, comfortable, slightly
stretchy fits.
</P>
<P>
   The trick in looking like an '80s gal updated for 2000 is to
take what worked best from the past and reject the rest. As Karl
Lagerfeld once told me, ``Fashion comes back, but always in a
different way.'' Imagine, for example, taking a pair of your old
bell-bottom slacks from the back of your closet and trying to pass
them off as today's boot cut. They'd never fly, let alone walk.
</P>
<P>
   Big, constructed '80s clothes don't work today. Big, softly
crushable clothes do. Oscar de la Renta's opulent Degas-style
evening dress made of yards of netting squishes when you sit _ in
the '80s, a similar style didn't. Clothes all across the spectrum
perform so much better than they ever did in dress rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   We're not following the '90s interval of gray-black-tan-neutral
minimalism with a surge of ostentation or vulgarity. Anything but.
But what we're seeing now is a backlash against that minimalism,
which dictated plain clothes, no jewelry, no color, no fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Too safe, too plain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, energy and sex appeal are back out in the open. The Hermes
bags and Van Cleef jewels fit the mix, along with cashmere in
abundance, pashminas in gently pretty colors, pearls, sapphire
earrings and a Verdura watch (like the one designed for Greta
Garbo). Wonderful luminous satins, velvets and floral chiffons.
Moderation. One wonderful piece of jewelry at a time. And more
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   We always said in the '80s that when the market went up, so
would hemlines. It's not true anymore. The market is up, hemlines
are sensible, but you can also run a company today wearing pink.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that moderation has to be too moderate.
That's where the decade of the '80s has really triumphed this time.
</P>
<P>
   Furs, feathers, higher heels, pink lipstick and big hair have
all reappeared. Off-the-shoulder ``boyfriend'' sweaters. Pony skin
and leopard boots. Silk blouses with or without ascot-tie
necklines, worn with slim or pleated skirts. Hemlines by choice
just below the knee. Chanel quilted chain belts.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that back then, women wore it all together,
head to toe: they came swinging into a room with jewelry on both
hands, a choker, cleavage, a Gucci printed initial bag. Now, it's
edited down to one great piece at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrasuede is back, too, in the new Halston collection designed
by Craig Natiello. Watch for a re-emergence of leotards, the basis
of Donna Karan's first collection, which should be back any minute.
Watch, too, for trends that won't be revived, like the huge
shoulders of the mid-'80s. They didn't sell then, and guess what?
They're not going to sell now. Simply not flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Are we ready for the fedora with our suits as Michael Kors
showed for fall 2000? Perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   The '80s beauty _ think ``Charlie's Angels,'' the first time
around, or Cher _ was created with lots of makeup and expressed
with complicated hairstyles, in keeping with that era of excess.
But it's not for today, when the extravagance is toned down and the
look is soft, feminine and all of a piece. Today, the hairstyles
are back but in a way that doesn't cry out, ``Look at me.''
Straight hair used to be teased for height and sprayed so it
wouldn't droop. In fact, not one wisp blew in a breeze. Today's
hair has to move, unless it's in an up-do that's meant to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Headbands are back, but they're skinny, unobtrusive. In the '80s
they were wide.
</P>
<P>
   Skin today glows with foundation, but it doesn't go on like a
mask anymore. Eyes are smudged instead of lined. False eyelashes
are back but only a few wisps at a time. Less, as it turns out, is
much more. If practice makes perfect, we're ready to perform. With
the '80s behind us, let's let them begin anew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1723EDT &QL; 
