A3089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MUSIC-BIOGRAPHY-NY     06-02 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MUSIC-BIOGRAPHY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIOGRAPHY' PROFILES SAM PHILLIPS OF SUN RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PACE   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ala. _ The man who discovered Elvis Presley will be
the subject of a two-hour documentary that premieres June 18 on the
Arts &AMP; Entertainment cable network's ``Biography'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Phillips: The Man Who Invented Rock 'n' Roll'' will look
at the life and influential career of the 77-year-old founder of
Memphis' Sun Records, which propelled to stardom not only Presley,
but Jerry Lee Lewis, Johnny Cash and other rockabilly artists of
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it, and they've done a great job with it,'' said
Phillips, a Florence native.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary marks the first time Phillips has participated
in a film devoted to his life _ including his pioneering work in
both radio and the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound is the greatest gift God ever gave to mankind,''
Phillips said. ``Music has brought more people together than any
other force on this earth, and radio remains the greatest tool we
have for communication. I've never been out of radio since the day
I started.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who Invented Rock 'n' Roll'' was written by Peter
Guralnick, a popular music historian whose works include include
``Sweet Soul Music'' and the two-volume Elvis Presley biography,
``Last Train to Memphis'' and ``Careless Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is one of the American masters, and his story demands to
be told,'' Guralnick said. ``We live in a culture that prizes the
country-club accent sometimes over the colloquial and chooses not
to recognize some of our most precious possessions. Because Sam
wrote his story in a colloquial voice, it has not been recognized
to the degree that it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is narrated by Billy Bob Thornton, the
Oscar-winning writer, director and star of ``Sling Blade.''
Interview subjects include Lewis, Ike Turner, Jerry Wexler, Rufus
Thomas, Little Milton, Rosco Gordon, Scotty Moore, George Klein,
John Prine, Marty Stuart and Phillips' wife and sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the sense that if Sam were to try again today, he
could find amazing artists who have something different that nobody
else could find,'' said Morgan Neville, who produced the program.
``It's his way of looking at the picture, and nobody else sees it
that way _ but it's completely inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   (The TimesDaily in Florence, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
