<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PIPELINE03-COX     06-02 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PIPELINE OWNERS FINED $3 MILLION FOR SPILL THAT KILLED THREE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal Office of Pipeline Safety announced
Friday it would levy a $3.05 million fine against the owner of a
gasoline pipeline that exploded last year, killing two boys and a
young man near Seattle, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, roughly equal to the combined amount of all previous
fines levied by the agency during the past decade, will be charged
to Olympic Pipeline, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm operates a pipeline that ruptured in the town of
Bellingham, Wash., last June 10, and dumped more than 280,000
gallons of gasoline into a creek running through a park.
</P>
<P>
   Two 11-year-old boys and an 18-year-old youth were killed when
the gasoline exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said Olympic had failed to properly train employees,
continued to operate the pipeline after discovering safety problems
and had failed to properly operate and maintain the line.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Olympic said the company would have no comment
until it had studied the fine. The company can oppose the fine if
it chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally Friday, the Environmental Protection Agency and
the Justice Department announced that a former service station
operator would be fined $4.7 million for a 10,000-gallon gasoline
leak.
</P>
<P>
   The gasoline had been left in underground storage tanks after
the station went out of business. Its former owner was Oliver Hill,
against whom the fine was levied. He could not be reached for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The three deaths in Bellingham energized a national pipeline
reform movement and brought the Office of Pipeline Safety (OPS)
under fire for allegedly failing to vigorously police owners of
more than a million miles of pipeline criss-crossing the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases like this, where a pipeline operator fails to take
appropriate actions to improve safety, we will penalize the company
to the fullest extent possible to ensure full compliance with
federal safety laws,'' said Kelley Coyner, head of the Department
of Transportation's Research and Special Programs Administration,
which includes the Office of Pipeline Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of OPS reacted cautiously to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly a step in the right direction,'' said Robert
Rackleff, a Leon County, Fla., county commissioner who is president
of the National Pipeline Reform Coalition. ``The death of three
people in Bellingham last June should have been a clarion call for
OPS to thoroughly review that standards for construction and
operation of pipelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Epstein, an engineer with Environmental Defense,(cq) an
environmental group, declared that the ``action, while welcome, is
simply not enough to prevent future tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline coalition backs legislation increasing the role of
state governments in the enforcement of pipeline regulation and a
stiffer set of fines.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
