<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR-600&AMP;     06-02 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-SLAVE-LABOR-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND GERMANY FAIL TO AGREE ON COMPENSATION FOR NAZI LABORERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Five months after German industry and government agreed
to pay Holocaust survivors nearly $5 billion, the deal became
ensnarled here Friday in disagreements with the United States over
the companies' insistence on immunity from future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, German and U.S. officials warned that the aging
population of Nazi-era slave laborers may have to wait until next
year before receiving any payments.
</P>
<P>
   After about 14 hours of talks on Thursday night and Friday
morning, U.S. and German negotiators failed to reach agreement and
gave up their hope that President Clinton would be able to sign the
final pact this weekend during his visit with European leaders in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and German negotiators said they were still confident of
reaching a final deal, and scheduled another round of talks in
Washington on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must agree on final arrangements by then,'' said Otto
Lambsdorff, a former German economics minister who is Germany's
lead negotiator on the issue. ``If we don't get the whole thing
going, then the million or so survivors will have to wait even
longer for the payments.''
</P>
<P>
   What has surprised many observers, including groups representing
Holocaust survivors, is that the dispute has erupted now over an
issue that appeared to have been settled last December.
</P>
<P>
   The main dispute is over German demands for ``legal closure,'' a
guarantee from the U.S. government that German companies will be
shielded from any future American lawsuits stemming from activities
during Hitler's Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Under the basic plan, German industry and the German government
will each contribute 5 billion marks to a new fund that will then
make payments to former slave laborers and several other categories
of Holocaust-era victims who have until now received little if any
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But German corporations have always insisted on receiving
immunity from future lawsuits over such claims, a guarantee that
this fund will resolve all claims once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is crucial because a primary motive of the
corporations in agreeing to create the new fund was that they faced
an explosion of class-action lawsuits filed in U.S. courts on
behalf of millions of former laborers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, led by Deputy Secretary of State Stuart
Eizenstat, agree in principle, but point out that the U.S.
government does not have the power to forbid future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the two sides appeared to have agreed on a
workable compromise: the U.S. government would file a strongly
worded legal brief that would be used to urge judges to reject any
future Holocaust claims on the grounds that they had been addressed
by the new fund.
</P>
<P>
   But German officials said Friday that the proposed U.S. brief is
not strong enough, because it rests largely on U.S. ``foreign
policy interests'' in rejecting future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is only a political statement then there is a risk that
a judge five years from now will have lost the context of what
happened here,'' said Wolfgang Gibowski, a spokesman for German
industry. ``We need legal wording, to explain that there are not
only political reasons but legal reasons to dismiss the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters more difficult, Lambsdorff has only raised 2.4
billion of the 5 billion marks that has been pledged from German
corporations. Hundreds of smaller companies that did business
during the Nazi period are still resisting calls to join the fund,
and some companies are now threatening to withdraw their pledges if
they are not ensured legal immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Lambsdorff has harshly criticized the German corporate hold-outs
and recently accused them of using the issue of legal immunity as a
``lazy pretext'' for not contributing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Negotiators sat down at about 3 p.m. Thursday and worked until
1:30 Friday morning. They resumed again at 8:30 am Friday, but then
broke off talks three hours later, and Eizenstat flew back
empty-handed to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers say German political and corporate leaders have
invested too much effort to turn back now, and they are anxious to
avoid the potential expense and nightmarish publicity of
Holocaust-related trials, which could last for years.
</P>
<P>
   But Eizenstat said Friday that it is now ``much more uncertain''
than before that the aging victims will receive any money this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gideon Taylor, head of the Jewish Claims Conference in New York,
said Friday that he remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that both sides remember what is at stake here,
and I think they will,'' Taylor said in a telephone interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
