<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will soar toward 100 degrees in southern Georgia
Saturday, fostered by a very warm ridge of high pressure several
thousand feet above the Southeast. The ridge will be part of an
expansive region of high pressure aloft that will span from the
torrid interior of Southern California to the sizzling Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Within this hot region, an island of diminished heat will lie
over Texas and Oklahoma, where an upper-level low, trapped within
the expansive warm ridge, will produce clouds, showers and
thunderstorms that will suppress temperatures. Rains spawned by the
trapped low will be locally heavy near the Red River Valley, where
rainfalls of 2 inches are possible in places.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt over parts of the northern
Plains as a disturbance moves east across Montana. Meanwhile, heat
and humidity will break decisively in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FLORIDA DROUGHT
</P>
<P>
   The gravity of the drought in Florida crystallized on Thursday,
when the National Weather Service issued climatological statements
for May. At Tampa, rainfall for the month was a mere 0.02 inches,
the driest May since records began there in 1890. The cause of the
drought is a warm high-pressure system thousands of feet aloft that
has held steady over Florida for much of the spring. The tenacious
high has effectively prevented air rising above the ground from
reaching rarefied altitudes, thereby suppressing thunderstorms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-FLOOR-NYT     06-02 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-FLOOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITS OF CELTIC FLOOR LORE TO BE AUCTIONED OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Celtics are absent from the postseason for a fifth
consecutive year, but the best parts of their old hardcourt _ the
parquet that ranks with the yellow brick road in the annals of
fabled flooring _ are preparing for a final game.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, parquet equals history. Maybe even art. So the floor
on which Larry Bird's sneakers squeaked and Red Auerbach's cigar
ashes fell will receive its last hurrah at an online auction
starting Monday on sothebys.amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many opportunities like this,'' said Leila
Dunbar, a senior vice president and director of collectibles at
Sotheby's, the auction house. ``What other floor in basketball has
this kind of history?''
</P>
<P>
   The auction was timed to coincide with the National Basketball
Association playoffs and will end June 15.
</P>
<P>
   From 1946 to 1999, the Celtics played on no home floor but the
parquet _ crafted out of scraps of northern Tennessee red oak for
$11,000 _ at the Boston Arena, the Boston Garden and the
FleetCenter. The finale for the geriatric floor came on Dec. 22,
when the Celtics lost to Atlanta, 98-81, in front of some of its
legends.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 40 of the 264 panels that comprised the floor are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the 2-foot-by-2-foot panels are laid out together at a
10th floor gallery at Sotheby's East Side building to recreate
center court _ leprechaun logo included. Another 20 autographed and
framed panels are to be displayed on walls where Impressionist
paintings hanged two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unique because it looked like no other floor,'' said
Bill Russell, the center of the Celtic dynasty from 1956 to 1969.
``But what was most significant about the floor was that teams
found it distracting. And that was all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams searched for reasons for losing to Boston, like the Boston
Garden's dark and cold locker rooms or the floor's dribble-killing
dead spots. ``It was part of our legend for kicking everybody's
butts,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   The auctioneers are not identifying or charging more for the
dead spots. But they have priced the floor panels in order of their
significance, with most of the proceeds going to charity.
</P>
<P>
   So, the minimum acceptable bid for center court is $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   The spot where John Havlicek stole the ball in Game 7 of the
1965 Eastern Conference finals: $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The panel where Russell made a spectacular block in the 1957
finals against St. Louis: $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The spot from which Phoenix's Garfield Heard launched his
amazing shot in the second overtime of Game 5 of the 1976 finals:
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mann, sales director of Boston Parquet at the FleetCenter,
examined old video to identify the panels of Celtic lore: Bird's
theft of Isiah Thomas' inbounds pass during the 1987 Eastern
Conference finals; Kevin McHale's favored low-post area; and where
Bob Cousy cried when he bid farewell in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parquet helped me pinpoint them because of the
intersecting pattern of the floor,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-life of the Celtics' floor is an anomaly, like a
25-year-old cat. Most NBA floors endure for seven to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, the Utah Jazz's Delta Center floor was removed and
auctioned off by Collectors Universe One-of-a-Kind. Some of the
panels were acquired by Upper Deck, of Carlsbad, Calif., which used
them to produce a limited edition of collectibles to commemorate
the last shot of Michael Jordan's careerin the 1998 finals, which
gave the Chicago Bulls their eighth NBA championship. Thursday, on
eBay, the bid for one of the items was $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck recently bought a home jersey worn by Joe DiMaggio in
1951, his final season, which failed to sell in April for the
minimum price set by the auction house Christie's. The pinstriped
top will be sliced into swatches and inserted as surprises in 2000
Upper Deck baseball card packs next month.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck has similarly diced a Jordan jersey and a Babe Ruth
bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' floor seems destined for a better, more intact
fate, especially for someone who can put center court in his or her
rec room. The 200-plus panels not consigned to sothebys.amazon.com
for the auction will be sold at retail at more modest prices, Mann
said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, never one to linger over nostalgia, has a few framed
panels hanging on a wall at his home. ``Sometimes I just look at
them and laugh,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
