<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3107 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TV-STYLE-REGIS-ART-$A     06-02 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STYLE-REGIS-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK LIKE A MILLIONAIRE FOR ONLY $77.50 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Weird? Please! I don't even want to think about
it!'' Regis Philbin said in his dressing room at the ABC studios on
West 67th Street last week.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin was not referring to the immense, bizarre popularity of
his show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' He was rifling through
a rack of shirts and ties bearing his own name. ``Regis by Van
Heusen'' is a line whose label promises to capture ``the style and
essence of Regis Philbin, America's favorite television
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   What are the odds of a man in his mid-60s becoming a style icon
and reinvigorating an entire category of men's wear? Especially
when that man is Philbin? As he himself is the first to acknowledge
_ in his inevitably emphatic style _ ``it's really strange!''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Philbin will officially introduce the Regis collection
at Macy's Herald Square, where the monochromatic Regis shirts and
ties will be sold as matching sets in seven colors (from blue and
gray to aubergine and khaki) for $77.50. On June 18, Father's Day,
department stores will begin selling the collection nationwide, not
as sets but separately. By year-end, 19 ``Millionaire'' shades will
be available, with shirts at $39.50 to $50 and ties at $38 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the licensing deal was struck, Macy's and other
department stores were busy creating a craze, with displays asking
customers, ``Who Wants to Look Like a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Many American men, it seems. Mark Weber, the president of
Phillips-Van Heusen, which is paying Philbin for his name and his
look, projected sales of $50 million for the Regis line this year,
based on the orders received so far. At Saks Fifth Avenue, sales of
solid shirts and ties had dipped until the ``Millionaire'' show
took off last summer, said Dan McCampbell, a vice president and the
men's fashion director there. ``There has been a noticeable
resurgence,'' McCampbell said. ``And I think it's pretty fair to
attribute it at least in part to this show.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Michael Corleone in ``The Godfather: Part III,''
just when you thought ties were out, Philbin pulled them back in.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As Brian Boyer, fashion director of the daily men's wear bible
DNR, said, ``We call it the Philbinization of neckwear.''
</P>
<P>
   The same man who used to wear banana-colored sports coats on
``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee'' is now as hip as Gucci, Prada
and Helmut Lang _ all of whom will be bringing back the suit and
tie this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin could not be more on trend. Don't think he doesn't know
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife took a second look at me!'' he said. ``And after 30
years, that ain't easy, to get that second look, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He preens. He boasts. ``I walk into a restaurant now and meet
some old friends who aren't into the style yet,'' he said. And what
does he say to them? ```Hey, come on. Get with the `Millionaire'
look. You guys'll never make anything out of yourselves!''
</P>
<P>
   The Regis shirts and ties had just come in. They were mixed in
with the other labels on the rack in his dressing room: Hugo Boss,
Cerruti and Beau Brummel, the SoHo men's store that has been
outfitting him for 10 years. Philbin ran the fabric between his
thumb and forefingers like a tailor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not really much when you look at the choice here,'' he
said. ``Burgundy, black. Different shades of gray, different shades
of blues. And a green. The green is really a big deal. Green is
such a departure. You can wear it with gray!
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there's one other wild card. The gold is pretty good, too.
It goes good with the gray and with the black. You can wear it with
almost anything and it pops right out. And that's what they want.
They want it to pop right out of the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   In 27 countries, ``Millionaire'' hosts cloned from the British
original wear the same look. Michael Davies, the show's executive
producer, put the show on American television and changed nothing.
The set, the music and the host's dark, elegant, vaguely ominous
wardrobe are all part of the formula.
</P>
<P>
   The British-born Davies, 34, described it as the sort of look
worn by ``professional soccer players in Hello! magazine.'' A money
look. And he saw Philbin as being money enough to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that Regis is a very hip guy,'' said Davies,
who came to the United States 10 years ago. ``On `Letterman,'
college kids would always applaud him. There's a certain hipness
within his squareness that sort of works.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   He said that at first, his star reacted to his sartorial
makeover with ``raised eyebrows'' but that now ``he's embraced
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said of some male contestants on
``Millionaire.'' Most still tend to be tieless, and at least one
showed up for his date with destiny in overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many fashion experts agree that if anyone can get the
increasingly tie-resistant American male to dress at least as well
as a British soccer player on a club crawl, Philbin can. Jim Moore,
fashion director at GQ, said that his magazine has been advocating
classier attire for the last three years but that ``it takes
someone like Regis to really get it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They see Regis in it,'' he said, ``and it just endorses it.''
</P>
<P>
   Average guys out there may feel more comfortable taking their
fashion cues from television than from GQ. Knowing this, apparel
companies have taken advantage of the medium as a marketing tool
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Botany 500 label was sold to Men's Warehouse three years
ago. But its legacy lives on Nick at Nite and TV Land. Something
like 75 male television stars have worn the Botany label since its
heyday, the '60s, from Dick Van Dyke's skinny suits to the plaid
blazers favored by Mike Connors on ``Mannix.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Carson lent his name to a long line of clothing and
leisure wear during his career, often combining stripes and checks
that would have made a used car salesman blush. In the '80s, Don
Johnson imported Armani's Euro look _ peach T-shirts under
billowing white suits _ for a generation of men who probably had no
business trying it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dorn, who was the press agent for Botany 500 for 25 years,
said that Telly Savalas set off a craze for colored vests when he
started wearing them on ``Kojak.'' They were especially popular in
Europe, Dorn said, where ``suddenly, everyone wanted to look like
Kojak.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that Philbin is enjoying his own ``Who loves ya, baby?''
moment, he must deal with serious questions about
celebrity-licensed apparel. Questions like, Who makes this stuff?
And, Are they being paid a living wage? After his daytime co-host,
Kathie Lee Gifford, got into highly publicized trouble in this
area, the last thing Philbin needs is a sweatshop scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Weber, Phillips-Van Heusen's president, acknowledged that
``given the Kathie Lee situation, Regis is going to be watching us
very closely.'' Weber said one million shirts and as many ties will
be made, starting in factories in the United States, then abroad in
countries ``yet to be determined.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TV-STYLE-REGIS-ART-$A     06-02 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STYLE-REGIS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: be determined.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (The company has factories in Costa Rica and throughout Asia.)
</P>
<P>
   As a makeup artist applied flattering tones to Philbin's cheeks
and forehead, his dresser, a recent addition to his staff, selected
a navy Regis tie, a blue Hugo Boss shirt and a blue Canali suit.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Martin crooned, ``You're nobody till somebody loves you,''
on the stereo. Philbin always plays Dino _ it relaxes him. Being
arguably the biggest television star in the country is stressful.
And stress is Philbin's shtick. Even basking in glory as a style
icon, he has to complain about something. So he recounted an
argument he had with his producer, Davies. The issue was two
buttons versus three.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought in a beautiful blue suit,'' Philbin said, working
himself up into one of his rants. ``And it was nice fabric and
everything, and it was two-button.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Michael Davies,'' he said, doing a pretty good Cary Grant
impersonation, ``said: `No! This is a three-button show.' So I lost
my suit!''
</P>
<P>
   It's always something. As Bill Zehme, a writer who is now
collaborating on his second book with Philbin, said of his
cantankerous subject, ``He's always said he lived under a dark
cloud, so now he's got the wardrobe to match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
