<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-WARCRIMES-38     06-02 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-WARCRIMES-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUP CHALLENGES RUSSIA TO INVESTIGATE MASSACRE NEAR
GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ An international human rights group on Friday
challenged the Russian government to seek out and try the Russian
servicemen who entered a neighborhood near Grozny on Feb. 5 and
killed at least 60 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The atrocity is believed to be the worst of the latest Chechen
war.
</P>
<P>
   In a report that documents the massacre and the pillage that
followed, Human Rights Watch called on Russian authorities to
pursue a vigorous investigation into what happened in a Grozny
suburb, Noviye Aldi.
</P>
<P>
   Released on the eve of President Clinton's arrival in Moscow,
the report _ drawn from accounts by more than 35 eyewitnesses _
comes as a rebuke to President Vladimir Putin, who has made
repeated promises to pursue reports of war crimes during the
eight-month war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian government has not undertaken any serious
investigation of these horrendous crimes,'' said Holly Cartner,
executive director of the Europe and Central Asia division of Human
Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure to address what amounts to war crimes in Aldi
directly contradicts Putin's statement on May 29 that `all
violations of the law in Chechnya will be stamped out in the most
severe fashion regardless of who committed them,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for two Russian officials in charge of various
investigations in Chechnya could not be reached for comment Friday.
Vladimir Kalamanov, named by Putin as the Kremlin's special envoy
for human rights, has said that his investigative team, which
includes two Europeans, have received corroborating evidence of
atrocities in Noviye Aldi as well as in Alkhan-Yurt and in the
Staropromyslovsky section of Grozny, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, only one known war crimes case has been put to a
Russian military court. That involves Col. Yuri Budanov, commander
of a tank regiment, who has been charged with raping and murdering
a Chechen woman.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch and Memorial, a Russian rights group, have
pressed Moscow to call in international, independent investigators,
arguing that Russian investigative teams are distrusted by local
people. Although both groups have compiled detailed eyewitness
accounts of alleged war crimes, no Russian official has contacted
them to see their evidence, according to Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reports of a massacre at Noviye Aldi began to trickle into the
overcrowded refugee camps in Ingushetia in mid-February. In an
interview with The New York Times published on Feb. 22, a woman,
who gave only her first name, Sapiyat, described how after several
days of round-the clock shelling by Russian forces the town fell
silent.
</P>
<P>
   `'``Suddenly, it became calm,'' she said. `'And the troops
started mopping up. We thought they would just check everyone's
passports. But it was a cleansing of everything alive. They killed
cattle, dogs, people _ children and old people.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Human Rights Watch report, the violence began
with the arrival of special police and ``contract soldiers,'' who
are older than regular army conscripts and more brutal and are
usually dressed in camouflage uniforms with hats or head scarves.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the soldiers spread through Aldi, they engaged in an orgy
of killing, arson and rape,'' the report said ``Human Rights Watch
has eyewitness testimony describing the murder of eight people; in
each case, the witnesses identified the killers as Russian contract
soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization confirmed the execution of 60 civilians, 52 men
and eight women, one 82 years old. A one-year-old infant was also
killed, according to Human Rights Watch. The report also recounts
second-hand testimony of a gang rape in which three women were
killed, while a fourth fled into hiding, devastated by shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
