<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV04-     06-02 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING THE INDOORS WITH SUMMERY SCENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All week, our old farmhouse in Maryland has been full of the
smell of mock oranges and fragrant roses drifting through the
kitchen window. The big double purple and white lilacs, which my
grandmother brought here shortly after she eloped at 16, filled the
house with their intoxicating scent weeks ago. Now, I am digging up
some of their suckers to make a new border along the old vegetable
patch.
</P>
<P>
   I'm devoting at least half of the old truck patch _ a rectangle
100 by 40 feet _ to cut flowers, growing them in long farmer rows,
alongside rows of pole beans and potatoes. The farmer in me revels
in the usefulness of these long, wide rows of plants, which can be
cut with abandon without worrying about bare stems in the border.
The more you cut many of these flowers, the more they bloom.
</P>
<P>
   This is also where I will put those mangy-looking tulips, now
that they have bloomed so heftily in the big pots by the kitchen
door and in the perennial garden. Lifting them makes room for
summer blooms, like the scabiosa and Russian sage I'm putting in
the pots, and all the oreganos, lavenders, salvias and you-name-its
I can't stop collecting.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I thought I'd give my bulbs a home for the summer
while they fattened up on all that food manufactured in the leaves.
But now I think I'll leave them right where they are, to bloom as
cut flowers next spring. And I'll add about 100 more, to have
plenty for cutting. Ridiculous as it sounds, this is the best time
to order bulbs for fall. The memory of the ones that worked is
still in your mind, and there are hefty discounts for orders placed
before July 1.
</P>
<P>
   I've ordered a lot of flamed Darwins, like Orange Bowl (red
petals licked with orange), Burning Heart (cream with blood red)
and Ad Rem (a huge red orange with gleaming gold edges), to name
only a few, and Princess Irene, the single early deep-orange tulip
with dark red, which is always sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Summer bulbs are also essential to a good workhorse cut-flower
garden. Giant Dutch irises _ I have Blue Ribbon, Purple Sensation
and White Perfection _ grow as high as 18 inches and are handsome
all by themselves in a tall vase. Spuria irises, which look like
butterflies, range in color from lemon yellow to burnt orange and
lilac blue.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not crazy about big gladioluses, but I like more delicate
types, like Gladiolus communis Byzantinus, the corn lily, which
blooms with the first roses and peonies. Acidanthera, from Africa,
is like gladiolus, but has spikes of white, four-inch fragrant
flowers with maroon throats. It has a three-foot stem and lasts
well in a vase. Gladiolus gandavensis, a French heirloom, is pale
yellow, with red in the center. The three-foot spikes bloom in June
and July.
</P>
<P>
   Oriental lilies also make terrific cut flowers, in moderation.
One is all you need to intoxicate the guests. I planted Casa Blanca
about six years ago, and the plants are spreading to the size of a
small hippopotamus.
</P>
<P>
   There's still time to plant seeds of annuals in the ground. I've
also ordered some flats through the catalogs, just to see how they
work. And I binge at my local nurseries, of course. I tell myself
it's for research, but it's really addiction.
</P>
<P>
   I have a lot of old-favorite annuals, like Firecracker zinnias
and the cut-and-come-again doubles you can find almost anywhere.
Also cleome, or spider flower, which has a globe-shape flower head,
full of delicate white, rose or purple petals and dangling
seedpods, which look more like cat whiskers than spider legs to me,
but anyway. Helen Campbell is a reliable bloomer and a prolific
self-seeder, but just deadhead, or snap off the flower heads, if
you're worried about its spreading elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmos is another workhorse, with tall billowy stems and
single-petal flowers, and the more you cut, the more will grow. It
now comes in many shades: orange, chocolate, pink-and-white
striped. But don't order the dwarf variety by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Lavatera, with satiny, cup-shape blooms in white or pink with
darker pink veining, is another flower that lasts well in a vase.
It's tricky getting it to germinate, so keep the soil moist, and
don't let the seedlings dry out. But once it gets going, it's tough
and drought-tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Lisianthus, a prairie native that thrives in heat, has delicate
cup-shape flowers that range in color from white to deep purple.
</P>
<P>
   Campanula persicifolia, with its spikes of blue and white
cup-shape flowers, will rebloom when cut, and it also self-sows. So
does Verbena bonariensis, whose purplish-pink flowers bloom on airy
five-foot stems.
</P>
<P>
   I love my trusty perennials, like purple and white coneflowers,
blanketflowers, Shasta daisies, black-eyed Susans, monardas,
verbascums and all the yarrows, which now come in deep red and
orange yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Think of accents, too, like a bit of Blackie, the ebony-purple
sweet potato vine, Ipomoea batatas, or its chartreuse cousin,
Margarita. The delicate greenish-yellow blossoms of lady's mantle,
as well as flowering dill, will lend an edge of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget sunflowers, which are hogs in the garden, but the
finches love them. Just a few look gorgeous in a tall urn, and
their faces are eerily expressive. My favorites include Tithonia,
the orange Mexican sunflower; Velvet Queen, a dark burgundy with
charcoal-color disks; and Italian White, a six-footer with
chocolate centers banded with gold.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying Penstemon eriantherus this year, a drought-tolerant
Midwestern species. It has dark-burgundy foliage on dark,
three-foot stems, with white or bluish flowers. You can never have
enough salvias, even if you have to plant them every year.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget Nicotiana alata, the white flowering tobacco, which
smells like jasmine. N. sylvestris is the jolly tall one, which
looks terrific in a vase. N. landsdorffii is the green bellflower
tobacco, but N. alata will make the guests swoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
