<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONTRIBUTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH CAMP DENIES LINK BETWEEN CORPORATE DONATION, REGULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Do corporate campaign donations, coupled with
access to high-ranking state officials and favorable treatment of
regulations, add up to influence peddling?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not, said a spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush, state
health officials and a lawyer for Metabolife International, a
herbal dietary-supplement company whose contributions to Bush's
1998 re-election effort coincided with the company's attempts to
avoid stringent health regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that just about anything and everything related
to Texas and state government will be brought up in the context of
presidential politics, even when the governor has no involvement
whatsoever in the decision,'' said Bush campaign spokesman Scott
McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it is the battle over regulating the stimulant
ephedrine, which is used in weight-loss products and
energy-boosting supplements.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Time magazine article highlighted the issue, drawing a
connection between Bush's 1998 campaign and favorable treatment for
companies such as Metabolife, which were eager to fend off a
proposed prescription requirement for ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
   The same year, there were meetings on proposed ephedrine
regulations among Bush-backed Health Commissioner William R.
``Reyn'' Archer III, other state health officials and makers of
products that contain ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, after taking public comments, the State Board of
Health approved regulations that fell short of requiring a
prescription. The rules, among other provisions, do require a
warning label on ephedrine products. Archer called them a first
step.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was sponsored by state Sen. Jeff Wentworth, a San
Antonio Republican and a lawyer who represented Metabolife
International. He donated $2,500 to Bush's gubernatorial campaign
in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said strongly there is no connection between those
two things, and that he donated money to Bush simply because he
supports him as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports of eight deaths in Texas and nearly
1,500 health problems associated with ephedrine products since late
1994, said state Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives have said their products are safe if
used properly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
