<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-AIRLINES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CALGARY, Alberta: Air Canada.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Air Canada gouges the public, Collenette warned, the
government will consider at the end of next year whether to allow
American airlines to carry passengers between Canadian cities.
</P>
<P>
   In a boost for Canada 3000, the charter airline, the government
changed its rules in April to allow it to sell one-way and walkup
tickets. The company announced in mid-May that it would buy four
more jets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the merger legislation stipulates that if a
discounter in eastern Canada starts up by September, Air Canada
cannot start a discount airline until Oct. 1, 2001. Ken Rowe, a
Halifax, Nova Scotia, businessman, has said that in July he plans
to start CanJet, a discount carrier to be based in Hamilton or
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, Russell Payson, chairman of Skyservice
Airlines, announced that in November he would start a discount
airline aimed at business passengers, which would serve Canada's
eight largest cities and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But of the six discounters started in Canada in the last 20
years, only WestJet still flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``WestJet is only the first or second successful clone of the
Southwest business model,'' said Julius Maldutis, an analyst for
CIBC World Markets, an investment banking company that helped
WestJet go public.
</P>
<P>
   Following Southwest's no-frills model, WestJet offers one class
of seats, no meals, no frequent flyer program, no airport lounges
and no tickets _ only confirmation numbers. To cut costs, it uses
only one class of plane, the Boeing 737; hedges on fuel prices,
uses incentives to keep employees nonunionized, and encourages
ticket sales through the Internet, which now account for about 11
percent of tickets sold. Until the expansion east, almost all
WestJet flights were under one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Deferring to Canadians' sense of propriety, WestJet assigns
seats, a deviation from Southwest's free-for-all. In return,
passengers _ or ``guests,'' in WestJet-speak _ pay fares that
average 40 percent below Air Canada's. On a recent day, Air Canada
charged walkup travelers the equivalent of $372 (American) for the
40-minute hop from here to Edmonton, Alberta's capital. WestJet's
walkup fare was $209.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low fares, short haul, and focus on people,'' said Smith, who
formerly ran an Air Canada subsidiary, Air Ontario. Believing he is
not competing directly with Air Canada, he added: ``We are putting
new travelers in the skies, getting them out of their cars, off
their couches.''
</P>
<P>
   To lift the morale of WestJet's 1,100 employees, all workers,
after three months, participate in a company profit-sharing plan,
which produced $4 million American last year. In addition, 70
percent of employees take part in a stock purchase plan, in which
the company matches employee contributions up to 20 percent of
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The formula appears to be working. Capping four years of steady
growth, WestJet's revenue passenger miles, a key indicator, were up
54 percent for the first four months of this year. In April, 78
percent of seats were filled, compared with 71 percent in April
1999. Helping to create a niche for WestJet, the combined airline
controlled by Air Canada cut seats by 11 percent this spring _
slightly more than the total number of seats WestJet already
offers.
</P>
<P>
   WestJet consistently turns a profit, while Air Canada and
Canadian incurred losses in the first quarter. WestJet shares
closed Friday at $24 (Canadian), up 25 cents, on the Toronto
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``WestJet is tightly run, well managed, there are no flies on
those guys,'' said Harry Gow, a board member of the Canadian
Association of Airline Passengers, a consumer group. ``There are
not many complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Hamilton is a typical WestJet move. Roughly midway
between Toronto and Buffalo, N.Y., this airport has lower user fees
than Toronto's, but comparable access to the region's 7.5 million
people. With Air Canada talking about moving into Hamilton this
fall or next year, WestJet supporters do not seem concerned. With
about 70 employees per aircraft, half the ratio of Air Canada,
WestJet has operating costs that are about 40 percent lower. In
past price wars, the discount carrier usually made money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Canadian matched WestJet's ticket prices, they
doubled the market,'' Maldutis recalled of Canadian Airlines'
losing battle in Calgary. ``But at those prices, Canadian lost
money, and WestJet made money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
