<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TIANANMEN-DOCUMENTARY     06-02 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-DOCUMENTARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S TIANANMEN SQUARE MASSACRE STILL FILMMAKER'S PRIME MOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even during the killing, it all seemed like a movie
to him.
</P>
<P>
   On a humid night in 1989, Ke Feng watched as the scenes unfolded
in the heart of Beijing: a tank smashing through a line of parked
buses in Tiananmen Square; a young woman dashing toward a row of
soldiers, then crumpling with a fatal shot to the head; a group of
chanting students falling silent as bullets ripped into them on the
Avenue of Eternal Peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soldiers were pouring out from the Museum of Revolutionary
History, from the Gate of Heavenly Peace,'' Ke said recently
between bites of bouillabaisse in a SoHo seafood restaurant. ``This
would be a great movie. I was thinking that at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   To those unfamiliar with Ke's history, his remarks might sound
like those of a callous observer. But the Shanghai-born filmmaker,
still boyish-looking at 31, was more than just a witness to the
Tiananmen Square massacre, the 11th anniversary of which is Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   About a week before soldiers killed hundreds of students in the
early hours of June 4, 1989, Ke oversaw the construction of one of
the most enduring symbols of the movement, the 27-foot statue
called the Goddess of Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the unwanted attention of Chinese government
officials, Ke and the others responsible for the statue's
construction have gotten little notice. But Ke, now a graduate film
student at New York University, has begun filming interviews and
raising funds for a documentary to be called ``Making Goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing that is not widely appreciated about him
is that the Goddess of Democracy would never have been built if not
for him,'' said T.D. Allman, a journalist who met Ke while covering
the demonstrations for Vanity Fair magazine. ``For one moment, his
egomania and the moving fingertip of history coincided. To some
extent, he has been living in the aftermath of that event ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   In the almost 11 years since he fled to the United States, Ke
has focused much of his creative energies on film projects about
the massacre. Last year, he completed a 28-minute fiction film
called ``The Official Account,'' for which he won the Directors
Guild of America award for Best Asian-American Student Filmmaker.
The movie tells of a Chinese television news anchor who is forced
to choose between reporting or covering up the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Ke said the events of Tiananmen inspired him creatively in the
same way that the Chinese Cultural Revolution of the 1960s and '70s
inspired filmmakers of the ``fifth generation'' movement like Zhang
Yimou, Chen Kaige and Tian Zhuangzhuang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me that your life could be a movie,'' Ke
said, ``and that compelled a sense of mission in me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Ke, a political science student, was graduating from
Fudan University in Shanghai when he heard about the demonstrations
in Beijing. Tens of thousands of students were calling for reform
of corrupt government practices. To spur protests in Shanghai, Ke
and several friends built an 8-foot Styrofoam version of the Statue
of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   After marching with it through Shanghai's main avenues, they
tried taking the statue to Beijing. But when soldiers stopped them
from boarding a train, Ke had to sneak on empty-handed. In Beijing,
he walked straight from the station to Tiananmen Square, where
thousands of students had camped out. He stumbled across a tent
housing protesters from the Central Academy of Art and Design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ke Feng came into the tent and talked with me about the
idea,'' said Bao Chao-Jun, an artist now studying computer
animation in Los Angeles. ``We knew it would be the best symbol for
democracy and freedom, if we built the statue there in Tiananmen
Square.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao rounded up about a dozen students from the sculpture
department of academy. Using a steel frame, Styrofoam and plaster
coating, they worked around the clock for three days. On May 29,
the statue was taken in four parts on tricycle carts to the square,
where students finished assembling it. Once standing, it faced the
mammoth portrait of Mao Zedong hanging to the north of the square.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted, Ke said he rested for several days in his
girlfriend's dormitory room. But on the night of June 3, Ke said he
and his girlfriend decided to camp out at the base of his
``creation'' to celebrate his 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, soldiers marched into the square and began firing
on the protesters. Ke said he and his girlfriend fled over stones
slick with blood. ``In the movies the people triumph, but there the
soldiers fired again,'' he said. ``It was the most killing I've
seen in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The government began tracking down many Tiananmen dissidents,
including those who built the statue. While some were being jailed,
Ke wrote to the University of California at Berkeley explaining his
role in the demonstrations. The school immediately admitted him to
a graduate program in Asian studies and mailed him an airplane
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Ke soon dropped out of that program and earned a master's degree
in political science at the University of Toronto. But filmmaking,
Ke said, held an irresistible allure, and he enrolled in the
graduate film program at New York University. He is expected to
graduate this year, having completed ``The Official Account'' for
his thesis film and begun planning ``Making Goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   That documentary, which is budgeted at $200,000, will take a
subjective, first-person point of view, Ke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my parents knew I was making this film, they would have a
heart attack,'' he said. ``They think I should tell different
stories. They think that in case nobody employs me in America, I
can make a film in China. I'm burning a bridge if I do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Allman, now a close friend of Ke's, said one of the young
filmmaker's greatest challenges was to move beyond the massacre as
his main source material.
</P>
<P>
   Ke has made a few attempts: a short film he completed recently
tells of a wedding photographer who falls in love with a
bride-to-be. And he is writing a screenplay involving a
Chinese-American tea merchant in 19th-century Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Ke said he would never be able to purge the killings from
his memory, nor has he been able to forget his last sighting of the
Goddess of Democracy. As dawn broke on June 4, 1989, Ke climbed
atop a nearby billboard and gazed out over the square. Plumes of
smoke rose from burning buses and tanks. In the center of the
debris lay a crushed pile of styrofoam and plaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bunch of kids at the time,'' Ke said. ``We didn't
know about consequences. I didn't intend to be a protagonist in the
story. But it ended up that I had a story with a beginning, middle
and end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
