<HEADER>
A3131 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AMERICAN-DAUGHTER-REV     06-02 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-DAUGHTER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD COUNTRIES, DUMB POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Mon., June 5.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wendy Wasserstein's ``An American Daughter'' offers a pretty
insightful look at a major reason U.S. politics is in the doldrums
these days, why we've got a couple of earnest but hopelessly bland
candidates running for president, one a stuffed shirt and the other
an empty suit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wasserstein's story, based on her play, only concerns
the confirmation of a nominee for surgeon general. But in
satirically dissecting how one woman's life is undone by the media
rabidly and rudderlessly chasing the merest whiff of scandal,
without a trace of context or perspective, it comments cogently on
any number of recent penny-ante incidents blown up to apocalyptic
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Lahti stars as Lyssa Dent Hughes, descendent of
Ulysses S. Grant, daughter of a conservative Indiana senator
(Stanley Anderson), wife of a prominent sociologist (Tom Skerritt),
crackerjack doctor and nominee for surgeon general. When an oily TV
interviewer (Jay Thomas) distorts the particulars behind the fact
that Lyssa once evaded jury duty and takes a joking comment she
made about her mother out of context, it quickly becomes elevated
to the level of scandal _ she's perceived as elitist and arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   OK, in the real world, no doubt everyone would simply shrug or
say, ``Way to go,'' at the revelation that a nominee for public
service weaseled out of jury duty. But Wasserstein's exaggeration
smacks of satire, and it's certainly no odder than nannies or
marijuana or masturbation observations or cola-can jokes damaging
the reputations of public figures, not to mention Ken Starr's
quixotic efforts to bring down the Republic with a stained dress.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein also makes another cogent observation: that
politicians with a modicum of integrity and intelligence are
essentially doomed, that they have to, in essence, dumb themselves
down to a certain extent lest they not seem populist enough, that
an interesting life is a liability and blandness is rewarded.
That's how George W. Bush _ whom even David Letterman has divined
as, in his words, ``a colossal boob'' _ can appeal to the masses,
while a truly intelligent candidate _ which this current campaign,
alas, hasn't seen _ would simply sink from sight or be dismissed as
a stiff, even though the country could use smart people at the helm
rather than clods adept at kissing babies.
</P>
<P>
   The screenwriter also explores the ceaseless white noise of the
media and its pundits. Wasserstein's most inspired creation here is
the character of Quincy Quince (Blake Lindsley), a young and callow
Elizabeth Wurtzel-esque feminist writer who elevates her generation
and gender and vaguely debases those who came before her, without
ever having honestly bothered to try to understand them from a
historical or sociological perspective.
</P>
<P>
   That Quincy is quite obviously an idiot has no significance to
the news shows that book her to spout her drivel _ she's written a
book, she's telegenic, she's provocative for the sake of
provocation, and her words at least seem to make some sort of
sense. Wasserstein also shows how glib, ill-informed asides from
news anchors and yammering heads on a show like ``The View'' subtly
influence national debate, how the media's pack mentality forces
reporters to flog a dead issue just because other outlets are, how
it's a lot easier to discuss trivial stuff than to do a pertinent
exploration of issues actually facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the writer missteps by giving Quince and Lyssa's husband a
predictable, hackneyed and too-convenient affair, and some viewers
simply won't be able to buy that such a hullabaloo could result
over such a minor misstep. Nonetheless, the dialogue has snap and
bite, Lahti's great in the role, and it's refreshing, in a summer
of ``reality'' TV, to get a bracing dose of reality from a smart
piece of fiction. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``An American Daughter.'' &QL; 
What: Playwright Wendy Wasserstein's drama about a surgeon general
nominee's destruction via politics and the media. &QL; 
The stars: Christine Lahti, Tom Skerritt, Lynne Thigpen, Jay
Thomas. &QL; 
Where: Lifetime. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
