<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3134 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OURSLER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      06-02 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OURSLER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTERNATE SELVES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our ghost selves, the ones that flicker and writhe like wobbly
TV screens, are strewn across the floors and walls of the Museum of
Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   Some whine. Some curse. Some shout, `Hey, you!' at startled
passersby. Some lie flattened and immobilized under chairs and
sofas. Some babble under their electronic ``breath'' in loopy
non-sequiturs, like Hollywood street people or alien abductees,
conversing with the secret voices that haunt their splintered
souls.
</P>
<P>
   Lumped together, these spooky little mannequins with
video-animated faces create an eerie din as you step gingerly
through MOCA's exhibition titled ``Introjection: Tony Oursler
Mid-Career Survey 1976-1999.'' The more you try to tune them out,
the more incessantly they penetrate your consciousness, like a
barking dog on a windless night.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Oursler has been tracking these voices and the mental
states they represent for most of his adult life, since his student
days at California Institute of the Arts in Valencia a
quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout that time, he has explored many different ways of
capturing the rambling look and sound of the human mind in
conscious and unconscious action: in paintings, video performances,
elaborate multi-media installations and, most identifiably, in a
growing series of ``talking'' effigies with videotaped faces and
explosive, passive-aggressive personalities.
</P>
<P>
   These anxious Mini-Me's are surrogates, of course, for humanity.
Like old-fashioned ventriloquist's dummies, they give voice to the
pent-up anxieties of their flesh and blood masters, anxieties that
for Oursler signify the overwhelming impact of a mass-media culture
that suffuses and shapes our very being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Introjection,'' the psychological term in the exhibition's
title, refers to the way our personalities unconsciously absorb the
tics and traits of the people and the world around us. Oursler sees
the modern mind as a big sponge, indiscriminately soaking up
snatches of passing conversations, pop jingles and TV soap opera
plotlines, along with more toxic substances like government lies
and a host of free-floating, Hollywood-induced emotional
pathologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mind is always shifting soundtracks,'' says Oursler,
speaking by phone in friendly, low-key cadences from his New York
City studio. ``You might be listening to a song, thinking about a
conversation you had with a friend of yours, and also trying to
write a grocery list. The human mind is capable of all these
incredible kind of combination of things.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, we are what we watch and hear. And what we watch
and hear these days is as likely to control us as we _ our
channel-zapping illusions of omnipotence notwithstanding _ are
likely to control it.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, Oursler is still, to an extent, creating what he terms
``anti-Hollywood art,'' wedding serious intent with tongue-in-cheek
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that he's against the mediums of film and television,
per se. Rather, Oursler believes mainstream commercial
manifestations, i.e. studio movies and network television, have
barely scratched the surface potential of the moving image and its
narrative forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in my 20s, I felt very much that people missed the
point in terms of representing consciousness in the moving image,''
he says, ``that, in fact, they weren't even close,'' with the
conventional cinematic progression of ``close-up, medium-shot,
long-shot. That was just not it. And I was trying to think about
the way that I thought, personally, what people really did with
their eyes, how people saw, how they shifted between memory and
being present.'''
</P>
<P>
   Practically from the first time he picked up a video camera,
Oursler sensed a new way of accessing the surreal strangeness of
life in the TV age, of taking the ghost out of the boob tube and
the cineplex projector.
</P>
<P>
   If, 100 years ago, the motion picture camera became an instant
stand-in for the outward-looking human eye, Oursler believed
videotape _ fluid, intimate and ever-mutable _ had become a smeary
mirror of our messy internal condition.
</P>
<P>
   He also found that video's origins as an amateurish and
spontaneous form of image-making gave it an interactive quality
lacking in big-budget entertainment beamed to passive audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it (video) was a way of just getting into this space
that I'd been peering into for my entire life, but I had never been
able to imagine any access to,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in upstate Nyack, across the Hudson River from New York
City, Oursler grew up in a Roman Catholic family with long literary
and artistic roots. His paternal grandparents were authors and
screenwriters, a great-aunt taught art, and Oursler's father was a
former Reader's Digest editor.
</P>
<P>
   Attending Cal Arts happened serendipitously. Though he knew
almost nothing at the time about the newly minted arts school,
Oursler found its then-remote physical location to be a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were the usual '70s collegiate distractions _ sex,
drugs, ``a lot of naked-by-the-pool'' _ the atmosphere at Cal Arts
was serious and experimental. The faculty included performance
artist Laurie Anderson and Conceptual art godfather John
Baldessari; composer John Cage was an artist-in-residence.
</P>
<P>
   Though Oursler now lives and works in New York, his years spent
in Los Angeles, the world's entertainment capital, clearly marked
his artistic growth. His work is both a critique of mass-culture
technologies and an attempt to go beyond them by fabricating a new
visual grammar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to understand the existing language,
because I think there's a lot of amazing, evolutionary things
happening, both visually, sonically, and having to do with language
and how they all kind of mix together,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Since he first began making art, Oursler's public-access TV
aesthetic has evolved into something slicker, but no less funny or
troubling. Without losing its sense of spontaneous urgency, his
work has exchanged crude cardboard props and low-res imagery in
video installations like ``Son of Oil'' (1982) for sophisticated
multi- channel video, and experiments in newfangled digital
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its cutting-edge immediacy, Oursler's output evinces
his strong interest in, and working knowledge of, the moral and
conceptual issues that have obsessed and bedeviled Western art for
eons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Optics,'' a 1999 mixed-media installation with video
projection, utilizes an old-fashioned camera obscura, miniature
glass devils attached to various light sources (blacklight,
floodlight), and projections of a tiny human figure tumbling
through space to suggest the eternal struggle between light and
dark, good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   The chillingly beautiful installation ``Aperture'' (1998), also
in MOCA's show, arranges small, gray plaster statues (a skull, a
gargoyle, cupids, kissing lovers) in a hypnotic tableau of dead
icons. An LCD video projector, mounted on a tripod, casts the
flickering shape of a scurrying cockroach across this grotesque
``still life,'' symbolically resurrecting its zombified components.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a concoction likely to capture the top Nielsen rating
anytime soon. But it could hearten those who believe visual
techno-culture's best days still lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see (on commercial TV) is what you can expect from
something that has to communicate to like 10 million people at
once,'' Oursler summarizes. ``It has to be something that's fairly,
I wouldn't even say dumbed-down, but it's got to be within a
certain kind of niche. And that's not what art-making is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
What: ``Introjection: Tony Oursler Mid-Career Survey 1976-1999'' &QL; 
Where: Museum of Contemporary Art, 250 South Grand Ave. &QL; 
When: 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesdays through Sundays and 11 a.m. to 8
p.m. Thursdays; through July 9. &QL; 
Admission: $6 adults; $4 students and seniors; free for MOCA
members and children under 12. Admission is free to all every
Thursday from 5 to 8 p.m. Call (213) 626-6222 or access MOCA on the
Web at moca.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
