<HEADER>
A3142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NURSE-AIDES0603-COX     06-02 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSE-AIDES0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nurse aides shortage has hospitals taking action
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They don't have licenses or shiny white smocks or
half the alphabet after their names, but nurse aides are the people
who take care of the infirm and incapacitated. They work in
hospitals, nursing homes and private bedrooms. They help bathe,
dress and feed the patients. They comb their hair, help them out of
bed and take them for walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do the hands-on care, help with all the activities of
daily living,'' said Debra Meador, who coordinates the nurse aide
training program at Miami-Jacobs College. And there aren't nearly
enough of them to go around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a crisis right now,'' she said. ``We've been hearing
from everyone who uses nurse aides, and they all need help.''
</P>
<P>
   The health care system has critical shortages in many
occupations. Hospitals are offering skilled nurses a few thousand
dollars in bonuses to take new jobs or keep their old ones. But the
budgets for nurse aides are such that employers can do little to
lure them than suggest how working with sick people is more
rewarding than asking hungry people if they'd also like fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to not only address them as aides, but also as key
members of our health care team,'' said Meador, whose 76-hour
training program graduates about 600 nurse aides a year. In order
to do that, she has brought together several forums this year to
exchange ideas among those who hire nurse aides and those who train
them.
</P>
<P>
   The forums so impressed the Ohio Department of Health that
Meador will be a keynote speaker this month at a conference in
Columbus. Health department officials aren't aware of any other
cities taking this sort of initiative to increase the supply of
nursing assistants, she said, ``and they want to encourage
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Jacobs also is holding a hospitality day Monday for people
to learn about what nurse aides do. ``It's for people who have
thought about becoming an aide or are thinking about going into
nursing or any other health care field,'' Meador said. ``They can
start as an aide to make sure health care is what they want to do.
It's just a two-week class.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is the inevitable result of separate influences
both increasing the demand for nursing assistants and reducing
their supply. Medicare and managed care plans are shifting patients
from hospitals toward nursing homes and home health care, areas
that use more nurse aides. Pending legislation and regulations
would require still greater ratios of nurse aides to patients. But
at the same time, a full economy gives lower-paid workers more job
options.
</P>
<P>
   Other jobs start looking good to a nurse aide on a short-handed
staff, Meador said. ``They're being pushed to the maximum. We burn
them out. They're overworked and they feel underpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the forum have attacked problems varying from
morale and training to such logistical details as finding
transportation and child care for an overnight shift. They've
talked a lot about ``encouraging and developing the nurse aide as a
person,'' Meador said. Add the right training and mentoring, she
said, and the job takes on the appeal of a career stepping stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special being to go into health care,'' Meador
said, so the least the system can do is recognize the value of
nursing assistants. ``They're the key caregivers. We have to have
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
