<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COASTAL STATE BONANZA MUST NAVIGATE TRICKY SENATE CURRENTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ A generous
<TEXT>
conservation measure that would funnel millions of dollars to
Southern states for environmental projects faces its first test
this month in the Senate, where it could receive a cooler reception
than in the House.
<P>
   Western senators are leery of anything that looks like a federal
land grab and individual lawmakers have a much greater capacity to
stall legislation in the upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not optimistic,'' worried one Florida House member, who
would like to see the measure pass, giving his state its $141
million share.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of the bill, busily preparing for a June 14 vote by
the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee, believe the
Conservation and Reinvestment Act has a good chance of passing this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are further along than we have ever been,'' said a
legislative strategist for Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., chief sponsor
of the measure. ``Members are coming up to her with ideas or
opinions. The question is whether we can reach an agreement that
can make everybody happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the fierce objections of property rights advocates, the $3
billion measure breezed through the House last month, swept along
by the dollars it would steer to oil-producing states and their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana was a big winner, getting a $300 million annual cut,
while Texas came in at $237 million. Mississippi and Alabama fared
well, receiving $78 million and $53 million respectively, while
North Carolina was allocated $46 million and South Carolina $26
million. Every state gets something.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has a few other things going for it in the Senate.
Republican lawmakers would like to have some environmental success
to tout during the fall campaign season and this bill may be their
best bet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi is
a backer though he is not likely to force it through over
substantial GOP opposition. And Alaska, the home state of Energy
Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, would get $167 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to work out a deal, supporters of the measure
are looking for conservative House members who backed the measure _
GOP Rep. Billy Tauzin of Louisiana comes to mind _ to ease the
concerns of Senate property rights warriors.
</P>
<P>
   AMBULANCE CHASING
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Rep. Robert Aderholt believes he has found another way
residents of small-town America are at a disadvantage as compared
to their more urban counterparts when it comes to health care.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican lawmaker introduced a measure that would allow
Medicare to pay for a patient's ambulance ride from an accident or
their home to an ambulatory care center. While trips to hospitals
or emergency rooms are covered, transportation to the newer
outpatient clinics are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many rural residents live a long distance from a hospital but
have access to a local ambulatory medical center,'' said Aderholt.
``This bill would mean quicker treatment to those in a medical
emergency. This bill could save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   HOWLING AT THE MOON
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Democratic members of the Blue Dog coalition have
sniffed around and found an element of campaign finance reform they
can support.
</P>
<P>
   The group that counts a large number of Southern lawmakers as
members is backing a measure that would require so-called stealth
political organizations to fully disclose the source of their
money.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new development, the groups from across the
political spectrum exploit a tax loophole that allows them to
anonymously run campaign attack ads. They have sprung up already in
the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``With millions of dollars involved, citizens deserve to know
who is attempting to sway their opinions and at what price,'' said
Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, a leader of the Blue Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook is bleak for enacting even small campaign
reforms prior to the November election.
</P>
<P>
   COVERT ACTIVITY
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Connie Mack and Bob Graham get all the attention when it
comes to Florida politicians mentioned as candidates for jobs in
the next administration. But it is another lesser known congressman
from the state who might actually end up serving under a new
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Porter Goss, the Republican chairman of the House
Intelligence Committee, is rated a top prospect for director of the
CIA or another national security post if Gov. George W. Bush is
elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   Goss, who has been intimately involved the past few years in
crafting new intelligence policy, concedes he would relish the
opportunity to play a role in putting theory into practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly like to be able to jump over to the
executive branch in one capacity or another to make sure we are
getting the applications we designed,'' said Goss, himself a former
CIA officer.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
