<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3151 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MYOB-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-02 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYOB-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Tues., June 6.) 
FOR USE ON OR AFTER JUNE 6,2000. 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on in tonight's episode of ``M.Y.O.B.,'' Riley, the lead
character/narrator, a feisty teen-ager played by Katharine Towne,
decries her fate at getting stuck on NBC: ``I would've preferred
cable, but, !ital!whatever.'' One sympathizes with her
disillusionment: A cable network would never have frittered away as
funny a sitcom as this in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Created by screenwriter/director Don Roos, ``M.Y.O.B.'' pretty
much cribs the best bits from his hilarious film ``The Opposite of
Sex'' _ the characters played by Christina Ricci (caustic,
seen-it-all blonde teen, here played by Towne) and Lisa Kudrow
(uptight educator, here called Opal and essayed by Lauren Graham).
Roos bolsters his show with very self-conscious but always
effectively amusing narration (that frequently pokes fun at the
conventions of TV storytelling) and takes cheeky swipes at shows
like ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Frasier,'' ``Friends,'' ``Ally McBeal''
and, particularly, ``Law &AMP; Order,'' but his show doesn't seem like
just another media-centric series. It's more a renegade, as
disgusted with the same old same old in sitcoms as you are, and
enjoying tromping around mucking things up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``M.Y.O.B.'s'' main problem lies in its name _ it's a sure bet
you have a troubled title if you have to explain what it means both
in the opening title sequence and a character's monologue (for the
record, ``mind your own business''). Well, that, of course, and the
fact it's not on NBC's fall schedule (and unlikely ever to return
in any fashion, as Graham's already found other work for the fall,
in the WB's dramedy ``Gilmore Girls'').
</P>
<P>
   Here, Riley shows up at Opal's school as part of her search for
her birth mother _ who may or may not be Opal's sister. She got
Opal's name when a buddy hacked a government computer system.
``Your friend Frankie committed a felony,'' Opal sniffs; ``Well,
two, after I finished thanking him,'' the underage Riley deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's all about going for shock value and doing the right
thing in the wrongest way imaginable; she's effective at both. When
she lights a cigarette and Opal chides her, ``If I had just seen
somebody drop dead of a heart attack, I would never smoke again,''
Riley shrugs, ``Well, maybe for me it'll take two.'' She resorts to
blackmail to win Opal the principal's job that's rightfully hers
and, in episode two, outs a peer to save that same job.
</P>
<P>
   Riley dismisses her own show as ``the whole fish-out-of-water,
odd- couple, unrequited-love combo platter you get every night on
every channel.'' True enough, but it's rarely executed as cleverly
as it is by Roos and company. Enjoy it while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The show: ``M.Y.O.B.'' &QL; 
What: Sitcom about an independent teen-ager who lives with an
uptight high-school principal who may or may not be her aunt. &QL; 
The stars: Katherine Towne, Lauren Graham. &QL; 
Where: NBC (Channel 4). &QL; 
When: 9:30 tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
