<SLUG> BC-RADIO-SISTERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWISTED `SISTERS'
</HEADLINE>
  The Dolans  yak it up on public radio 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loyal listeners of public radio are accustomed to moments of
dead air _ those long silences between movements in a symphony or
the announcer's dramatic pause before reading the title of the work
just played.
</P>
<P>
   But listeners should not expect much quiet during the weekly
broadcast of the conversation show ``Satellite Sisters,'' debuting
at 9 this morning on KCRW-FM (89.9).
</P>
<P>
   Except for a possible repeat of that time when the five Dolan
sisters actually choked with laughter simultaneously as Lian Dolan
talked about quaffing an old hotel mini bottle of mouthwash that
had gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were laughing so hard we couldn't talk,'' said Lian, the
35- year-old baby sister who lives in Pasadena and records her part
of the hourlong show in a Los Angeles studio. ``We've tried not to
laugh so hard on the air. We're getting better at it, but sometimes
it just happens. We crack each other up.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which launched April 1 on WNYC-FM in Manhattan, is an
hour of chat among the five siblings and occasionally a close
friend or two who chime in with a meaningful topic or a well-told
anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole idea is that everyone has a story to tell, so it can
be serious like a breast self-exam or it can be just a really funny
story that you'd love to hear at a dinner party,'' Lian said. ``We
had a friend who came in and told a flat-out hilarious story about
finding a woman intruder that broke into her house wearing an
evening gown, sitting on the toilet in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolans are all over the map, figuratively and literally,
having gone different directions in their personal lives and making
their homes in Portland, Ore. (Monica), New York (Sheila and Liz),
Pasadena (Lian) and even Bangkok (Julie). Liz (who quit her
high-powered job at Nike to start her own marketing firm), Lian (a
mother and wanna-be screenwriter) and Julie (a former college
administrator) are the official hosts, uplinked from their
far-flung studios, with Sheila (an elementary school principal) and
Monica (a nurse) calling in about every other week.
</P>
<P>
   Even in their 30s and 40s, they haven't lost that knack for
bantering they perfected as kids while doing the family dishes in
Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Liz brought up the idea for the radio show in 1996 when the
women were on a retreat at a California spa. Before they were out
of the mudbath, all had agreed to do it. WNYC, Oregon Public
Broadcasting and Mudbath Productions produce the show, which is
distributed by Public Radio International.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few constraints on the Satellite Sisters'
subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to come at anything from a personal angle, whether it's
money or health. It has to have a personal beginning with one of us
or one of our guests,'' Lian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of shows that do the top 10 reasons to get life
insurance very well. We don't need to cross those lines. In fact,
in the development stage we played around with a lot of different
kinds of stories and when we did those how to save for college for
your children (topics), we sounded like bad versions of Katie
Couric, so we scrapped that whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Satellite Sisters'' is girl talk that holds the interest of at
least some of the male listeners from its WNYC lead-in, ``Car
Talk.'' It's unscripted comedy without the two-drink minimum. For
over-achieving or overwhelmed women, it's a vicarious girls' night
out over a cup of morning coffee.
</P>
<P>
   They award honorary Satellite Sisterhood to any listeners or
guests who come up with good responses to questions that have no
right or wrong answers, such as, ``Would you rather win a Nobel
Prize or an Oscar?'' and ``Have you ever lied to your doctor and
about what?''
</P>
<P>
   Lian, a mostly stay-at-home mother of two boys _ Brookes, 4, and
Colin, 2 _ says in light of the show's close-to-home perspective
she is ever on guard against sounding even vaguely like a certain
broadcast personality with a reputation for telling too many cute
anecdotes about her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In preproduction meetings, that is our code word for we're not
going there _ `That's a little Kathie Lee,''' Lian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is really more about the relationship you have with
your children than your children,'' she said. ``Most of the
segments are turned around back on me as opposed to telling cute
stories about my kids. It's 'how did this affect me,' and hopefully
there are some broader lessons in that. Yes, it's a worry, the
Kathie Lee moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Satellite Sisters are not worried, however, about the
prospect of getting any on-air competition from their three
brothers, their former tormentors who have been relegated to
occasionally reading the ``Sisters'' closing credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what that would sound like,'' said Lian. ```Hey,
how's it going? Well, good. All right, talk to you later.' It's
laughable, the idea of Satellite Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolans take e-mail at www.satellitesisters.com, their Web
site that will be expanded June 17. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Satellite Sisters.'' &QL; 
What: A new weekly conversation show featuring the five Dolan
sisters. &QL; 
Where: KCRW-FM, 89.9. &QL; 
When: 9 a.m. Sundays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
