<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giant baseballs make Turner Field debut
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So maybe your cutoff should have been the second beer.
</P>
<P>
   But that really was a giant baseball at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans got the first look Friday at the Atlanta Braves'
and New York Yankees' ``All-Star Balls'' _ the first of 500 giant
plastic baseballs to be displayed throughout the city for Major
League Baseball's All-Star Game in July.
</P>
<P>
   The six-foot balls were unveiled during a pregame ceremony
Friday and will be on display in Monument Plaza in front of the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball promotion, which is patterned after the highly
successful Cows on Parade exhibit in Chicago last year, will run
for the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   So far, dozens of businesses have plunked down big bucks to buy
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Patron sponsors, at $27,000 each, include Georgia-Pacific Corp.,
Southern Co., Worldspan, iXL Enterprises, Bell South Corp., UPS,
PepsiCo Inc., Delta Air Lines, Bank of America, Priceline.com, and
the Sherwin -Williams Co.
</P>
<P>
   Patron sponsors get three balls to decorate and display _ one
each for an American and National League team and one to decorate
any way they want.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, sponsors get tickets to the All-Star Game and other
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We verbally have commitments from about seven more, but we
don't count them unless we have their checks in the bank,'' said
Bill Howard, vice president of tourism and public relations for the
Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau, which is also a patron
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Others can purchase individual balls for $5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those have been sold. Buyers include MARTA, Marriott
International, Visa International, the Buckhead Life Group and Saks
Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Denmark, a furniture retailer, plans to display its
ball in front of its showroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an American and I'm still trying to get into the
sport,'' said John Querl, corporate controller and a native of
Zambia. ``I think it's a neat idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to have a city full of baseballs,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
