A3163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRLINES0603-COX     06-02 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airline merger reports rising
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Talk of airline mergers heated up Friday amid reports
American Airlines has had exploratory talks about buying Northwest
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The unconfirmed reports follow last week's move by United
Airlines to buy US Airways for $4.3 billion in cash, pending what
is expected to be a tough antitrust review by federal regulators in
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe a United-US Airways deal will force
United's top rivals, American and Atlanta-based Delta, to pursue
their own acquisitions or lose national market share _ especially
in crucial East Coast markets.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Delta has made no move. But an American-Northwest
marriage could clear the way for it to make another run at
Continental Airlines, which Delta tried unsuccessfully to buy in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest currently owns a 51 percent voting stake in
Continental but likely would have to divest it before a sale to
American, leaving Continental free to entertain other offers.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman Clay McConnell declined comment on the
American-Northwest reports.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I would reiterate that Delta is monitoring the
competitive situation closely in order to ensure our interests are
protected and that Delta will be successful regardless of the
industry environment.''
</P>
<P>
   A Minneapolis television station and Dow Jones News Service
reported that American and Northwest executives have had
preliminary talks. Spokesmen for both carriers declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones said it was unclear whether the talks would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest stock jumped on the reports, gaining $6.37 1/2 to
close at $35.43 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   If the United-US Airways deal survives regulatory review and
labor hurdles, United would become dramatically stronger along the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   That would put pressure on both Delta and American and could
trigger a consolidation among the top six airlines, some analysts
believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a Soviet planner point of view, we think the most logical
airline combinations are United/US Airways, Delta/Continental and
American/Northwest,'' Salomon Smith Barney analyst Brian Harris
said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts think such a massive consolidation has little
chance of government approval.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe American may court Northwest simply to give
anti-trust regulators more of a reason to block the United-US
Airways deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like a copycat move to bring out more regulatory
heat,'' Merger Insight analyst Tom Burnett told Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
