<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 4, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ISSUE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lurking just below the surface
in the campaign of 2000 is the issue of personal privacy.
Democratic and Republican pollsters both say it is a sleeper issue.
By Richard J. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-REVIEW (United Nations) _ For years the United
States has classified some countries, like Iraq and North Korea, as
``rogue states.'' Now, as the world becomes more democratic _ more
than 60 percent of countries have elected leaders _ something more
complicated enters the political lexicon. Call them ``rogue
democracies.'' By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   HEIGHT-VANITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ A study appearing this month in
the American Statistical Association Proceedings reports that many
Americans appear to lie about their height. Not weight or age,
though they lie about that, too. But height? Why? By Eric
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   DETERRENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ For nearly half a century the Cold
War world's tense stability was built on a simple bit of political
philosophy. Nicknamed, appropriately, MAD, for Mutual Assured
Destruction, it held that the leader of a country advanced enough
to build nuclear weapons would never actually use them if he was
assured his nation would also be obliterated by his enemy. As
nuclear technology proliferates, however, the nuclear equation is
becoming more complicated, and a new view of deterrence is growing
rapidly in importance. By Michael Oreskes.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GINGRICH-REVIEW (Washington) _ As Gov. George W. Bush rolls
out policy address after policy address, congressional Republicans
are watching in admiration as he does what Newt Gingrich, Trent
Lott and the self-effacing J. Dennis Hastert could not: win a fresh
hearing for ideas cherished by true-blue conservatives. It's the
Newt-less revolution. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The ``I Love You'' bug,
allegedly launched by a Philippines computer student with too much
time on his hands, touched off a cyber-flu season. More than 29
variants have emerged so far, including diabolical derivatives with
names like ``NewLove'' and ``Resume _ Janet Simons.'' The question
is, what's love got to do with it? Quite a lot, perhaps. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-ROCK&AMP;ROLL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Perhaps it was inevitable
that as the Internet began permeating the culture, the techie
language that was once confined to textbooks and instruction
manuals would begin to sound beautiful, or at least pretty enough
to sing. Physicists, who among other things invented the World Wide
Web, have been quick to realize that their lexicon is no longer too
obscure for pop songs. By James Gantz.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
