<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV04-B     06-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 4, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are that you've seen part of the dandy advertising
campaign for the U.S. Mint's new gold-colored dollar coin, mostly
on television. A slyly animated visage of George Washington,
familiar from the $1 bill, pops up in a variety of modern
situations and urges you to treat those new Sacagawea dollars just
like any other coin. ``What are you waiting for? It's money. So use
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But have you seen the coin itself? If only the marketing plan
were as good as the ads.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how few people have had one of those new Sacagawea
dollars in their hands, especially in New England. The advertising
campaign is half over and the golden coins still are hard to find
anywhere but in a stamp machine or at the Post Office.
</P>
<P>
   Banks no longer have difficulty ordering them from their
regional Federal Reserve Banks. But consumers tend to stash the
ones they are given on dresser tops and drawers, to buy them in
rolls only for special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The new coin was designed to replace the Susan B. Anthony dollar
coin, first issued in 1979. which was one of the more peculiar
blunders of the presidency of Jimmy Carter. The coin was virtually
indistinguishable from a quarter by size or weight or color.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Susie'' was introduced at a time of raging inflation
(remember the hapless William G. Miller, who was chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board?) and quickly came to symbolize Carter's
inability to manage the currency at any level. Consumers resisted
using it at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   The new dollar coin has none of these defects. It's heavier than
the quarter, bigger, thicker, easy to distinguish by feel in the
pocket. It's bright gold in color, at least when it's new, thanks
to its brass-manganese cladding.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it affords a good civics lesson. The coin shows the
shining face of Sacagawea, carrying her infant son upon her back.
The Shoshone woman guided the Lewis and Clark expedition across the
mountains and to the Pacific Ocean from 1804 to 1806.
</P>
<P>
   Pedants, too, have had their fun with the coin. No likeness of
the native American woman survives. Lewis and Clark always spelled
her name with a G, but most persons pronounce it as if it were
spelled with a J. She almost certainly carried her baby in a sling
across her chest.
</P>
<P>
   But Sacagawea remains one of America's most durable symbols of
cross-cultural cooperation, and a famous working mother to boot _ a
fitting symbol for these times. The coin itself is an undisputed
success.
</P>
<P>
   Its distribution is another story.
</P>
<P>
   The initial roll-out took place in January. Commercial banks,
which ordinarily would have been instrumental, asked for a repreive
while they returned the excess currency they they had built up in
anticipation of Y2K. They didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the US Mint proceeded to ship coins via registered mail
to 2,900 Wal-Mart stores across the country, in hopes of putting
the coin directly into the retail cash drawer.
</P>
<P>
   The banks were furious. And soon it was apparent that the coins
were going straight out of the retail cash drawer into the dresser
drawer. Consumers were hoarding the bright new dollars, stacking
them on window sills or giving them as gifts. They were not going
into circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint has continued to pump the new coins out. Some 650
million have been shipped to date. Banks no longer have trouble
ordering them. But many don't bother.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Sacagawea dollar is making headway, especially
as a universal token for machine transactions. The Mass Transit
Authority of New York City is giving change from fare card machines
in dollar coins. The Chicago Transit Authority has eliminted paper
in its fare boxes; passengers must change their bills for coins.
The Washington subway may yet convert to dollar coins.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, which at 85 cents still has the cheapest mass transit of
any big city in the nation, may go to a $1 fare in the fall; look
for the golden dollar to make its debut then. Meanwhile, automated
car washes, toll roads, vending machines and airport luggage carts
are rapidly converting to four-tube changers to handle the new
coins.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint expects to pump out more than a billion $1 coins this
year, more than all the ``Susies'' shipped in the past 21 years. No
federal agency has been more ``reinvented'' than the Mint: it has a
chief technology officer, strategic business units for circulation,
numismatics (coin collecting) and protection, a wicked good web
site (www.usmint.gov) and a $43 million advertising budget,
financed by the savings on the $1 coin.
</P>
<P>
   So why the stumbling? European nations and Canada all have
introduced the equivalent of the dollar coin. In each case they
deliberately withdrew the counterpart banknote. The coin quickly
and completely replaced the bill.
</P>
<P>
   No such move is contemplated by the US Treasury Department,
which administers the Mint. The reason is determined opposition
from a coalition of lobbying interests known as ``Save the
Greenback.''
</P>
<P>
   One big backer is Massachusetts Crane Paper Co., which makes the
high-tech paper on which US currency is printed. Another is the
zinc lobby. Much of its mining and fabrication business is located
in Vice President Al Gore's home state of Tennesee, including a
company which has a lucrative contract to supply blanks for the
penny. The penny is 97.5 percent zinc. The dollar coin, on the
other hand, is 88.5 percent copper.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminate the penny to make a place in cash registers for the
Sacagawea dollar? It makes sense. But the Treasury is right to
fully support demand for the dollar bill for the forseeable future.
The management of the currency is a highly-charged emotional issue.
As George Washington says in those ads, ``I still look good on
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
