<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STOCK-CHARTS-2TAKES-N     06-02 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-CHARTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PATTERNS HIDDEN IN MARKET SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, the craggy peaks and sharp precipices of the
common stock chart have redefined the American landscape. Charts
flash on television screens and computer monitors, inspire animated
debate and wild expectations, and become minor obsessions. Anyone
who follows charts cannot follow them casually; too much is at
stake. But anyone who follows them closely can be baffled by their
vast swings, unexplained moves and dizzying plunges.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, professional commentators would argue, these
movements are hardly arbitrary. Among the reasons they offer for
the ups and downs: changes in interest rates, shifts in foreign
policy, technological innovations. And theories abound for how to
predict the fate of a company's stock chart.
</P>
<P>
   Investors like Warren Buffett have championed ``value''
investing, in which a company's cash flow, future earnings and
assets are rigorously analyzed; stock prices are expected to
reflect a rational analysis of value.
</P>
<P>
   One interpretation of stock market behavior, known as the random
walk theory, has less faith in reason: Prices randomly stumble
around a perceived value like a drunk looking for a lost coin; no
past price can tell us anything about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Other theories argue that the future can indeed be anticipated
by examining past activity through computer analyses of the rate of
stock sales, or calculations of the averages of stock prices over
the last 200 days, or examinations of seasonal price patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, another set of techniques appeals to the
fundamental hope that in the bewildering movements of the
marketplace, a deeper order is being revealed. It is known as
``technical analysis.'' As the Internet has turned the market into
a mass market, technical analysis, once the domain of professional
traders, has entered the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Software programs like Omnitrader and Internet sites like
www.barchart.com bring the approach home. Television discussions of
``support levels,'' and ``consolidation,'' ``break outs'' and
``corrections,'' have made the vocabulary as familiar as a weather
man's references to low-pressure systems, pollen count and
wind-chill factors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the theory of technical analysis, nothing needs to
be considered aside from a chart showing price movements and
volumes of trades. Forget profit statements, business plans and
inflation figures; ignore whether the company makes widgets or lays
fiber optic cable. Investors, the theory believes, have already
come in contact with all these bits of knowledge, reacted to them,
judged their impact on other investors, and acted upon them. The
result is a stock's price; and the intensity of commitment to that
price is measured in the volume of trades.
</P>
<P>
   Technical analysts examine charts, draw geometric shapes,
connect points and mark off familiar patterns. Each pattern has a
meaning in the analyst's lexicon, providing a glimpse of what might
happen next. Some technical analysts, having seen a promise of
pictorial order, go further, arguing that there are even more basic
rules governing these shapes, rules that grow out of what they
consider basic laws of nature and geometry; some get even more
fantastical, invoking the principles of astrology. These latter
hypotheses do not seem to have a major following, but few traders
work without using some of the techniques of technical analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In one classic text, ``Technical Analysis of Stock Trends,''
(seventh edition, 1997, St. Lucie Press), Robert D. Edwards and
John Magee trace technical analysis back to a set of ideas first
advanced a hundred years ago by Charles H. Dow, a founder of Dow
Jones &AMP; Co. The market, they explain, moves in longterm trends in
which stocks either rise or fall; those trends are subdivided into
other secondary or tertiary trends in which retreats and advances
also take place.
</P>
<P>
   The entire effect, they suggest, is like the ebb and flow of the
tides, punctuated by individual waves washing against the shore,
whose own surfaces are, in turn, shaped by more chaotic ripples.
The goal of analysis is to identify places where the tide will
change.
</P>
<P>
   Charts can help, analysts argue, if their pictorial language is
properly understood. These patterns tend to have geometric names
like a ``right-angle broadening formation'' or pictorial names like
``falling wedge.'' A chart might, for example, create a ``head and
shoulders formation,'' which is composed of three jagged hills, the
central one (the head) reaching the highest point. These patterns
and scores of others can best be understood as maps of human
behavior, revealing ways in which investors act and react.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consider one fundamental example: the ``head and shoulders''
pattern. When a stock's price is rising, analysts argue, the
pattern is almost always followed by a reversal. Why? Imagine a
stock moving from $10 to $12 and back, forming a ``shoulder.'' It
then rises again to $15 before falling again to $10, forming a
``head.'' Finally another shoulder forms, resembling the first. Why
should this mean that the stock will eventually fall from $10?
</P>
<P>
   Well, think of the behavior this pattern portrays. The first
rise is energetic, with heavy volume, but the fall back from $12
reveals some doubts. Some owners cautiously sell off a bit, but
others may hold on as the first shoulder is formed. The head
represents yet another burst of support. But though the stock
reaches higher, the trading has less volume. Conviction is limited
and the stock drops again.
</P>
<P>
   Two such rises and falls might be thought inconsequential, but
by the time the stock rises yet again, worry becomes palpable. The
faith in the stock cannot be supported. Finally, the stock begins
its extended fall, plunging below $10, which is picturesquely
referred to as the ``neckline.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty shown in this pattern might be affected by a
company's fortunes, or the state of the economy, or changes in the
marketplace, but according to the theory, interpreting the pattern
requires no knowledge of any of this. ``Head and shoulders'' is a
pattern caused by conflict; it reveals a gradual defeat of bullish
optimism. And the pattern has the same meanings for any stock being
considered.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of analysis then goes even further: rules not only
predict broad patterns, they also provide guidance about the extent
of a rise or fall. For analysts, charts almost seem to follow
aesthetic principles. For example, analysts suggest that in the
``head and shoulders'' pattern, the second shoulder will tend to
mirror the first, and the rise of the ``head'' will tend to be
matched by the extent of the fall after the stock drops below the
``neckline.'' There is something uncanny about such assertions;
they are much more difficult to justify as laws of human behavior.
But they reveal a determination to find order in the midst of
seeming chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that these sorts of rules have so many exceptions
that they can hardly be relied upon; that patterns are best seen in
retrospect, when they are no longer helpful; that analysts' ideas
can end up becoming self-fulfilling prophecies. And indeed, while
investment banks and trading houses have technical analysts on
staff, strict analysis is generally tempered by considerations of
other factors.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort to find pictorial order seems almost universal.
The Japanese, for example, have used a 300-year-old method of
charting known as ``candlesticks,'' made familiar in the West after
the analyst Steve Nison examined them in books like ``Beyond
Candlesticks: New Japanese Charting Techniques Revealed'' (1994,
Wiley). Instead of just marking the range of a day's trading with a
single vertical line, as on Western charts, the Japanese create
candlesticks: small rectangles whose ends represent the stock's
opening and closing prices. If the price fell during the day, the
candlestick is darkened (and is called a ``long black body''); if
the price rose, it is left unshaded (and is called a ``long white
body''). In candlestick charts, technical analysis becomes almost
poetic, with patterns named ``morning star,'' ``hanging man'' and
``falling window.''
</P>
<P>
   But if charts reveal hidden patterns, some believe there are
even deeper esoteric patterns guiding the charts. In ``The
Psychology of Technical Analysis'' (1993, Irwin), which The
Financial Times of London said would ``entertain and intrigue keen
investors,'' Tony Plummer, a British trader, argues that the ebb
and flow of human activity actually follows a pattern that
resembles the curve of the Nautilus shell. That curve, which
expands outward without changing its shape, recurs throughout the
natural world in various organic forms (pine cones, sunflowers,
tree leaves). It is an image of a certain form of growth that,
Plummer suggests, also applies to the large-scale actions of the
marketplace. He argues that a properly drawn Nautilus curve _ and
it is by no means easy to find the proper curve _ will intersect
with the stock's highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   Major turning points in stock charts, other theorists have also
argued, occur at intervals determined by the Golden Mean _ a ratio,
approximately equal to 1.618, that also determines the shape of the
Nautilus curve.
</P>
<P>
   Similar arguments are made in ``Fibonacci Applications and
Strategies for Traders'' by Robert Fischer (1993, Wiley) and are
regularly described in survey texts like ``Technical Analysis of
the Financial Markets'' by John J. Murphy (1999, New York Institute
of Finance). The quest for order would now seem complete: charts
not only are rife with symmetries and patterns, but they also
reflect a ratio that is considered one of the most beautiful in the
natural world.
</P>
<P>
   It is, perhaps, too much to believe, that the cumulative effect
of individual decisions to buy and sell would create such hidden
patterns. But the attempt to make sense of the chart is no
different than the attempt to explain any complex system. In fact,
push the notion of hidden pattern a bit further and chart reading
can even turn religious: The stock analyst Perry J. Kaufman devotes
10 pages to financial astrology in an otherwise scrupulous
theoretical text, ``Trading Systems and Methods'' (1998, Wiley), a
method few analysts would confess to using.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these assertions are not widely accepted; they are
extensions of the theory, not exceptions to it. Technical analysis
has its believers and detractors, but it is an unusual attempt to
make sense of an exceedingly mysterious phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the market may be created by its participants but it
is also independent of them; it reflects their will but also
affects their will; its participants believe they are free, but
their actions fall into familiar patterns. The chart is not just
the record of a company's share price; it is the record of attempts
to guess the future. It is a trace of human behavior. So what are
we seeing when we examine these charts? Images of ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
