<HEADER>
A3170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RUN-WOMEN-ENDURANCE-H     06-02 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WOMEN-ENDURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WOMEN RUNNERS SAY AGE IS NO LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim; ATTN: Ark., N.Y.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM REYNOLDS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If they were baseball players, their arms
probably would be showing signs of wearing out. Basketball players,
their explosiveness may be dwindling. Football players, slower and
more vulnerable to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Distance runners, though, appear to be of a different makeup,
especially when it comes to determining the best years of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   They are not at their athletic peak at 19 or 23 or 28. The
performances of world-class runners indicate that turning 30 is not
the bridge to the end, but rather the beginning of the best years
of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that people don't understand about
running,'' Lynn Jennings, who won her eighth Freihofer's Run for
Women championship in 1998 at the age of 37, said before finishing
third here last year. ``It's a sport that tends to reward maturity.
It's not like all the other sports. We keep getting stronger as we
go, and if we stay healthy, we can compete at the highest level
that much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Freihofer's Run, which will be contested on the
streets of Albany for the 22nd consecutive year on Saturday, has
its share of elite runners between the ages of 20 and 25, with
24-year-old Blake Phillips-Russell and 25-year-old Jennifer Rhines
headlining that list.
</P>
<P>
   However, four other women on most lists of runners expected to
contend for this year's championship were born in the 1960s. Libbie
Hickman is 35, Sylvia Mosqueda is 33, Anne Marie Lauck is 31, and
Donna Garcia is 32.
</P>
<P>
   And each appears to be just on the cusp of her running prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in their 30s and they're still among the best out
there,'' said Ryan Lamppa of the United States Track and Field
Association. ``There's no limit to what a lot of them can do.''
</P>
<P>
   So, is the thirtysomething set of women distance runners in this
country like fine wine? Do they get better with age?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can keep getting better every year, if you do things
intelligently and take care of yourself,'' said Hickman, who is the
favorite in the Freihofer's Run. ``All you do each year is keep
getting stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Goddard-Kenah, now 29, won her first Freihofer's title
here last year. She is not in this year's field because of an
injury, but she knows that her window of opportunity to win the
Freihofer's should remain open for several more years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she maintains that her best years may be four, five,
perhaps even six years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the way it is with women. We get stronger and even
faster as we age,'' Goddard-Kenah said. ``The more years of
distance running you have under your belt, the easier it gets. With
age you can run more mileage, and that just makes you stronger
every year, so what you do one year just keeps paying off down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Freihofer's race director George Regan understands that runners
like Jennings have helped make his race what it is, but that
runners like 1997 champion Elva Dryer and Goddard-Kenah are the
future stars of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't even hit their peak yet,'' Regan said. ``That's
amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Goddard-Kenah, like most of the other elite distance runners in
this country, says she logs many more miles per week in her
training now than she did when she was younger, and said that the
increase in mileage has been a key to her longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies indicate that a teen-aged female who logs more
than 40 miles per week regularly over an extended period can hurt
her long-term running potential, for the simple reason that asking
so much from a young body can take too much out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Evans, who chairs the Nutrition, Metabolism and
Exercise Laboratory at the University of Arkansas, published a
report that found wide-ranging differences in opinion when it comes
to peak athletic performance. Some sports psychologists quoted in
the study say the typical peak age for athletes is 18. Others say
it comes around 33. That alone would seem to prove that ``peaking''
is an inexact science.
</P>
<P>
   His report says, in part, that sprinters tend to have more
fast-twitch muscle fibers that give them explosiveness, strength
and quickness. Distance runners generally have more slow-twitch
muscle fibers, which the report says take longer to deteriorate.
Thus, the increased longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long I'll be able to stay at that peak once I
get there,'' Goddard-Kenah said. ``I just know I'm not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Extreme amounts of mileage done before the body is finished
growing and maturing makes it more prone to injuries, and those
injuries take their toll later in life, Hickman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take care of yourself when you're younger,''
Hickman said. ``Knock on wood, I've been injury-free for my whole
career, and that may be because I increased, increased, increased
my mileage slowly. It only makes sense to do it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she's a better runner now than she was a decade ago,
Hickman didn't hesitate. No question about it, she said, adding
that she has no plans to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can use the same speed I had as a 25-year-old,'' Hickman
said. ``Now my endurance is so good that I can continue it. When I
was younger I couldn't keep that speed up, except maybe in 1,500s.
My speed for 5ks and 10ks now is good enough to be competitive
internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the American female running greats, Mary Slaney, hasn't
been as fortunate as Hickman in terms of injury prevention. Slaney
has said she has lost count of the number of surgeries that have
been performed on her 41-year-old body, but knows the number is
more than 20. Still, Slaney said at the 1996 Olympic Trials that
even then, at 37, she was running as well as she had at any time in
a career that has spanned nearly a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Salazar, the former marathon world-record holder who
helps advise Slaney now as part of his duties with Nike, said
Slaney's obsession with competition is what helped her survive
those injury-laden years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say that she's like a racehorse,'' Salazar said.
``She can just run herself out, and when you have little nagging
injuries, that can cost you, especially at her age.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaney said she does not believe in chronological age, instead
clinging to the axiom that you truly are only as old as you feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as long as you're interested and feel good about
yourself and what you are doing,'' Slaney said before the 1996
Olympic Trials for the Games in Atlanta, ``there isn't a reason to
stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
