<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3172 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BLUECROSS-FREEMA     06-02 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BLUECROSS-FREEMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPPING AWAY AT THE COMMUNITY OF NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, June 3, and thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By JOSHUA B. FREEMAN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few may have noticed, but last week saw another step in the
dismantling of New York's pioneering social benefit system. Eliot
Spitzer, the state attorney general, announced that he would no
longer oppose converting Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield to a
for-profit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, various government and nonprofit health,
housing and cultural institutions have been turned into
money-making entities outside of public control. Slowly, the city
and state are giving away a civic patrimony that earlier
generations of New Yorkers built with their money, imagination and
political will.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, New York hospitals founded what became Empire Blue
Cross to ensure themselves steady income while giving people a way
to finance hospitalization. Individuals were the first subscribers,
but the plan took off after it began signing up groups of workers.
Unions, by demanding that employers provide coverage, helped fuel
Blue Cross' meteoric growth after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, some Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans in other
states began turning themselves into for-profit companies. They
argued that because of increased competition, they needed access to
private capital and they needed to shed mandated responsibilities,
like accepting all applicants or charging all customers the same
fee. In some states, officials responded by allowing them to
privatize but forcing them to finance nonprofit foundations, a
route Empire Blue Cross is now trying to take.
</P>
<P>
   Empire Blue Cross has long been mired in problems, stemming from
both mismanagement and competition that picked off its healthiest
customers, leaving the organization with the sickest, most
expensive clients. (Until recently, state regulations required Blue
Cross to accept applicants that other plans could reject.)
</P>
<P>
   These problems are serious, but they can be addressed without
privatization. For more than 60 years, Blue Cross has acted not for
the benefit of stockholders, but for its customers. Isn't that
model still important? A large nonprofit insurer provides a
benchmark for private competitors and an alternative for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over privatization is not unique. In 1996,
debate raged over Co-op Village, a complex of cooperative
apartments on the Lower East Side, which had originally been
financed with government subsidies and union loans. After fierce
debate, residents decided to abandon rules that required them, upon
moving, to sell their shares back to the cooperative at the
original price. Residents have profited from this plan, but the
conversion has reduced opportunities for other working and
middle-class families. In 1996, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sold off the
city's broadcast facilities. A public uproar forced the sale of
WNYC radio to a nonprofit foundation, but the municipal television
station went into private hands.
</P>
<P>
   Once public and quasi-public assets slip out of public control,
it is almost impossible to retrieve or replace them. While
privatizing any one might seem reasonable in the face of problems,
the cumulative effect is to destroy a web of institutions that
helped keep New York City livable and attractive during decades
when many cities drastically declined. In good times, public
services and safety nets do not seem so important. In bad times, it
is too late to get them back.
</P>
<P>
   (Joshua B. Freeman, a history professor at Queens College, is
the author of ``Working-Class New York.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features.
</P>
