<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-NASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC MAKER WANTS TO FOCUS ON PHOTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Graham Nash took a quick glance at his photos before beaming a
top-of-the-line, professional smile at those who were waiting to
meet him.
</P>
<P>
   He was late and he was limping, but he owned the room as soon as
he walked into it.
</P>
<P>
   Star power. Nash uses it to connect. He makes connecting look
easy, and he makes it look like fun. He's not in Seattle to talk
about his star power, however.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to focus on his photographs. They're at the Benham
Studio Gallery, along with Elliott Landy's rock portraits, through
June 24 in honor of the opening of the Experience Music Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a gallery to show you what you do,'' Nash said. In
his case, of course, a gallery shows him a small part of what he
does. He knows that people who hail him on the street aren't
smiling because they love his images. They're responding to Crosby,
Stills, Nash &AMP; Young, especially recently, after a highly
successful reunion tour.
</P>
<P>
   He could point out that he's been taking photographs longer than
he's been making music, but usually he doesn't bother. He doesn't
have to. He's a real deal in photographic circles, and the exhibit
demonstrates why.
</P>
<P>
   His crisp, black-and-white photos are offbeat portraits of his
friends and bizarre slices of daily life, printed with exquisite
attention to tonal detail. Nash is a pioneer in digital printmaking
technology. In 1991, he and his friend Mac Holbert founded Nash
Editions in Southern California. It's a fine-art digital
printmaking studio whose clients range from David Hockney to Olivia
Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an unlisted phone number and don't advertise,''
Holbert said. ``We only work on small editions. You have to really
want to work with us to find us.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbert looked sympathetic as Nash declined a chair. Nash broke
both legs last year in a boating accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got rods and pins and plates and screws in this leg,''
Nash said, looking down. ``It's like owning a small railroad.
Bacteria love metal. If you get an infection, they camp out
there.'' Sounds gruesome, but Nash is certain antibiotics will soon
restore his once-confident stride.
</P>
<P>
   Old rock 'n' rollers aren't noted for their confident strides.
It's a burn-out business. At 58, married for 23 years and the
father of three children, Nash looks not just healthier but sexier
than he did in his dissolute prime.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1960s he was bone thin and often stoned. According
to the photographic record, he was also self-absorbed, a quality
that has disappeared completely. Today he looks pleased to be on
planet Earth and curious to see what will happen next.
</P>
<P>
   Nash moved to the rear gallery to see Landy's portraits of rock
superstars in New York from 1967 to 1969. Between the two shows
there is only one overlap: Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   Nash and Landy are big Dylan fans, with Nash having the greater
claim, because he insists Dylan is not just a seminal songwriter
but a great singer. ``Dylan has 40 different ways to sing a phrase
and can kill you with each one,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's portrait of Dylan is lovely, but Landy's are a world:
Dylan looking like a young Amish father with his toddler son; Dylan
buried behind a piano; Dylan smiling a completely unguarded,
personal smile (later the cover of ``Nashville Skyline''); and
Dylan standing on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Landy, 58, has fabulous black-and-white shots of Jimi Hendrix,
The Band and Janis Joplin. He has even better color shots of Procol
Harum, Joplin and John Lee Hooker, the last bathed in acid-yellow
light and wearing a snappy, peach-colored suit.
</P>
<P>
   His photos became famous enough for Landy to receive the
ultimate 1960s compliment: the rumor he didn't exist at all. There
was even evidence: His name is an anagram of Dylan's (Landy/Dylan),
proving that Dylan must have been behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Nash was struck by one of Landy's black-and-white shots of Jim
Morrison, a blurred moment in which Morrison seems to float in
front of the microphone. ``Whatever Jim was, it's there, man,''
Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   Nash and Landy suddenly seemed to realize that they were
surrounded by a host of dead friends' portraits. ``We're lucky be
be standing here talking to each other after all that went on,''
Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's photos couldn't be more different. Although there are a
few rock stars in evidence (David Crosby, Joni Mitchell, Dylan),
the photos aren't about character, soul or personal magnetism.
They're about light and how it plays with the bizarre loose ends of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Landy's black-and-white tones are often muddy, but Nash's are
exquisite, with depths in the darks and volume in the lights. He
never arranges anything or sets up a shot. ``Life is weird enough
without me trying to make it weirder.''
</P>
<P>
   One print is a window he shot from below, with a rubber chicken
hung in its center as decoration. The tones are magisterial, but
the content is tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Nash disagrees, finding no fault with the anonymous decorator's
taste. ``Anybody who hangs a rubber chicken in a window is OK by
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A computer program called Photoshop gave him the print of
Crosby's face with his eyes closed. At the time he was listening to
the first playback of ``Suite: Judy Blue Eyes.'' Crosby looks a
little like the melting-mercury bad guy in ``Terminator 2,'' but
more blissful and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all blissful and sweet now, aren't we?'' Nash asked,
grinning. ``I know I am. I live with my family in Hawaii with no
address. To get there you take Power House Road and turn right
after the 25th telephone pole. It's paradise. Who'd complain about
that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
