<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3175 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TV-FASHION-SEX-$ADV04     06-02 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FASHION-SEX-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSING DOWN THOSE TRENDY `CITY' GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps because I am not from New York, and even now do not live
there but rather arrive each morning by train through the aqua
light of Grand Central, then up the Vanderbilt stairs and into the
glare and slow-moving traffic of 43rd Street, I am more apt to
identify with writers who saw the city from afar.
</P>
<P>
   The one who described New York best, especially that sense of
how easy it is to feel out of the game even before one has a chance
to be in it, was Joan Didion. She wrote, ``When I first saw New
York I was 20, and it was summertime, and I got off a DC-7 at the
old Idlewild temporary terminal in a new dress which had seemed
very smart in Sacramento, but seemed less smart already, even in
the old Idlewild temporary terminal.''
</P>
<P>
   That line, from an essay called ``Goodbye to All That,'' which
originally appeared in 1967 in The Saturday Evening Post, came back
to me the other afternoon as I sat in my kitchen near the Hudson
previewing the new episode of the HBO series ``Sex and the City,''
which begins its third season Sunday night. It stars the perky
Sarah Jessica Parker and is based on columns Candace Bushnell wrote
in the mid-1990s for The New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   I watched not only the latest installment, which has Carrie
(played by Parker) and her gal pals tripping off to Staten Island
in their mules and tube tops to see a bunch of fire department
hunks wiggle around in their underwear at a pin-up contest, but
also all of the first season and most of the second. I cooked a ham
and made a strawberry pie.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell isn't a great writer. She doesn't have Didion's range
or Fran Lebowitz's wit, and the world she described _ often,
admittedly, against deadline _ would be unrecognizable to anyone
who had never spent evenings at Elaine's or in junior lofts
wondering why men didn't realize just how wonderful the eligible
women of New York are.
</P>
<P>
   But Bushnell was in the right place at the right time. She
picked up early on the strange gulf that existed between men and
women who were perhaps too smart or selective for their own good,
but who, in any case, could not see themselves sleeping with
someone who didn't have money or beauty, or at least some
incredible ability in the sack to make it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this picture of Manhattan singles warily advancing
toward one another with no thought of building nice stable
relationships _ who cares about that? _ was both sad and funny. But
by the end of the '90s, with films like Neil LaBute's ``In the Co.
of Men'' taking an even colder view of modern romance, Bushnell's
``downtown babes'' and Gucci-clad ``modelizers'' had begun to seem
almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Until someone from HBO sent me the tapes, I had paid scant
attention to the television version of ``Sex and the City,'' an
oversight that might be construed as derelict on my part,
considering that the show has been widely praised for being up on
fashion trends. But I'm wary when the mainstream media calls a show
like ``Sex and the City'' influential, then cites examples of
trends it started, without evidence. It's the same concern I have
whenever the fashion elite get behind a single look or declare that
jewelry is out: the influence rarely travels as far from the center
as one might be led to believe by the fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't flip my skirt when people who work for fashion
companies told me they had successfully placed products, like
handbags, on the show, and hoped to do more in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Watching an earlier episode in which the show's four principal
characters struggle with their Vuitton bags as they board the
Hamptons Jitney, I can see how a little logo flogging might be good
for both Vuitton's business and establishing the characters'
priorities. But it's hard to think that a series that purports to
reflect hip New York is doing itself any good by showing stuff you
can get anywhere. Even I still expect New York to be emphatic when
it comes to knowing what's smart.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, though, the clothes selected by Patricia Field,
the show's costume coordinator, reflect what's happening in New
York and in fashion, and jibe as well with the characters'
personalities. In the season opener, the gimlet-eyed Samantha Jones
(played by Kim Cattrall) swans into a local firehouse wearing
turquoise fur and a leopard slip for some personal 911 relief from
Ricky, her latest slab of honey-coated beef. Ricky's sweet, but as
usual, Samantha isn't interested in what's between his ears.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene from next week's episode, Samantha discovers that the
stock trader she's just had sex with buys his suits in the boy's
department at Bloomingdale's. When the little guy counters with a
stiff insult, you get the feeling that Samantha has finally met her
match.
</P>
<P>
   The dopey art dealer Charlotte York (played by Kristin Davis)
turns up in chic strapless numbers, including a tube top (big this
summer), while Miranda Hobbes, the lawyer played by Cynthia Nixon,
sticks with her minimalist look. Gold hoop earrings are the most
conspicuous accessory, but this is not a surprise. They've been
making a comeback for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's wardrobe is something of a disappointment, or maybe the
fuzzy coats she has on over her clingy babe attire are simply a
reflection that she's still dragging her breakup with Big around
like a cord of wood. She seems in a funk, and not even the hint of
dirty mischief with a politician, for whom she thoughtfully dresses
like Jackie Kennedy (vintage Halston, ironed hair), can lighten the
load.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, as I was going through all those episodes, I
couldn't help feeling depressed myself. Not for Carrie. She isn't
such a tough nut to crack. At the end of last season, as she and
her friends were sitting around a cafe table (does anyone in New
York have that much time?) commiserating over her breakup with Mr.
Big, she said something that just confirmed my impression that the
series gets no closer to revealing the truth about New York and its
chop-breaking single girls than a bus ride through Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Barbra Streisand's politically charged character
Katie in the film ``The Way We Were,'' Carrie said, ``The world's
made up of two types of girls _ simple girls and the Katie girls.''
Everyone around the table smiled triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if Katie was going to the barricades, these girls are
going to Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from enjoying the sex scenes, some cool clothes and
moments of crisp repartee between Samantha and her big (and not so
tall) dates, I can't see people, even in other cities, sustaining
interest in characters and a plot line whose novelty had already
begun to wear off (hey, this is New York) when Darren Star, the
producer, turned it into a television series.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, looking at those four women sitting around
the table dishing their dates, isn't Star's ``Sex and the City''
just a swankier version of ``The Golden Girls''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
