<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOROS-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOROS HEDGE FUND CHIEF EXECUTIVE RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tumult for the hedge fund empire of George Soros continued
Friday when Duncan Hennes, who was hired last summer to be chief
executive of Soros Fund Management, announced his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought in to do one thing, and George doesn't want to
do that anymore,'' Hennes, 43, said in a telephone interview. That
thing, he said, was to build a larger hedge fund business.
</P>
<P>
   Soros, a billionaire financier and philanthropist, announced in
April that his two top fund managers, Stanley Druckenmiller and
Nicholas Roditi, were leaving and that the fund that made Soros
famous, the Quantum Fund, would be renamed the Quantum Endowment
Fund and changed in emphasis to reduce exposure to risk.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, however, Hennes spoke of his hopes to build up
other parts of the hedge fund business and seemed to have no
intention of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Hennes said that Soros had decided not to move
forward aggressively in hedge funds, although the firm's operations
that invest in real estate and in private companies were continuing
to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``George needed to take some time to decide what he needed to
do,'' Hennes said. ``He has a lot of charitable obligations. He
needs to create a platform where he can manage his money in a way
that is less volatile, in a way that he can assure he will meet his
obligations to the charities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennes said he would step down on June 30, but remain as a
consultant to Soros Funds for another three months. He said he did
not know what he would do after that.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Soros Fund Management, Hennes was executive vice
president and treasurer at Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Pattison, a spokesman for Soros Fund Management, said that
while the private equity and real estate operations were expanding,
more employees were expected to leave the hedge fund operation.
``We do expect some employees to leave on their own, and that
others will be asked to leave,'' he said. Soros employs about 240
people, although no figures were available regarding the hedge fund
business and the other operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Quantum Fund had comparatively good returns for three
decades, but stumbled earlier this year when it did not sell
technology stocks soon enough. It also lost money in foreign
currencies when it wrongly expected the euro to rise against the
dollar. That led to the departure of Druckenmiller and to Soros
deciding to seek a more conservative strategy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
