<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3177 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NY     06-02 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WE ALL PASS GO. THEY COLLECT $200. 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At long last: Schadenfreude dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   This has not only been a great spring for those rooting for the
comeuppance of Bill Gates, but for anyone who has had quite enough
of New Economy New Millionaires and their irritatingly
unostentatious brand of ostentation. Just a short list of recent
flameouts includes boo.com (a fashion site that burned through $135
million in months), den.net (a ``digital entertainment network'' of
postage-stamp-sized ``entertainment'') and RedRocket.com (toys from
Nickelodeon). Among the countless former high fliers in a Wall
Street tailspin are Drkoop.com and Michael Saylor's MicroStrategy,
whose shares have dropped from $333 in March to around $23 today,
amid investigations for alleged accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these sites rode in on a wave of hype as excessive as
those that herald Hollywood's bigger bombs. (On the Web, as in show
business, the big hits are often sleepers.) Saylor was being
canonized in the press as a Medici _ for underwriting a dubious, if
free, on-line university _ just as his stockholders fell on his
sword. Now that these start-ups are in peril or ruin, their press
is almost as apocalyptic as the initial buzz was celebratory. When
Disney bought a 60 percent interest in Toysmart.com back in August,
an expert at Forrester Research gushed to The Associated Press,
``There's nothing bad in it for Disney.'' When Toysmart went
belly-up last week, another Forrester analyst authoritatively told
The AP it was ``the wrong company selling the wrong product at the
wrong time.'' Now you tell us!
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder if these pundits visit the sites they
initially tout. I found from personal experience five months ago
that den.net was nearly impenetrable even on a fast connection and
that no one in its office would come to the phone to explain why.
If anyone wonders whether Barnes &AMP; Noble has mastered online
bookselling, just try, as I did this week, to order from its
not-ready-for-e-time ``same-day delivery'' service. With
competitors like this, no one at Amazon need go sleepless in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally satisfying as these rags-to-riches-to-rags dot-com
sagas may be, however, they are often irrelevant to the long and
looming future of the Internet. Like some other favorite story
lines of the past few years _ the kiddie-porn scare, the ``Blair
Witch'' craze, the day-trader menace _ tales of the Nasdaq bubble
are transient sideshows in the Web's early gold-rush phase that may
look like quaint olden-days phenomena once the Internet is
seamlessly integrated into our lives. As with the original
California gold rush's prospectors, it's inevitable that more
dot-com prospectuses are going to pan fool's gold than pay dirt.
The disasters won't slow the progress of this new technology any
more than earlier economic setbacks did the spread of the railroad
and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The truly illuminating Internet stories are sometimes less
visible than the morality plays of hubristic e-celebrities and
evanescent IPO's. That may be because they are buried in the very
architecture of a technology few of us laymen understand _ or
because they involve the media's own selfish interests. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Into this category falls the newest pair of corporate marriages
in the increasingly intertwined
Internet-cable-entertainment-telecommunications industry:
AT&AMP;T-MediaOne and AOL-Time Warner. The stories of these mammoth
couplings have been dissected as stock-price dramas and
captains-of-industry personality profiles, to be sure. But if it
hadn't been for the divine intervention of another corporate giant
last month _ Disney _ even a hint of the worst-case scenarios
possible in this new media landscape would have been invisible to
most Americans. Few still understand how these new powerhouses
could make our current cable and phone companies look like kindly
mom-and-pop operations by comparison.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   What Time Warner did to Disney, throwing ABC off its cable in
seven cities until a public outcry forced a retreat, is just a tiny
window into how these corporations can behave in their even more
powerful future, when cable TV service will be inseparable from
Internet service. There is nothing to stop one of these new
megaliths from exerting a larger and more surreptitious chokehold
on all the electronic services that their cable wires will bring by
the bundle into our homes tomorrow, from chat rooms to e-shopping
to movies. Even in the few weeks since the Disney fiasco, when you
might think Time Warner would be too chastened to risk more
censure, it has been caught misbehaving in Texas, where its cable
company offered its employees bounties to place bogus orders for a
rival Internet service offered by Southwestern Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has since apologized for its recent transgressions,
but if it can try to squelch Disney (itself of late described by
The Wall Street Journal as ``one of America's most aggressive
corporate bullies''), imagine what it can do to far smaller
companies, let alone consumers, once Disney and the other giants
inevitably make deals to secure their pieces of the pie. Not unlike
Windows, which blackballed Web software not made by Microsoft, or
the most recent edition of AOL, which snaked into its user's
computer settings to override competing programs, the future AOL-TW
threshold into the Internet/TV can be engineered for nefarious
purposes. It could, for instance, make its own products, like Time
and CNN, come on screen easily and fast while slowing down (or
blocking) the alternatives, whether Newsweek or Drudgewannabe.com.
It could do the same with merchants, TV channels or non-AOL
Internet service providers. In other words, it could control the
entertainment and even the news grid on your computer/TV screen
much as the movie studios (including Time Warner's ancestor, Warner
Brothers) limited Americans' entertainment choices in cities until
antitrust action ended their restrictive practices in 1948. The
result wouldn't be the democratic, go-anywhere-you-want Internet of
yore but a more elaborate version of cable TV, in which your cable
company adjudicates your programming choices.
</P>
<P>
   It would be like ``someone constantly dealing the deck and
knowing every card and shuffling at will, but never letting you
know if you're being dealt every card or not,'' says Jeffrey
Chester of the Center for Media Education. Gerald Levin, of Time
Warner, and Steve Case, of AOL, have pledged not to be naughty, but
even if we take them at their word, they'll not be running their
company forever. What's more, what they say already fails to square
with what they do. This week USA Today persuasively charged AOL
with foot-dragging on last summer's promise to open up its
instant-messenger system to all non-AOL Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote to any possible future misbehavior is not
necessarily to stop the merger _ a non-starter anyway _ but for
regulators to set simple rules of the information highway (and
build them into its construction) so that all comers have equal
access to its various lanes. Yet most of the political pressure on
Washington comes from the media giants, not the spottily informed
public. TV news, the main news source for most Americans, remains
silent about this part of the merger story, in which so much is at
stake for its corporate parents; it's easier to talk about Levin's
open-necked wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do politicians want to take on media corporations whose news
divisions cover them and whose donations increasingly support them.
At my request, the Center for Responsive Politics broke down total
campaign contributions by industry over the past decade, and the
result shows a rapid increase of total donations by media,
communications and electronics companies since the explosion of the
Internet _ a stiffer increase than even those made by the health
care industry. The parties more or less split the loot.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has taken a ``do-nothing attitude''
about insuring fairness for all in the Internet's future, according
to Lawrence Lessig, the Harvard law professor who has more than
anyone framed this issue. Nor is there any Teddy Roosevelt
Republican in sight to ride to the rescue. Still, some
public-interest advocates are hopeful that voters will be provoked
into anger over time, if only because media companies arrogant
enough to pull the plug on Regis Philbin may, like Microsoft before
them, eventually overplay their hand. But it may take something as
startling as a totalitarian new voice saying ``You've got mail'' _
Charlton Heston's, perhaps _ to wake the country up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
