<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL WILL NOT LOOK FURTHER INTO NATO BOMBING OF
YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. chief war crimes prosecutor said
Friday that there was no basis for a formal investigation into
whether NATO committed war crimes during the bombing of Yugoslavia
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although some mistakes were made by NATO, I am very satisfied
that there was no deliberate targeting of civilians or unlawful
military targets by NATO during the bombing campaign,'' the
prosecutor, Carla del Ponte of Switzerland, told the Security
Council Friday. She said that a detailed statement on her decision
would be released as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary commission from Russia, Yugoslavia's strongest
international supporter, and Western lawyers working for the
Yugoslav government, had brought allegations of NATO war crimes to
the tribunal last year. Several human rights groups have also
raised questions about NATO attacks on civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-week NATO bombing campaign was intended to stop Yugoslav
repression of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, the Serbian province now
under the administration of NATO and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the NATO actions taken to the Balkans tribunal by critics
alleging war crimes were an airstrike on a passenger train crossing
a targeted bridge; the bombing of a Serbian television center;
killing of refugees in a convoy mistaken for soldiers; the use of
cluster bombs that can fragment over a wide area, in one case
hitting the grounds of a hospital; and the use of depleted uranium
in weapons. There were also more general allegations of genocide
and deliberate destruction of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now able to announce my conclusion, following a full
consideration of my team's assessment of all complaints and
allegations, that there is no basis for opening an investigation
into any of those allegations or into other incidents related to
the NATO bombing,'' Del Ponte, a former Swiss attorney general,
told the council. She did not discuss the allegations themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans war crimes tribunal, based in the Hague, has played
down the importance of these charges since they were first made
public late last year. Officials have said that the tribunal was
formed to charge individuals, not institutions or organizations,
with war crimes. NATO officials have answered or dismissed the
charges, but have said errors were committed.
</P>
<P>
   Among these charges they include the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade. U.S. officials subsequently said that the
bombing was an unfortunate accident resulting from the use of
outdated maps an incorrect intelligence information, but China has
rejected this explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte, who is also chief prosecutor of a war crimes tribunal
for Rwanda, which is based in Arusha, Tanzania, conducted only an
informal study of the allegations against NATO, officials said. She
has been more deeply involved in formal charges against
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, who was indicted by the
tribunal last year.
</P>
<P>
   But she told the council that she felt she had to examine the
allegations against NATO because it was her ``obligation and
responsibility'' to look into all complaints and charges. She said
that she had amassed a lot of material from Yugoslavia and
elsewhere to support the allegations, and that it had now all been
examined an analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte acknowledged that the NATO bombing campaign a year ago
and the indictment of Milosevic and other high-level Serbian
officials had all but ended cooperation from Yugoslavia, apart from
on the allegations against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``This severely hampers my ability to conclude my investigations
involving Serbian victims,'' she said. She and her investigators
have been denied visas to enter Yugoslvia, she said, making it
impossible to talk with Serbs who claim to have been the victims of
war crimes by any side.
</P>
<P>
   The International War Crimes Tribunal for the Balkans was
created seven years ago to deal with atrocities committed in the
civil wars that followed the breakup of Yugoslavia in 1991. At the
start, it dealt mostly with Bosnia and Croatia, where abuses were
committed by Serbs, Croats and Muslims. A warrant is still out for
the arrest of the Serbian leader in Bosnia, Radovan Karadic, and
his military commander, Ratko Mladic.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the tribunal has extended its
investigations into Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
