<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, June 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ In the strongest signal yet that the
booming U.S. economy is finally slowing, the Labor Department
reported Friday that the nation's private sector employers, instead
of hiring, shed 116,000 jobs in May, the largest drop in more than
eight years and the first since the economy began to boom in the
mid 1990s. The stock market immediately celebrated. By Louis
Uchitelle. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under 2-line, 3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to MARKET story, inside Business.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEFENSE (Moscow) _ In a bid to recast the debate over
missile defense just before his summit meeting with President
Clinton, Russian President Vladimir Putin has suggested an
alternative to the proposed American defense against missile attack
by nations like North Korea. Putin hinted that the United States
and Russian could collaborate on new ways to shoot down enemy
missiles soon after they were launched. By Michael R. Gordon.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,400
words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 3-column New York day photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMO (Washington) _ More health maintenance
organizations will soon pull out of Medicare or curtail their
participation, disrupting insurance coverage for hundreds of
thousands of elderly people, according to federal officials,
independent experts and managed care executives. Cigna Corp. said
Friday that it would end coverage for 104,000 Medicare
beneficiaries in 11 states: New York, New Jersey, Connecticut,
California, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Maryland, Tennessee, Texas
and Virginia. By Robert Pear. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: ITALY-GAYS (Rome) _ World Pride Roma, a global gay pride
festival, is expected to draw gays from all over the world to Rome
on July 1 for a week's worth of conferences, fashion shows, a gay
pride parade and a concert featuring Gloria Gaynor and The Village
People. By Alessandra Stanley. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POWERPLANT (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Pataki administration gives
final environmental approval to plans to build the nation's largest
power plant along a verdant stretch of the Hudson River, marking
the start of a new generation of plant construction in New York. By
Richard Perez-Pena. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Budgeted earlier as PATAKI-POWERPLANT)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SUBURBS (Smyrna, Ga.) _ In state after state, a platform
of conservative social issues that once monopolized the
conversation of Southern suburbs _ lower taxes, welfare reform,
crackdowns on crime _ has been supplanted by a new agenda: managing
growth and transportation, bringing in high-tech jobs, and above
all improving public education. In a swath of states from the
Carolinas to Mississippi, Democratic governors have made these
issues their own, and Republicans are struggling to keep up. By
David Firestone. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-DEMOCRACY (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Everything has
changed in Indonesia since its strongman, Suharto, was pushed from
office just two years ago. The clamor of democracy is everywhere,
along with the violence and instability that accompany a time of
unfettered transformation. And nothing has changed. Indonesia is
still focused on the ideas, the directives _ even the whims _ of
one man, its new president, Abdurrahman Wahid. By Seth Mydans.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AIR-CRASH (Washington) _ The Federal Aviation
Administration threatens to shut down major maintenance operations
at Alaska Airlines, which would ground the airline within months.
The agency, its attention drawn to the airline by a fatal crash
last January and a federal grand jury investigation, says that the
carrier has a persistent problem in keeping track of whether
required maintenance has been done. By Matthew L. Wald. (Scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
