<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dual top lede)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Nasdaq composite index soared 6.44
percent Friday, ending its best week ever, as investors cheered
data suggesting that the U.S. economy is slowing and that the
Federal Reserve may be done raising interest rates. The gains in
many technology stocks echoed the wild trading seen in January and
February, with many big tech companies rising 10 percent or more on
heavy volume. Other indexes also gained, though much less than the
Nasdaq. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-ASSESS (New York) _ This week was the best ever for the
Nasdaq composite, which rose 18.98 percent. That was nearly twice
the gain in the previous best week for the index, a 9.71 percent
rise recorded only six weeks ago. But is this move real, or is
volatility just going wild? That may be the most difficult question
for stock market watchers. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AIRLINES (Calgary, Alberta) _ After Air Canada's
acquisition of Canadian Airlines this spring, Canadians are waking
up to an airline market more reliant on a single carrier than in
any other major Western nation. Air Canada has 82 percent of the
market _ far above the 60 percent held by Lufthansa in Germany. But
with passengers and lawmakers complaining that the merger has
created a monopoly, the government is encouraging discount
airlines. And there are, increasingly, alternatives. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-MERGERS (Undated) _ The road to the future of the domestic
and perhaps even the global airline industry now appears to pass
through Minneapolis. That is where Northwest Airlines has its
headquarters. And in the wake of last week's announcement by UAL
Corp., the parent of United Airlines, that it plans to buy US
Airways for $4.3 billion, the chairman of Northwest, Gary L.
Wilson, and the chief executive, John H. Dasburg, are suddenly the
men to see. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
