<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-DASANI0603-COX     06-02 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DASANI0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke launches Dasani advertising campaign
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola is spending about $12 million on the first
national TV ad campaign to boost sales of Dasani, its year-old
bottled water that's become the fifth best-selling brand.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has developed a special 12-ounce plastic bottle
so Dasani can be sold out of vending machines that dispense
12-ounce cans. That could expand sales considerably because bottled
water is popular at workplaces, where can vending machines far
outnumber the 20-ounce bottle machines.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, which will include another $3 million of
spending in the print media, uses the tagline ``Life Simplified.''
It's aimed at Dasani's core drinkers _ women aged 25-49.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very busy and stressed,'' said Dasani brand manager
Monique Acevedo. ``So our message to her is to replenish her body
and mind with Dasani.''
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo said the national campaign, created by Berlin Cameron &AMP;
Partners, is being rolled out now after the company spent the past
year solidifying its distribution network.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, with only about a half year of distribution, Dasani
became the No. 5 water brand in the U.S.,'' said John Sicher,
editor and publisher of Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can predict that in a year or two, it will be one of the top
two bottled water brands in the U.S., along with Pepsi's Aquafina.
Dasani will benefit from the power of the Coke bottling and
distribution system and from Coke's marketing muscle and
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million ad budget ``is a pretty good hunk of money to
put behind a small brand,'' Sicher said. But, he added, ``Dasani
will most certainly become a much bigger brand quite quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because the newer bottled water segment of the
industry is growing much faster than the more mature carbonated
soft-drink sector.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, sales of bottled water grew 35 percent to about 600
million cases, while sales of carbonated soft drinks in the United
States increased 0.5 percent to about 10 billion cases, according
to Beverage Digest data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amercian consumers have been developing a love affair for
bottled war in portable packages,'' Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Dasani's new 12-ounce bottle could be expanded to other
Coca-Cola beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're exploring with other brands, but Dasani
is leading the way,`` said Coca-Cola spokesman Scott Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
