<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-44     06-02 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ISRAELI WITHDRAWAL, BORDER WITH LEBANON COULD ERUPT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Every square inch of land counts in the
reckoning of victory and defeat in the Middle East. And every inch
along the Lebanese-Israeli border is going to be counted, probably
twice, before anyone can say whether Israel's withdrawal from
southern Lebanon last week will ultimately count as an installment
on regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine days since the pullout, the frontier between the
countries has remained tranquil for the first time in more than 25
years. The only spike in tension occurred on Sunday, when Israeli
soldiers fired rubber-coated bullets at a few Lebanese men who,
giddy with newfound bravado, plunged through a border fence to
plant a Hezbollah flag under the noses of their longtime enemies.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still dangerous territory. Although the physical
boundaries between Lebanon and Israel have been redrawn, the
political map contains the same ambushes and obstacles as before
the Israeli retreat.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Syria has not made its own deal with Israel to return
the occupied Golan Heights, the potential for instability and
violence remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis may no longer wake up in the morning to hear of
another soldier killed in southern Lebanon,'' said Joseph Samaha, a
Lebanese expert who writes for Al Hayat, the pan-Arab daily
newspaper. ``But still, each day, in terms of regional strategy,
they will know they can never enjoy peace or integrate into the
Middle East until they have an agreement with Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria has been sending mixed signals about how it will behave in
the new atmosphere. In the extreme, experts said, Syria could
encourage guerrilla attacks on Israeli targets in Chebaa Farms, a
strip of land abutting the Golan Heights that the Lebanese
government, with mild Syrian backing, claims as its own.
</P>
<P>
   An outbreak of violence, with the expected Israeli reprisals,
could ruin Syria's efforts over recent weeks to gain international
approval by cooperating with the United Nations over the Lebanon
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Syria could also keep the temperature in the region turned up by
more limited, and less bloody, means. It could permit Lebanon,
which has so far refused to claim sovereignty over the liberated
south and send its army into the liberated zone, to keep on arguing
indefinitely with the United Nations over whether the withdrawal
has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had years of low-intensity warfare here,'' said Simon M.
Karam, a lawyer in Beirut and a former ambassador to the United
States. ``Now we will have a low-intensity diplomatic imbroglio, a
crisis that's always brewing at just over 98.6 degrees, like
someone who is mildly sick.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lebanon, a tiny nation of barely 4.5 million people, is
effectively a satellite state to its bigger and more militarized
neighbor, Syria. Some 30,000 Syrian soldiers are stationed in
Lebanon, and the Lebanese government always toes the Syrian line on
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Syrian strategy, in peace negotiations with
Israel and through the Hezbollah guerrillas it encouraged to attack
Israeli occupation forces, has been to link the liberation of
southern Lebanon to the recovery of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Israel will not enjoy peace, Syrian officials have often said,
until it leaves the Golan Heights and southern Lebanon. Lebanese
officials, taking their cue from Damascus, refused to negotiate
with Israel, insisting that the occupation of southern Lebanon has
to end, but always adding that they could never sign a separate
peace agreement before Syria regained its land.
</P>
<P>
   That stand was shaken when Israel announced three months ago
that it would cut its losses and quit southern Lebanon, with or
without a peace agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian reaction was summed up in a warning from Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa that such a move would be suicidal. In
Lebanon, the prospect of a unilateral Israeli pullout caused a
shiver of panic, and officials immediately raised other issues.
</P>
<P>
   No Israeli pullout would comply with U.N. resolutions unless
Lebanese prisoners in Israel were freed, the officials said.
Palestinian refugees have to be given the right of return, and the
United Nations has to disarm Palestinians in refugee camps in
Lebanon so that they could not, in theory, attack Israel and
provoke fresh Israeli retaliation against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Since the withdrawal, Lebanon has repeated those demands and
added new ones, like recovering Chebaa Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Although Syria has permitted Lebanon to act as its devil's
advocate, Syrian officials have also tried hard to portray
themselves as cooperative with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   This week, according to a U.N. envoy, the Syrian officials said
they accepted the U.N. position that for purposes of verifying
whether Israel has complied with U.N. Resolution 425, the pullout
will be complete, even if it does not include Chebaa Farms.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, from 1978, calls for Israel's complete
withdrawal from the Lebanese territory that it occupied in that
year. Most of the Chebaa Farms land was seized by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   But for their Lebanese clients, Syrian officials also left their
position muddy by reassuring Lebanon this week that Chebaa Farms
was also occupied Lebanese land.
</P>
<P>
   The murkiness of the Syrian stance has left the Lebanese
government and the Syrian-backed Hezbollah militia floundering.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Hezbollah official, Muhammad Raad, said this week that
the militia had a right to continue its armed struggle against
Israel until Chebaa Farms had been returned to Lebanese control and
the Lebanese government had verified that Israel had left every
inch of Lebanese territory. But Raad would not say whether
Hezbollah would exercise that right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we say we want to claim our land back, we are not going
to act carelessly,'' he said. ``We will resist in the right time
and the right place, so the resistance will be effective. It could
take 20 years even. We are very patient, and we will not be in any
dispute with Lebanon or with Syria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
