<HEADER>
A3209 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-UTILITIES-$ADV     06-02 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-UTILITIES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTUNE TELLING FOR PROFIT AND POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notoriously vulnerable to rising interest rates, utility stocks
fell 23.5 percent last year, their worst performance in a
quarter-century, as the Federal Reserve made credit more expensive
on three occasions, starting June 30.
</P>
<P>
   So what has happened this year as the Fed raised rates another
three times? The stocks have not only rallied but have performed
better than any other group. The Standard &AMP; Poor's utility index
has returned 18.6 percent through Friday while investors in the S&AMP;P
500 have lost 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What's to explain this turnaround? Several things, industry
analysts and portfolio managers say, not least the fact that
utilities are among the few sectors that pay handsome dividends,
resulting in yields that are high even by historical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this year's rally, investors in many utilities are
flirting with 7 percent _ quadruple the 1.6 percent average yield
for the Dow industrials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dividend income is one of the few real things you get from a
company,'' observed William Reaves, president of a Jersey City
money management company that specializes in utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Unfashionable as such thinking has become in a
technology-dominated investment world, it is clearly attracting
some investors partial to equities but weary of the gyrations that
have become commonplace on the Nasdaq and, all too often, for
high-priced blue chip stocks as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're jumping into utilities,'' said Edward Tirello, who
analyzes the group for Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. The appeal is not
just high yields, he added, but that utility stocks are highly
liquid and the companies in many cases offer prospects for growth
in a newly deregulated environment.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the industry is steadily, though slowly, shedding its
traditional reputation as supersensitive to changes in interest
rates. No longer do most utilities need to borrow huge amounts to
build new generating capacity. Many of the companies are raking in
so much cash that they have become lenders and investors
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And many analysts say that after years of underperforming,
utilities are bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The values are pretty compelling right now,'' said Daniele
Seitz, director of equity research at UBS Warburg. She cited
``hidden value'' that deregulation is unlocking for many companies,
such as from energy-trading and telecommunications, and the
relatively friendly attitude that state officials have taken in
awarding compensation for so-called stranded costs for plants that
are no longer competitively viable.
</P>
<P>
   With federal encouragement, half the states have facilitated
some form of free market in electricity and natural gas, with
consumers getting a choice of suppliers. This kind of deregulation
is changing the risk-reward profile of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although strategies differ, the industry is gravitating roughly
into three camps _ those oriented toward generating power (like
Edison International, based in Rosemead, Calif.), those that
distribute it (GPU of Morristown, N.J.) and those that follow the
traditional route, doing both (Southern of Atlanta, Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Generation is considered riskier but distribution remains
subject to price regulation, and analysts say it is too early to
know the winning strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know which plan's going to work out better,'' Tirello
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the companies do stand to benefit from strong growth in
demand for power, which many believe will result in shortages in
some parts of the country this summer. And there is little risk
that fresh capacity will put downward pressure on rates anytime
soon, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, utility dividends, after a decade in which many
companies cut payouts in response to Wall Street pressure to
transform themselves into vehicles for rapid growth, seem
relatively secure again. That fad is over, Reaves said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about favorite stocks, Seitz cited American Electric
Power, a Columbus, Ohio, holding company yielding 6.86 percent with
an energy-trading operation, good fuel diversification and the
scale to be a major supplier. She also likes New Orleans-based
Entergy (4.18 percent), the company that has the industry buzzing
about its aggressive embrace of deregulation, and Duke Energy of
Charlotte, N.C. (3.81 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Tirello favors Atmos Energy, a Dallas-based gas distributor
(6.20 percent); American Water Works, ``a natural monopoly'' in
Voorhees, N.J., (3.76 percent); and such electrics as the
Dallas-based TXU (6.76 percent) and New Jersey's Public Service
Enterprise Group (5.88 percent).
</P>
<P>
   As for Reaves, who has been following the industry for some 50
years, the high-yield standout is the St. Louis-based Ameren,
paying 6.98 percent and increasing its earnings 6 percent a year.
He also likes Virginia's Dominion Resources (5.73 percent) and, for
the patiently venturesome, the growth-oriented Peco Energy in
Pennsylvania (2.31 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``The stocks tend to do better when there's caution in the
market'' generally, Reaves said. But he said many investors were
still inhibited by old notions about these suppliers of basic
household services.
</P>
<P>
   That is likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
