<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW0603-COX     06-02 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Job reports bring optimism to market
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This week's news _ showing a definite slowing of the
U.S. economy _ may put a hold on interest rate hikes by the Federal
Reserve, analysts said Friday. If it turns out that way, investors
have reason to cheer some more, as they did most of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The news was capped on Friday by the government's report of
less-than-expected job growth and a rise in the May unemployment
rate to 4.1 percent from 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The hoped-for news sparked a stock market rally that gave the
technology-loaded Nasdaq composite index a record one-week
percentage gain of 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing sentiment was that the Fed's year-long series of
six interest rate increases is finally taking hold and slowing an
economy the central bankers think is running at an inflationary
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Friday's job growth report especially should
lead to a pause in the Fed's policy of raising rates on short-term
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to see how, given this report, the Fed could
raise the fed funds rate on June 28,'' said First Union chief
economist David Orr. He suggested that the jury is still out on
what the Fed might do next, given the possibility of later, more
disappointing economic reports.
</P>
<P>
   At A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, chief strategist Alfred E. Goldman said,
``I think the odds have now changed and there will not be another
rate hike soon. I think the Fed will be out of our face for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Fed stops raising interest rates, history suggests
that investors can expect near-term stock market gains, Standard &AMP;
Poor's analyst Sam Stovall said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He studied the market's reaction at the end of the Fed's
1994-1995 series of seven rate increases, which were also designed
to cool an inflationary economy. The last rate hike was on Jan. 31,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The S&AMP;P 500, which fell 1.5 percent in 1994, went on to post a
19.5 percent rally in 1995,'' said Stovall.
</P>
<P>
   In just six months after the last 1995 rate hike, the technology
sector had rallied 49 percent, financial stocks by 22 percent,
consumer stocks by more than 15 percent and utilities _ the
smallest increase _ almost 6 percent, Stovall's study showed.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned, however, that his survey should be viewed by
investors as ``a guide'' and not a forecast, ``since today's
economic and market conditions are different from those found in
the beginning of 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the market's performance, Robinson-Humphrey senior
strategist Robert S. Robbins said the ``typical summer stock market
rally appears to have begun,'' boosted by a rally in the bond
market that has sent Treasury yields back below 6 percent. That
reduces the bond market's competitiveness against stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to maintain that the yield on the long bond peaked
at 6.74 percent this past Jan. 18,'' said Robbins. ``Our outlook
calls for the 30-year (Treasury bond yield) to decline to 4.75
percent within the next two and a half years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, the next major reports will be the
government's chief inflation gauges: the Producer Price Index on
June 9 and the Consumer Price Index on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's trading, demand for technology stocks propelled the
rally in the Nasdaq market. Friday's gain of 230.88 points to
3,813.38 was the index's third-biggest one-day point gain.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Nasdaq rose more than 608 points, just shy of
20 percent, for its best weekly gain since the 9.7 percent increase
the week ended April 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.3 percent on Friday and
almost 5 percent for the week; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 2
percent on Friday and 7 percent for the week; and the Russell 200
index of smaller stocks 4.2 percent and 12 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
