<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-DEMOCRACY-(     06-02 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-DEMOCRACY-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDONESIA, THE MORE THINGS CHANGE, THE MORE THEY STAY THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif.)   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Everything has changed in Indonesia since
its strongman, Suharto, was pushed from office just two years ago.
The clamor of democracy is everywhere, along with the violence and
instability that accompany a time of unfettered transformation.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing has changed. For all the talk about democratic
principles and local empowerment, Indonesia is still focused on the
ideas, the directives _ even the whims _ of one man, its new
president, Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Will the country's separatist movements be crushed by force or
courted with blandishments? Will its military leaders be the hard
men fostered by Suharto or a new generation of liberal thinkers?
Will its press remain open and free? Will Indonesia begin toying
again with the idea of strict currency controls?
</P>
<P>
   For all the clamor of political debate and the new empowerment
of the country's Legislature, these are all fundamental questions
whose final answer lies with one man, the president.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in sharp contrast to Suharto, who was forced to step
down in May 1998 after 32 years in power, Wahid's ability to enact
his policies is dangerously limited.
</P>
<P>
   As he built his top-down structure of personal control, Suharto
so eviscerated the nation's institutions that his successors have
inherited a hollow and nearly useless bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government here is almost hydroponic'' _ like a floating
structure with dangling, ineffectual roots _ said a Western
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid was a compromise president, the product of back-room deals
seven months ago to replace Suharto's immediate successor, B.J.
Habibie. Though Wahid is personally popular, he lacks a broad
political base. Even his Cabinet, the product of his deal-making,
does not fully support him.
</P>
<P>
   So he rules through the force of his personality, through his
moral authority, through the weakness of his rivals and through a
sort of light-hearted bullying in which he pummels potential
challengers with jokes, insults and impulsive personnel changes.
</P>
<P>
   But when he issues direct orders, one of his Cabinet ministers
said, he can never be sure what the result will be. His
subordinates may be recalcitrant or incompetent or simply lack the
bureaucratic machinery to act effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a president from whom everyone expects too much,''
said Daniel S. Lev, an expert on Indonesia at the University of
Washington in Seattle, who was visiting Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a president without the institution of the presidency,''
Lev said. ``Every major administrative institution and political
institution has essentially been destroyed, crushed. There is
really nothing left to work with. It doesn't matter, in a sense,
how good the people are that you appoint because the institutions
are devastated. There's corruption everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, seven months into his presidency, Wahid finds his
country in a slough of discontent, its reforms slowing, its leaders
consumed by personal rivalries, shaken by outbreaks of religious
violence and increasingly annoyed by the mannerisms of its quirky
president.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent missteps have particularly shaken public
confidence. They include the still-unexplained firing of a highly
respected economic minister, Laksamana Sukardi, and his replacement
by a political ally of the president. And they include scandals
involving the president's youngest brother and his personal
masseuse that have evoked fears of a return of the corruption and
nepotism of the Suharto years.
</P>
<P>
   Most dangerously, the public restiveness grows out of a sharp
economic downturn that has seen the currency, the rupiah, lose up
to 18 percent of its value this year and the stock market plunge by
27 percent. Although the overall economy is growing and could
exceed last year's increase by as much as 3 percent, the slump has
caused a panic in this still-traumatized nation, where it was an
economic crash that led to the forced resignation of Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Western diplomat offered a succinct analysis of the
current challenges facing Indonesia: ``It's the economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid is not a president who takes a great interest in the
economy, and the economic team he has assembled _ skewed by his
political deal-making _ is widely viewed as weak.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has not been helped by a series of ill-considered
statements by government officials, most strikingly by Kwik Kian
Gee, the president's chief economic minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a foreign investor, I wouldn't come to Indonesia,''
Kwik said in a recent, and much quoted, interview with Dow Jones
Newswires. ``The law enforcement is not there, but not only that,
the whole thing is so confusing. How can you come here?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like Wahid, Kwik spent much of his career in opposition to the
Suharto government. Both men, like some other leaders, still speak
and act as if they were in opposition rather than in charge.
</P>
<P>
   So Kwik _ the government's chief economic manager _ blamed ``the
way the government is managed'' for the weak economy. He criticized
his boss for appointing a welter of economic councils and advisory
groups, leading to inconsistent policies.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wahid told reporters he might just take over
economic management himself, despite his lack of background. He
then said he might take action to control currency fluctuations _ a
seeming reference to the creation of a currency board, an eccentric
idea of Suharto's that aroused shudders among investors.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But while the surface of public life here drifts and sloshes in
what sometimes seems a sea of incompetence, fundamental changes are
being prepared in the structure of the nation and its governance.
</P>
<P>
   Donald K. Emmerson, a professor of political science at Stanford
University, calls it ``the rebirth of the Indonesian political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissions are preparing constitutional amendments for a
congress scheduled in August that would put in place a democratic
system with striking similarities to that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of Wahid, these changes are likely to include
direct election of the president, a bicameral legislature, a system
of judicial review, decentralization of some power to the provinces
and even perhaps an American-style bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Emmerson suggested that there may be mirror images here.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto placed his emphasis _ and staked his legitimacy _ on
economic development, while corrupting and bankrupting the
political system. It appears that the new government of Wahid,
while drifting economically, has embarked on an ambitious program
of political development.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto took the easy way; he crushed dissent by force. Wahid
has more faith in the ability of his countrymen to live together in
peace; this is a time when that faith is being tested.
</P>
<P>
   It is rainy season in Jakarta, and the gray skies and occasional
cracks of thunder speak to the national mood.
</P>
<P>
   All debates and rivalries and even outbreaks of violence are
focused now on August, when the national assembly will meet to
debate, to pass laws and to hear a state-of-the-nation report from
the president. No one is sure if a storm is coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
