<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3238 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DEFILED-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-02 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFILED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOULD-BE SATIRE IN SEARCH OF ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think Bill Gates is the anti-Christ? Do you believe that
Starbucks and The Gap are evil empires? Do you consider amazon.com
a threat to American democracy? Then, boy, does the Geffen
Playhouse have a show for you.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds as if you might empathize with Harry Mendelssohn, the
deranged, neo-Luddite city librarian who rants and raves his way
through ``Defiled,'' Lee Kalcheim's well-meaning but sketchily
drawn and lead-handed new work about technology and its
malcontents.
</P>
<P>
   How discontented is Harry (Jason Alexander)? Well, as we meet
him, he's duct-taping bundles of dynamite to the inner columns of
an unnamed metropolitan library.
</P>
<P>
   His beef? The cynical library brass is abandoning the old card
catalog system in favor of a newfangled computerized version. Like
Theodore Kaczynski, Harry is a Harvard-trained loner who'd rather
unabomb than switch to the cold new world of malls, cell phones and
(shudder) Burger Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there's only one man to handle this job: Lt. Columbo,
aka Brian Dickey, a cagey police negotiator cagily played by none
other than Peter Falk. Though Falk could be accused here of
self-impersonating a police officer, his loose, cockeyed
performance supplies an enjoyable foil to Alexander's uptight,
hyperactive megalomaniac.
</P>
<P>
   Tautly directed by Barnet Kellman, the two veteran actors'
yin-yang chemistry makes ``Defiled'' interesting for about 20
minutes. The problem is that Kalcheim has written a 1 hour-long
play. Once the dynamic is set, ``Defiled'' spins itself out in
improbable plot twists and humdrum emotional disclosures of the TV
``hostage melodrama'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   Character revelations are scattered throughout the dialogue
rather than woven irrevocably to the plot. Dickey, who asks little
from life other than a happy home and a good night's sleep, carries
a thermos of coffee and offers Harry nips of whiskey from a hip
flask between crisis flashpoints. He's wed to an Italian woman, a
great cook, naturally, who realizes ``it's no picnic being married
to a cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry's psychic scars, we learn, reach back to his failed
engagement 18 years ago, and before that to the day that his
practical-minded father gave him a short-haired, fuss-free dog
instead of some more exotic breed. Which gives ``Defiled'' its
promisingly absurdist subtitle, ``The Convenience of a Short Haired
Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in ``Defiled'' there's a scathing black-comic satire
struggling to get out. Kalcheim settles for a generic genre piece
with highbrow aspirations, a choice that seriously undercuts the
play's moral arguments against the dumbing-down of global culture.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Alexander's heroic efforts, in particular, to wring
every possible insight from his lines, the dialogue quickly starts
to repeat itself. Harry succeeds in fending off Dickey with a
remote control detonator, but Falk and Alexander can't fend off the
been-there, done-that feeling that clings to the play like sulfur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defiled's'' single set, a bricks-and-mortar library reading
room of reassuring solidity, has been beautifully designed by D.
Martyn Bookwalter to mesh with the Geffen's elegant interior. Jon
Gottlieb's sound design of helicopters and police bullhorns
persuades us we could be in the middle of a deadly armed standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defiled'' contains at least one big bang, all right, and it's
an absolute doozy. Too bad this technophobic play couldn't have
stopped worrying long enough to embrace some verbal pyrotechnics of
its own. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Defiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Where: Geffen Playhouse, 10886 Le Conte Ave., Westwood. &QL; 
When: 7:30 p.m. Tuesdays through Thursdays; 8 p.m. Fridays; 4, 8:30
p.m. Saturdays; 2, 7 p.m. Sundays, through July 2. Special 2 p.m.
matinees June 14 and 15. &QL; 
Tickets: $20-$42. Call (310) 208-5454. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
