<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ANNUNITY-SEC-$ADV04-N     06-02 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNUNITY-SEC-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC PLANS WARNING ON ANNUITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 4) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, federal regulators have been looking into whether
people who invest in variable annuities are getting a fair shake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, while the regulators continue to gather information from
brokerage firms and financial advisers across the country for
possible sanctions, the Securities and Exchange Commission is
sending up a red flag on these controversial but increasingly
popular investments, which are basically a combination of mutual
funds and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, according to SEC officials, the agency plans to take
the unusual step of publishing an investor alert on its Web site,
www.sec.gov, on the pitfalls of variable annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the agency used an alert to emphasize to
investors that dazzling past performances of mutual funds might not
be reason for future investments. But the SEC has not previously
sounded a warning on variable annuities, which were developed by
insurance companies to attract some of the billions going into
mutual funds and which lately have been accumulating money from
investors at a faster clip than standard, less expensive mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting concerns that sales representatives often do not tell
potential customers all they need to know about variable annuities
_ and certainly do not emphasize the drawbacks _ the SEC document,
``Variable Annuities: What You Should Know,'' reads like a sober
antidote to a salesman's smooth patter. It is filled with
cautionary passages clearly designed to make a potential buyer stop
and think whether he or she really would want to put money into an
investment that financially penalizes those who might need cash in
less than six or seven years and charges for features, like a
lifelong stream of payments after retirement, that are rarely used.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the restrained voice of government, the agency
warns, in particular, that bonuses now being offered as a lure by
many variable annuity companies ``may not be in your best
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives complain that companies that pay
customers bonuses of 3 percent or 4 percent to get them to switch
their variable annuity investments often make potential buyers
think they are getting something for nothing. But the SEC alert
points out that this is may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher expenses can outweigh the benefits'' of a bonus, the
agency says. It lists several ways, not always obvious, by which
variable annuity companies take back the bonus payments, including
higher penalties for withdrawals and extending the periods over
which such penalties apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before purchasing a variable annuity with a bonus credit,''
the agency says in its alert, ``you need to ask yourself _ and the
financial professional who is trying to sell you the contract _
whether the bonus is worth more to you than any increased charges
you will pay.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the pioneers of variable annuity bonuses, American
Skandia, just this year became the No. 1 selling variable annuity
company, taking the lead away from Hartford Life, which, until a
few months ago, had not offered bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mackey, chief executive of the National Association for
Variable Annuities, said he had not seen the SEC document but that
he agreed with the agency that there should be full disclosure. He
added that bonus annuities were suitable for some people and that
it was up to sales representatives to ``be familiar with their
clients' circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   While one of the main advantages of variable annuities over
mutual funds is that investments are not taxed until the time of
withdrawal, the agency notes that Individual Retirement Accounts
and 401(k) retirement plans, which offer the same feature at no
cost, ``are often more advantageous than variable annuities.''
</P>
<P>
   Several pending lawsuits accuse variable annuity companies of
inappropriately selling variable annuities to IRA and 401(k)
investors, giving them a useless, double tax deferral feature at a
higher expense than if mutual funds had been used.
</P>
<P>
   Another seldom-used feature of variable annuities is a guarantee
that an investor's heirs will receive at least the original
investment, regardless of how poorly the market performs. But
long-term investors rarely fail to at least break even. Again, the
agency advises, before paying the extra money for a variable
annuity, ``Carefully consider whether you need the benefit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
