<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-ISRAEL-MOTHERS-ART-     06-02 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ISRAEL-MOTHERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PEACE MOVES CLOSER, FOUR MOTHERS' WORK MAY BE DONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In 1997, two Israeli army helicopters collided on
the way to Lebanon, killing 73 soldiers as they crashed in the
front yard of the school that Rachel Ben Dor's children attended.
At the time, Ben Dor's oldest son was a soldier in Lebanon, and
several of his former classmates, recent graduates like him, died.
</P>
<P>
   That pushed Ben Dor, an opponent of what she saw as Israel's
senseless involvement in Lebanon, over the edge. Summoning three
friends to her kitchen in a northern kibbutz, she hatched a group
eventually called The Four Mothers _ Leave Lebanon in Peace.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the military and political establishment dismissed
them as overly emotional and ignorant of security concerns. But
later, after they spawned a significant anti-war movement, they
were derided on a baser level. An army commander crudely insulted
them using a slur for women earlier this year, but in a signal of
how the tide had turned, he was pressured to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Four Mothers met with Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
who last week completed the unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon that
they had pushed for.
</P>
<P>
   The women once called traitors were embraced by the nation's
most decorated former general, and the whole issue came full
circle, dizzyingly for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There we were inside the Defense Ministry that we used to
picket, kissing and hugging with the prime minister and the army
chief,'' Ben Dor, 42, said. ``And all the generals were standing
there, thinking I don't know what. It was so amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis celebrated the Four Mothers this week. The
Jerusalem Post on Friday called them ``one of the most successful
grassroots movements in Israeli history.'' The women took a classic
Israeli stereotype _ the silent, suffering soldier's mother _ stood
it on its head and dared to challenge the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, it was so shocking to the Israeli public
that it was mothers who were demanding answers from the
government,'' said Linda Ben Zvi, a leading member but not one of
the original four. ``Mothers were supposed to make the schnitzel
and hand-wash the uniforms and play the passive role in-bred in
Israeli society.''
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1980s, large anti-war rallies challenged
Israel's invasion of Lebanon. But then the country fell largely
silent for more than a decade. Israel's occupation of a what it
called a ``security zone'' in southern Lebanon, with its annual
death toll of 25 to 35 Israeli soldiers, became a reality that
seemed immutable. The helicopter crash sent a spasm of doubt
through the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a sign from the skies, telling us the whole thing
had to be stopped,'' said Ben Dor, a teacher and mother of three
sons. ``For many, many nights afterward, people who had sons in the
army didn't sleep. They were waiting for the devil to come knocking
at their door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Israel, we are all the time thinking that the army knows
what it is doing, and sometimes we have to think twice,'' she
continued. ``Someone should say this is crazy, I decided. It was
crazy to educate our children to be decent and then at 18 send them
places to kill the other people. We should send our children to die
because our leaders can't solve our problems by talking?
</P>
<P>
   ``And on a more specific level, the army's plan wasn't working.
If they were in Lebanon to protect northern Israel, why were the
Katyusha rockets falling on us?''
</P>
<P>
   The women began with small street protests at intersections.
They wrote letters to lawmakers. They organized debates at northern
kibbutzim.
</P>
<P>
   After the first story about them appeared on national
television, they received calls from all over the country. Working
women all, they found themselves at the vanguard of a movement,
without any organization, time or money. And they knew that what
they were doing would take all that plus endurance.
</P>
<P>
   It also took its toll on their families. One mother quit when
her soldier son demanded it. Ben Zvi had a hard time figuring out
how to react when her son, Or, won a medal for fighting in Lebanon.
He asked her if she was proud. And with difficulty she told him he
was, because ``his reality was the war'' and she had raised him to
excel at whatever he did.
</P>
<P>
   On talk shows, the mothers were placed opposite generals who
patted them on the shoulders and rolled their eyes when they spoke.
``It was a tremendous miscalculation,'' Ben Zvi, a professor, said.
Eventually, the military understood that the women were shaping
national opinion, and began to attack them as bad for the morale of
the soldiers and the country.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late; the Israeli news media loved the mothers,
and the public appreciated the way that they memorialized every
soldier who died.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the shift in public sentiment, the three leading
candidates for prime minister in the last election promised to
bring the boys home from Lebanon. Barak, who took office last July,
made it a pledge with a date: by July 7, 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in imitation of a military custom, Ben Dor pinned a
medal on Barak's chest _ with force. It was a Four Mothers button.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers, who will meet on Saturday to vote on whether to put
themselves out of business as an organization, do not need them
anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2009EDT &QL; 
