<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0603-COX     06-02 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Howard suffers new day of losing legal arguments
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tempers flared again Friday among lawyers in the
murder trial against NFL star Ray Lewis as a defense attorney
accused prosecutors of goading the judge into declaring a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, one of several between the prosecution and the
defense, arose while District Attorney Paul Howard questioned
Atlanta police Detective Ken Allen, the lead investigator in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd like to try it all over again,'' Steve Sadow, who
represents co-defendant Joseph Sweeting, said after court
adjourned. ``Howard knows it can't go any worse than it's gone so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard strongly denied that securing a mistrial was his
intention. ``Far from it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney expects to rest his case Monday or early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sadow objected when Howard asked Allen about a statement Lewis
gave the morning Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, were
killed during a Buckhead street fight. Howard wanted Allen to say
whether Lewis told police Sweeting had been with him that night _
knowing Lewis didn't identify his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Sadow vigorously objected, saying it was an improper line of
questioning and that Howard knew it. ``This is in my opinion
prosecutorial misconduct,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner, as she did
repeatedly throughout a day of many defense objections, ruled
against Howard, ordering the prosecutor to steer clear of that line
of questioning.
</P>
<P>
   During the first two weeks of testimony, Bonner has not
hesitated to sustain defense objections over the prosecution's mode
of questioning. ``Mr. Howard, I have ruled'' has become a common
courtroom refrain as Bonner cuts off Howard's protests of her
rulings, urging him to move on.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Howard has taken these rulings in stride.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday he did a slow burn.
</P>
<P>
   After Bonner sustained yet another defense objection, Howard
growled, ``All right.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis defense attorney Tony Axam then leaped to his feet and
told Bonner that Howard's ``All right'' was uttered in an improper,
``derisive tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard, after court adjourned, downplayed his agitation. ``When
you fight for justice and what you think is right . . . you can't
be dissuaded or frustrated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Lollar-Owens, Lollar's aunt, seemed frustrated by the
rulings, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``These other people can submit anything; they can say anything;
they can laugh at anything,'' she said, referring to the defense
teams. ``But (prosecutors) get stopped every time they try
something, every time they say something.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen spent most of the day identifying items in brown evidence
bags containing such items as victims' clothing and bullet casings
found at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's clothing, its belt still looped in his bluejeans and his
slashed jacket, drew sobs from the victim's family. Allen testified
that he twice interviewed limo driver Duane Fassett the day of the
killings. It was during these interviews that Fassett said he saw
Lewis strike a victim and that he overheard co-defendants Sweeting
and Reginald Oakley admit to stabbing the two men. But Fassett did
not deliver this when he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Howard knew he couldn't get into the content of Fassett's
statements and danced around the subject during his examination of
Allen. But when he asked Allen if he obtained an arrest warrant
after interviewing the limo driver, Axam objected again. And Bonner
sustained it.
</P>
<P>
   The flustered district attorney rose to argue, but Bonner cut
him off, saying to the deputies, ``Bring the jury back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
