<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FIRST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAND FOR FIRST NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a sad day when First Night has money troubles.
</P>
<P>
   This celebration of the New Year _ a triumph of cultural good
cheer over winter cold _ is part of what makes Boston Boston.
Indoors and on the streets, this public party has for 25 years
featured art, music, dance, displays, theater, poetry, fireworks,
and fabulous parades _ not to mention the ice sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   After this year's impressive celebration, however, First Night
ended up $750,000 in the red. With work the figure has fallen to
under $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Night is not going under,'' insists the event's
executive director, Geri Guardino. She has already gotten help from
``major stakeholders'' _ a mix of corporations, foundations, and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Guardino expects to cut the remaining deficit by some $450,000
within a month, negotiate a break with some vendors, and carry a
deficit of $150,000 to $200,000 into next year.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sign that Boston-lovers should open their wallets. A
joint infusion of cash could clear First Night's books entirely.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, corporations, foundations, and individuals
who haven't been asked but cherish First Night should contribute.
Over the long term, companies that aren't yet should consider
becoming corporate sponsors. This would free organizers to focus on
one crucial thing _ the coming First Night 2001 celebration. And
vendors could participate with greater confidence.
</P>
<P>
   First Night is an appealing investment. Besides its priceless
emotional worth to the greater Boston area, Guardino points out
that the event has not had an accumulated deficit until now.
Surpluses from years in the black have always made up for years
with losses.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is the birthplace of First Night, and it has become a
model for over 200 similar celebrations. Locally, the event's
Neighborhood Network draws in adult and teenage participants from
all over Boston. This dazzling, precedent-setting hometown party
deserves to be kept in peak financial health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
