A3253 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-JOURNAL-BOS     06-02 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESS TO MEDICAL RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 04, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year, US taxpayers invest more than $17 billion in medical
research through the National Institutes of Health alone. The money
is well spent _ it helps in the development of new drugs, new
surgical techniques, new insights into public health. But the
public has to pay again for access to the fruits of much of this
research.
</P>
<P>
   The former editor of the Journal of the American Medical
Association, George Lundberg, wants to change this. Speaking at the
Harvard School of Public Health last week, Lundberg called on JAMA
and other medical journals, including Boston's New England Journal
of Medicine, to start making available most of the content of their
print magazines on line for free.
</P>
<P>
   It is a worthwhile idea, not least for its benefit to doctors
and lay people in parts of the developing world who cannot afford
either print or Internet subscriptions to the publications. The
proposal comes at a pivotal moment for many medical journals, as
they explore how best to operate in an online environment that is
increasingly swamped by health Web sites that do not adhere to the
same standards of editing, insulation from advertisers' influence,
and peer review that have won the good journals their status.
</P>
<P>
   Three journals _ the British Medical Journal, JAMA, and the
Annals of Internal Medicine _ now put articles on the Internet for
free, but JAMA just announced that it would switch to a
paid-subscription-only service within the next few months.
Officials of the Massachusetts Medical Society, owners of NEJM, are
looking at new print and online options for expanding revenue
potential. Just last year, the longtime editor of the NEJM, Dr.
Jerome Kassirer, was fired for resisting plans of the medical
society to find new ways to profit from NEJM, many of which run the
risk of compromising the standards that have lent the magazine its
prestige.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, NEJM officials note that there is also an
element of self-interest in Lundberg's proposal. He is now editor
of Medscape, a free online service of medical information that
accepts ads. That site would gain some in popularity _ and in
appeal to advertisers _ if it could include links to free articles
at the top journals' sites. Still, there is no question that
Lundberg's plan would expand the public's access to medical
research, and the example of the British Medical Journal, in
particular, shows that it can be made to work.
</P>
<P>
   The trick for journal publishers is to find ways to expand
online access without forgoing too much of the print subscription
and ad revenue that pays for the editing so crucial in setting
peer-reviewed journal articles apart from other Web material. But
the goal of expanding access should be a high priority for
publishers. Not only will greater access improve the public's
health consciousness, it is also a fair payback for the taxpayers'
generous support of medical research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SOUTH-SUBURBS-ART-2TA     06-02 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-SUBURBS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULATION SHIFTS IN THE SOUTHEAST REALIGN POLITICS IN THE SUBURBS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMYRNA, Ga. _ When he was swept into the Georgia House of
Representatives in 1994 at the crest of the Republican revolution,
Randy Sauder seemed to personify Cobb County's reputation as one of
the most conservative suburbs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sauder was in favor of mandatory execution for twice-convicted
murderers, abolishing the state parole board and barring Atlanta's
public transportation system from the county. He became an ally of
fellow Cobb County resident Newt Gingrich and a national Republican
organization voted him the top freshman state legislator in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Sauder infuriated the Republican Party in
Georgia with an audacious heresy. As he saw the future of his
district, he became a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Sauder's conversion says much about the population changes that
are transforming the suburbs of Atlanta and other cities in the
Southeast, rearranging the political order along with the
priorities of state leaders. Nearly 2.5 million Americans moved to
the Southern states along the Atlantic Coast during the 1990s, by
far the largest growth of any region in the country, and they have
proven to be far less conservative than long-term residents.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbs once dominated by religious conservatives are
increasingly home to moderate Republicans, and moderate Republican
districts are teetering on the edge of Democratic reascendancy. As
officials of both parties have begun to move away from divisive
racial and social issues and toward the center, the effect on
public policy has been dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   In state after state, conservative social issues that once
monopolized the conversation of Southern suburbs _ lower taxes,
welfare reform, crackdowns on crime _ have been supplanted by a new
agenda: managing growth and transportation, bringing in technology
jobs and above all, improving education. In a swath of states from
the Carolinas to Mississippi, Democratic governors have made these
issues their own, and Republicans are struggling to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My district has changed so dramatically since I was first
elected,'' Sauder said recently, over biscuits at a Shoney's
restaurant near his house. ``The people moving in want to see
action on issues like education and sprawl, and it's the Democrats
that have grabbed those themes and delivered. The Republicans
around here are seen as bickering and obstructionist.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a matter as racially charged as the Confederate battle flag
on the South Carolina Capitol, which comes down on July 1, has
largely been resolved, mostly at the request of suburban voters who
made it clear they had other priorities.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time as centrist Northerners, mostly white, moved
South, an inner ring of Southern suburbs that were once nearly all
white have become more diverse, attracting large and stable
populations of black, Hispanic and Asian residents who do not as a
rule support a conservative political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In Cobb County, where blacks once had to sue to rent apartments,
the number of black residents has grown fivefold since 1980, rising
to 12 percent of the county's population today from 4 percent 20
years ago, according to the Census Bureau and the county. There has
been a similar shift in other Atlanta suburbs, such as Clayton and
Gwinnett counties, along with suburbs of Charlotte and
Raleigh-Durham in North Carolina, and Columbia in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The population shifts, driven by the South's quickening economy
and the prosperity of a mobile middle class, do not necessarily
presage a partisan realignment like the mass movement of white
Southern Democrats to the Republican Party in the 1980s and 1990s.
Nor are they necessarily good news for Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although two state legislators have switched to the Democratic
Party in South Carolina, and more could do so in Georgia, the
pendulum swing is more ideological than political. Its most lasting
effect may be a race by officials of both parties to the center,
mostly at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the explosion of new residents in the 1990s
has actually produced a new breed of Republican in a state
dominated for decades by Democrats and religious conservatives.
They seem to be precisely the kind of voters targeted by the
campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As North Carolina has filled up with cul-de-sacs, we have
become simultaneously more Republican and far less conservative,''
said John N. Davis, executive director of the North Carolina Forum
for Research and Economic Education, a nonprofit, research group
supported by business that conducts surveys of newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are pro-government Republicans, who want the best soccer
fields, schools and police departments that government money can
buy,'' Davis said. ``And suddenly you see formerly conservative
candidates for office pushing education and environment programs
that they would have tried to cut 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that many of the newcomers come from the Northeast where
it is normal to be Republican and moderate or Republican and
left-of-center, a combination rare in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Native Southerners, whether Democratic or Republican, identify
themselves as conservative far more often than newcomers in his
organization's polls, he said. A similar survey by the University
of North Carolina last year showed that 34 percent of non-native
Southerners considered themselves conservative, compared to 42
percent of native Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers are prodding elected officials to be more aggressive
about spending tax money on their priorities. In the last three
years, residents in 19 out of 20 counties in the Atlanta area have
voted to raise their sales taxes to pay for schools and other
projects, often by overwhelming margins.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
