<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SOUTH-SUBURBS-ART-2ND     06-02 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-SUBURBS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SMYRNA, Ga.: overwhelming margins. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Cobb County, where voters raised the sales tax in 1998 for
new schools, the county commission has proposed a tax increase to
buy parkland, and commissioners say they believe voters will
support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinnett County, a northeast Atlanta suburb that has been a
developer's paradise, recently imposed a seven-month moratorium on
rezonings. (The move is mostly symbolic, but coincides neatly with
the re-election campaigns of most of the county commissioners.)
Suburban politicians make it clear that in both substance and
style, they are following a more mellow electorate.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``My district is still a conservative place, but the social
issues of the '90s are not the fundamental foundation of people's
politics anymore,'' said Rep. Johnny Isakson, a Republican who
replaced Gingrich in Georgia's 6th Congressional District and whose
easygoing moderation bears no resemblance to his predecessor's
partisan fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken care of matters like a balanced budget and welfare
reform,'' Isakson said, ``and now people are more concerned about
quality of life issues, education and transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Bill Clinton made an art out of appropriating
Republican themes, Democratic governors in the Southeast have edged
aside Republicans in seizing the issues at the top of suburban
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who have opposed Democratic initiatives to raise
teacher salaries and hold schools accountable with testing regimens
are gleefully painted as obstructionist, and the effects are
visible. Both legislators in South Carolina who switched to the
Democratic Party complained that Republican leaders tried to force
them to vote against education programs that their constituents
supported.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans insisted that the party-switching did not
represent a trend, and that deeply conservative values still
prevailed in the South. Q. Whitfield Ayres, a Republican pollster
in Atlanta, said the increased emphasis on quality-of-life issues
was the result of an improved economy, not a political shift. But
other Republicans said their party had fallen behind in the race to
capture newcomers with unpledged loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transformation is going on around the South, and the
Republican leadership just does not get it,'' said Matt Towery, a
Republican and former state representative from Cobb County who was
Gingrich's campaign chairman for many years. ``They're still
talking about tax cuts, but the Democrats now have the issues that
appeal to presidential-year voters, the environment, gun safety.
You can't win these counties as a gun-toting, anti-abortion
Republican anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But partisanship still prevails. All but one of the 16
Republican state legislators from Gwinnett County voted against
Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes' overhaul of Georgia's education system,
which passed nonetheless. The law mandates many of the ideas that
Republicans have championed: smaller class sizes, an end to teacher
tenure, strict accountability of each school, as measured by
comprehensive tests.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed the bill, Barnes deliberately chose a school in
the district of the one Gwinnett Republican who had supported him.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, in fact, has been one of the South's shrewdest observers
of these demographic trends, assembling an agenda with
pitch-perfect resonance for suburban voters _ the education bill, a
powerful new transportation and planning authority, a managed-care
bill of rights _ while also retaining his popularity among urban
and rural residents.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked to strengthen the Democratic majority in the
Georgia Legislature in anticipation of the redistricting that will
follow this year's census, targeting districts like Sauder's in
Smyrna. (If he had not switched, Sauder acknowledges, he would
eventually have faced a Democratic opponent with the governor's
strong backing.)
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Kahn, the governor's chief of staff and principal
political strategist, said the population shifts in Georgia have
been of significant benefit to the Democrats, and could make a
difference in Gore's favor this November, although the state is
considered a tossup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outer ring of suburbs are still very Republican, but some
of the counties on the inner ring that had gone Republican are
clearly trending back to the Democrats,'' he said. ``I think Gore
could do better in the suburbs than people expect, particularly
with women. In a close state, you make an impact at the margin, and
the suburbs are the margin now.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those swing districts is likely to be in Smyrna and the
south Cobb area, home to both Sauder and, before he moved to the
governor's mansion, to Barnes. The district has become one of the
fastest-growing integrated regions in Georgia, a leading
destination for middle- and upper-middle-class white and black
families buying homes in the $200,000 range and above. Kahn said
the governor's hometown of Mableton, just southwest of Smyrna, is
now about equally black and white.
</P>
<P>
   The welcome mat for black home buyers represents quite a
turnaround for Smyrna. As recently as 1988, Aunt Fanny's Cabin, a
restaurant with a slavery theme, could be found in Smyrna. But the
restaurant closed in 1994, the city replaced its decaying downtown
with a landscaped civic center and professionals caught in
Atlanta's rush hour began to appreciate Smyrna's easy access to
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Keith De Cay, one of many black homeowners who bought a house in
the affluent Austin Lake section of Smyrna recently, said he was
impressed by the city's friendliness, selecting it after a transfer
from New Orleans based on the number of residents who offered to
give him directions when he pretended to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lifelong Democrat, and I had heard this was a very
Republican area, so I didn't know what to expect,'' said De Cay, an
executive with Dataradio Corp., which makes wireless modems. ``But
I just haven't found that old-guard kind of politics here. They're
building schools and community centers and parks, and that's what I
want to see my elected officials do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
