<HEADER>
A3257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SLAIN-TEACHER0603-COX     06-02 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAIN-TEACHER0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A shaken widow thanks the public for their support
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In her first public statement since her
husband was shot and killed outside his classroom, Pam Grunow
avoided the political questions that others around the nation have
been asking.
</P>
<P>
   Trembling but holding back tears Friday morning, Grunow thanked
the school, strangers across the country, the community and
``Barry's basketball buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   She was a reluctant spokeswoman who had to exit early from the
17-minute news conference to keep from losing her composure. Her
lawyers and a public relations firm organized the Sheraton Hotel
news conference for her and three of Barry Grunow's siblings in
response to a barrage of interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still in shock and I am unable to comprehend,'' said the
widow, wearing her husband's wedding ring on a chain around her
neck.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Christopher Larmoyeux, deflected questions about
gun control, school safety and youth violence. Pam Grunow, her
brothers-in-law Kurt and Steve Grunow, and sister-in-law Kay
Nichols concentrated on thanking the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family intends to be part of that debate. But not today,''
Larmoyeux said. ``Let's give these folks some space, let them find
their own answers.''
</P>
<P>
   They were reluctant to answer questions about Nathaniel Brazill,
and whether the 13-year-old gunman should be tried as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Barry Krischer, who favors trying the teenager as
an adult, has left messages for family members but has not
discussed the case with them, according to Krischer spokesman Mike
Edmondson. Larmoyeux said the family will set up a meeting with
Krischer next week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's news conference came a week after Brazill shot and
killed Barry Grunow on the last day of classes at Lake Worth Middle
School. In that time, Pam Grunow has gone from an anonymous
stay-at-home mother of two to the focus of a news conference that
would be televised live locally and replayed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The one message she wished to offer the world concerned Barry
Grunow's dedication to friends, family and community, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't go anywhere without Barry's students coming up and
saying 'Mr. Grunow, Mr. Grunow,''' she recalled, the only time she
smiled during the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Grunow's brother Steve came the closest among family
members to entering the debate over school violence, vaguely
suggesting the family would work to make sure this never happens
again.
</P>
<P>
   But he focused on thanking the community for the good they'd
done: taking care of Pam and Barry Grunow's house and children,
cooking food for them, bringing cookies, sending gifts and flowers,
creating a memorial at Lake Worth Middle School, writing poems and
songs.
</P>
<P>
   The school district voted earlier this week to pay the family
Barry Grunow's $40,809 full salary for the next 17 years, when he
would have been eligible for retirement. Pam Grunow will get
another $145,000 from other public sources. Callers to local radio
station WRMF have donated more than $20,000 toward the two
children's education, and an officer at First United Bank said
corporate sponsors and individuals have sent more dollars from
around the world to an account set up in the family's name. The
family's probate attorney, Bob Sorgini, said he did not yet know
how much the family has received in donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important, obviously, that Pam and (5-year-old
son) Sam and (9-month-old daughter) Lee-Anne can have, hopefully,
as normal a life as possible after this,'' Steve Grunow said during
his brief statement.
</P>
<P>
   Larmoyeux said the family had not decided whether to sue. His
law firm has begun its own investigation into the shooting, though
he stressed that he would not interfere with police and
prosecutors. The family will offer more detailed statements about
the crime itself and related issues after the grand jury meets,
most likely sometime this month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larmoyeux, whose partner Bob Montgomery led a multi-billion
dollar lawsuit against the tobacco industry, said the gun
manufacturer Phoenix Arms and the school district would be included
in his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the world wants to know why,'' Larmoyeux said. ``And all
of those individuals have to be able to answer the question, why?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
