<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA WARNS ALASKA AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing about 150 instances of ``sloppiness'' in record-keeping
and maintenance oversight at Alaska Airlines, Federal Aviation
Administration officials said Friday they are prepared to prohibit
the airline from performing major maintenance work on its own
planes.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Seattle-based airline improves its maintenance system
and oversight, the prohibition could lead to the grounding of
Alaska Airlines' 89-plane fleet, one aircraft at a time, as the
planes are scheduled to receive so-called heavy maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented proposal gives Alaska Airlines seven days to
respond. If an adequate remedy cannot be found within 30 days after
that, the FAA will bar the airline from doing heavy maintenance
that is performed on aircraft at regular intervals.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has flights in Alaska, the western United States,
and Mexico. It does not have any flights in New England.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said they found no examples of maintenance
problems that could have affected a plane's safety of flight, but
said the problems uncovered were very serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The root cause was the result of management effectiveness and
a certain amount of sloppiness,'' said Nick Lacey, director of the
FAA's Flight Standards Service.
</P>
<P>
   The action comes out of a special FAA inspection of the carrier
in the wake of the Jan. 31 crash of an Alaska Airlines MD-80 off
the coast of Southern California that killed all 88 on board.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection, which is continuing and may result in civil
fines, found:
</P>
<P>
   --Instances of planes being put back into service when records
did not reflect that all necessary work had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   --Procedures for in-depth inspections of aircraft were not
adequately defined in company manuals.
</P>
<P>
   -- In-house audits were unable to detect and correct problems
within the maintenance department.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said it was highly unlikely that the airline could
implement corrective policies and actions and prove their
effectiveness within the 37 days. The FAA, however, could extend
the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kelly, chairman and chief executive of Alaska Airlines,
Friday said the company would meet the seven-day deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to say that many if not all of the findings the
FAA outlined . . . were addressed by us over recent weeks as soon
as they were raised by the FAA during its audit.'' The airline has
rewritten its maintenance manual and has taken initial steps to
improve its in-house review.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the action gives the company the chance ``to prove to
the FAA, the traveling public and ourselves that the changes we've
already instituted are working and are making us a better
airline.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the accident, several other problems at the
airline _ including the firing this week of two pilots who failed
to adequately pressurize the cabin and then continued the flight _
and the government oversight will damage the public's perception of
the airline, which has had an enviable safety record.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Alaska Airlines fell $1.1875, about 4 percent, to
$30.75 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Jan. 31 accident involved a malfunction of the
horizontal stabilizer, and a sitting grand jury is investigating
maintenance practices at the airline's facility in Oakland, Calif.,
the FAA inspection focused on maintenance by the airline at its
facilities in Oakland and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's 16 inspectors on the special investigation and Alaska
Airlines then reviewed the 79 aircraft in the fleet that had gone
through heavy maintenance and found about 150 examples of problems
with either the documentation of the work completed, or the
inspections of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is serious that the company did not pick up on these
problems,'' Lacey said. ``This is more than a paperwork problem.
Aviation accidents come as a result of small errors and the
inability to detect small errors.''
</P>
<P>
   All planes were reinspected to make sure all the work was done,
and ``we did not find anything that would affect the safety of
flight of the aircraft. If we had found sloppy maintenance, or
found serious corrosion we would have taken a different action,''
Lacey said, referring to shutting the airline down.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Alaska will not be able to outsource its
heavy maintenance ``because if they cannot assure the quality of
their own maintenance, we will not allow it to be done by anyone
else,'' Lacey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said the FAA will continue to provide extra oversight of
the airline for the short term, but cannot continue it
indefinitely, which means the airplanes will be grounded if Alaska
management cannot remedy the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has hired consultants to help them improve the
oversight of the maintenance program.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines will also be required to submit a growth plan to
the FAA district office for any proposed expansion of services.
</P>
<P>
   While some industry observers said the proposed FAA action
reflects a tougher agency than the one that seemed supportive of
ValuJet even after one of its planes crashed in Florida in 1996
killing everyone on board, Lacey said the FAA has also learned from
the Alaska audit.
</P>
<P>
   FAA inspectors who are regularly assigned to the airline did not
pick up on the problems. ``The principal inspector has been here
eight years and that may have been too long,'' Lacey said. ``We
will continue to look at what we can do better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-DEATH-BOS &LR;      06-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PENALTY WITHOUT COMPASSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 04, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush sought to put his
``compassionate'' side on display last week by giving a 30-day
reprieve to a man on death row to allow further DNA testing of
evidence in his case. No American who cares about equal justice
should be reassured by this move.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1995 Bush has executed 131 inmates, more
than any other governor. He has pushed for accelerated appeals, so
Texas now leads the nation in the pace of executions. The state
does not have a ``life without parole'' option, which many who
support capital punishment say they would prefer if it were
available. Texas also does not forbid the execution of the mentally
retarded. Bush has done nothing to change this.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Bush vetoed a modest ``indigent defense bill,'' which
would have established a statewide legal aid program to provide
lawyers for poor criminal defendants. Texas has no such program.
Instead, defendants are represented in court by lawyers who are
often friends or campaign contributors of the state's elected
judges. The legal representation provided such poor defendants has
been spotty, at best. Some of the lawyers have been literally
caught napping in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide has been running against Texas on the death
penalty, and Governor Bush appears to have taken notice. His own
Illinois state campaign chairman, Republican Governor George Ryan,
called a moratorium on executions earlier this year, after DNA
testing proved several death row inmates were innocent. At least a
dozen other states have moratorium bills pending in their
legislatures, and there is one in Congress, sponsored by Senator
Russell Feingold of Wisconsin. New Hampshire's legislature voted to
ban capital punishment outright, but the bill was vetoed by
Governor Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said he would support DNA testing ``to erase any
doubts or concerns'' about innocent people being executed, though
only a handful of states guarantee post-conviction DNA testing for
the condemned, and Texas isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of more sophisticated DNA tests has, paradoxically,
been a boon for both opponents and defendants of capital
punishment. A national organizing drive called ``the innocence
project,'' supported mostly by law and journalism students, has
succeeded in overturning dozens of death row cases by demanding DNA
tests whenever physical evidence was available. But death penalty
supporters like Bush rely on DNA to bolster claims that the system
works. In February, Bush boasted: ``I am confident that every
person put to death under my watch in Texas has been guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, however, the verdict hinges not on physical
evidence that can be tested but on eyewitness testimony, which is
both very powerful to jurors and notoriously unreliable. The system
is still fraught with prejudice and error.
</P>
<P>
   The probability that innocent poeple are being executed may be
the most compelling reason to oppose capital punishment, but it is
not the only one. Capital punishment does not deter crime. It is
worth remembering that states with death penalties do not have
lower crime rates than those without; quite the opposite is true.
No state in New England has executed a prisoner since the Supreme
Court declared the punishment constitutional in 1976, and it has
the lowest regional crime rate in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The United States stands in the ignoble company of Congo, China,
and Iran among top countries putting prisoners to death, and it is
increasingly isolated among the world's democracies. The punishment
is degrading, uncivilized, and brutalizing to the entire society.
There is nothing compassionate about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
