<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      06-02 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVRATILOVA SHOWS FLASHES OF OLD FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Ghost walked into an intimate tennis parlor named
Court 1, smiled at the solid wave of applause from 3,518 patrons
filling the concrete bowl, and was surprised to hear them begin
singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were singing for my opponent, Sabine Appelmans,''
said the lefthanded ghost, with a laugh. ``She's been voted
Belgium's most desirable woman, so I guess the place was loaded
with Belgians.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Sinatra wasn't around to sing ``Young at Heart'' to
this Ghost of Championships Past, whose baptismal name you may
recognize: Martina Navratilova.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it is like seeing a ghost, watching Navratilova again.
Making some of the good old moves at Stade Roland Garros Thursday,
this good old girl of 43 stole a piece of the French Open show with
her lifelike reappearance _ and a victory _ almost as we remember
her.
</P>
<P>
   Her brilliant career was supposedly interred six years ago with
appropriate written and spoken eulogies at Madison Square Garden,
buried in defeat by Gabriela Sabatini (although she did play a
couple of mixed doubles tourneys). Sabatini has vanished, but here
is Navratilova again. Inhabiting a major stage once more, she's
doing a second-coming shtick _ doubles only _ on hallowed dirt
where she holds the local record of seven such titles, the first
back in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose she hits the jackpot again alongside 29-year-old Mariaan
de Swardt? Would it be a grande dame's resurrection, something like
80-year-old Jessica Tandy winning an Oscar for ``Driving Miss
Daisy'' in 1989? What's driving Miss Martina here, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun,'' she said, after the nearly two-hour, first-round
excursion into dusk, a thriller that she and de Swardt, a South
African, snatched from the Belgian-Italian alliance of Appelmans
and Rita Grande, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ``That was a blast. The competitive
juices are flowing again.''
</P>
<P>
   She's five wins short of a title, of course. Whatever, nobody
had ever before won a major match so long after the embalming of a
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I doing it? Because I can,'' she said with a grin.
``Winter of '99 I was feeling out of shape, and I didn't like it. I
started to work out again, played basketball, some tennis. And
hockey _ my team just won the Colorado women's championship. We are
tough. It was great for the legs. I'm as fit as I ever was. So I
thought, well, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not a comeback,'' she insisted. ``Just four
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it a cameo-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, I could play decent singles,'' she said. ``If I was
down-and-out financially and had to, I believe I could return to
the tour and make a living. I'm not saying what kind of living. But
I wouldn't starve. Which reminds me, I'd better start bringing my
own food to the tournament like I used to do. In the players'
dining room I counted 18 different desserts and not one vegetable
dish. French cooking is great _ but not for an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' she said, pointing to a clay smudge on her
right knee. ``That's from getting way down on volleys. You do that
enough and, if you're not in shape at my age, you can't get out of
bed the next day. I won't feel it. I'm ready for more.''
</P>
<P>
   She is holding her beloved, crippled Bina, a two-legged toy fox
terrier. ``A thalidomide puppy she was, but you should see her get
around like a kangaroo,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Navratilova was getting around a lot better than de Swardt, whom
you may recall as the 1998 winner of the Boston Cup, the WTA Tour
stopover staged at Babson College in Wellesley. Her flying volleys
and the savvy of a woman who owns a record 162 doubles titles
remain. That held them together until de Swardt got her power and
touch harnessed in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a partner stronger and faster than me. Well, Mariaan
is a much bigger hitter,'' Navratilova said. ``We're friends who
communicate a lot. She'd been out, injured, and didn't have a
partner. She wanted very much to play Wimbledon, and asked me if
I'd play with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me thinking. Wimbledon is bringing back old champions
to celebrate 2000, and I'm doing some TV. So, OK. But I said I
can't jump right into Wimbledon and embarrass myself. Mariaan
wanted to play 10 tournaments. Nope. Too much. I figured we could
build up playing Madrid (where they went 1-1), here, then grass at
Eastbourne and Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I love the grass,'' on which she won 19 Big W
titles, an untouched nine in singles. ``I don't want to hear about
Billie Jean's record.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the 20 overall titles that Billie Jean King
hung up at Wimbledon, the last paired with Navratilova in 1979.
``I'm not trying to get a piece of that, just have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, King wished her ``the best of luck. It would be
great if Martina and Mariaan won. She'd be the only player to win
Wimbledon titles in four different decades.''
</P>
<P>
   As Navratilova departed Court 1, she was beaming, her blue eyes
gleaming behind the granny glasses as she inhaled the applause and
the aroma of one more victory _ her 991st in doubles, if you must
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better than the last time I was here, 1994,'' she said. ``I
lost to Miriam Oremans in the first round and smashed my racket to
smithereens. I thought it was my last match in Paris. Court 1. I
didn't make it to Court Central, where I won all my titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess I exorcised a few ghosts on this court,'' said the
Ghost of Championships Past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
