A3264 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLAN     06-02 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTAVIO'S RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Tonight at the Rose Bowl, the Los Angeles
Galaxy meets Galaxy East _ otherwise known as the New York/New
Jersey MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   The player allocation that brought Mexican superstar Luis
Hernandez to the Galaxy also paid huge dividends for the
MetroStars. Two Galaxy starters, Clint Mathis and Roy Myers, were
sent from L.A. to New York, where they joined Galaxy alumni Steve
Jolley, Mark Semioli and Daniel Hernandez on a team that appears to
be on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars are led by former Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano,
fired by L.A. five games into the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   New York is coming off its biggest win of the season, having
defeated the Chicago Fire 4-1 last week with goals from Jolley and
Mathis and an assist from Myers. The Metros are 5-6 after a poor
start.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is heading the other direction, struggling through a
1-1-4 stretch. L.A. has the second-best record in the league at
6-1-6.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars might have the Galaxy right where they want them.
The Galaxy is missing striker Cobi Jones and defender Greg Vanney,
who are with the U.S. national team during the U.S. Cup. MLS
all-star defender Robin Fraser is injured and striker Sebastian
Vorbe is with Haiti's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Octavio said he couldn't wait to play us with his whole
team,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``He should be happy we're
not playing him with our whole team, but we're happy to play them
either way. We're not going to cry about things.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano will not be on the field tonight. He was red-carded
during a team scuffle with the Fire last week. He will watch the
game from the press box.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, the Metros have plenty to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, this will mean something extra for the guys who were in
L.A.,'' said Zambrano. ``I think all of them in one way or another
feel they weren't part of the nucleus here, otherwise they wouldn't
be with us. They want to win this one badly, there's no doubt about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano is not convinced the Galaxy is a depleted team since
the Hernandez signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all, the Galaxy is still the team to beat,'' said
Zambrano. ``They finally got the piece they were looking for to
take them to a championship and this team has to win a
championship. There's no reason why they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about chemistry and their loss of players?
</P>
<P>
   ``They got Luis Hernandez,'' Zambrano said. ``He's the type who
can win you a championship. There are very few foreign players who
have his kind of impact on a team. I don't think anyone would
disagree that Luis is the best foreign striker in our league's
market. He will carry that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he might have a few surprises in his lineup.
Midfield/striker Sasha Victorine played defense in a scrimmage this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A win) could set a great tone,'' said Schmid. ``But I told
our guys not to be concerned about the results as much as us
playing good soccer. We haven't played good soccer in the last
three to four weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
