A3266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CUBA-U.S.-CLAIMS-NYT &LR;      06-02 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-U.S.-CLAIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA CALLED WILLING TO NEGOTIATE WITH U.S. FIRMS WHOSE ASSETS IT
SEIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cuba is prepared to negotiate with U.S. companies
that had property confiscated when Fidel Castro came to power 41
years ago, according to a U.S. Chamber of Commerce official who
returned from Havana on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A dialogue on settling claims would be the first since Castro
took power in 1959 and seized assets from many foreigners who owned
houses or did business there. The United States and Cuba do not
have formal diplomatic relations and have not held bilateral talks
on the disputed assets, Clinton administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is being made as several U.S. lawmakers, the Chamber
of Commerce and some American corporate executives have sought to
improve ties with Cuba, which is subject to a strict trade embargo
by the United States. Some U.S. companies are eager to see the
embargo eased so that they can conduct business in Cuba, where
Canadian and European rivals have invested hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber vice president, L. Craig Johnstone, said senior
Cuban officials were ``receptive to the notion'' of negotiating
settlements when he met them this week. He said Foreign Affairs
Minister Felipe Perez-Roque and the president of the National
Assembly, Ricardo Alarcon, were among the officials who expressed
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong sentiment in Cuba today that the relationship
has the potential of improving,'' Johnstone said. ``I think this is
an attempt to incur good will and appear reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban Foreign Ministry official said Friday that he had no
information about discussions with Johnstone. He said his
government had long offered to discuss compensation claims with the
United States, because Cuba wants to be compensated for losses
incurred under the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5,900 U.S. companies and individuals have $6 billion in
claims against the Cuban government for property seized after 1959,
an administration official said. The claims were adjudicated by
U.S. courts in the 1970s and have been pending since then. The
official said he was not aware of any recent Cuban offers to
discuss settlements.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said that they do not expect much progress in
resolving asset claims until relations with Cuba are normalized.
But the overture by Cuban officials seems intended to bolster U.S.
business support for better ties between the nations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone said the negotiations would be sponsored by the
Washington-based chamber and held outside diplomatic channels. He
said the Cuban officials indicated a preference for discussing
claims with selected U.S. companies, but added that they did not
rule out resolving disputes with other claimants down the road.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many U.S. claimants are eager to reach
settlements with Cuba outside official channels. Johnstone said
that several companies within the chamber's corporate membership
have indicated a willingness to do so, but he declined to name
them.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate attempt to improve commercial ties, Cuban
officials agreed for the first time to allow a delegation of
private restaurateurs and farmers to visit the United States in
September, Johnstone said. He called the exchange a breakthrough
because it would allow a relatively obscure part of the Cuban
economy to emerge into the international spotlight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
