<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-NORTHEASTERN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHEASTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEASTERN NAMES NEW HEAD FOOTBALL COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Brown took over as Northeastern's head football coach
Thursday with the blessings of his former boss, University of
Massachusetts coach Mark Whipple, himself a candidate for the
Huskies' job 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don is an excellent coach and person,'' said Whipple of Brown,
a 1976 Norwich University graduate and former All-New England
running back. ``He'll get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don was my assistant at Brown and here at UMass. We had
success working together at both places and I feel he'll do a
terrific job. He has a solid background and I'll miss him. But he
deserves a chance to be a head coach at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Word around Amherst was that if Whipple were to leave, he'd have
been succeeded by Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a native of Spencer, Mass., replaces Barry Gallup, who
resigned last month after nine seasons to become director of
football operations at Boston College. Gallup beat out Whipple, who
was head coach at New Haven, and BC's Tom O'Brien, for the NU job
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who signed a multiyear contarct, was one of three
finalists, according to NU athletic director Ian McCaw. ``We had
over 60 applicants and I broke it down to eight,'' McCaw said. ``Of
those eight, three were interviewed: (Maine coach) Jack Cosgrove,
(Harvard assistant) Bruce Tall, and Don. Don was a nice fit. I feel
very comfortable with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern's four captains, Steve Arienta, Kyle Porter, Matt
Comella, and Chris McEwan attended each interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about playing for Coach Brown even if this is my
last year,'' said Arienta, a tight end from Parsippany, N.J. ``I
like him. He's honest and right to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also appreciate the defense he threw at us last year when we
played UMass. His teams do a lot on defense. I saw UMass films last
season and played against UMass and I really liked what he
installed.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass defeated Northeastern, 77-0, last season.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five decades, Northeastern has been a graveyard
for coaches. In nine seasons Gallup was 38-60-1 with winning
seasons in 1996 (6-5) and 1997 (8-3); Paul Pawlak was 35-67-1 from
1981 to '90; and Robert ``Bo'' Lyons was 34-52-1 from 1972 to '80.
</P>
<P>
   The last Husky coach with a winning record for his career was
Joe Zabilski, who was 101-76-6 from 1948-71. Many of NU's opponents
were in Division 2 and 3 during those years.
</P>
<P>
   The past figures don't bother Brown, who is known for defensive
expertise. ``I believe in the now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's defenses at Plymouth State (1993-95) were feared and
respected. He stressed an intelligent, swarming defense that
featured quickness and the ability to adapt. His 1998 Brown defense
held opponents to 19.4 points a game, the Bears' best in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is to attack from both sides of the ball,'' said
Brown. ``We will be a ready football team and we will play with
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I have to let the dust settle and next week I'll
talk with all the coaches who assisted Barry Gallup. We'll see what
fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I have to say I'm excited about Northeastern even
more now than before the first interview. Meeting the four captains
told me a lot about the Northeastern players and the program. They
made me want the job even more. I can't wait to meet the rest of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown repeated the words aggressive and intensity several times.
His wife, Debbie, said, ``We've been close since I was 10 years
old. He's that kind of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown started coaching at Hartford (Vt.) High School and went on
to coach at Mansfield University in Pennsylvania and Dartmouth
under Joe Yukica. He made a name for himself as a defensive whiz at
Yale under Carm Cozza from 1987-93.
</P>
<P>
   At Plymouth State, Brown's teams posted a 25-6 record, including
back-to-back undefeated regular seasons, two Freedom Conference
titles, and two trips to the NCAA Division 3 playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
