<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-     06-02 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES UNITED EUROPE TO INCLUDE RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (SUBS for complete rewrite including byline, dateline; story is now
500 words longer)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AACHEN, Germany _ Honored in this ancient European center for
his service to European unity, President Clinton Friday urged
America's European allies to invite Russia into their military and
political unions.
</P>
<P>
   Standing under an unforgiving sun in the courtyard of the
ninth-century cathedral where Charlemagne is buried and where many
Holy Roman emperors and German kings were crowned, Clinton told an
audience of several hundred people that to do otherwise would
destroy the vision of an undivided Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered his speech after he was awarded the
Charlemagne Award, which is given to a world leader who furthers
the cause of European unity.
</P>
<P>
   And in the spirit of unity on the eve of a two-day summit
meeting in Moscow with President Vladimir Putin, he made clear that
Russia deserved Europe's warm embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't yet know if Russia's hard-won democratic freedoms
will endure,'' Clinton said, citing the country's economic crisis
and the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But he envisioned a time when a prosperous, democratic Russia
would be offered membership in NATO, the military alliance created
a half-century ago to contain the Soviet threat, and in the
15-member European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the stakes are so high, we must do everything we can
to encourage a Russia that is fully democratic and united in its
diversity; a Russia that defines its greatness not by dominance of
its neighbors, but by the dominant achievements of its people and
its partnership; a Russia that should be, indeed, must be, fully
part of Europe,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means no doors can be sealed shut to Russia _ not NATO's,
not the EU's,'' he said. ``The alternative would be a future of
harmful competition.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that if Russia decided it did not want to join NATO and
the European Union, then they must make sure that their eastward
expansion does not create ``barriers to trade, travel and security
cooperation'' with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has long said Russia could eventually
become a member of NATO if it met the military alliance's stringent
requirements. Up to now, Russia has shown no interest in joining.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, it has been a member of the interim Partnership for
Peace, a sort of junior partnership in NATO that includes no
military umbrella. In 1997, NATO and Russia signed an agreement
that allows for additional consultations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Clinton nor the Europeans have ever suggested that
Russia should join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton characterized his views as part of larger strategy for
the transformation of Russia from a hostile dictatorship to a
friendly democracy that belongs to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do everything we can to encourage a Russia that is
fully democratic,'' he said. ``Though Russia's transformation is
incomplete, there clearly is reason for hope in Russia's remarkable
journey over these last few years _ from dictatorship to
democracy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He offered no blueprint on how to reach such ambitious goals.
But this is the last scheduled trip to Europe in the his
presidency, and Clinton was in a mood to be magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture could also be seen as a symbolic peace offering to
Moscow, defining Russia as a great power and potential partner as
Clinton and Putin prepare for talks on such contentious issues as
Washington's proposal to develop a limited missile defense system
and Russia's prosecution of the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the other essential task for the Europeans was to
bring the Balkan region into the global mainstream. ``That is the
only way to make peace last in that bitterly divided region,'' he
said. ``Our goal must be to de-Balkanize the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also challenged the image of the United States as
a superpower bully with more power, money, military might and
political will than Europe, and portrayed it instead as a close
friend who wanted to pay his respects and clear up what he called
``potentially harmful misperceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception right now in America that Europe doesn't
always carry its fair share of our mutual responsibilities,'' he
said. As proof that the statement was untrue, he pointed out that
Europeans were providing more than 80 percent of peacekeeping
troops in Kosovo and of the money for economic reconstruction
there. He also said Europeans paid for more than 60 percent of all
aid to Central America after it was ravaged by Hurricane Mitch in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, there is a perception in Europe that
America's power _ military, economic, cultural _ is at times too
overbearing,'' Clinton added. He acknowledged that America's
dominant military role in NATO's air campaign in Kosovo accentuated
such fears.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was welcomed to Aachen by Mayor Juergen Linden and
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Linden put a yellow-ribboned medallion over Clinton's head, as
10 other medallion-wearing recipients of the award, including
President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic and King Juan Carlos
of Spain, looked on from the makeshift stage.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was fitting for what may be Clinton's most
comprehensive reflections on Europe in the final months of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Although Aachen, a western city a few miles from the Belgian and
Dutch borders, was severely damaged during World War II, in 1944 it
became the first German city to be occupied by the United States.
Today, it is on the cutting edge of Europe's information economy.
</P>
<P>
   In honoring Clinton for his contributions to Europe, Schroeder
praised him for ``preserving, strengthening and further
developing'' America's partnership in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton becomes the third American, following former secretaries
of state George Marshall, the architect of the plan to rebuild
Europe after World War II, and Henry Kissinger, to receive the
award.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he would donate the $2,500 that comes with
the award to a student exchange program between the sister cities
of Aachen and Arlington, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
