<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MCCAW-TELEDESIC-ART-$     06-02 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAW-TELEDESIC-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAN CRAIG McCAW KEEP HIS VISION OF TELEDESIC FROM CRASHING  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sun., June 4) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ It's time for the latest installment of ``Who
Wants to Second-Guess a Billionaire?'' In today's episode, Craig
McCaw, the publicity-shy cable television and telecommunications
entrepreneur with a fabled knack for anticipating the future, hits
quicksand in his pursuit of a high-risk dream.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's investments include a maze of advanced wired and
wireless services. But none presents a more formidable puzzle than
Teledesic, his futuristic scheme to dot the heavens with a
288-satellite network for voice and data communications.
</P>
<P>
   To most satellite experts, Teledesic's prospects have always
seemed uncertain. But the outlook for attracting investors would
appear to be considerably gloomier now that the spectacular
bankruptcy of the Iridium phone system, problems in several other
satellite ventures and the relentless advances of land-based
competitors have confirmed Wall Street's worst fears about how
tough it is to build a successful satellite business.
</P>
<P>
   Teledesic is already scaled back from the mind-boggling
840-satellite system McCaw first announced in 1994 and the start of
service has been delayed from 2001 to 2005. Still, the venture
McCaw has referred to as ``an Internet in the sky'' remains by far
the most ambitious commercial project in space.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, McCaw and his backers put up $1.2 billion to
take control of bankrupt ICO Global Communications, a smaller
satellite venture. But that hardly made the outlook any clearer.
ICO could, as McCaw contends, be a steppingstone to Teledesic. Some
experts, however, predict it will become the rationale for scaling
back Teledesic into a more marketable venture.
</P>
<P>
   For now though, Teledesic continues to grandly promise nothing
less than a full array of high-speed video, data, and voice
services to the vast portions of the planet beyond the reach of
today's ground-based wired and wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thinking of tens of millions of customers for
satellites,'' said Samuel A. Farrer Jr., a Reston, Va.-based
satellite expert. ``No one else is talking those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one else would dare to. In an age of singular
entrepreneurs who have achieved unfathomable wealth by leading the
charge into the Information Age, the 50-year-old McCaw has been
among the boldest, repeatedly going deeply into debt to buy
licenses and communications properties that soared in value as he
improved them and new technology spread.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say they have often talked of the need to be ``90
percent'' certain before embarking on a new investment or strategy.
``But Craig's feeling of 90 percent was often Craig alone,'' said
Wayne Perry, who was a young Seattle attorney helping an equally
youthful McCaw buy cable television companies when he went to work
full time for him in 1975. ``It might be 40 percent to someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the complexity of the challenges facing Teledesic,
consider the hurdles that were already in its path when Iridium
collapsed last summer.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, rapidly evolving and expanding terrestrial
services have been chipping away at the parts of the world for
which satellites had been the only option.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, demand for satellite systems is certain to be
fragmented among services already in orbit or soon to be there.
Teledesic's focus is on computer users at fixed sites rather than
mobile customers like ICO Global and other satellite phone
companies. But those who might compete in certain segments range
from international phone companies like Globalstar, a Vodafone
Airtouch PLC subsidiary, and regional operators like the Asian
Cellular Satellite System as well as proposed high-capacity
satellite networks from consortiums led by Hughes Electronics,
Alcatel and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Teledesic's technical feasibility is still in
question. The company has missed deadlines to settle specifications
with Motorola, its prime contractor _ which is expected to be
replaced by Hughes Space Systems, ICO's prime contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The need for overseas phone companies to sell Teledesic services
locally is another risk factor. ``It's a mess trying to get your
partners around the world working together when it's not their core
business,'' said J. Armand Musey, who follows the industry for Banc
of America Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But even assuming those hurdles could be completely overcome and
the service launched for $10 billion, the lowest estimates around,
what then? Teledesic has just two groups of potential customers
that seem out of reach of the competition: computer users in remote
lands and waters who will pay for the electronic equivalent of an
all-you-can-eat buffet and users in the developed world who will
pay to have a backup satellite Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to construct a business model with a $10 billion
investment and I can't,'' said Farrer. ``He clearly sees things I
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Preternatural far-sightedness, though, is part of McCaw's track
record. ``He's the billionaire whom even billionaires find
interesting,'' said O. Casey Corr, whose biography of McCaw,
``Money From Thin Air,'' is scheduled to be published next month by
Times Books/Random House.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's admirers include Bill Gates, a childhood acquaintance
and now a neighbor, who put $5 million into Teledesic in 1994 after
reviewing the business plan on his honeymoon. (He has since added
millions more.) Gates told Fortune magazine in 1996 that McCaw
``understands the communications business and where it's going
better than anyone I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Detractors tend to have more qualms than criticisms. ``I'm not
sure he's a visionary,'' said Michael Cleamon, a San Francisco
consultant who has worked with Teledesic. ``He's a gambler.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalists say that perceptions of McCaw as an extreme risk-taker
underestimate his fanatic attention to escape routes from his bets
and his willingness to shift course when conditions change
unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always knows where the back door is,'' said Robert
Ratliffe, a long-time aide. ``I don't know of a single time where
conditions have changed so much that Craig couldn't morph his
position into something useful.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein may be the clue to Teledesic's future. McCaw and his
backers could have acquired Iridium for far less than the sum they
are sinking into ICO. But ICO offered a big advantage: None of its
12 planned satellites is in the air yet, and that gives McCaw's
engineers a chance to tinker with the design of both the satellites
and the ground stations.
</P>
<P>
   The McCaw group's stated goal when ICO goes into service in 2003
is not only to sell phone service to mobile customers, as its
founders originally planned, but also to deliver email and data.
The data capacity will be just an hors d'oeuvre compared to the
Teledesic feast, but it will be a step in the direction McCaw wants
to go.
</P>
<P>
   His latest plan calls for merging the two ventures as soon as
possible, generating revenue from ICO to help fund Teledesic, using
ICO's connections to local phone companies around the world to
market Teledesic, and tailoring Teledesic's satellite network to
run traffic through ICO's ground stations, which have already been
linked by a high-capacity fiber network.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suspect, though that ICO _ even if it manages to
become profitable _ will be less a steppingstone than a path of
retreat for McCaw from his intentions to launch and operate a
full-scale Teledesic network.
</P>
<P>
   After getting ICO running, step two will be to move on to
Teledesic, predicts Roger Rusch of Telastra, a consulting firm in
Palos Verdes Estates, Calif., that advised bondholders in the ICO
bankruptcy. ``But step three,'' he said, ``will be to cancel step
two.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History suggests, though, that McCaw will not abandon his grand
vision simply because everyone around him sees that as the sensible
option. Many of his decisions have been described as intuitive, an
attribute McCaw himself has often ascribed to his severe dyslexia.
Unable to digest long documents, he has become a master at sizing
up the interests of those he is dealing with and staying focused on
fundamental questions, like how potential customers will perceive a
new service.
</P>
<P>
   When his intuitions harden into conviction, associates say, even
his most trusted advisers cannot budge him.
</P>
<P>
   One such occasion was McCaw's decision to acquire control of
Nextel in 1995, according to Tim Donahue, a longtime McCaw
executive who is now chief executive of Nextel, the digital
wireless carrier based in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other cellular phone systems, Nextel grew out of the
radio dispatch sector and can easily tie many users into a single
conversation. Five years ago, though, Nextel was burdened by debt
and by the poor quality of its two-way radio equipment from
Motorola, losing hundreds of millions of dollars annually and
searching for billions to build out service in the cities where it
had licenses.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw plunged in anyway, relying in part on Motorola's
commitment to improve the system if he became involved. By 1999,
Nextel's customer base had more than doubled, its stock was up 600
percent, it was branching out into foreign markets and Microsoft
had decided to invest $600 million to develop Nextel Online, an
Internet service for Nextel customers. Today, McCaw and his fellow
investors were sitting on a $3.4 billion gain on their investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves big problems with big opportunities,'' said Peter
Currie, a senior executive with McCaw Cellular Communications
during Teledesic's formative days.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCaw's charitable interests have a way of escalating into
grand schemes. His effort to return Keiko, the killer whale
featured in the movie ``Free Willy,'' to the wild has become a
multi-million-dollar project to vastly extend knowledge about the
lives of the orcas of the North Atlantic where Keiko, then about 2,
was captured in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's career began prematurely, in tragedy. The second of four
sons of J. Elroy and Marion McCaw, a socially prominent and wealthy
Seattle couple, it was Craig who, on a visit home from Stanford
University, discovered his father dead from a stroke. Although only
19 years old at the time, Craig had been the son most interested in
the family's financial affairs, including a small cable television
business where he worked during the summer, and he was quickly
accepted as the primary manager of the family's interests going
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out Elroy's estate was no simple task. The elder McCaw
had been an avid dealmaker and borrower who loathed documentation
and paid little attention to the actual operations of the
businesses he owned. But Craig quickly set about expanding the
family's cable investments as soon as the legal clouds lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, McCaw began adding paging businesses to the portfolio.
Seven years later, when the Federal Communications Commission
licensed the first cellular phone companies, he was an active
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw prided himself on beating industry service standards.
Unlike his father, he concluded early on that happy customers
produce more revenue, which helps support more rapid expansion. But
he became best known for his willingness to borrow what seemed like
astronomical sums to bid aggressively for new properties, confident
that they would grow rapidly enough to cover his soaring debts. He
was sure that latecomers to the cellular business would pay far
higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, McCaw focused on building a nationwide network of
cellular phone licenses, in the belief that customers would be
attracted to any service that allowed them to roam freely at a
reasonable cost with a minimum of trouble. The value of such
freedom seemed obvious to a man who preferred flying, kayaking,
sailing and camping in remote regions of western Canada to working
in his office. (Water pistol wars tend to erupt when McCaw is stuck
at work too long, according to Ratliffe.)
</P>
<P>
   To build up a war chest for the increasingly expensive battles
for cellular territories, he unsentimentally sold his family's
cable television business for $755 million in 1986 and, with the
help of Michael Milken, became a major issuer of high-yield bonds.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for making risks pay off was established by the
wealth generated in cable television. It exploded into the realm of
business legend when he sold McCaw Cellular to AT&AMP;T for $11.5
billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is like a great painter,'' said Steven Rattner, who as an
investment banker at Lazard Freres was involved in many of McCaw's
dealings. ``He doesn't paint the same thing twice, but you can see
similarities in the brush strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaw's satellite plans provide the most obvious test of such
skills, but they are hardly McCaw's only concern at the moment.
Through Eagle River Inc., an investment firm based in this Seattle
suburb, he has controlling interests in both Nextel and Nextlink,
which provides businesses with high-capacity telecommunications and
Internet services in the United States and Europe. In February,
McCaw gathered $470 million to fund the expansion of Nextel's
network into secondary and rural markets by spinning off Nextel
Partners Inc. in a public offering; the 40 percent stake controlled
by McCaw through Eagle River or Nextel is currently worth almost
$1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw has said there is no grand plan to link his
telecommunications empire together, but associates like Donahue,
Perry, and Dan Akerson, chief executive of Nextlink, look for ways
the various companies can work with each other. Nextel uses
Nextlink networks, and Perry foresees both companies promoting
Teledesic's capacity as a backup service for their business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw acknowledged that the companies could end up competing
against each other in some areas. ``Our dream, however, is to find
ways to make competitive situations more synergistic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McCaw would announce a grand plan unless forced by some
business need. Teledesic came to light when the company had to file
a petition for radio spectrum with the Federal Communications
Commission. Those in his inner circle say he is open with them, but
often difficult to read. Russell Daggett, vice chairman of
Teledesic, says associates have to ``connect the dots'' of McCaw
commentary to come up with executable plans, and Dennis Weibling,
president of Eagle River and a close financial adviser since 1982,
says that McCaw's good ideas come interspersed with ``things that
will make you bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, McCaw is so wealthy that he has a greater margin of
error than early in his career. After remarrying in 1998 following
a bitter divorce in 1997, then becoming a father for the first
time, he also has less of his life wrapped up in making his
business bets pay off. Where he once kept his aircraft, yachts and
other toys deployed to make business and vacations as convenient as
possible, he now juggles them to support family life, although not
always with the same success.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of infrastructure can keep you on schedule with
kids,'' he recently told a bemused Ratliffe.
</P>
<P>
   But McCaw remains fascinated by the satellite opportunity and is
unlikely to retreat drastically anytime soon. His interest began in
1986, when he explored putting satellites in orbit above the Indian
and western Pacific oceans to serve Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It was rekindled in 1990 when Ed Tuck, a pioneer in using
satellites to pinpoint the location of boaters, hikers and others
with handheld transmitters, suggested using satellites in low-earth
orbits for a global phone system that would not suffer the
disruptive delays that plagued calls using geo-stationary
satellites in high orbits.
</P>
<P>
   In McCaw's hands, the vision expanded to encompass a variety of
computer applications that could benefit from eliminating that
signal lag, known as latency. The devil was in the details: No one
could see how Teledesic could afford, much less control, the 840
satellites in the original plan, which would be constantly shifting
their positions in relation to the earth's surface. Beyond that, no
one had ever secured permission from regulators around the world to
use the broad swath of high-frequency radio spectrum Teledesic
wanted for such communications.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw handed the challenge to Daggett, a lawyer by training, and
has yet to look back. Today, Teledesic has its regulatory
approvals. It also has big name investors like Boeing ($100
million), Motorola ($750 million, including assets from Celestri, a
planned network that was folded into Teledesic), and Prince
Alwaleed bin Talal of Saudi Arabia ($200 million).
</P>
<P>
   Teledesic's new headquarters in Bellevue, Wash., presents a
thrifty facade: it is the back half of a warehouse abutting a
railroad line in an industrial section of town. But inside is a
confidently over-budget mixture of cool and whimsy, complete with
an on-site coffee bar.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ICO deal, the apparent prosperity could not quell
reports that Teledesic's progress had stalled. Indeed, if anyone
but McCaw had been involved, Teledesic would probably have been
dismissed long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But McCaw is someone you never bet against,'' said Musey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
