<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GUATEMALA-PHILANTHROP     06-02 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-PHILANTHROPY-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH PHILANTHROPY IN A LOW-TECH GUATEMALAN VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 4) 
 By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO LA LAGUNA, Guatemala _ It is early evening on a hazy
spring night, and a group of children are gathered on the shores of
Lake Atitlan, eagerly awaiting the visit from Karin Stahl. Her boat
has just pulled in to this tiny Mayan village 90 miles west of
Guatemala City, and it is as if a celebrity has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karina!'' they cry, rushing toward the docks. ``Bienvenidos,
Karina!''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl grins and hugs each child, doling out kisses like
chocolates, asking questions in flawless Spanish. She has been
coming to this village of 12,000 since 1997, and everywhere she
goes people call out to her. Three families have even named their
newborns Karina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't she beautiful?'' Stahl asks a companion, cradling one of
her namesakes.
</P>
<P>
   Two young boys offer to help with Stahl's bags, but they give up
when they discover how heavy the bags are. Inside, amid the heap of
clothing, are four gleaming new Compaq Presario laptop computers,
complete with DVD's. There is also a server, a monitor and
Spanish/English translation software _ all courtesy of eBay, the
online auction house, where the 34-year-old Stahl works.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, eBay has donated 15 computers and two printers to
Colegio Bethel, a private school here in San Pedro. The school was
founded 11 years ago by Emilio Battz, a local pastor, and his wife,
Ester, who live in a modest home on the premises with their three
children.
</P>
<P>
   About 350 students, in kindergarten through 9th grade, attend.
Their parents pay 25 quetzales ($3.25) a month for the elementary
school and 40 quetzales ($5.20) for junior high. And while these
rates sound nominal, families struggle to make the payments. Many
live in adobe or bamboo huts, four or more to a bed, with no
running water, no telephones, and limited electricity. They share
outhouses with neighboring families and bathe in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   But five days a week their children come to Bethel, where, in
addition to studying traditional subjects like math and history,
they are learning to use computers.
</P>
<P>
   The region is known for its unique handicrafts, with brightly
patterned designs and intricate embroidery. One goal is for
students to sell these wares _woven and beaded place mats, napkins,
hats and scarves _ on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, the force behind the San Pedro project and, separately,
the director of the eBay Foundation, the company's philanthropic
arm, said she would like to provide scholarships or loans for the
children to continue their higher education outside the village.
They would repay the loans by returning to Bethel to work as
interns for a year, helping students learn the e-commerce process,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of us at eBay have made so much money,'' Stahl said.
``We want to help kids do something with their lives other than
selling fruit. The point is to give them some means to get out, to
give them a vision of what they can do with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, women here earn about 5 quetzales (65 cents) if they
sell their goods to a third party; the wholesaler then typically
resells the items for 10 times that price. Some local men make the
handicrafts, too, though most work in the fields, growing coffee,
corn and cotton, for 20 quetzales a day. If families here could cut
out the middlemen, the theory goes, their options would expand.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the rate of economic growth in Guatemala rose to
5.1 percent _ the highest level in the 1990s, when the economy
expanded at a yearly average of 4.1 percent. But last year, the
growth rate slumped to 3.5 percent, according to Bank of Guatemala
estimates. And, in any event, ``to have an impact on poverty
reduction and to accommodate the population explosion, the economy
should be growing by 6 percent,'' said Maurico Valdes, the Central
America coordinator for the United Nations Development Program.
``Computers may help.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl met Battz in July 1997 while traveling and working in
Guatemala for Compassion International, a U.S. relief organization.
When she joined eBay as an account manager in October of that year,
she wondered how she could continue helping the village. She
mentioned San Pedro in conversations with colleagues, and her
enthusiasm spread throughout the company. A year later, she
returned here with the first round of computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karin is passionate about the project,'' said Meg Whitman, the
chief executive of eBay. ``All 1,200 of our employees know about
the school; it's part of our culture now. We have a bulletin board
with the children's photographs on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last August, nearly 30 eBay employees and relatives, including
Whitman's 15-year-old son, joined Stahl on a trip to San Pedro,
where they trained teachers on computers. Another group is heading
out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   On this spring trip, though, there is just Stahl and Ron
Sackman, 34, a friend and a consultant for Lucent Technologies, the
communications equipment maker. Sackman is linking the new
computers to the Internet. This is not an easy task; the dial-up
connection is extremely slow, and the school only has one phone
line _ in Battz's home. Web access is costly _ about $60 to open an
account and $10 a month after that, not including local and
long-distance telephone charges, in an area where incomes average
about $900 a year.
</P>
<P>
   To curb costs, Sackman runs a 200-foot cable from Battz's home
phone into the main server in the school. ``I'm hoping to do it so
the kids can write e-mails during the day, and then late at night,
when the rates are lower, the e-mail will automatically send,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   While he fiddles with the cable, Juan Cruz, Bethel's computer
teacher, sets up the new machines. ``Hay mas mouse pads?'' (``Are
there any more mouse pads?'') he asks. He flips through a manual he
has put together, a 100-page curriculum that includes the history
of technology and a step-by-step guide to Windows and other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, 25, learned computers in Guatemala City, then returned to
San Pedro, his native village, to teach. ``These kids never saw a
computer before, but now it's like no big deal to them,'' he said.
``They're so happy to take classes; otherwise they have to go to
Guatemala City, and it's very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is not especially new to Guatemala; there are
cybercafes in the capital and in tourist towns. But it is a novelty
in this village, which did not have electricity until the mid-'90s.
The school has had power for just two years; before that, teachers
would dangle an extension cord out a window and ``borrow'' a
neighbor's.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Now, while there is Web access in San Pedro, there are no paved
roads _ just dirt and loose rocks. Dogs and chickens roam freely.
Few tourists visit, except for some travelers who are generally
understood to come for the marijuana, which grows abundantly in the
hills. And though there are six other schools in the village _
three private and three public _ Bethel is the only one with
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual for schoolchildren in a rural area like San
Pedro La Laguna to have Internet access,'' said Valdes of the
United Nations. ``In the more elitist private schools in the larger
cities, it might be more common, but even basic things like
electricity and telephone lines aren't always there to make
computer technology work.''
</P>
<P>
   The computers are ``a giant step,'' agreed Battz, 47. ``Our kids
are getting three years of computer training. It's excellent.'' A
byproduct is that the computers have enhanced the children's
self-esteem. ``I'm a Mayan, and we're typically very timid and
think we're less important than those people with blue eyes and
blond hair. Now that the children are learning new skills, they are
seeing their own value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he wants to also train parents on the machines _ a
necessity if the villagers are to sell their wares on eBay, since
children aren't supposed to use the auction site on their own. That
will be a formidable challenge, as most of the adults are
illiterate and speak only Tz'utuhil, the indigenous language.
</P>
<P>
   The parents seem thrilled with their children's education. ``I
like that she studies,'' said Diego Pop, 60, whose daughter, Vila,
is an eighth grader at Bethel. A widower, Pop works in the fields
and supplements his income by embroidering clothing. He earns about
85 quetzales, or $11, for a pair of pants that takes about three
weeks to complete. ``I don't want her to be like me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lidia Gonzalez, the mother of 14-year-old Norma, cannot read or
write; she earns her living selling pots and pans in the local
market. ``It's important that she doesn't suffer like me,'' said
Gonzalez, 29. ``I want her to study in the capital so she'll get a
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer skills certainly can't hurt. ``If students acquired
programming skills or were able to do word processing or
spreadsheets or knew how to surf the Web, that would increase their
job prospects tremendously,'' said Susan Peacock, senior associate
at the Washington Office on Latin America, a human rights
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, realities often fly in the face of these dreams. Vila Pop,
for example, is the youngest of six children, and she has been
saddled with the responsibilities of cooking and cleaning for her
father and brothers since her mother died three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although she plans to further her education, it's not uncommon
for students to drop out of school. According to a 1999 U.N.
Development Program report on Guatemala, only about 56 percent of
the Guatemalan population had attended school through the 9th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   That number is only an estimate, Valdes said. ``A lot of people
are migrant workers, and they migrate with their whole family
during the harvest of sugar cane, so the children leave school to
go with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How much time will the villagers actually have to devote to the
Net? Would they be better off with clothes and food instead of
computers, as some critics suggest?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think computers are a luxury, but we can't say
that rural areas only need water and sanitation and basic health,''
Valdes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let the technological gap go on, but you have to
devise a way to make it economically self-sustaining,'' Valdes
added. ``In poor, rural, isolated areas, you can't just have
computer access at a school. It has to become an information center
for the community, because otherwise it's too expensive. There are
local merchants and professionals who can benefit from a connection
and, with time, be able to pay something for it. But these issues
have to be discussed at the local level, in the villages, and not
by people in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said she would like to integrate into the junior high
curriculum instructions for selling online, including shipping
preparation and accounting. ``The village is slowly growing in
tourism, so this program will provide students the business and
people skills to successfully help their community grow,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there are more pressing issues. Back in the computer
lab, Sackman has managed to get online, though it takes nearly 15
minutes to download a page. The students hover around him
excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   He checks his own e-mail account and prints out a few pages to
show the students. Stahl also goes online _ only to learn that she
did not win a bidding war for a house she had hoped to buy back
home in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bid $100,000 over the asking price, and I was still
outbid,'' she said. She glanced at the children clicking away at
the computers and sighed. ``As if it really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
