<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3296 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HONDA-HYBRID-$ADV04-N     06-02 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA-HYBRID-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA'S HIGH-MILEAGE, HIGH STAKES HYBRID 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With gasoline prices pushing toward $2 a gallon in
some parts of the country, Honda could not have picked a better
time to bring out a car that gets 70 miles to the gallon on the
highway. Sure enough, the Honda Insight, the first hybrid car to be
sold in the United States, is off to a fast start, at least by the
standards used to measure alternative vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Honda has sold more than 1,100 of the futuristic-looking
Insights since the car went on sale in December, and the company
recently raised its sales target for this year to 6,500 cars, from
4,000. While even that new goal might seem small, it is double the
number of purely electric cars sold by all manufacturers combined
in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether hybrid cars, which combine
gasoline engines and electric motors, will provide an alternative
to electric vehicles for reducing emissions. The issue is expected
to come to a boil in September when the California Air Resources
Board considers whether to relax its mandate that starting in 2003,
10 percent of all vehicles sold in the state must give off no
emissions or extremely low emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Insight became the first product ever honored by
the Sierra Club for ``excellence in environmental engineering,''
environmentalists worry that the auto industry will try to argue
that hybrids, which still emit low levels of pollutants, should be
allowed to substitute for true zero-emission vehicles, weakening
air-quality goals.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with electric vehicles is their limited
battery range. The cars can travel only 50 to 100 miles or so
before the batteries must be recharged, a process that takes
several hours. But a hybrid uses the batteries only to supplement a
gasoline engine. Moreover, the batteries can be recharged
automatically using power from the gas engine or from braking, so
hybrids do not have to be plugged in. Indeed, the Insight rarely
has to be taken to a filling station because it can travel 600
miles on a single tank of gas.
</P>
<P>
   The high mileage comes not just from having batteries carry some
of the load. Honda went all out to achieve an eye-popping economy
rating, but some of the steps it took ultimately limit the car's
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Insight seats only two people. It has only a five-speed
manual transmission. Its gas engine is a tiny 1-liter, 3-cylinder,
although Honda says that because of the Insight's lightweight
aluminum body, aerodynamic design and assistance from the
batteries, the Insight behaves like a 1.5-liter subcompact.
Finally, the aerodynamic design, with its tapered rear end and
skirts over the back wheels, will discourage drivers who don't like
to be stared at on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Insight might also be vulnerable to competition from the
Toyota Prius, another hybrid that goes on sale this month. The
Prius gets ``only'' about 50 MPG but seats four or five people and
has an automatic transmission; it also received the Sierra Club's
engineering award, during the New York auto show in April.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota executives, in a put-down of the Insight, boast that the
Prius is a ``real car'' and say that they hope to sell 12,000 in
the first year. The Prius will be priced around $20,000, not much
different from the Insight's list price of $18,880 without
air-conditioning and $20,080 with it. Both Toyota and Honda are
presumed to be losing money on each hybrid they sell.
</P>
<P>
   The Insight drives pretty much like any other car. One
difference, which makes the car eerily quiet, is that the engine
shuts off when the car is not moving, the shift is in neutral and
the foot is off the clutch. The engine starts up immediately when
the clutch is engaged and the car is put in gear.
</P>
<P>
   Also different is the dashboard, which has some extra displays
showing the car's fuel economy at any given instant and providing
up and down arrows suggesting when to shift. That makes driving the
Insight like playing a video game _ one with the goal of maximum
fuel economy. My score was about 45 MPG on fairly empty city
streets and 60 on a smoothly flowing highway, below the EPA
estimates of 61 in the city and 70 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   But despite hybrids' high fuel economy, some environmentalists
fear that the vehicles will be used as an excuse to postpone or
eliminate California's requirement for zero-emission vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The state air resources board is scheduled to review its
so-called mandate in September, and lobbying is expected to be
fierce. The mandate, which once called for 10 percent of a
company's sales to be zero-emission vehicles, has already been
weakened twice. It now says that only 4 percent of sales have to be
truly emissions-free and the other 6 percent can be extremely low
polluting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But automakers say it is next to impossible to meet even the 4
percent target because battery-powered electric vehicles will be
the only way to achieve zero emissions by 2003, and those cars have
been shunned by consumers. Fuel cells, a new technology for
achieving zero emissions, are not expected to be widely available
until the second half of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry has not yet publicly stated its position,
some automakers are expected to argue that a greater improvement in
air quality could be achieved by selling a larger number of pretty
clean hybrids rather than trying and failing to sell a smaller
number of totally clean electrics.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say the auto companies have not tried hard
enough to develop and sell all-electric vehicles, and they don't
want hybrids to be used as an excuse to take the pressure off.
Hybrids ``are still running on gasoline,'' said Roland Hwang,
transportation program director for the Union of Concerned
Scientists. ``You still have to have something in the program that
says we're moving to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the air resources board have said they hope to keep
some of the zero-emission requirement because it has prodded the
development not only of electric cars but of hybrids, too. If the
mandate is relaxed a third time, electric vehicles might never be
commercialized. What California does is expected to be followed by
New York and Massachusetts as well, and possibly by some other
states.
</P>
<P>
   But hybrids might not be the total answer either. ``Hybrids are
a means of increasing fuel efficiency,'' said Robert J. Bienenfeld,
manager of sales and marketing for alternative-fuel vehicles at
Honda. ``They are not necessarily the way to approach air-quality
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Insight is now classified in California as a ULEV, or
ultra-low-emission vehicle, and as such it would not qualify to be
counted in the 6 percent of extremely low-emission vehicles that
each manufacturer must sell in the state starting in 2003. The
Toyota Prius, however, is a SULEV, or super ultra-low emission
vehicle, which could qualify if it meets certain other
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while all companies are developing hybrids, some
probably won't have them on the market by 2003. Ford has announced
that its first hybrid will go on sale that year, a version of its
new Escape sport utility. The president of Toyota, Fujio Cho,
recently said that his company was working on a hybrid SUV, too.
DaimlerChrysler is showing off a hybrid Dodge Durango that uses an
electric motor not so much for high fuel economy, but to bolster
the performance of a gasoline V-6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current regulations, SULEV's are given only partial
credit toward the emissions goals. It might take three hybrids to
count as one zero-emission vehicle in the overall 10 percent goal.
Thus, if hybrids are to account for 6 percent of the emissions
goal, they will actually have to account for 18 percent of actual
sales, which would mean 100,000 hybrids for the top six
manufacturers alone. Even with the extra practicality of hybrids,
that could be a tough goal to reach, especially if gasoline prices
drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see this as a mass-market car,'' Bienenfeld said of
the Insight. ``Six months ago, gasoline was $1.10 to $1.15 and no
one was walking into a dealership demanding a high-fuel-economy
car.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
