<HEADER>
A3299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JOBS-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      06-02 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOWER ECONOMIC GROWTH BUOYS STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New figures showing that the Federal Reserve's campaign to slow
economic growth is working sent the stock market surging Thursday,
with the Nasdaq Composite index posting the biggest weekly gain in
its 29-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government reported that the jobless rate jumped to
4.1 percent last month, from 3.9 percent in April. After months of
unusually strong job growth, the private sector reduced payrolls in
May by 116,000, the largest monthly decline in business hiring
since the recession of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nation's economy remains strong and generated
231,000 new jobs last month, most of those jobs were limited to the
US Census Bureau's hiring of temporary workers to assist in
gathering data for the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Investors cheered the jobs report, which they interpreted as a
signal that the Federal Reserve might not raise rates again at its
next meeting, June 27 and 28, to contain inflation. If the Fed acts
at all, economists predicted that its members would probably raise
rates only a quarter-point.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's half-point increase in the federal funds rate, to 6.5
percent, at its May meeting was the seventh _ and the largest _
rate hike since the central bank began its campaign a year ago to
slow the US economy and relieve some of the inflationary pressures
building because of rising wages and soaring oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the stock market has performed well when the
economy is expanding. But that relationship was turned upside down
in recent months, because investors and Fed members have been more
concerned that the economy's growth is too brisk and might spark
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Given the May jobs report, ``You can certainly argue that the
Fed's series of tightening moves has in fact started to bear
fruit,'' said William Cheney, chief economist for John Hancock
Financial Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although a one-month slowdown in job creation is not full proof
of a slowdown, Cheney predicted that it would be convincing to the
Fed's members when they meet again later this month. ``Unless we
get a bad inflation number in the two weeks, the Fed is unlikely to
make another move at this meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite index, which has slumped badly since March,
surged 230.88 points Thursday, ending a strong week in which the
technology-dominated index gained 19 percent, closing at 3813.38.
This week's rally trimmed the Nasdaq's losses for this year to 6.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also built on gains made during
the week, rising 142.56 points Thursday, to 10,794.76. The Dow has
also dropped about 6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Fine, comanager of the Small-Cap Growth Fund and the
Aggressive Growth Fund for Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co., said he still views
the recent surge in Nasdaq as ``a rally in a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fine predicted the Nasdaq could rise above its current
level by the end of this year, he was cautious. ``There's still not
enough (trading) volume to show that there's conviction behind the
buying,'' he said. The rally appears to be ``a bounce from an
oversold position.''
</P>
<P>
   What became clearer in the jobs data issued Thursday is that the
economy is slowing, according to David Wyss, chief economist for
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a Lexington consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   A slowdown in job creation, added to recent reports of lower
manufacturing activity and weaker chain-store and housing sales _
all ``are pointing in the same direction,'' Wyss said. ``The brakes
are finally working'' by slowing the economy, as the Fed intended
by raising interest rates steadily over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fed members, led by chairman Alan Greenspan, will
continue to watch inflation, especially in the wake of reports that
the closely watched employment cost index has risen 4.3 percent
during the year ending on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering that report, the US Department of Labor in its jobs
report Thursday said that wages in May rose only 1 cent, to $13.65
an hour, after a 6-cent rise in April and a 13-cent rise in the
first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fed may again raise rates, Wyss said a
quarter-point increase is most likely and a half-point increase
``is off the books now.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Labor reported that the US Census Bureau
hired 357,000 temporary workers last month to collect data for the
2000 census. That more than offset a decline in private-sector
payrolls and resulted in total job growth of 231,000 in May. That
was sharply below the 414,000 jobs created in April.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's employment declined by 991,000 in May, to 134.7
million, pushing up minorities' unemployment. The jobless rate
among blacks increased 0.8 percentage points, to 8 percent, and the
Hispanic jobless rate was up 0.4 percentage points, to 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only the service industry saw tangible job gains in May amid a
widespread scaling back in the private sector. And the 17,000
addition to service-company payrolls paled in comparison with the
industry's pace, an average of 103,000 a month this year.
Employment by construction firms, manufacturers, retail, and
transportation establishments were all down. The financial and real
estate industry payrolls were ``little changed,'' the government
said.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of slowing growth, the average hourly workweek
for factory workers declined one-tenth of an hour, to 34.4 hours,
for the first time in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relatively underprivileged lose every time the economy
slows a bit,'' John Hancock's Cheney said. But, he added, ``a 4.1
percent unemployment rate is still very favorable, and the
opportunities are better than they've been for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
