<SLUG> BC-CALIF-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. HOUSING DEVELOPMENT MUST PROVE WATER RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a decision that reflects the importance of
water and environmental concerns for California's rapid growth, a
state court judge has temporarily blocked construction of the
single largest housing development ever approved by Los Angeles
County, a 22,000-home planned community on the Ventura County
border.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling late Wednesday, Judge Roger D. Randall of Superior
Court in neighboring Kern County ordered the developer, the Newhall
Land and Farming Co., to prove that it can assure adequate water
for its planned project, Newhall Ranch. Randall also ordered the
developer to conduct more detailed reviews of the project's effect
on traffic and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County and a coalition of environmental groups had sued
Newhall and Los Angeles County to block the project; the case was
moved to Kern County to avoid a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means construction on the project will be delayed
until 2003, a year later than the developer's schedule, said a
spokeswoman for Newhall Land, Marlee Lauffer.
</P>
<P>
   The project's opponents said they hoped the delay and the
requirements for further environmental review might lead to scaling
down the development, which Newhall had already shrunk from 25,000
units to win the approval of Los Angeles County last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that the delays this causes will maybe cause them
to take a harder look at the project and find some ways to reach
more compromise,'' said Lynne Plambeck, vice president of the Santa
Clarita Organization for Planning and Development, which joined the
suit with the Sierra Club and a group called Friends of the Santa
Clara River. ``I think we have a lot of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Ranch development is scheduled in phases over 20 years,
but big as it is, it would barely make a dent in Los Angeles
County's total projected need for new housing, now estimated at
about 25,000 units per year.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said they would have to review the ruling
before deciding whether to appeal it. Lauffer, the Newhall
spokeswoman, said that ``we think, based on our initial review,
that we can resolve these issues over the next year,'' adding that
the ruling seemed to turn on ``relatively minor issues that the
judge has requested additional analysis on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Antonette B. Cordero, an assistant county counsel for
Ventura County, which has adopted some of the nation's most
stringent measures to control growth, said that ``the judge is not
just saying they have to generate more paper on this project, he's
saying they have to go out and do some more analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Randall held that Newhall must demonstrate that
``adequate water sources are available for build-out of the
project,'' especially in dry years, Cordero said. The judge also
required the developer to further study the environmental and
traffic effects of the project in Ventura County, where it has
extensive holdings but does not currently plan to build, and on the
Santa Clara River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speculate on what changes they may have to make once
they go back and do that,'' Cordero said.
</P>
<P>
   Randall's ruling included rejecting Ventura County's argument
that it was entitled to joint approval over the whole project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
