<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ALASKA-AIR-CRASH-575&AMP;     06-02 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIR-CRASH-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA THREATENS ACTION THAT COULD SHUT AIRLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration threatened
Friday to shut down major maintenance overhauls at Alaska Airlines,
which would ground the airline within months.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, its attention drawn to the airline by a fatal crash
last January and a federal grand jury investigation, said that the
carrier had a persistent problem in keeping track of whether
required maintenance had been done, and that managers had not
noticed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA gave the airline, a unit of Alaska Air Group, seven days
to show why its maintenance hangars should not be shut down, and
said that unless it was persuaded, it would order a shutdown 30
days after that.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed order to shut the airline's maintenance hangars was
highly unusual. Although the agency has occasionally gone even
further, simply grounding carriers, it seldom threatens such tough
action against carriers as big as Alaska, which has a fleet of 89
jets and flies up and down the West Coast and to Hawaii, Canada and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's director of flight standards service, Nick
Lacey, said the lapses, 150 cases over three years, were worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aviation accidents come as a result of a series of small
errors and inability to detect small errors,'' Lacey said, speaking
to reporters here a few minutes after the airline was notified of
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While no unsafe conditions were found that were attributable to
the maintenance problems, an airline that cannot spot its own
problems and correct them ``lacks the required redundancy,'' Lacey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the problems were merely paperwork, he responded,
``Paperwork, that's kind of a trite word.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paperwork is very important,'' he continued. ``It's basically
the way the airline assures that the work has been completed and
performed.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline's chairman, John Kelly, said in a news conference at
the company's Seattle headquarters that the company had begun
remedying its problems, as the FAA pointed them out. Kelly made
public a list of veteran aviation safety specialists the company
had hired recently, among 70 new maintenance and engineering
employees, and described new procedures that were being followed
before planes were released to carry passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman portrayed the FAA announcement as a demand that the
changes already in the works be put on a firm timetable, and that
they be made permanent. ``I don't blame them,'' he said, promising
to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that the FAA had found 166 gaps in the paperwork, but
he noted that 267,000 documents had been reviewed. That meant the
airline had made errors on 0.06 percent of the documents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lacey, speaking in Washington, said the company's
cooperation, generally good safety record and skilled personnel
were a factor in deciding not to ground the planes at once.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of longstanding lapses at the carrier is bad news
for the FAA as well as the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has been struggling to improve its oversight of
airlines since the crash of a ValuJet DC-9 in May 1996, and has
invested heavily in new inspection systems.
</P>
<P>
   What led to the discovery of what Lacey called ``sloppiness'' at
Alaska was not the perceptions of its inspectors or the systems put
in place by FAA management, but the crash in January of one of the
company's MD-80 aircraft, and a continuing grand jury investigation
into maintenance practices at the airline's hangar in Oakland,
Calif.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until a final decision is made, FAA inspectors are functioning
as quality-control personnel for the airline, Lacey said. He added
that inspectors who tracked down the aircraft at airports around
Alaska Airlines' extensive route network found in all cases that
the work had been performed.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said he could not comment on the Jan. 31 crash of the
MD-80, which was en route from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, to San
Francisco, because that investigation was in the hands of the
National Transportation Safety Board. But that crash has raised
questions about whether the airline's maintenance and operational
practices might have played a role.
</P>
<P>
   All 88 people on board were killed when the pilots lost control
of the plane's pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling wreckage from the coast off Los Angeles, investigators
found the thread stripped from a jack screw, a device like a garage
door opener, that moves the horizontal section of the tail up and
down, and a subsequent inspection of jack-screw assemblies in
planes nationwide found a high incidence of problems on Alaska
Airlines planes, which might be signs of a maintenance problem.
</P>
<P>
   The airline flies mostly Boeing 737s and MD-80s, and at any
given time, five or six of its planes are in hangars at Oakland or
Seattle for heavy maintenance. Without the authority to release
those planes back into service, ``you basically have a shrinking
airline,'' Lacey said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline could not contract out the work, although it could
lease planes from others.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said he hoped that the airline and his agency would reach
agreement on a plan to correct the management deficiencies, and
that the airline could show that the plan was working, before the
agency shut the hangars.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors reviewed other aspects of the airline but did not
find major problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that there were areas needing improvement; for
example, pilots are supposed to be retrained annually but are
allowed a one-month grace period. Alaska Airlines conducts 80
percent of its recurrent training in that 13th month, Lacey said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market reacted unfavorably to Friday's announcement;
shares of the airline closed at $30.75 on the New York Stock
Exchange, down $1.1875. But analysts said it was still a sound
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a bona fide franchise,'' said Kevin C. Murphy, an
analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, who added, ``Their raison
d'etre is to be the north-south operator on the West coast, and
that ain't too shabby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will give them the kind of shock therapy they
need to make sure they exceed FAA standards,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others noted that Alaska Airlines had pioneered safer
navigation techniques, along with automated kiosks at airports that
dispense tickets, and that it was experimenting with having
passengers check their own luggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Alaska Airlines isn't here next year, it will be because
they were bought by another airline, not because of safety,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a proposed merger between United Airlines and US
Airways, analysts have suggested that Alaska could find itself a
takeover target by a larger carrier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
