<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3309 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-KLECZKA-BLAIRV     06-02 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-KLECZKA-BLAIRVALUE-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: GLEN A. KLECZKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, June 4) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glen A. Kleczka, 37, the lead manager of the $58.0 million
William Blair Value Discovery fund, admits to being a foodie, but
he rarely finds time to cook at home in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managing the portfolio and servicing clients doesn't leave me
a lot of time,'' said Kleczka (pronounced Klehch-kah). ``So I tend
to eat better when I travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, running the fund requires extensive travel as Kleczka
checks in with the management of companies in whose stock he is
interested. And if Kleczka puts on a few pounds as a result, well,
his shareholders at least are the better for it. William Blair
Value Discovery returned 11.8 percent a year, annualized, for the
three years through May 31, compared with 4.8 percent for its small
value peers, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Kleczka credits the fund's value philosophy, which he describes
with great simplicity. ``We buy broken stocks,'' he said, ``not
broken companies.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``broken stock'' typically trades at 50 percent or so off its
five-year-high stock price. Its valuation _ Kleczka typically
compares a stock's current price to its three-year forward earnings
potential _ is depressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a company that is not ``broken'' often has several other
attributes: leading market share, improving profitability, and
management that is purchasing shares or initiating share buyback
plans. Kleczka tries to find stocks that will rise 15 to 20 percent
annually over three years and whose earnings will rise 12 to 20
percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not supercharged topline growth companies,'' he
said. ``We'd rather see slower growers with improvements in
profitability and expanding profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Each month, Kleczka screens 11,000 stocks with market
capitalizations below $1.5 billion. Expensive companies are excised
from the list using a variety of valuation measures, such as a
companies' cash to share price, which he generally likes to see as
high as possible. He also discards those that trade for more than
twice their tangible book value, that is, book value excluding
goodwill and other intangibles. That leaves him with some 750
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he and the fund's two co-managers, David S. Mitchell and
Cappy Price, investigate the remaining candidates. By reading
company reports, filings and Wall Street research, they are
generally able to find sufficient cause to eliminate 550 more
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they visit companies to evaluate management and seek
clues to the company's improving prospects. Kleczka figures he
spends about 40 to 50 percent of his time on the road and talks to
more than 100 companies each year.
</P>
<P>
   Kleczka and his co-managers each prepare four-page investment
theses for these stocks and exchange them with their colleagues. In
biweekly meetings, they debate possible purchases, which they make
only when they reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The fund holds 50 to 70 stocks and, because it seeks to offset
gains with losses, distributed no capital gains in 1998 and 1999. A
small distribution is expected this year.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the fund is focusing on capital goods companies and
other firms in the industrial economy.
</P>
<P>
   Kleczka owns shares of Landstar System, a national trucking firm
in Jacksonville, Fla., whose truck drivers operate as independent
contractors. They own their trucks and pay all expenses, turning
over a small portion of their revenues to Landstar. ``That business
model is very attractive because it reduces capital costs and
eliminates price increases, especially in diesel fuels,'' he said.
The company also generates a lot of free cash flow, which it uses
to buy back shares.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares in January 1997 for $24 each, 40 percent below
their five year highs after the company had difficulties
integrating several acquisitions. Profitability has since improved,
he said, and it is using the Internet to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has consistently exceeded rising earnings
expectations in the last two years,'' Kleczka said, ``and we'll
continue to see that.'' Shares closed Friday at $53.25, or between
10.2 and 9.7 times his 2000 per-share earnings estimate of $5.20 to
$5.47. His 12-month price target is $63.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Arch Chemicals, of Norwalk, Conn., which
manufactures and markets chemicals used in the microelectronics and
water industries. He bought shares in November for an average price
of $15.50, after the price had fallen about 40 percent following
Arch's spin off from Olin Chemicals in February 1999. ``It's
extremely cheap,'' Kleczka said, ``and historically, spinoffs tend
to outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Arch plans to sell a low-margin water chemical distribution
business, which should increase its overall profitability, he said,
and plans a venture with an industrial gas company to run its
semiconductor chemicals business more efficiently. Shares closed
Friday at $18.25, or 8.9 times his earnings estimate of $2.05 this
year. He forecasts a three-year annual earnings growth rate of 12
to 15 percent and has a 12-month price target of $24.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite: Overland Data, in San Diego, which makes
magnetic tape data storage systems used by big businesses to back
up their enterprise-wide servers. He bought shares for $10 at the
February 1997 initial offering and added more the next year, as the
price fell to $4. Overland has $14 million in cash on its balance
sheet, (about 20 percent of its stock price), and no long-term
debt, Kleczka said.
</P>
<P>
   Its earnings have been flat, he said, because money has been
reinvested in the business. At year-end 1999, it became an
exclusive original equipment manufacturer for Compaq Computer,
which has one of the largest installed server bases in the world.
That will create economies of scale and should help Overland
increase its operating margins to 9 percent over the next two
years, from 5 percent now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares closed Friday at $9.875, or 15.2 to 13.2 times his June
2001 per-share earnings estimate of 65 cents to 75 cents. His
12-month price target is $12 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
