<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SUMMIT NEARS, CLINTON URGES WEST TO FORGE TIES WITH RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ On the eve of a Kremlin summit, President Clinton said
Friday that major Western institutions, including NATO and the
European Union, must remain open to Russia. Even if such overtures
are rejected, Clinton said, cooperation with Russia remains
``absolutely necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's determination that the West remain engaged as Russia
continues to emerge from 70 years of communist despotism and a
government-controlled economy was at the heart of the president's
remarks as he became the third American to accept the 50-year-old
Charlemagne Prize. The award honors work for European security and
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flies to Moscow Saturday for his first visit to the
Russian capital since Vladimir Putin succeeded Boris Yeltsin as
president. Clinton is scheduled to meet Putin, a 47-year-old former
KGB agent, over dinner Saturday and hold several discussions over
the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must work to build a partnership with Russia that
encourages stability, democracy and cooperative engagement with the
West _ and full integration with global institutions,'' Clinton
said in a 20-minute address in the courtyard of the cathedral in
Aachen, Germany, Charlemagne's seat as the eighth-century Holy
Roman emperor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means no doors can be sealed shut to Russia _ not NATO's,
not the EU's,'' Clinton said. ``The alternative would be a future
of harmful competition between Russia and the rest _ and the end of
our vision of an undivided continent.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, expressing a widely held view, doubt that
Russia will soon be interested in or realistically prepared to be
members of the major military or geopolitical alliances, but
Clinton said that would not let the West off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Russia may very well decide it has no interest in
formally joining European or transatlantic institutions,'' Clinton
said. ``If that happens, we must make sure that, as the EU and NATO
expand, their eastern borders become gateways to Russia, not
barriers to trade, travel and security cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Building such ties ``won't be easy,'' Clinton said, ``and there
is still mistrust to be overcome on both sides, but it is possible
and absolutely necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received the prize, a gold medal draped over his neck on
a blue and gold ribbon, in a sunny ceremony that attracted a number
of former award winners, including King Juan Carlos of Spain,
President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republican and former British
Prime Minister Edward Heath.
</P>
<P>
   The prize carries a $2,500 stipend, and Clinton said he would
use the money to provide scholarships in Aachen, a city in far west
Germany near the Dutch and Belgian border, and its sister city of
Arlington, Va., a Washington suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced by German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder as
a ``true European,'' but Schroeder again raised warnings about the
prospect of a U.S. missile-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said there was no question the United States had a
``sovereign'' right to undertake the program, on which Clinton has
promised a decision this year, but the chancellor renewed a call
for caution that he voiced Thursday in welcoming Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this issue could have effects well beyond the U.S.A., it is
in the sense of the alliance that it be treated in a spirit of
partnership,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-missile system is expected to be a major point of
discussion in the Clinton-Putin sessions. Clinton argues the system
would be aimed against the missiles of nations such as Iraq and
North Korea. The Russian leader has argued it could have offensive
uses and would contravene arms-limitation agreements, including the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention the anti-missile issue in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   He reviewed several continental disputes, especially in
southeastern Europe, including the Balkans. Clinton called
specifically for the European Union, a largely Christian area, to
admit Turkey, which would be its only predominantly Muslim member.
Clinton said the move would be ``good for the entire world, which
is still too divided over religious differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Although trouble spots remain, Clinton said Europe is ``more
united, more successful and more peaceful than ever'' and remains a
shining example of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Western Europe could come together after the carnage of
World War II, if Central Europe could do it following 50 years of
communism, it can be done everywhere on this Earth,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
