<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POWERPLANT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE PLANS TO BUILD NATION'S LARGEST POWER PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The administration of Gov. George Pataki on
Friday gave final environmental approval to plans to build the
nation's largest power plant along a verdant stretch of the Hudson
River 30 miles south of here, marking the start of a new generation
of plant construction in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of competition in the electricity market and a
surge in demand in the last few years have created a sudden rush to
build power plants in the Northeast, after a generation of a lack
of interest among power companies. The plant approved Friday, in
the town of Athens in Greene County, on the west bank of the river,
is expected to be followed in quick succession by half a dozen or
more in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 million Athens plant, proposed by Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric Corp., a major California utility company, would be New
York's first example of new technology that makes natural-gas fired
power plants far more efficient than older ones and, as a result,
put out far less air pollution. Environmentalists say its emissions
would be less than 10 percent of those from a plant built in the
1970s or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be the first to take advantage of new cooling
methods that allow it to use far less water from the river than
older plants do, an important environmental concern because water
intake pipes and the discharge of heated water into the river can
kill fish by the millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very fortunate that the technology has advanced to the
point that we can have efficient, low-cost power with very little
effect on the environment, and we are insisting on the best
available technology,'' said John P. Cahill, commissioner of the
state Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was proposed two years ago, the Athens plant has met
with ferocious local opposition, in part because it was
representing the leading edge of a boom in industrial development
on the banks of the Hudson, after the river had undergone more than
a half-century of transition from industrial thoroughfare to the
attractive centerpiece of a fairly bucolic region.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, opponents repeatedly tried to portray PG&AMP;E as
a corporate villain, reminding reporters and politicians that it
was the company that poisoned much of a California town in a story
made famous by the movie ``Erin Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Community and environmental groups protested that the plant
would mar the view of a swath of the Hudson Valley filled with
forests, farms and small towns _ a view made famous by the 19th
century painters of the Hudson River School. Environmentalists also
said the plant could disrupt a sensitive spawning ground for fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in absolutely the wrong place,'' said David Gordon, a
lawyer with the group Riverkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and Democrats in the Legislature have also
complained that a new state law on approving power plants, pushed
through by Pataki last year, does not contain enough environmental
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   But many environmentalists, while they disliked the process and
the location of the Athens plant, also hailed the construction of
new, more efficient plants as an important advance against air and
water pollution. They hope that the new plants, combined with new
air emissions regulations that Pataki has promised to impose on
older, dirtier plants, will put some of those old plants out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators had indicated they would allow the new plant to
take in more than 4 million gallons of water a day from the Hudson.
But Friday, Cahill said that he would grant the plant a water
permit that allows it to use just 180,000 gallons daily. That
compares with more than 1 billion gallons a day for some plants,
like the two active Indian Point nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   By setting the figure so low, environmentalists said, Cahill
will force the Athens plant to use the latest cooling technology,
with the least effect on fish. It would also eliminate the need for
the cooling towers and plumes of steam that are a visual signature
_ and an eyesore _ for most plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is a victory for the Hudson and sets a precedent
with national implications,'' said Ned Sullivan, executive director
of the environmental group Scenic Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The permit granted by Cahill is widely seen as the last serious
hurdle for the plant, barring a lawsuit. It still must be approved
by a siting board controlled by the governor, and by the Army Corps
of Engineers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The plant is the first approved in New York since the late
1980s. At a capacity of 1,080 megawatts _ 4 percent to 5 percent of
average demand statewide _ it would have the largest output of any
plant in the country. Applications have been filed for more than a
dozen other power plants around the state, including many on or
near the Hudson, and some in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   After last July's heat wave caused blackouts and brownouts
across much of the Northeast, energy experts warned that the region
_ in fact, much of the country _ was dangerously close to
outstripping its power supply, and that it would take four or five
years to build enough new plants to catch up to rising demand. New
York City and Long Island are in particular danger, because there
too few transmission lines to greatly increase the amount of power
imported from elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
