<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-SCOTUS-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WILL TEST JUSTICES' PROWESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass.)  (For release Sunday, June 4) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Supreme Court confronted its first
Internet case three years ago, the justices received special
training from their library staff. The lessons ``helped assure each
of us that we knew how to use the Net and understood the technical
matters at issue,'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer recalled a few weeks
ago at a symposium on biomedical research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Thus empowered, the court went on in that case, Reno vs.
American Civil Liberties Union, to produce a unanimous decision
that struck down the Communications Decency Act on First Amendment
grounds and established the primacy of free speech principles in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Microsoft antitrust case will be heading toward the
Supreme Court _ although whether directly from Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's final U.S. District Court ruling, expected this
week, or after review by the Court of Appeals here remains to be
seen. The court has gotten its collective feet wet, clearly, but in
the world of platforms, applications, source codes and interfaces,
familiarity may not be fluency.
</P>
<P>
   So the question remains: are the justices ready to swim?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is almost certainly yes, in the view of a broad
consensus of antitrust experts and students of the court. Year in
and year out, they pointed out, the justices manage to handle hard
cases requiring substantial specialized knowledge across many
fields. But the intersection of old law with new technology that
the Microsoft case represents offers a special challenge that at
least one expert cautioned could test the limits of the court's
competence.
</P>
<P>
   Institutionally, the court remains a novice. The Supreme Court
launched its first Web site (www.supremecourtus.gov) only two
months ago, long after many other courts had established an
Internet presence. A rather static venture that lets users read the
court's opinions and check its calendar, it received one million
hits in its first month, to the considerable surprise of officials.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though Windows NT runs the court's computers, and the
justices' law clerks are undoubtedly as computer savvy as other
members of their generation, the justices themselves, who range
from 52 to 80, all came of age at a time when doing legal research
meant reaching for a book, not a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Substantively, the Microsoft case presents layers of complexity
_ not only the technology of the specific products at issue, but
fiercely contested assumptions about the relationship between
competition and innovation in the fast-changing technology
marketplace. To be told that they hold the future of the
information industry in their hands _ a point the briefs will
undoubtedly try to impress on the justices _ would be more than a
little daunting for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in recent interviews, several people pointed to Jackson
as an example of the judicial ability to climb a steep learning
curve. Whether or not they agreed with the trial judge's approach
to the case, no one seemed to doubt that by the end of it, he had
an impressive mastery of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Jackson never founded a dot-com or acquired any special
credentialing,'' observed John Shepard Wiley Jr., a professor of
antitrust and intellectual property law at the University of
California at Los Angeles. ``For 200 years, federal judges have had
the brains and the motivation to deal with cases people might
assume are beyond their competence. They are used to rolling up
their sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent law, for example, ``puts incredible demands on generalist
judges,'' Wiley said, because new patents are by definition at the
cutting edge of technology. ``You can have a degree in gene
splicing, but if it's 10 years old, it's not worth much,'' he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   One antitrust expert, Andrew I. Gavil of the Howard University
Law School, noted that the justices regularly decided complex
cases, in antitrust, food and drug law and many other fields
requiring specialized knowledge. ``It's hubris to think that the
Supreme Court can't figure this out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he added in a wry tone, ``it's not like Aspen
Skiing'' _ a reference to an admittedly more accessible 15-year-old
antitrust decision that found the owner of three mountains in
Colorado to have maintained an illegal monopoly by refusing to deal
with the owner of a fourth mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft case presents ``interesting legal issues, but not
unique ones,'' Gavil said, noting that at the heart of the case are
antitrust principles with which the court is completely familiar.
``What Microsoft did with its monopoly and how the law treats that
is not that complex,'' he said. ``Did it have a pro-competitive
justification, or did it engage in behavior that cost it something
in the short run in order to hinder its rivals in the long run?
That's a very conventional antitrust question.''
</P>
<P>
   The aspect of the Microsoft case that most closely combines law
and technology, Gavil said, is whether Microsoft's bundling of its
Internet browser with its Windows operating system was an illegal
tying arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson _ who earlier in the case conducted his own experiment,
disabling Internet Explorer on his own computer in 90 seconds _
ruled that it was in his April conclusions of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on that, the justices will be able to use pretty standard
doctrine,'' Gavil said. ``You don't have to be able to read source
code to know what you see on the screen when you turn on your
computer. If you know that there are programs that can be
downloaded from the Internet, you've gone pretty far toward being
able to understand the government's theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader question of how judges deal with the substantive
complexity of the cases before them has been a subject of growing
interest, much of it revolving around the capacity of so-called
junk science to sway impressionable jurors. In an important 1993
decision, Daubert vs. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, the Supreme
Court reinterpreted the federal rules of evidence to require judges
to serve as gatekeepers, weeding out bad science and preventing
unqualified ``experts'' from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   The Daubert case and two subsequent Supreme Court cases that
elaborated on it have spawned a whole body of law, still a work in
progress and all of it judge-made.
</P>
<P>
   To cite just one example, federal appeals courts are split over
how to assess the reliability of a doctor's testimony about a
differential diagnosis _ the conclusion that a plaintiff's symptoms
are caused by one medical condition and not another. Some courts
allow testimony that reflects standard clinical practice, while
others reject testimony not based on published scientific studies.
The Supreme Court may eventually feel obliged to resolve the
dispute, as well as others stemming from the Daubert case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on judges who are generalists, and judges learn what
they need to learn,'' said Richard M. Cooper, a Washington lawyer
who has argued many technically complex cases since his days as
general counsel for the Food and Drug Administration. Most
recently, he won a Supreme Court case on behalf of the tobacco
industry against his former agency's effort to regulate cigarettes
as drug delivery devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties and friends of the court briefs educate the
judges,'' Cooper said. ``The lawyer's job is to marshal the
relevant science, economics and technical information in a manner
that an intelligent lay person can understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our system, and it's a useful discipline,'' he added.
``The Endangered Species Act, for example. Are we really wiping out
that rare species? How do we know?'' For the Microsoft case, he
said, ``if it's something economists can understand and explain to
lawyers, lawyers can explain it to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cass R. Sunstein, a University of Chicago law professor whose
recent book on the Supreme Court, ``One Case at a Time'' (Harvard
University Press, 1999), commends an incremental approach to
deciding hard cases, was one hesitant voice who warned that the
Microsoft case might indeed lie at the outer limits of the court's
institutional competence.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he noted that antitrust cases, unlike most
other cases of equivalent complexity, go to court in raw form,
without having been predigested by an administrative agency with
special expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a court is stuck with a technically complex case, it can
usually turn to strategies of avoidance,'' Sunstein said. ``In
administrative law, you defer to the agency. A real development of
20th century law was the shift from judicial to administrative
lawmaking. We don't have the common law of nuisance; we have the
EPA. We don't have the common law of fraud; we have the FTC.''
</P>
<P>
   But in antitrust, essentially common law constructed by judges
from the Sherman Act's cryptic phrases, the strategy of avoidance
``is not available,'' he said. Without an expert agency to defer
to, explained Sunstein, judges cannot take the path of least
resistance _ that is, ``letting specialists make the first-line
decisions, subject to review by generalists for some sign of
arbitrariness or unfairness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Microsoft context, he said, that leaves the court without
much of a lifeline as it navigates uncharted territory. ``To the
extent that this case can be resolved on standard antitrust
doctrine, the facts are pretty straightforward,'' Sunstein said.
``What's messy is to figure out how to apply antitrust when
technology and the market are both changing rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the justices, no one has given more thought to the
relationship between law and science than Breyer, who also happens
to have taught antitrust at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that in this age of science, we must build legal
foundations that are sound in science, as well as in law,'' he said
in a 1998 speech to the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, which he praised for a study on expanded roles for
court-appointed experts.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in his speech last month at the Cambridge
biomedical research symposium, Breyer said the view that Supreme
Court justices ``need not know science but only law to make
decisions'' was ``increasingly unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of ``creating a generalist voice that will speak
for an age of specialization,'' he said, was ``difficult to
accomplish, but it is important to try.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-ART-     06-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-SUIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE SMOKING DAMAGES ARE ARGUED, PLAINTIFFS FIGHT FOR AIR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the din here in the old courtroom, lawyers fight for
billions of dollars as the people in the gallery fight for air.
</P>
<P>
   With as much as $100 billion at risk in a lawsuit brought by
Florida smokers against cigarette makers, lawyers argue hot and
loud whether the tobacco companies should be punished with a huge
judgment _ until the state court judge, tired of all the shouting,
quiets them down.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the lull, the survivors of a pack-a-day past can be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of ruined lungs and surgically altered voices drifts
softly across the pews in the Miami-Dade Courthouse. The hiss of
oxygen bottles mixes with the tortured breaths of lifetime smokers,
and men who suck air into their lungs through holes in their
throats whisper hoarsely to women widowed by cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the front pew, which he has occupied every court day for 22
months in various stages of the lawsuit, 62-year-old Guillermo Saa
speaks through an electronic voice box. A white bib covers the hole
surgeons left after cutting away part of his throat, his larynx and
other cancerous tissue around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   With each breath, the bib gently rises and falls, rises and
falls.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that their scars and surgeries and shortened lives
might be partly their fault, that they could have quit, if they had
truly tried, is not something these former smokers entertain for
very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stop,'' Saa said outside the courtroom, in his
mechanical voice. ``The most I lasted was two or three days.''
</P>
<P>
   The former smokers and their friends and family members file
into the courtroom every day, a dozen or so, sometimes more, and
always sit in the first few rows on the right-hand side. These are
mostly older people, who started smoking years before it was common
knowledge that the habit could kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Saa comes to see the trial, which is his own story in a way,
played out.
</P>
<P>
   He knew, long before his operation to remove the cancerous
tissue in 1982, that smoking could kill him or ruin his life, but
the habit, the pure pleasure it gave him, was overpowering, he
said. Like others in this courtroom, he became hooked as a young
man, before he knew of the long-term effects. When he did know
smoking could kill him, quitting required more will than he
possessed.
</P>
<P>
   He sits day by day beside people who know that craving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have pulmonary emphysema,'' said Valentin Venas, 72, of
Miami. ``I cannot be cured.'' He started smoking when he was 12.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the way it is with smoking, people here said. If it
does not ruin the quality of your life, as it did with Saa, it
steals the end of it. The people in the first few pews are not the
worst off of the 300,000 to 500,000 people who are joined in the
lawsuit against five major cigarette makers. The worst off, under
oxygen tents, cannot come to the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are more dead than living, still waiting,'' said
Saa, who lives with his wife, Nancy, on Miami Beach. But he never
goes into the ocean. He is afraid that the water will slip down the
hole in his throat and drown him.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit they have come to monitor has already cost the
cigarette industry $12.7 million in compensatory damages. The same
jury in Miami-Dade Circuit Court is hearing the punitive stage,
which is expected to continue for about another week, so the
smokers are cautious but hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   They point out that many courts have already found cigarettes to
be a dangerously addictive product, one designed to be so. One inch
of small print on the side of a cigarette pack _ a warning easily
overlooked, or ignored _ was flimsy protection from that, the
smokers said.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Ruiz, who came here from Puerto Rico, where smoking is
almost a national pastime, comes to the trial and sits there, for
her dead husband. ``In the middle of the night he would go to the
bathroom, and then he would lie down and smoke,'' said Ruiz. Her
husband, Francisco Ruiz, died from cancer in 1978. ``He would give
up food, just to smoke more.''
</P>
<P>
   Each person here has a story of how easy it was to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoking for me was by choice,'' said Saa, of the beginning of
his habit. He was on an airplane flight from Colombia to Miami, in
1954. A flight attendant, he said, handed out sample packages with
just three cigarettes inside. Three cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hooked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saa came to the United States to study English in Louisiana. He
noticed that everywhere he looked, even the hallways of public
buildings, there were cigarette vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone smoked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the culture. Movie stars who got the girl smoked. Women
smoked _ but only sitting down. Even professional athletes smoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't warnings,'' Saa said. ``In 1964, they started to
give notice'' of the health risks of smoking. ``I already had the
addiction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, there was always the feeling that while it
might happen to others, it could not really happen to him, the same
feeling that people have driving past the scene of a bloody highway
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would harm me this much,'' Saa said. ``I
never thought I would get like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies countered the warnings with their own
scientific data.
</P>
<P>
   Some taking part in the lawsuit say it is not about the money
and some say that is exactly what it is about, forcing the tobacco
companies to pay for ruined lives. But with as many as 500,000
joined in the lawsuit, even a $100 billion judgment would be spread
pretty thin.
</P>
<P>
   Saa said she and her husband lost everything to his medical
bills, including their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a fatal life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Saa said there was one good thing about his ordeal. His children
do not smoke. They look at him, and cannot. He talks to
schoolchildren, to show them how dangerous it is to smoke, and the
high price they could someday pay for trying to be cool.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the tobacco industry have argued that the modern-day
executives have changed, that they recognize the dangers, that they
have refused to aim advertisements at new smokers. That, the
tobacco lawyers said, should be considered by the jury in any
judgment of punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The former smokers in the courtroom shake their heads at that.
The legacy of distrust is too strong.
</P>
<P>
   But smokers who have quit think that quitting, while painful,
was possible, and that it has saved them _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any innocent victims here,'' Donald
Livingstone, 70, a lawyer and former smoker, said as he passed by
the courtroom. ``All these people took the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The terrible thing about quitting, some smokers said, is that a
seed might have already been planted deep inside the body that
flowers into death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit at 55,'' Livingstone said. ``I knew my life would lose
all its quality to it.'' But, he said, ``if I had a lethal
diagnosis, I would probably light up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
