A3321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-RADIO0603-COX     06-02 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RADIO0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed deal could move around the local radio dial
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's fourth-highest-rated radio station, the
adult R&AMP;B formatted Kiss 104.7 (WALR-FM), may soon move down the
dial to 104.1 _ knocking smooth jazz station Jazz Flavors (WJZF-FM
104.1) off the air _ if Cox Radio's offer to buy Midwestern
Broadcasting is accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The news came late Friday, when Cox Radio announced it had
exercised a right of first refusal to buy Midwestern Broadcasting
for $280 million _ one of the highest price tags for a radio deal
in Atlanta history.
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern's chief asset is WALR-FM (104.7), which it purchased
in 1992 for $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cox Radio, Midwestern hasn't responded to the
offer. Midwestern Vice President David Dickey was not available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would not include two other properties owned by the
Dickey family in Atlanta, WCNN-AM (680) and Glory 1340 (WALR-AM).
</P>
<P>
   The deal would expand Cox Radio's power in Atlanta. It's the
city's biggest group owner of radio stations, with WSB-AM (750 _
news/talk), B 98.5 (WSB-FM 98.5 _ soft rock), Jazz Flavors (WJZF-FM
104.1 _ smooth jazz), 95.5/The Beat (WBTS-FM 95.5 _ rhythmic Top
40) and Fox 97 (WFOX-FM 97.1 FM _ oldies). Cox Radio is majority
owned by Cox Enterprises, which owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Morgan, co-chief operating officer for Cox Radio, said the
company ``would not change'' Kiss 104.7's format. Cox Radio also
announced a deal with Salem Communications to trade the license and
transmitting facilities of WALR-FM for the license and transmitting
facilities of KKHT-FM in Houston. Cox will retain WALR's
``intellectual property,'' i.e. the format, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Salem, specializing in religious programming, recently bought
arts station WGKA-AM (1190).
</P>
<P>
   No one was available Friday to say what it plans to do with the
104.7 frequency in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
