</P>
<P>
   MCCAW-TELEDESIC (Kirkland, Wash.) _ Can Craig McCaw salvage
Teledesic, his futuristic scheme to dot the stratosphere with a
266-satellite network for voice and data communications? Many
investors are second-guessing McCaw, but he just plowed another
$1.2 billion into the project, which he considers ``an Internet in
the sky.'' The 50-year-old billionaire is described as farsighted,
a gambler and the ``billionaire whom even other billionaires find
interesting.'' By Barnaby J. Feder. With photo and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-SCOTUS (Washington) _ When the Supreme Court confronted
its first Internet case three years ago, the justices received
special training from their library staff. Now the Microsoft
antitrust case is heading to the Supreme Court. Are the justices
ready for the world of platforms, applications, source codes, and
interfaces? By Linda Greenhouse. With photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ At first glance, the 30 percent growth
in operating income that IBM booked last year looks impressive. But
check out Footnote W and you will see that just under a third of
the increase came from IBM's employee pension plan. ``Obfuscation
is the name of the game, not just for IBM but for a lot of
companies,'' explains one consultant. By Gretchen Morgenson. With
graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-LINDAHL (Zurich, Switzerland) _ In the three years since
Goeran Lindahl took over the Swedish multinational ABB _ part of
the empire associated with Sweden's Wallenberg dynasty _ he has
shed the power generation, nuclear and rail divisions that marked
ABB as an anchor of the old economy to gain it a larger place in
the technology-driven world of the new. He has also dismantled the
company's complex ownership structure, which involved two holding
companies and four categories of stock to protect control of the
Wallenberg family in Sweden and the Schmidheiny family in
Switzerland. Alan Cowell profiles Lindahl and ABB.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-CZECHOSLOVAKIA (Prague) _ Czechoslovakia becomes a
pioneer in wireless banking and bill-paying. By Peter Green.
