<P>
   INVEST-UTILITIES (Undated) _ Utilities have been showing
surprising resilience in a rising interest rate environment. Here's
what lies ahead. By Robert D. Hershey Jr. With graphic of the
Standard &AMP; Poor's Index. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-RETURNS (Undated) Two of this country's most influential
finance professors, Eugene F. Fama of the University of Chicago and
Ken French of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, have just
completed research showing that the expected return from stocks is
more than five percentage points a year lower than previously
thought. Though this research has not yet been published, word of
it is beginning to spread. By Mark Hurlbert. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-CALLIES (Undated) _ Remember the Goldilocks
economy? The not too hot, not too cold, low inflation porridge
beloved by Alan Greenspan and financial markets? The latest numbers
seem to indicate what had been a steaming dish is beginning to cool
and it could turn stone cold. Kenneth N. Gilpin interviews
Christine Callies, chief U.S. market strategist at Credit Suisse
First Boston. She likes electrical equipment companies that are
developing new-economy growth rates and are trading at old-economy
prices: SCI Systems, Sanmina and General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-KLECZKA-BLAIRVALUE _ (Undated) Glen A. Kleczka, lead
manager of the $58 million William Blair Value Discovery fund, sums
up his value philosophy simply: ``We buy broken stocks,'' he said,
``not broken companies.'' A ``broken stock'' typically trades at 50
percent or more off its five-year-high stock price, and its
valuation is depressed, he said. A company that is not ``broken''
has several attributes: leading market share, improving
profitability, and management that is initiating share repurchase
plans. By Carole Gould. With graphic and photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANNUITIES-SEC (Undated) _ Monday, the Securities and Exchange
Commission plans to take the unusual step of publishing an investor
alert on its Web site, www.sec.gov, on the pitfalls of variable
annuities. Joseph Treaster describes the SEC document, ``Variable
Annuities: What You Should Know,'' as reading like a sober antidote
to a salesman's smooth patter. The agency warns, in particular,
that bonuses now being offered as a lure by many variable annuity
companies ``may not be in your best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-COLUMN-DOLE (Undated) _ Bob Dole is an unlikely
spokesman for older Americans. After all, the former Kansas senator
voted against the creation of Medicare in 1965, although he has
since supported it. He loathes the idea of retiring and, at 76,
doesn't consider himself old. But he has become a hero to senior
citizens for surviving prostate cancer, for speaking out about
using Viagra, the impotency drug, and for his sense of humor.
Actually, he says, some of the Viagra jokes made at his expense
were pretty funny. By Fred Brock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRYSTALBALL-ECONOMCY (Washington) _ The writer looks into a
crystal ball and foresees: two interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve this summer; a larger than expected federal
surplus; and, the new economy emerging as a campaign issue. The
crystal ball is a prototype without a warranty. Check back in a few
months to determine its accuracy. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Daniel Akst suggests forfeiting the
professional quality stove or the new sports utility vehicle and
saving up for a really important commodity _ freedom. Ditch that
lucrative but unworthy gig you've been slaving at all these years
and do something you believe in _ teach school, start a business,
move to the country, read a book, for Pete's sake. Unfortunately,
the author concludes, freedom has a marketing problem.
</P>
<P>
</P>
