<P>
   TV-FASHION-SEX (New York) _ Times fashion critic Cathy Horyn
writes about the style on ``Sex and the City'' and comes away
disappointed in the clothes and the show. She raises the question:
Isn't the show ``just a swankier version of ``The Golden Girls''?
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STYLE-REGIS (New York) _ Monday Regis Philbin will introduce
Regis, by Van Heusen just in time for Father's Day June 18. Fashion
magazines say the ```millionaire look'' of monochromatic shirts and
tie sets is ``on trend.'' In fact, if the manufacturer's $50
million sales projection is accurate, then Philbin may have found a
licensing path to becoming a millionaire. By Rick Marin. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   GAVIN-PROFILE (New York) _ Gavin Brown, a British-born art
dealer, represents a roster of rising stars, the best known of whom
is Chris Ofili, whose creativity with elephant dung created a fuss
at the Brooklyn Museum. Brown is also the proprietor of Passerby, a
bar adjacent to his gallery. Next door, Brown's wife, Lucy Barnes,
runs a clothing boutique. All three are part of a nexus of cool in
Manhattan on West 15th Street. By Elizabeth Hayt. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOM-READING (Undated) _ Harold Bloom, the Yale professor whose
latest book is ``How to Read and Why,'' writes about the depressing
experience of reading the latest Michael Crichton thriller
downloaded onto a portable PC. ``Crichton's prose is as dead as the
14th century,'' he writes, ``and if you're reading it on a
hand-held computer, it is a double ordeal, physical and
stylistic.'' Information may be fine transmitted on a screen, he
concludes, but ``wisdom and beauty cry out'' for a book.
</P>
<P>
   NITE-OUT-TELLER (New York) _ A night on the town with Jurgen
Teller, the fashion photographer, who is best known for discovering
Kate Moss and creating a look that has been described as dirty
realism and heroin chic. Bob Morris, the reporter, says Teller's
images have helped lower the traditional standards of beauty. ``I
don't care about fashion at all,'' Teller says, and he adds that
being a fashion photographer is a ``kind of pathetic occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   EIGHTIES-RETURN (Undated) _ From her boutique in Beverly Hills,
Gale Hayman, had a front row seat for the lavish fashion of the
'80s. Now, she reports, furs, feathers, higher heels, pink
lipstick, pony skin and leopard boots, Chanel quilted chain belts
and big hair have all reappeared. The difference is that back then,
women wore it all together, head to toe. Now it's edited down to
one great piece at a time.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ This is the best time to order bulbs
for fall. The memory of the ones that worked is still in your mind,
and there are hefty discounts for orders placed before July 1. By
Anne Raver
</P>
<P>
   The following stories moved in the ``i'' category.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ISSUE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lurking just below the surface
in the campaign of 2000 is the issue of personal privacy.
Democratic and Republican pollsters both say it is a sleeper issue.
By Richard J. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-REVIEW (United Nations) _ For years the United
States has classified some countries, like Iraq and North Korea, as
``rogue states.'' Now, as the world becomes more democratic _ more
than 60 percent of countries have elected leaders _ something more
complicated enters the political lexicon. Call them ``rogue
democracies.'' By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   HEIGHT-VANITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ A study appearing this month in
the American Statistical Association Proceedings reports that many
Americans appear to lie about their height. Not weight or age,
though they lie about that, too. But height? Why? By Eric
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   DETERRENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ For nearly half a century the Cold
War world's tense stability was built on a simple bit of political
philosophy. Nicknamed, appropriately, MAD, for Mutual Assured
Destruction, it held that the leader of a country advanced enough
to build nuclear weapons would never actually use them if he was
assured his nation would also be obliterated by his enemy. As
nuclear technology proliferates, however, the nuclear equation is
becoming more complicated, and a new view of deterrence is growing
rapidly in importance. By Michael Oreskes.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GINGRICH-REVIEW (Washington) _ As Gov. George W. Bush rolls
out policy address after policy address, congressional Republicans
are watching in admiration as he does what Newt Gingrich, Trent
Lott and the self-effacing J. Dennis Hastert could not: win a fresh
hearing for ideas cherished by true-blue conservatives. It's the
Newt-less revolution. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-VIRUSES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The ``I Love You'' bug,
allegedly launched by a Philippines computer student with too much
time on his hands, touched off a cyber-flu season. More than 29
variants have emerged so far, including diabolical derivatives with
names like ``NewLove'' and ``Resume _ Janet Simons.'' The question
is, what's love got to do with it? Quite a lot, perhaps. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-ROCK&AMP;ROLL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Perhaps it was inevitable
that as the Internet began permeating the culture, the techie
language that was once confined to textbooks and instruction
manuals would begin to sound beautiful, or at least pretty enough
to sing. Physicists, who among other things invented the World Wide
Web, have been quick to realize that their lexicon is no longer too
obscure for pop songs. By James Gantz.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   PERU-REVIEW (Lima, Peru) _ Authoritarianism and democracy have
long coexisted in this region where nation states were founded by
generals and oligarchs where the ideals of the European
Enlightenment never developed very deep roots. Octavio Paz, the
Mexican essayist, once wrote that the problem with democracy in
Latin America is that it was ``imported but not adopted.'' By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-REVIEW (Port Au-Prince, Haiti) _ More than five years
after a United States-led military occupation restored democratic
rule in Haiti, the civil serenity that Haitians hoped for remains
elusive. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-REVIEW (London) _ Northern Ireland is locked in a grim
struggle to trade in tested old tribal instincts for risky new
communal ones, and the tensions and reluctances of that swap were
on display this week in the actions of a key figure in the peace
negotiations, David Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-REVIEW (Nairobi) _ The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea
is often described as the most deadly in the world, fought on
terrain of little consequence while millions of people in two very
poor countries face starvation. This is all true. But the war is
also something else, something that has become quite rare: A war
fought between the regular armies of two nations, in which both
sides generally follow the rules of war. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
