<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-COMPTON-OBSERVATO     06-02 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPTON-OBSERVATORY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA SET FOR CRASH OF HUGE SPACECRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   by WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a mix of sadness and anticipation, NASA
engineers on Friday prepared for the fiery death this weekend of a
giant spacecraft that has made pioneering discoveries in gamma ray
astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   After gradually lowering the orbit of the 17-ton craft, the
Compton Gamma Ray Observatory, with a series of rocket firings _ a
process they have already begun _ technicians will guide it into
Earth's atmosphere early Sunday, Eastern Daylight Time, for a fatal
plunge into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time NASA will have intentionally guided so
large a craft to its destruction, in hope of minimizing danger to
people on the ground. The bus-size spacecraft has been operating
with only two of its three stabilizing gyroscopes since December,
and NASA officials calculated that if it lost another gyroscope and
came down on its own, there would be a 1-in-1,000 chance that
someone would be killed by the debris.
</P>
<P>
   So engineers at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt,
Md., who have controlled the scientific mission of the observatory
during its nine years in space, now find themselves getting ready
for its death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood right now is pretty sad,'' Dr. Neil Gehrels, Compton
project scientist, said in an interview from Goddard on Friday.
``It's been a great mission with a great spacecraft, and now it's
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, engineers began a four-stage process to slowly lower
the observatory in preparation for its final descent, into the
atmosphere. That day a 23-minute firing of small thruster rockets
aboard the craft brought the low point of its orbit down to 226
miles, from 316. Then a 26-minute firing on Wednesday night lowered
the orbit to 155 miles and let engineers fine-tune their
projections for the spacecraft's terminal dive into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The final stages for Compton's controlled re-entry are to begin
on Sunday at 12:01 a.m., EDT, with a 26-minute rocket burn that
slows the craft and lowers it to a 95-mile-high orbit. This is to
be followed by a fourth and final thruster firing, of 30 minutes'
duration starting at 1:30 a.m., that will nudge Compton down to 48
miles. At that altitude, the thicker atmosphere will begin heating
and breaking apart the spacecraft, which will be streaking in at
16,000 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said about six tons of metal debris was expected
to survive re-entry and smash into a remote part of the Pacific
about 2,500 miles southeast of Hawaii about 2:20 a.m., EDT.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard, the Federal Aviation Administration and other
agencies have issued warnings for ships and planes to avoid that
area during the operation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NASA has arranged for the Air Force to monitor the final
destruction of Compton with one of its special Cobra Ball
missile-tracking airplanes, equipped with radar scanners and
infrared and optical sensors. Officials want the plane to track
different pieces of the spacecraft as it breaks up, to help NASA
refine computer programs designed to predict the behavior of large
craft as they re-enter the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrels said several large pieces of the Compton observatory
were expected to survive re-entry almost intact before hitting the
ocean, including the solid aluminum bus, or keel, on which the
craft was built; a large sodium-iodide crystal weighing several
hundred pounds; and four 125-pound pieces of tungsten that are part
of one of the instruments aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Also raining down will be 5,500 bolts of various sizes made of
heat-resistant titanium metal. ``These are going to come down
basically intact, like the spray from a shotgun blast,'' Gehrels
said.
</P>
<P>
   Compton will be the biggest spacecraft to fall from orbit since
the United States' 100-ton Skylab space station burned up over the
Indian Ocean in July 1979. Although most of Skylab disintegrated in
the atmosphere, some pieces survived the uncontrolled re-entry and
landed in Western Australia. No one was injured in the Skylab
episode, but NASA officials say the risk of injury from descent of
a large craft is too great to leave to chance.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have criticized NASA, however, saying it acted
too quickly in deciding to bring down Compton, for which there is
currently no substitute for observations in gamma ray astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   The $670 million spacecraft, deployed by the space shuttle
Atlantis in April 1991, is one of NASA's Great Observatories
series, like the Hubble Space Telescope and the Chandra X-ray
Observatory, designed to study the heavens at all wavelengths of
the electromagnetic spectrum. Gamma rays, which are invisible and
have energies greater than visible light and ultraviolet or X-ray
radiation, appear to come from the most violent cosmic phenomena
and reveal details about the universe that otherwise could not be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James M. Ryan, a professor of physics at the University of
New Hampshire, who used one of Compton's special telescopes, said
NASA had not seriously pursued contingency plans like running the
observatory with two gyroscopes, or even one. Many scientists,
including some at NASA, are angered by the decision to kill
Compton, he said, but are afraid to speak out publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No section of astronomy has hung so much on one spacecraft as
the gamma ray people,'' Ryan said in a telephone interview. ``We
are going to be blind to a huge chunk of the universe for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward J. Weiler, NASA's chief scientist, said it was his
decision to bring the observatory down now, because waiting, he
said, would have increased the risk of human injury from an
uncontrolled re-entry. He acknowledged that engineers at Goddard
had come up with a theoretical backup plan to continue operating
the observatory and bring it down later, but he said that it would
have increased risk to humans by eight times and that there was no
way to test it. And engineers calculated that there was a 1-in-10
chance that a second gyroscope would fail in as little as a year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could the Goddard engineers, if they had more time, come up
with a way to control the observatory?'' Weiler said. ``I'd bet my
house that they could. But I can't bet a human life on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiler noted that the Compton mission had been planned to last
three to five years, and had lasted nine. ``We got a lot of value
out of this observatory, and scientists will be analyzing data from
Compton for years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrels, of Goddard, said that some 20 percent of Compton's data
had not been studied yet and that analysis of what had been
gathered before the spacecraft's science instruments were turned
off a week ago could occupy scientists for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Further, ``the silver lining here is that there are some
exciting new gamma ray missions coming soon,'' Gehrels said,
including the launching of Europe's Integral spacecraft in 2002,
the flight of the United States' Explorer Swift mission in 2003 or
2004, and the launching of the giant Gamma-Ray Large Area Space
Telescope around 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
