u f BC-CANCERDRUG-SUIT-BOS &LR;      06-02 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCERDRUG-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREMED ASSAILS PATENT LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president of EntreMed Inc., a Maryland biotech firm
developing some of Dr. Judah Folkman's novel cancer drugs, Thursday
denounced a patent suit against Folkman as a ``reprehensible
attempt'' to discredit the cancer researcher, and added the action
is ``egregious, tasteless, and shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Holaday, EntreMed's chairman, president, and chief
executive, said that Abbott Laboratories' suit over a patent on a
form of the drug angiostatin is aimed at obtaining ``the rights to
a product it neither discovered nor owns.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical giant, based in Abbott Park, Ill., filed the
suit this week after three years of negotiations over rights to
``Kringle 5'' _ a form of the drug angiostatin, which starves
tumors by shutting off their blood supply. The suit contends that
Folkman and Children's Hospital, where Folkman has a large
laboratory, wrongly obtained a patent on Kringle 5, which is said
to be a particularly potent form of angiostatin.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, Children's, and EntreMed _ all named as defendants _
maintain that Kringle 5, like the other forms of angiostatin, were
discovered in Folkman's laboratory. Children's officials said
Thursday they will file a reply to the lawsuit within the required
20 days, and said they believe they will prevail in court.
</P>
<P>
   Holaday said in Thursday's statement that patents held by
Children's, which is affiliated with Harvard University, and by
EntreMed cover all combinations of Kringles 1 through 5. A form of
angiostatin that includes Kringles 1-3 is undergoing initial human
testing in Philadelphia; it is not at issue in the legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, the pioneer of the field of angiogenesis _ the growth
of blood vessels that feed tumors _ has no personal financial
interest in EntreMed or in the development of angiostatin.
</P>
<P>
   Companies frequently sue each other over patent rights in the
burgeoning biotech world, but one patent expert said firms usually
don't sue academic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be reluctant to bring suits against our friends in the
universities, because of the collaborative opportunities and
goodwill we get from them,'' said Thomas J. DesRosier, vice
president and chief patent counsel at Genzyme Corp. in Cambridge.
He said, however, that Abbott is known for being aggressive in
intellectual-property issues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vituperative language in Abbott's suit, which
contends Folkman and the hospital perpetrated ``fraud'' and
``conspiracy,'' DesRosier said he doubted Folkman's reputation
would suffer from the accusations, unless they proved true.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty highly respected, and the general philosophy is
that you give people of Folkman's stature benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed stock closed up $2.5625 Thursday, to $26.1875, on the
Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
