<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHAIR-TRIAL0603-COX     06-02 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-TRIAL0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VBy Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal jury Friday convicted Gary Paul Karr
of participating in the disappearance of Madalyn O'Hair, giving
prosecutors their first conviction in the presumed murder of
Austin's loudest atheist and her family.
</P>
<P>
   But the verdict leaves the case's most vexing question
unanswered: Where are the bodies of O'Hair, her son and
granddaughter?
</P>
<P>
   Jurors found Karr not guilty of conspiring to kidnap O'Hair, her
son Jon Garth Murray and granddaughter Robin Murray-O'Hair. But
jurors also delivered four guilty verdicts, ranging from extortion
to taking stolen goods across state lines, as Karr listened
expressionlessly.
</P>
<P>
   With eight previous felony convictions, he faces life in prison
under the federal ``three strikes'' law. Sentencing is scheduled
for Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's best chance for a reduced sentence could be cooperating
with federal authorities, perhaps by revealing where the O'Hairs
are buried. Federal law gives defendants one year from their
sentencing date to cut their jail time by substantially helping
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But Karr has maintained his innocence, never indicating that he
has additional information to give, even for a plea bargain, said
his attorney, Tom Mills. ``I would be open to it, but he has never
said that to me, even in confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-man, four-woman jury returned the guilty verdicts
after deliberating 32 hours over four days in Austin's federal
courthouse. In a case without bodies, eyewitnesses or direct
physical evidence, prosecutors sought to convince jurors that the
O'Hairs died in a September 1995 kidnapping scheme masterminded by
the family's office manager, David Roland Waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough case, a very complex case,'' said federal
prosecutor Gerald Carruth. ``We're satisfied with the jury's
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Waters recruited Karr and Florida friend Danny
Fry to hold the family hostage for one month and extort $500,000 in
gold coins from them. Prosecutors believe the trio was killed,
dismembered in a North Austin storage unit and buried in a Hill
Country ranch.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, several jurors said that without bodies, they
felt uncomfortable concluding that the O'Hairs were killed. And
they were troubled by the fact that Jon Murray _ who flew to New
Jersey to retrieve the money with Karr, and even sat in a bank
conference room with an off-duty police officer during the alleged
kidnapping _ did not appear distressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One belief on the jury was that the O'Hairs were part of a
scheme to obtain money, and that scheme went wrong,'' said jury
foreman Hector Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors did believe that Karr conspired to extort money from the
family. He was found guilty of extortion, interstate traveling to
aid in racketeering, committing a criminal act to gain financially,
and interstate transportation of stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors used credit card receipts, van rental records,
telephone bills and testimony to tie Karr to the disappearances.
The case included more than 70 witnesses and hundreds of documents.
</P>
<P>
   Juror Jeff Babcock praised the prosecution's circumstantial
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just the quantity of the evidence, it was the
quality of the evidence,'' he said. ``They connected it all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is: What next?
</P>
<P>
   Karr is the first _ and only _ person convicted in the O'Hair
disappearance. Waters has not been charged in the case. Fry was
killed, his body dumped in Dallas County. And prosecutors barely
touched on suspicions surrounding a fourth man, Gerald ``Chico''
Osborne, alleged to have rented the storage unit where the bodies
were dismembered. Osborne recently pleaded guilty in Fort Worth to
unrelated gun charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have until October 2000 _ when the five-year statute
of limitations expires _ to charge additional suspects with any
non-capital offenses in the O'Hairs' disappearance. After that,
federal prosecutors have only one option: murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   But whether officials will go after Waters is unclear. The
53-year-old Illinois native, who pleaded guilty in 1995 to stealing
$54,000 from the O'Hairs' atheist organization, is serving 60 years
in state prison for probation violation in that theft. And proving
a murder case without additional evidence could be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Karr cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have long suspected that Karr knows more than
he's telling. Before trial, plea negotiations between the two sides
stalled when they could not agree on a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   If Karr talks, authorities could stage a new search for the
bodies. Trial testimony indicated that the O'Hairs, believed to
have been buried on a Hill country ranch, may have been moved to an
unspecified subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors won't detail their next move. But Robert Pitman,
chief of the U.S. Attorney's Office in Austin, said the
investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that the United States will not rest until we
have done everything in our power to bring all responsible parties
to justice,'' Pitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said the trial left them with no doubt that Waters
spearheaded the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the evidence pointed to David Waters,'' Rodriguez
said. ``The difficulty of our decision was linking Karr to David
Waters. First, we had to decide that Waters had committed a crime.
Then we had to connect Karr to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the O'Hair mystery begins in 1993, when Waters
answered a newspaper ad for a typesetter at American Atheists, the
O'Hairs' Austin-based organization. Waters, who could type 90 words
a minute, was hired and eventually became the O'Hairs' office
manager.
</P>
<P>
   After Waters stole $54,000 from American Atheists, the O'Hairs
sought a restraining order against him and erected a security fence
around the atheist headquarters. When O'Hair blasted Waters in an
atheist newsletter, Waters vowed revenge, testimony in Karr's trial
showed.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1995, the family abruptly disappeared from their
Austin home. Dirty breakfast dishes sat on the table and medicine
for the ailing Madalyn O'Hair's was left behind. The family's
cherished cocker spaniels _ Gallagher, Gannon and Shannon _
remained unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Waters, Karr and Fry held the family hostage at
the Warren Inn in San Antonio and forced them to transfer $600,000
from New Zealand to a New Jersey bank account. Karr and Jon Murray
flew to New Jersey to pick up the money, later converting it into
gold coins in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Only $500,000 was retrieved. The O'Hairs vanished in late
September, leaving the remaining $100,000 in gold unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Waters allegedly hid the gold in a Burnet Road storage unit.
Three San Antonio men testified that they stole the gold while
breaking into random units _ blowing it all on cars, strip clubs
and jewelry in two frivolous years of spending.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also believe Fry _ who, unlike his companions, had
never been convicted of a felony _ was killed because the
kidnappers feared he would talk.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers contended that Karr, a handyman who spent 20
years in prison for armed robbery and kidnapping, was hired to
guard the O'Hairs as they prepared to flee the country to escape
federal tax problems. Defense lawyers suggest the family is
secretly living in a remote location. Prosecutors suspect their
bones were washed away by floods and possibly eaten by feral hogs.
</P>
<P>
   As one lawyer said, ``The might have washed away to the Red
Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
