<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO MARTINEZ TO SIT OUT A START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pedro Martinez has started 10 games in eight
cities this season, picking up baseball converts at each stop.
Friday night, he arrived in his ninth city on the Pedro Tour and
made an announcement: Saturday's show has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was scheduled to make his 11th start Saturday night at
Veterans Stadium against the Phillies. But after experiencing
soreness near the left side of his rib cage _ Jimy Williams called
it a ``hot spot'' _ the Red Sox ace decided it would be wise to
rest. He said he will be able to resume his magical season (8-2,
1.05 ERA) Thursday against the Indians. Tim Wakefield will
temporarily take his place in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' Martinez said several times Thursday, when
asked to describe his injury. He said he has had problems with his
oblique (muscle) since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to pitch with it for five years,'' he said.
``It's not a big deal. It's just something that we're trying to
take care of right now. I could pitch and be fine . . . We're just
trying to be careful with it because it's a little bit (inflammed)
and it's going to get worse if I keep pitching on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also weak from the flu and everything else, so it was the
perfect time to play it smart.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last start, May 28 against the Yankees, Martinez threw a
complete-game shutout to defeat Roger Clemens. But it took 128
pitches for the 170-pound Martinez to complete the game, and he did
so even though he was weak from the flu symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid was sick,'' Williams said. ``He pitched that game in
New York and that probably made it worse. We're going to help him
get his strength back now. He was bothered a little bit when he
threw on the side, so we're just going to back off a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The No Pedro News was disappointing to Philadelphians. The
Phillies are the worst team in the National League. They usually
play before empty blue seats here (they are fourth-worst in NL
attendance), so Martinez on the mound was a good reason to buy a
ticket. Both daily newspapers had stories on Martinez. One headline
referred to him as the ``Boston Strangler.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if fans want to chant and wave K cards, they will have to
do so for Wakefield, the Sox' ubiquitous emergency man. The
knuckleballer has started for both Martinez brothers in a pinch,
either because of suspensions (Pedro in Baltimore) or injuries
(Ramon in Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitching on one day's rest, which is more rest than he
had in Baltimore,'' Williams said of Wakefield, referring to a
relief appearance May 10 against the White Sox and a start the next
night against the Orioles. ``That's OK,'' Williams said of
Wakefield's short rest. ``I feel good about it.'' Later, the
manager added that, ``This is a marathon. We have to try to take
care of things the way we think it's best to take care of them.
We're trying to keep as many players healthy as we possibly can so
we can go out there and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   As reporters surrounded his locker Thursday and began asking
questions, Martinez scanned the crowd and noticed the serious
faces. That's when he announced, again, that ``this is no big
deal.'' So, he was asked, when will he pitch again?
</P>
<P>
   ``In my very next outing,'' he said with a shrug. ``I'll just go
out there and pitch again. I'll be in the same rotation. Just
(Saturday's) start, I'm not going to make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
