u s BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-02 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO NOW JUST A FOOTNOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It turns out that Salt Lake's dreaded ``geld'' memo, which some
believed would prove the bidders bribed International Olympic
Committee members to land the 2002 Winter Games, was much ado about
little. Most of the memo, which lists members by their last names,
is so cryptic as to be useless, e.g. _ MUKORA: geld, half and half.
KUMAR: Health, kids, geld. MZALI: Son a future.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``geld'' is the German word for money, nothing in the
memo indicates that any changed hands. Some entries, though, are
telling: HAGGMAN: Husband needs a job. HAGGMAN is Pirjo Haeggman,
the Finnish member who resigned last year after it was disclosed
that her husband worked for the bid committee. And most of the
members with ``geld'' next to their names, such as Congo's
Jean-Claude Ganga and Mali's Lamine Keita, ended up expelled in the
IOC's housecleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most members were relieved when SLOC chief Mitt Romney
released the memo during last week's IOC meetings in Rio de
Janeiro. ``I was glad I was blank,'' said US member Anita DeFrantz.
</P>
<P>
   Blank, too, was IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, Canada's
Dick Pound (who chaired the IOC's investigative panel), and
Australia's Kevan Gosper, who recently caught heat for a family ski
trip to Utah that was subsidized by the bidders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A magnificent splash
</P>
<P>
   Inge ``Inky'' de Bruijn of the Netherlands turned in the most
astounding performance in swimming history in Sheffield, England,
last weekend, hanging up world records in the women's 100 freestyle
(53.8 seconds) and 100 butterfly (56.69), equaling the global mark
(24.51) in the 50 free, and breaking the standard in the
non-Olympic 50 butterfly for fun. De Bruijn not only chopped more
than a second off Jenny Thompson's 100 fly record, she became the
first woman to go faster than 54 seconds in the 100 free, where she
busted the record set by China's Le Jingyi at the 1994 world meet.
Nobody has had that kind of a meet since Mary T. Meagher set her
two butterfly records in 1981. Thus the challenge for Thompson, who
was favored to win both the 100 free and fly at Sydney. De Bruijn's
times probably had something to do with the new Fastskin bodysuit
she was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One last (hand)stand?
</P>
<P>
   Who'll lead the US women's gymnastics squad back to the medal
stand in Sydney? Could be Shannon Miller, who at 23 has come out of
retirement to try for her third Olympic team. ``Shannon stepped
into the gym at our May camp and it was like a bombshell,''
reported team coordinator Bela Karolyi. ``The young ones' eyes
turned big and round and popped out of their heads. Shannon is
Shannon _ she's sturdy.'' Miller and two of her 1996 gold-medal
teammates (Amy Chow and Jaycie Phelps) have good chances to make
the six-member team. Not so Dominique Moceanu, says her former
mentor. ``The kid is not working,'' Karolyi said. ``She's trying to
get by on shortcuts.'' . . . Lighter load for Marion Jones, Michael
Johnson, Maurice Greene, and the rest of the sprinters at the US
Olympic track and field trials in Sacramento next month. The
qualifying rounds will be reduced from four to three to save legs.
Looks like a traffic jam in the men's 10,000, though, which will be
run as a final. More than 40 runners have already qualified . . .
In case anybody gripes if Jones is put on the women's 4 x 400 relay
without running the event at the trials, there's a precedent.
Florence Griffith Joyner was named to the quartet at Seoul and
anchored it to a silver medal. As it is, the 49.59 that Jones hung
up at the Mt. SAC Relays in April would have won last year's world
meet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting picky on selections
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the USA Softball people had to pick the Olympic team
over again after an arbitrator ruled that they'd based their
selections on more than just last summer's training camp, using
performance since the last Games and ``intangibles.'' That was the
gripe of part-time second baseman Julie Smith after she didn't make
the squad. So federation officials went back to Square 1 _ and
chose the same team again . . . Esther Kim, the US taekwondo
fighter who gave her Olympic spot to injured friend and training
partner Kay Poe, has become the consolation-prize queen. First, Poe
promised to buy her a plane ticket to Sydney. Now, the IOC has
invited Kim and her coach/father as their expenses-paid guests and
promised her a special award (probably the Olympic Order). ``I feel
like I have a gold medal in my heart,'' said Kim, after Samaranch
called her at her Houston home . . . The US women's soccer team
can't say it didn't have enough tuneups before the Olympics. By the
time it heads for Sydney, it will have played 32 matches in eight
months, three more than it has ever played in a calendar year.
After the ongoing Pacific Cup in Australia (where it lost, 1-0, to
China in their first meeting since last year's World Cup final),
the Americans play in the CONCACAF Gold Cup (meeting Brazil in
Foxborough June 27), a tournament in Germany, two games at Norway,
and three August matches in the States against Russia, Canada, and
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quite a feat
</P>
<P>
   Ben Olsen and John O'Brien may see double duty with both the US
Olympic soccer team and the World Cup qualifying squad this summer.
Usually, the Cup qualifiers begin after the Games. Not so this
time, with the Americans playing four of their first six regional
matches before the Olympics. No conflict, though, according to Cup
team coach Bruce Arena, who said Olympic coach Clive Charles can
have whatever under-23s he wants. ``It's not my position to
interfere with his team,'' Arena said . . . The US men's basketball
team will play its way across the Pacific to get ready for the
Olympics. The Americans will spend a week in Maui, facing Canada
and a US college all-star team, then four days in Japan, where
they'll meet the Spanish and Japanese. Then it's on to Melbourne
for a final week of workouts and a final exhibition with the
Australians before the Olympic opener against China . . . Among
this year's crop of inductees to the National Wrestling Hall of
Fame is former Emerson and Harvard coach Jim Peckham, who directed
US teams in 38 major international events, including the 1976
Olympics, and also competed in the 1956 Games, where he placed
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No country club in Sydney
</P>
<P>
   How will the East Timor athletes get to compete in Sydney, even
though their country still isn't recognized by the IOC (because it
doesn't have enough sports federations). They'll go generic,
wearing plain white uniforms and marching behind the Olympic flag.
No chance that they'll hold up the parade _ we're talking maybe
four runners and boxers . . . North and South Korea won't compete
together in Sydney, but they may march together in the opening
ceremonies. Samaranch has suggested it and leaders of the countries
will discuss the idea at their upcoming summit in Pyongyang. If it
happens, the teams will parade behind the Olympic flag . . .
Sticking around for a fourth shot at Olympus is Canadian skater
Elvis Stojko, who'll still be chasing his first gold medal (after
two silvers) at 30 at Salt Lake City . . . Used to be you had to
win a gold medal to get your face on a cereal box. Five of the
eight US athletes who'll grace Kellogg's packages this summer
(Jones and Greene, swimmer Lenny Krayzelburg, diver Mark Ruiz, and
cyclist Alison Dunlap) haven't heard the anthem played for them.
Those who have are Thompson, Chow, and softball player Leah
O'Brien-Amico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
