<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-02 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: A MAJOR POLITICAL SPEECH THAT WAS NEVER
DELIVERED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death on Tuesday of Robert P. Casey, the Democratic governor
of Pennsylvania from 1987 to 1994, was a reminder that one of the
most significant speeches in the last decade of American politics
was never delivered. It was significant, in fact, precisely because
it was never delivered.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 Democratic National Convention, Casey asked to
present a minority report opposing the party's plank on abortion
that declared ``reproductive choice'' a ``fundamental right''
deserving government financing. The party leadership barred Casey
from addressing the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The Casey obituaries mentioned the event, but they did not fully
capture its significance. It was a watershed in the nation's
political-moral discourse. At the national level of one of the two
major political parties, opposition to abortion had become
literally unspeakable.
</P>
<P>
   This was a momentous achievement for supporters of the right to
abortion. By 1988, of course, the Democratic Party platform had
already become uncompromisingly in favor of abortion rights. Gone
was the mollifying phrase in earlier platforms that Democrats
``fully recognize the religious and ethical concerns which many
Americans have about abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   But refusing the podium to the liberal and immensely popular
Casey (he won re-election in 1990 by the largest margin in
Pennsylvania history) went a step further. As David R. Carlin Jr.,
a frustrated Democratic state senator from Rhode Island, put it in
an Op-Ed article for The New York Times in August 1992: ``The
national Democratic leadership has made it plain that there is no
room in the party for opposition to abortion. Being pro-choice is
not simply a majority opinion; it has become a mandatory
position.''
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, that is not always true, but at the national
level it remains the case eight years later. No Democrat with
pretensions to national leadership can afford not to be strictly in
favor of abortion rights. Quite a few, including Vice President Al
Gore, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., have
jettisoned their previous reservations about abortion. When
something becomes undiscussable, it is pretty much irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   For abortion foes who had already cast their fortunes with the
Republican Party, the Democrats' sidelining of Casey meant little
more than another opportunity to say, ``We told you so.'' But for
those who considered themselves liberals or dyed-in-the-wool
Democrats, the moment posed a moral dilemma that remains unresolved
even now.
</P>
<P>
   Casey was their kind of politician, and if his credentials could
not earn one a hearing for an anti-abortion case, what could? The
Philadelphia Inquirer's obituary called him ``a fervent Democrat''
and a man who ``stood solidly behind some of his party's most
enduring ideals, particularly in his concern for poor and
blue-collar citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   He strove for health insurance for all Pennsylvanians and,
failing that, gained coverage for poor children whose families
became ineligible for Medicaid. He backed labor rights and tax
breaks for the poor, improved the workers' compensation system,
increased financing for public schools, mandated trash recycling
and upgraded local sewer and water facilities.
</P>
<P>
   He even pushed through a controversial tax increase _
``despised'' was the word used for it in The Inquirer obituary _
that allowed Pennsylvania to remain fiscally strong through
recessionary days and passed on a financial surplus to his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   That successor, Gov. Tom Ridge, is facing a similar interdict on
the other side of the abortion issue. A Republican who favors
abortion rights and, like Casey, an extremely popular leader in a
crucial state for the presidential race, Ridge has been promoted as
a possible running mate for Gov. George W. Bush Bush _ to cries of
betrayal and threats of abandonment from anti-abortion Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Litmus test'' is the term for this kind of unbendable standard
about abortion among Republicans, although it can operate at least
as rigorously among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is nothing wrong with litmus tests, in morals
and politics, no less than in the laboratory. Political parties
have every right to rule some topics totally off limits. Reasonable
citizens do not complain that Holocaust deniers, champions of
totalitarianism or defenders of lynching are denied recognition and
barred from convention microphones.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Democrats opposed to abortion and
Republicans who favor abortion rights should be lumped with such
company. In an editorial calling the Republican platform
``merciless'' on abortion, also in August 1992, The New York Times
warned that ``moderate, mainstream voices'' should not be kept from
making their case at the party's convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to free expression on abortion,'' the editorial
added, ``the Republicans have no patent on manipulation. The
Democrats acted even more crudely in New York last month. They were
so devoted to freedom of choice that they buried freedom of speech,
refusing to allow Gov. Robert Casey to voice anti-abortion
sentiments at their convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing that same month as a ``pro-life Democrat'' and a
sympathizer with the ``wimpy liberalism'' that rejected the
``winner-take-all mentality'' on both sides of the abortion debate,
Carlin said: ``We have been locked out of our own house, yet we
have no desire to enter the Republican house next door. We are
political pariahs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the success of the abortion rights' movement
that, two presidential races later, Republican divisions over
abortion continue to be scrutinized while the pariah status of
people like Carlin, with all its attendant resentments and election
booth abstentions, can be largely ignored. Ridge has a real chance
for the vice-presidential slot, while Casey would get even less a
hearing today than he did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1992 another Casey speech went undelivered, this time
at Cooper Union School of Architecture in New York. Casey was to
speak in the school's Great Hall, where, in 1860, Abraham Lincoln
had challenged the Supreme Court's acceptance of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting demonstrators in favor of abortion rights, however,
kept Casey from speaking. When Nat Hentoff, stalwart civil
libertarian, maverick opponent of abortion and writer for The
Village Voice, which was sponsoring the event, admonished the
demonstrators with recollections of Stalinism and left-wing
intolerance, they could not have cared less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murderers have no right to speak,'' they shouted, referring to
the dangers of illegal abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The title of this undelivered speech was ``Can a Liberal Be
Pro-Life?'' At Cooper Union, the demonstrators' answer was a
raucous ``No.'' In the Democratic Party, the answer is less raucous
but otherwise no different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
