<HEADER>
A3343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OHAIR-EXTORTION-NYT &LR;      06-02 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-EXTORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN GUILTY OF EXTORTION IN O'HAIR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From a headless, handless corpse on a muddy
riverbank to $500,000 in stolen gold and to a stream of receipts
from fancy hotels, federal prosecutors here used an ineluctable
chain of circumstantial evidence to convict a sometime handyman on
charges relating to the disappearance of the atheist Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, her son and her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman, Gary Paul Karr, 52, of Novi, Mich., was found
guilty Friday in U.S. District Court here of conspiracy to commit
extortion, traveling interstate to commit violent acts, money
laundering and interstate transportation of stolen property. He now
faces mandatory life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquitted of conspiracy to commit kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came nearly five years after O'Hair disappeared in
1995 along with her son, Jon Garth Murray, and her granddaughter,
Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, 76 at the time of her disappearance, drew national
attention when she made a legal challenge that led that to a 1963
Supreme Court ruling that effectively banned prayer in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son and her granddaughter disappeared in 1995. They
are presumed dead, but their bodies have never been found, nor has
anyone been charged in their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyer, Tom Mills, said he was disappointed with the
verdict, particularly because the jury found his client not guilty
of kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the basis of their whole case,'' Mills said. ``It
seems to undermine their whole theory. We have no kidnapping and no
murder, and yet he's still facing a life sentence for these
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   During the three-week trial, prosecutors built a mountain of
circumstantial evidence against Karr, who has three prior felony
convictions. Using 66 witnesses and 325 exhibits that included
credit card receipts and telephone bills, prosecutors linked him
with two other men suspected of killing O'Hair, her son and her
granddaughter and robbing them of $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities charged that Karr and two friends, Danny Fry and
David Roland Waters, kidnapped O'Hair and her family in late
September 1995, extorted money from them over a monthlong period
while holding them captive in San Antonio, then killed and
dismembered them at an Austin storage locker.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial, prosecutors said they believe that Karr and Waters
later killed Fry, cut off his head and hands and left his body on
the banks of the Trinity River near Dallas in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The federal authorities are still debating whether to try Karr
and Waters for murder in the death of Fry. Prosecutors have said
that they may try to strike a deal with Karr to gain his testify
against Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Karr's lawyers insisted that the
government had not proved its case beyond a reasonable doubt. They
contended that O'Hair had been planning for some time to flee the
country to avoid a battle with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The defense called only four witnesses, including the Rev.
William Gordon, a Baptist minister from Georgia, who testified last
week that he saw O'Hair eating pasta in a restaurant in Romania in
1997. But Gordon could not definitively say the woman he saw was
O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors countered with O'Hair's tax lawyer, Craig Etter, who
told the court that O'Hair's tax problems had largely been worked
out by the time of her disappearance and that fleeing the country
would have been out of character for the outspoken atheist.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was Karr who was on trial, much of the testimony
focused on Waters, a former office manager for O'Hair's American
Atheist organization, whom the authorities believe masterminded the
plot. Waters was convicted of stealing $54,400 from the group in
1994 and is serving a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence introduced by the prosecution showed that O'Hair and
her relatives had used $90,000 in credit cards and liquidated bank
accounts and that Murray bought at least $500,000 in gold coins the
month before O'Hair and her relatives disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after the disappearance, Waters and Karr went on a
spending spree, prosecutors said, spending thousands of dollars on
motorcycles, computers and expensive hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the Internal Revenue Service began looking
into the case in 1996 after The San Antonio Express-News reported
that officials of the American Atheist organization filed forms
with the IRS, reporting that the group was missing $610,000 and
that they believed Murray had the money.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, Jeff Sloan, 43, said the prosecutors presented a
compelling case for all of the charges against Karr, but they could
not agree on the kidnapping charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't necessarily say there was no kidnapping,'' Sloan
said as he left the courthouse. ``It was something we didn't
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said the jury could not agree on the intent element in the
kidnapping charge. Asked what he thought about the fate of O'Hair,
her son and her granddaughter, Sloan, who works for a computer
company in Austin, said he believed they were dead.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, eight men and four women, deliberated for more than
32 hours over four days before reaching their verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Karr is scheduled to be sentenced on Aug. 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
