<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3344 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-PIPELINE-FINE-SPI &LR;      06-02 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-FINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS CALL FOR RECORD FINE IN PIPELINE BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal regulators say Olympic Pipeline Co. should
be fined a record $3.05 million for ``unsafe and illegal''
operation of its pipeline in connection with an explosion that
killed three people, but some residents of Bellingham said that
doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three million? I figured it would be higher than that,'' said
tow truck driver Bob Howard, gazing at the still blackened creek
banks behind the building where he works. ``Look at the damage that
was done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three million is not enough,'' said Shannon Louy, who works at
a Bellingham gas station not far from where the accident occurred
nearly one year ago. ``The only way to get their attention is to
slap them in the pocket book.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle attorney David Beninger, who spoke Friday morning with
the families of two 10-year-old boys killed in the explosion, said
the money does little to ensure safer pipeline operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot of money for the average person, but it is like
a toll in the road for these companies,'' Beninger said. ``None of
that money goes to ensure greater pipeline safety or to pay for
inspectors or to create laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said they would have gone farther if possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a pattern of numerous violations that relate to key
safety areas such as design, training, emergency response,'' said
Kelley S. Coyner, administrator of the federal Department of
Transportation agency responsible for pipeline safety. ``We want to
underscore that we would have fined them more but for the caps that
are in place in our current law.''
</P>
<P>
   In justifying the fine _ which dwarfs the previous record by
$2.3 million _ federal investigators highlighted a series of
lapses, oversights and shortcuts that resulted in dangerous
operation of a pipeline carrying highly volatile gasoline through
residential Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympic conducted its operations in an unsafe manner and
violated numerous federal pipeline safety standards,'' Coyner said.
``There were sustained and multiple violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators paint a picture of a company that relied on
operators whose training was incomplete or unverified and who
failed to respond adequately when potential problems were
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Vice President Carl Gast declined comment on the penalty
because he had not had a chance to review the details of the
proposed fine. The company can challenge all or part of the
findings and Gast defended his company's actions since the rupture
and explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past several months, Olympic has worked very hard
to comply with all of the safety directives issued by the Office of
Pipeline Safety, and even now is engaged in a comprehensive
internal inspections program of its entire 400-mile network,'' he
said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the Bellingham accident is still under
investigation by another federal agency _ the National
Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline broke June 10, 1999, spewing 229,000 gallons of
gasoline into a Bellingham park. The gasoline ignited an enormous
fireball that raced more than a mile down a creek.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the blast were Wade King and Stephen Tsiorvas, both
10, and 18-year-old Liam Wood. The 400-mile pipeline runs from
northwest Washington refineries to Portland. A 37-mile segment has
been closed since the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham city officials, many of whom have lobbied actively
for greater oversight since the accident, said the record fine
sends an important signal. ``I'm pleased to hear it,'' said Terry
Borneman, Bellingham city councilman and family friend of Stephen
Tsiorvas. ``While it doesn't go anywhere near bringing back the
lives lost due to negligence, it does help to remedy some of the
footdragging that has gone on when finding answers to questions
posed to Olympic Pipeline at neighborhood meetings and Senate
hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham Mayor Mark Asmundson said the fines were ``right on
track and appropriate under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has indicated is that we need a change in the
federal regulations (dealing with pipeline safety),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason King, 26, the brother of Wade King, said the $3 million
penalty is a ``small step'' in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me personally it's still kind of a farce overall,'' he told
the Associated Press in a phone interview from the Bellingham car
dealership where he works with his father, Frank King. ``The fact
that a company is able to, in so many words, deny responsibility
for their own actions and try to place blame on third parties ...
and then be allowed to continue to operate is the real tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The families of the three victims have spent the past year
lobbying Congress and working to keep the issue of pipeline safety
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make sure Wade's death wasn't pointless,'' said
the Rev. John Riggs, Wade King's family priest at St. Paul's
Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators found eight violations in Olympic's
operation of the pipeline ranging from inadequate training of
control room personnel, failing to investigate structural
``anomalies,'' and not maintaining daily operating records as
required by law. Six of the eight violations carry a penalty of
$500,000 each, while the penalty attached to each of the remaining
violations was $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most alarming violations, according to federal
officials, occurred in 1994 when a local water treatment plant
installed pipes above the gas lines operated by Olympic. Excavation
is the most common cause of damage to pipelines, accounting for
more than 80 percent of structural damage. Because of that, federal
rules require that officials from the existing pipeline be onsite
to ensure that no damage is done during construction.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that well-known requirement, investigators said
documents supplied by Olympic showed that monitoring took place on
only three days during the eight months of construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to indicate that inspections were not done as
frequently as necessary to verify the integrity of (the)
pipeline,'' investigators said in a letter to Gast detailing the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Another violation revolved around tests Olympic conducted in
1996 and 1997 to see if there was any structural weakening in the
pipeline. The testing revealed two possible ``anomalies'' in close
proximity, including a possible thinning of the pipeline wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These conditions, particularly when grouped together,'' the
letter to Gast said, ``are of the type that could adversely affect
the safe operation of a pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   In documents submitted to the Washington Department of Ecology,
Olympic said it intended to excavate around the area to check the
problem in May 1997. The work, however, was never done.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline operators also violated safety rules by not
following-up when a critical ``isolation valve'' moved to the
closed position ``uncommanded'' more than 50 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympic was aware of and did not investigate these abnormal
occurrences,'' the letter to Gast says.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there was no evidence to suggest that operators
noticed the problem or did anything to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bellingham accident has galvanized efforts to update and
toughen federal laws governing pipeline safety. Washington's entire
congressional delegation is supporting legislation to accomplish
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the state's U.S. senators, Democrat Patty Murray and
Republican Slade Gorton, have introduced bills. Other lawmakers,
including Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen. Fritz Hollings,
D-S.C., also have introduced measures.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bills differ, they all call for more aggressive
inspection of pipelines, tougher enforcement, higher penalties for
violations and public disclosure of pipeline routes.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Jack Metcalf, a Republican whose district
includes Bellingham, has joined with two other members of the
Washington delegation, Republican Jennifer Dunn and Democrat Jay
Inslee, to introduce a pipeline safety bill.
</P>
<P>
   But prospects for passing a new law this year are bleak. The
Senate has had several hearings on the issue, but none of the bills
is scheduled to be considered by a full committee. The pace is even
slower in the House. No hearings have been held and none are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the lack of action has her ``worried'' and she hopes
Friday's action by the Transportation Department will jumpstart
efforts in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an important step,'' she said of the proposed fine.
``But we need to pass legislation this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Inslee echoed that sentiment. ``We can't rely on fines,'' he
said, adding that while the record fine appears large, ``I don't
think it's an untoward number. This is equivalent to several
minutes revenue for the parent company.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Amy E. Nevala, Michael A. Barber and George Foster
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
