<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARKANSAS: FORMER STATE SENATOR SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   Nick Wilson, once an immensely powerful Arkansas state senator
who reigned for years over both houses of the General Assembly, was
sentenced on Thursday to 70 months in federal prison after pleading
guilty to a racketeering charge. Wilson, once known as a reformer
who occasionally clashed with Gov. Bill Clinton, was the subject of
a two-year investigation by federal prosecutors, who charged him
and nine others with stealing nearly $2 million from state
programs.
</P>
<P>
   After months of denying the allegations, he was convicted of tax
evasion by a federal jury last year, and then pleaded guilty to the
racketeering charge in March. Wilson, 58, will also have to return
the money, which was diverted from programs providing attorneys to
children in child-care disputes, among others.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA: COMPETITION FOR LUGAR
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, David Johnson, the Democrat trying to unseat
Republican Sen. Richard G. Lugar, has raised nearly $1 million,
``more money than Lugar's last two opponents combined,'' said
Johnson's campaign manager, Timothy Shock. That and Johnson's
background as a policy adviser to two governors, Evan Bayh (now an
Indiana senator), and the current governor, Frank L. O'Bannon, has
Democrats and some political analysts calling him Lugar's strongest
opponent in years. ``I feel very good about where we are,'' Shock
said. Lugar's going to have a real race this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experts believe that Johnson, who has never run for
public office before, has little chance of defeating the four-term
senator, who has raised over $4 million and has $2.3 million cash
on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lugar is very well known,'' said James McCann, a political
science professor at Purdue University. ``He's got a very good
base. He's got name recognition no one could buy. It's definitely
uphill with Johnson.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH No public events
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Washington
</P>
