<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BRITAIN-CONSOLING-PHI     06-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONSOLING-PHILOSOPHER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH WRITER DISTILLS GREAT PHILOSOPHERS INTO ENGAGING ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Suppose you were a writer whose book received an
unfavorable review. Your response _ depending on your temperament _
might be to indulge in a paroxysm of self-loathing or to retreat to
your cave of self-righteousness, railing at the reviewer's
incompetence and mean spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Alain de Botton, the author of ``The Consolations of
Philosophy,'' has a third suggestion. What you should do, he says,
is take a deep breath, sweep aside your emotions and apply the
eminently sensible reasoning of the Roman philosopher Seneca, a
great expositor of Stoicism and a first-hand student of the hand of
fate. Among other things, Seneca was forced to abandon his house
and all his worldly goods and sent to live by himself in exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``One element of Stoicism is to think that you can survive, that
what is essential for life is a lot less than you might think it
is,'' de Botton explained in a recent interview, as he
absent-mindedly nibbled on a tuna sandwich. Tall, thin and
delicate-looking, he presented a poised and thoughtful figure, his
air of slight melancholy at war, perhaps, with his constant
undercurrent of amusement.
</P>
<P>
   If you can use Seneca to cope with anger and disappointment, the
30-year-old de Botton argues in his book, there's no reason you
can't turn to Socrates when you're discouraged by your
unpopularity. Or to Montaigne to keep from feeling horrified by
your physical appearance. Or to Epicurus to liberate yourself from
feeling sad that you don't have more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different philosophers for different times,'' said
de Botton, whose book examines six of them. ``There are moments
when Nietzsche's heroic stance, bombastic and rather hysterical, is
very nice. There are times when Montaigne's more gentle and
accepting side seems relevant. To spend some time in the company of
a philosopher like Montaigne is very pleasant, even if you don't
become a committed Montaigne-ian.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain has had plenty of opportunity lately to take in de
Botton's message. A best seller here, the book was made into a
television series, one show per philosopher, with the author
describing and illustrating his points about each one. When de
Botton, who is sometimes called ``Dr. Love'' because of his three
novels with love themes and his philosophical advice to the
lovelorn, went to Manchester for the series, he told a shop-aholic
whose life was being ruined by his addiction that he might find
solace in the teachings of Epicurus. In London, he told a delivery
man prone to terrible spasms of road rage how he might calm down by
reading Seneca instead of The Sun, the popular tabloid newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   And when de Botton visited the home of an attractive young woman
whose boyfriend had just left her, de Botton, in the midst of
applying the lessons of Schopenhauer _ who, he writes, may be among
the finest philosophers for the griefs of love _ found himself
asking the heart-broken subject out to dinner. They are now dating.
</P>
<P>
   De Botton's book is only slightly less quirky than his approach
to television. In elegant essays that filter interesting
biographical data about the philosophers through the prism of his
playful mind _ Schopenhauer's closest relationships, we learn, were
with a series of poodles _ de Botton urges his readers to return to
what he sees as the ancient purpose of philosophy: teaching people
how to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write a book that would rescue a certain totally
neglected tradition in philosophy, which is the pursuit of
wisdom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Consolations of Philosophy'' is written in an easygoing,
accessible style and filled with whimsical illustrations that help
make its points. But it is by no means a survey of philosophy in
the manner, say, of the phenomenally popular novel ``Sophie's
World'' by Jostein Gaarder. De Botton says he wanted to write in an
engaging, persuasive way because he is easily bored when he reads,
and he assumes others are, too. But it is his breezy approach, as
much as anything else, that has unsettled some serious students of
philosophy. Reviewing the book in The Observer of London, Peter
Conrad said it ``wickedly veers between sagacity and silliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, de Botton suggests, they have misunderstood his intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't written an introduction to philosophy or the
complete guide to any of these philosophers,'' he said. ``What I've
really done is simply written six essays looking at six different
aspects of their thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also trying to do a tricky thing which annoys some people.
I'm not surrendering my claim to be accurate, to get all the facts
right, to be quite scholarly. But at the same time I don't want to
write in a scholarly way at all. I'm being rather brazen about this
and standing up against the opposition, because it's my deepest
belief that you can be at once serious and yet easy to read and
playful. And however much I may fail in that attempt, I believe in
that as a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an approach that he used with much success in his three
novels and, most notably in his last book, ``How Proust Can Change
Your Life,'' a funny, robust and joyous argument for negotiating
the daunting thickets of ``Remembrance of Things Past.'' At first
overlooked in Britain, de Botton's book leapt into public
consciousness and then on to best-seller lists on both sides of the
Atlantic when John Updike raved about it in The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``His curious, humorous, didactic and dazzling book bears the
subtitle `Not a Novel,''' Updike said in the review. ``It contains,
however, more human interest and play of fancy than most fiction.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   De Botton is not a French aristocrat, though that is what
Britons generally assume when they hear his name, which is
pronounced in the French manner, and see his picture. He comes from
a rich family _ his father is a successful financier _ but one that
has always emphasized achievement above anything else, and de
Botton has had to make his own way in the world. The family name
was originally Spanish, but his father was born into a small,
thriving community of Jews in Cairo. His mother comes from
Switzerland, which is where de Botton spent his early years.
</P>
<P>
   De Botton was sent to Harrow, a top-notch boys' boarding school
in Britain, at the age of 8, and had to learn not only English, but
also how to thrive in a place that glorified athletes, something he
is not. He did it by being clever, he said, and by agreeing to do
other boys' homework for them.
</P>
<P>
   After Cambridge University, from which he graduated with a
double-starred first, roughly the equivalent to summa cum laude, de
Botton drifted into academia, looking to acquire a Ph.D., first at
Harvard and then at King's College London. He dropped out of both.
``I was very confused,'' he said. ``I wanted to pursue the history
of ideas, but I found myself not sitting comfortably in any one
discipline. I didn't want to be a philosopher and didn't want to be
a historian, and I got quite depressed by the whole thing. I
thought, `Oh, God, maybe I won't get a job at the end and it will
all be quite miserable.'''
</P>
<P>
   But de Botton said he took a cue from Nietzsche, which is,
according to de Botton: Don't panic about panicking, life is
difficult, and angst is a normal human response.
</P>
<P>
   Unfailingly charming and, one suspects, unlikely to lose his
temper, de Botton has nonetheless had his share of sleepless nights
and crippling self-doubt. He describes his 20s as an anxious time
and says that for him, reading great thinkers is nothing but a
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make myself sound obsessive in this area, but
I've always looked to figures from literature or history as sources
of interesting ideas on how to live,'' he said. ``People come up
with all sorts of responses about what to do about anxiety, and one
of them is the quest for knowledge. I intellectualize things.
That's my way of dealing with anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   But, de Botton said, he is only human. Before he
intellectualizes, he frets, rages and sometimes wallows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seneca would say that one can't help but have emotions,'' he
said. ``Philosophy is for an hour later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
