<P>
   (NYT201) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-1 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. Achmed Valdes and his wife, Ivette Garcia,
watching a tape of Valdes in Guantanamo in which he is gently
shaving a black friend. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT202) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-2 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little tat binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. For Joel Ruiz, there is little time for
relaxation. On this night, he collects cover charges at his uncle's
bar, Annie Mae's, in a black Miami neighborhood. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT203) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-3 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. Achmed Valdes, in cap, plays soccer with
other white Cubans. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT204) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-4 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. In Cuba, Joel Ruiz played soccer. In Miami,
he plays basketball with black friends. (Librado Romero/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT205) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-5 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. A portrait of Ruiz, top, and Valdes. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT206) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-6 -- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. Valdes in his truck which he drives around
Florida hauling cargo for $9.60 an hour. (Librado Romero/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT207) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- RACE-IMMIGRANTS-7-- Achmed
Valdes and Joel Ruiz say they remain as good friends as ever, yet
they both know there is little that binds them anymore but their
memories of the Cuba they left behind. Had they not become best
friends in another country, in another time, they would not be
friends at all today. Ruiz with his great-niece who lives with him
along with her mother in Miami. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   Our report today also includes:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-3 --
Despite another heroic effort from Latrell Sprewell, the New York
Knicks collapsed against the Indiana Pacers and Reggie Miller
Friday night losing 93-80. Returning to Madison Square Garden, the
scene of some of his greatest performances, Reggie Miller played
the villain again and came through in the clutch. Scoring 34 points
and making five 3-pointers, four in a span of 6 minutes late in the
game. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-2 -- The
New York Knicks head coach Jeff Van Gundy sits in despair as the
Knicks season was coming to an end as they collapsed against the
Indiana Pacers and Reggie Miller. Miller saved his best for last,
shooting the Pacers into the NBA Finals for the first time ever
with a vintage barrage of Knicks-killing 3-pointers. Scoring 34
points and making five 3-pointers, Miller led the Pacers past New
York 93-80 Friday night in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1 -- _
Reggie Miller saved his best for last, shooting the Indiana Pacers
into the NBA Finals for the first time ever with a vintage barrage
of Knicks-killing 3-pointers. Scoring 34 points and making five
3-pointers, four in a span of 6 minutes late in the game, Miller
led the Pacers past New York 93-80 Friday night in Game 6 of the
Eastern Conference finals. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 4 --
INVEST-KLECZKA -- Glen A. Kleczka, 37, right, the lead manager of
the $58.0 million William Blair Value Discovery fund, admits to
being a foodie, but he rarely finds time to cook at home in
Chicago. Kleczka,who loves to cook, knows the ingredients of an
undervalued company. ``We buy broken stocks, not broken
companies,'' he says. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 4 --
MCCAW-TELEDESIC -- Craig McCaw, the publicity-shy cable television
and telecommunications entrepreneur with a fabled knack for
anticipating the future. McCaw's investments include a maze of
advanced wired and wireless services. But none presents a more
formidable puzzle than Teledesic, his futuristic scheme to dot the
heavens with a 288-satellite network for voice and data
communications. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIAMI -- June 2, 2000 -- FLA-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT -- With as
much as $100 billion at risk in a landmark lawsuit brought by
Florida smokers against cigarette makers, lawyers argue hot and
loud whether the tobacco companies should be punished with a huge
judgment. ``I never thought it would harm me this much,'' Guillermo
Saa, 62, says of smoking. Saa lost part of his throat and his
larynx to cancer. (Andrew Itkoff/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JUNE 4 --
CAR-REFINANCE -- Glenn Jutting, 51, refinanced his car at a lower
interest rate that he found on the Internet at the PeopleFirst.com
Web site. His new loan, for the $20,000 balance he owed on his car,
is at 7.49 percent for five years. His original note was for six
years, so his new monthly payment is actually $25 larger, but he
will make fewer payments; all told, he will save $800. (Glenn
Oakley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEHALEM, Ore. -- June 2, 2000 -- ORE-ADOPTION-HILL -- In
the nearly two years that Oregon voters and courts have spent
wrangling over the nation's first voter-approved initiative
granting all adult adoptees access to their birth certificates, the
legal fight here has often been cast as the most excruciating of
moral dilemmas. But Helen Hill, the 45-year-old adoptee who
spearheaded the successful campaign for the measure in 1998 and
celebrated a final victory this week before the United States
Supreme Court, says she is puzzled by the notion of such a dilemma.
(John Gress/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
TV-STYLE-REGIS-B&AMP;W -- On Monday Regis Philbin will introduce Regis,
by Van Heusen - just in time for Father's Day. Fashion magazines
say the ``millionaire look'' of monochromatic shirts and tie sets
is ``on trend.'' Johnny Carson is one of a long line of television
stars who, like Philbin, have lent their names to clothing lines
during their careers. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- June 2, 2000 -- AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS --
Daimler-Chrysler's 2000 Jeep Grand Cherokee has successfully pulled
off the Jekyll-and-Hyde feat of turning the Jeep into a luxurious
and smooth highway performer while at the same time saving its
solid off-road soul. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- June 2, 2000 -- GORE-CANCER -- Vice
President Al Gore and his wife Tipper before a giant pink ribbon
symbolizing the fight against breast cancer during a rally on the
National Mall sponsored by the organization, National Race For The
Cure, Friday. Gore promised on Thursday to step up the war against
cancer and support programs that would enable scientists to find a
cure. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- TV-FASHION-SEX -- Sarah
Jessica Parker as Carrie in ``Sex and the City'' goes straight in
Halston and Jackie Kennedy shades. People who work for fashion
companies say they have successfully placed products, like
handbags, on the show, and hope to do more in the future. (Criag
Blankenhorn/HBO) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) METULLA, Isarel -- June 2, 2000 -- ISRAEL-MOTHERS --
Following the 1997 crash of an Israeli military helicopter en route
to Lebanon which left 73 soldiers dead, Rachel Ben Dor, an opponent
of what she saw as Israel's senseless involvement in Lebanon,
formed a group that became known as the Four Mothers. Many Israelis
celebrated the Four Mothers this week following Israel's withdrawal
from southern Lebanon. Soldiers celebrated with withdrawal last
week after crossing the Lebanese. border. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
GAVIN-PROFILE -- Gavin Brown, a British-born dealer, who represents
a roster of rising stars, is more than an art dealer. He is also
the proprietor of Passerby, a bar adjacent to his gallery, which is
a cliquish rendezvous for art and fashion. Brown's gallery and bar,
right; (his wife) Lucy Barnes' boutique of simple, quirky designs,
left. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) AUSTIN -- June 2, 2000 -- TEXAS-ELLIS -- As President Pro
Tem of the Texas Senate, Rodney Ellis, a liberal black Democrat, is
not a nationally known name. But his brief tenure as acting
governor, when Gov. George W. Bush was out of state this week, gave
him a crucial role in the fate of a death row inmate, and in the
Bush campaign. Ellis in front of the State of Texas capitol,
Friday. (Mathew Sturtevant /The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- SPRING-HEAT -- Deborah Bins,
of Brooklyn, keeps cool with a spray bottle equipped with a fan
during Friday's sweltering heat. Afternoon readings peaked in the
upper 90s over many parts of the Middle Atlantic states including
New York. The high humidity in the city made it feel like the
mercury had hit over 100 degrees Fahrenheit. (Ruby Washington/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- June 2, 2000 -- HOME-HISTORIC-BOS --
The once-proud Major Lawson Nurse house in Framingham was nearly
demolished a few years ago. But Ann Welles, a self-described
``sucker for old homes,'' was one of the townsfolk who cared. When
an architect told her it was salvageable, she bought it and began
to renovate. ``We did this whole thing on a shoestring,'' she said.
(Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. -- June 2, 2000 --
COMPUTERS-LAN-BOS -- A LAN party is a self-contained video game
marathon, a bring-your-own-PC event. Twenty-two people - 21 of them
male - hauled their computers and monitors to this little house,
which belongs to players Matthew and Sarah Andrade. The guests came
from three states and range in age from 11 to 40. They call
themselves the BadLANs. (Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- TIANANMEN-DOCUMENTARY --
About one a week before Chinese soldiers killed hundreds of
students in the early hours of June 4, 1989, Ke Feng oversaw the
construction of one of the most enduring symbols of the movement in
Tiananmen Square, the 27-foot statue called the Goddess of
Democracy. Ke, now a graduate film student at New York University,
has begun shooting interviews, collecting film and raising funds
for a documentary to be called ``Making Goddess.'' (James
Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
