<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 06/02/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   RACE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sunday, and continuing for the next six weeks, The New
York Times will publish a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived
in America.'' The following photos have moved with the first and
second installments of the series.
</P>
<P>
   With RACE-CHURCH:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
RACE-CHURCH -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. Howard Pugh, who owns a
concrete company, at a job site with Johnny Clark, left, and Donald
Roberts. He draws a distinction between his black church friends
and his black employees, whom he calls ``the boys.'' (James
Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT102) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
RACE-CHURCH-2 -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. The Pughs, left, and the
Burches at the Assembly of God Tabernacle in Decatur, Ga., where
blacks make up almost half the congregation. (James Estrin/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT103) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
RACE-CHURCH-3 -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. Roger Brumbalow, pastor
of the Assembly of God Tabernacle, sees in his flock ``a
multiracial, multicultural maturing body of believers.'' (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT104) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
RACE-CHURCH-4 -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. Sunday morning at the
Assembly of God Tabernacle.(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT105) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 5 --
RACE-CHURCH-4 -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. Madge Mayo and Ruben
Burch during the fellowship portion of a service. Mayo says she has
been touched by the bigheartedness of the Tabernacle's black
members. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) ATLANTA -- June 2, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 4 --
RACE-CHURCH-6 -- Race relations in America is being defined less by
political action than by daily experience. At a catfish supper at
their house, Howard and Janice Pugh flanked Ruben Burch, second
from left, and William and Lula Turner. When Pugh makes an
offensive remark, his black friends say, they remember his goodness
and turn the other cheek. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
