</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FRAMINGHAM, Mass. -- June 2, 2000 -- HOME-HISTORIC-BOS --
The once-proud Major Lawson Nurse house in Framingham was nearly
demolished a few years ago. But Ann Welles, a self-described
``sucker for old homes,'' was one of the townsfolk who cared. When
an architect told her it was salvageable, she bought it and began
to renovate. ``We did this whole thing on a shoestring,'' she said.
(Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. -- June 2, 2000 --
COMPUTERS-LAN-BOS -- A LAN party is a self-contained video game
marathon, a bring-your-own-PC event. Twenty-two people - 21 of them
male - hauled their computers and monitors to this little house,
which belongs to players Matthew and Sarah Andrade. The guests came
from three states and range in age from 11 to 40. They call
themselves the BadLANs. (Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 2, 2000 -- TIANANMEN-DOCUMENTARY --
About one a week before Chinese soldiers killed hundreds of
students in the early hours of June 4, 1989, Ke Feng oversaw the
construction of one of the most enduring symbols of the movement in
Tiananmen Square, the 27-foot statue called the Goddess of
Democracy. Ke, now a graduate film student at New York University,
has begun shooting interviews, collecting film and raising funds
for a documentary to be called ``Making Goddess.'' (James
Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
