<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3353 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAILEY0603-COX     06-02 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defender of the famous defends himself
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ F. Lee Bailey, cast in dual roles as defendant
and star witness, wept as he recounted the deaths of his wife and
mother, then went on to spin a tale of double-dealing, backstabbing
and money-grubbing among big-time drug dealers, big-fee attorneys
and government lawyers eager to claim credit for a big case.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's two days on the witness stand Thursday and Friday were
a bravura performance, perhaps the most important of his 40-year
career. Bailey, who lives in Manalapan and practices in West Palm
Beach, is fighting for his career, which the Florida Bar is trying
to end through this disbarment trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he dropped nuggets of insider legal gossip that
widened the eyes of courtroom spectators_mostly retirees who left
the golf course and ``Judge Judy `` to watch the real thing_such as
a casual mention that former client O.J. Simpson did so poorly on a
lie-detector test before his murder trial that Bailey's co-counsel,
Robert Shapiro, stopped the test and grabbed the polygraph charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read them, but nobody else ever has,'' Bailey said,
``because he says now he doesn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier County Circuit Judge Cynthia Ellis, who is conducting
the trial, will make her recommendation to the state Supreme Court
after the trial ends next week. If Florida were to disbar Bailey,
he would automatically be disbarred in Massachusetts, where he's
also licensed, as well as in federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, this is serious,'' said Don Beverly, the
West Palm Beach attorney representing Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   The Bar says Bailey committed seven ethics violations in his
handling of millions of dollars in stock and properties once
belonging to a client, international drug-smuggler Claude Duboc.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey spent several months of 1994 flying back and forth to
Europe, working out a complicated deal with the U.S. government for
Duboc to turn over $100 million in cash, stock and property in
exchange for the possibility of a lighter sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the deal fell apart and Duboc wound up in prison for
life with no hope of parole. Bailey wound up in jail himself for 44
days. He was out of money, in debt and facing career extinction.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the disbarment case is 607,000 shares of stock in
BioChem Pharma, a Canadian pharmaceutical company headed by a
friend of Duboc's. Bailey says the government agreed to let him
have the stock free and clear for his fees and expenses, but
reneged when the stock's value skyrocketed from $6 to $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration connected Duboc to six
different multi-ton seizures of hashish and marijuana in San
Francisco and Canada, an operation that Bailey says earned the
smugglers $600 million. The money was laundered through shell
corporations in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Duboc spent part of the loot on a $25 million pleasure palace in
France, ``built in the spirit of Errol Flynn,'' in Bailey's words,
and featuring cameras in every bedroom. He also had a ranch in
Hawaii, an 80-foot yacht, a slip in Cannes, and a fleet of
Porsches, Jaguars and Mercedeses.
</P>
<P>
   After Shapiro called him into the case, Bailey said he met with
federal prosecutors to see what they had on Duboc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat around a broken desk and postured with each other,'' he
said. ``They convinced me they had a strong case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey persuaded Duboc that the only hope he had of getting a
sentence that amounted to less than life _ Duboc was in his 50s _
was to provide ``extraordinary'' cooperation. That meant giving up
all his assets and not keeping anything back. That was the carrot
he dangled in front of the prosecutors, Bailey said, and they took
it.
</P>
<P>
   They took it so totally, he said, that they offered not to touch
$3.5 million in cash in a Luxembourg bank so that Duboc could
transfer it to Bailey for his legal fees and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no conditions whatever attached to the $3.5
million,'' Bailey testified vehemently. ``That was mine.'' And the
government wanted the transfer kept quiet, he said, because lawyers
for a co-defendant of Duboc's might want a similar deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the government's request, this case was 'papered' as little
as possible,'' he said. ``They wanted the matter of fees kept out
of documents, and I trusted them, a fact for which I am terribly
sorry to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Duboc proposed that Bailey take the BioChem Pharma stock,
worth about $6 million, to keep it from being dumped on the market
and depressing the value. The government agreed that he could take
the stock instead of the $3.5 million, Bailey said, and warned him
that if the stock went down, he would get no other money.
</P>
<P>
   Duboc signed the stock over to him, it went into his Swiss bank
account, and he took a $1.5 million loan against it to pay his
expenses and legal fees while he tried to dispose of the other
properties for the government, Bailey said. He also sold a third of
it to repay that line of credit when needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government took no interest in the stock until January 1995,
when it suddenly shot up in value, Bailey testified. With the value
at nearly $18 million, the government claimed Bailey was only
holding the stock ``in trust.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Ocala agreed with the government and gave
Bailey three weeks to give up the stock or go to jail. Bailey went
to jail and ultimately raised the money to repay $2.3 million in
loans he'd taken against the stock by mortgaging his house and his
74-foot yacht.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Duboc had fouled up the deal by trying to hide
some of his money from the prosecutors, and Bailey had fallen out
with not only the government but also both co-counsels: Shapiro
over power struggles in the Simpson trial and prominent Miami
lawyer Ed Shohat, who Bailey said had given Duboc bad advice and
had tried to get control of $700,000 in Japanese stock that Duboc
owned.
</P>
<P>
   Both Shohat and Shapiro testified against Bailey, supporting the
government's position that all Duboc's assets were to be forfeited.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey told Bar attorney David Ristoff on Friday that he has
turned up evidence to corroborate his claim that prosecutors never
mentioned holding the stock ``in trust'' in negotiating meetings.
He said he intends to introduce the evidence _ notes made by one of
the government lawyers _ next week.
</P>
<P>
   During Ristoff's cross examination, Bailey stopped and asked for
water and pain medication for his bandaged left hand. He said he
had surgery on the hand in April for a condition that causes
tendons in the palm to draw down the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been getting much sleep at night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's celebrity drawing power filled seats in the Collier
County courtroom, bringing several active and retired lawyers to
watch the defender of the famous defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   John Greer, a retired practitioner from Iowa, was untouched by
Bailey's tearful references to the death of his wife, Patricia,
last year from pancreatic cancer and of his 90-year-old mother in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as phony as a $7 bill,'' he said, waving a hand
dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ludwig and Dennis Harrington, semi-retired lawyers from
Pittsburg, just smiled when asked to evaluate Bailey's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a consummate witness,'' Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
