<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART     06-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING AND KNICKS' SEASON FINALLY ENDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 17, NYT18, and NYT19 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Knicks' season ended with Patrick Ewing
sitting slumped on the bench with his thoughts to himself. There
was disbelief in his stare. It was over. He had played through his
pain, pushed himself for his team, but it was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Missing six of his last nine shots, Ewing struggled toward the
end of what might have been his last, best chance at a championship
as the Indiana Pacers eliminated the Knicks at Madison Square
Garden Friday night, 93-80. The Pacers won Game 6, and took the
Eastern Conference finals, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell scored 32 points, and Allan Houston faded away
in the second half and contributed just 10. Larry Johnson did not
have any 4-point miracles in his holster, and scored just seven
points. The Pacers were led by Reggie Miller's 34 points, 17 of
which came in the fourth quarter, and Dale Davis' 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Knicks could not re-create the same magical trip
to the NBA finals they went on last year. They could not muster the
same kind of desperate energy that propelled them last year when
Ewing was injured. Although there were so many reasons the Knicks
could not hold off the Pacers, all failures are usually traced to
Ewing. The numbers will show the Knicks won without him, and could
not find victory with him against Indiana. But it may be simpler
than that. Friday night the Pacers looked hungry and more resolved
to put their Knicks demons away.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had that look in his eyes. And there was no defense
against Indiana's wispy 3-point wonder. Miller scored most of his
points in the second half. He sank the Knicks' spirits time after
time.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks made up a nine-point halftime deficit on the
energy of Sprewell and the post presence of Ewing, the game was
tied after three quarters. But the Pacers quickly took over the
lead after Miller curled around screens, took his place on the
perimeter and came away with two 3-pointers in two minutes. The
Knicks were down, 72-69, with 8 minutes 45 seconds left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight 3-point misses by Austin Croshere gave the Knicks
a chance to get back in the game. But they failed to take advantage
of the situation. After another 3-pointer by Miller off a pump-fake
of Sprewell, plus two free throws by the spindly guard, the Pacers
held a nine-point lead with four minutes to go. The deficit was 10
points with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks entered this game with confidence _ made glaringly
apparent by the pre-game guarantees of Ewing and Chris Childs _ but
they also arrived with a lot of excuses if they fell.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, the Knicks harped about how injuries had limited
their effectiveness while others whispered familiar criticisms
about Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadows, some mumbled about how Ewing clogged the lane,
how he slowed the team and how the five playoff games they had won
without him against the Pacers this year and last season were no
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was the only Knick bold enough to actually voice how
unsure he was about whether the team was better with or without
Ewing. ``The numbers don't lie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes to the fragileness of how we handle it,'' coach
Jeff Van Gundy said. ``The Patrick thing, the only way he can win
in this series is to win. That's all we have to worry about. Just
win, because if we win it's all a moot point. If we lose, then it's
going to be his fault and my fault for playing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was unfazed by the inspection of his every move. He came
out, started with a couple of jumpers and helped the Knicks keep up
with a quick start by a Pacers team that started with one strategy
in mind: drive the lane. That aggressiveness spilled over into
their rebounding. The Pacers built a 50-41 halftime lead mostly on
their 22-17 rebounding edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were the team scrambling, the ones playing with more
desperation. The Knicks slipped into the locker room at halftime
and came out with the same attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell delivered the jolt to the Pacers. Whether Ewing was
coming along on the ride or not, he was going to push it and take
over the third quarter. Twice, he pulled up on the break and hit
jumpers in the lane, followed by a hook shot in the lane over a
reeling Jalen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   When the time was right, the ball went into Ewing. With 8:17
left in the third, he connected on a 3-point play on the
overmatched Rik Smits to tie the score, 52-52. The Pacers missed
five shots in a row before Miller hit a 3-pointer over Houston in
transition to give Indiana back the lead with just over six minutes
left.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three minutes, both teams played intense defense.
Ewing came up with a blocked shot, Charlie Ward pulled off a steal
and the Knicks forced the Pacers into a 24-second violation with
2:53 left in the third quarter. Meanwhile, Davis, forced to play
Ewing because of Smits' foul trouble, poked the ball away from his
man. And the Pacers cooled off Sprewell by collapsing on him. With
3:17 remaining in the third, the Pacers held a 57-56 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing continued to pick on Davis until it paid off. Ewing missed
a layup, but sneaked in for a rebound and picked up a foul with
2:41 on the clock. He hit both free throws to give the Knicks the
lead since the opening three minutes of the game. But the Pacers
absorbed that blow and, after a 3-pointer by Miller, the game was
tied at 62-62 entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Knicks were rebounding. They were also keeping tabs
of Travis Best much better than they did in Game 5. The point guard
tandem of Ward and Childs was holding up against Best and Mark
Jackson. Only when Childs and Ward found foul trouble in the first
half did Van Gundy dip into the big backcourt lineup for a total of
four minutes. It was not successful. Both times the Pacers scored
and forced turnovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
