<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-ELLIS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-02 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ELLIS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SENATOR IS SAND IN THE GEARS OF TEXAS' DEATH ROW EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eleven years ago, when a plane carrying Rep.
Mickey Leland of Texas on a hunger relief mission crashed in
Ethiopia, Rodney Ellis, a young Democratic councilman in Houston,
was grief stricken and shaken.
</P>
<P>
   He had not only lost his mentor, but he was supposed to have
been on that plane and had even fumed at Leland for bumping him
from the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Urged by Leland's widow to run for his seat in Congress, Ellis
gave it some thought before deciding instead to seek the state
Senate seat that Leland had once held.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since then, Ellis has become perhaps the leading
political force behind the decidedly unpopular efforts in Texas to
slow the state's speedy executions and erase what he said are the
inequities that often keep black, Hispanic and indigent defendants
from a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem an unusual role for a man who, like almost every
influential Texas politician, said that he supports the death
penalty. But Ellis' deep reservations about the system, and his
occasional clashes with Gov. George W. Bush, earned him the
spotlight this week.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush's campaigning in California and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a
Republican, in Europe, Ellis, as the Senate president pro tem,
became the acting governor and was left to decide whether to grant
a reprieve for convicted murderer Ricky McGinn. Bush announced on
Thursday in Sacramento, Calif., that he had recommended a 30-day
reprieve, which Ellis had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, Ellis had mostly made up his mind five days
earlier, having conferred with his staff and read an order by a
state judge imploring an appeals court to postpone the execution to
allow DNA tests; defense lawyers said the tests might exonerate
McGinn of raping his 12-year-old stepdaughter. McGinn was convicted
of murdering the girl, but prosecutors could not have asked for a
death sentence without also getting the rape conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said that the case kept him awake until 3 a.m. Monday
night, thinking, ``What if I disagree with Governor Bush? How would
we resolve that?'' His wife told him to call Bush's aides first
thing on Tuesday, which he did, so Bush would have the chance to
return to Texas to make sure the execution was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But to his surprise, Ellis said, Bush's aides said they were
already seriously considering a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   To Ellis, a 46-year-old Democrat, McGinn's case highlights only
some of the state's criminal justice problems: Ellis said it is
outrageous that there was no process allowing the new DNA tests to
be conducted, as the state's highest criminal appeals court,
without explanation, refused to postpone the execution.
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, Ellis has advocated banning executions of
the mentally retarded; giving juries the option of sentencing
murderers to life without parole, thus making it easier for jurors
to forego the death penalty; and putting control of court-appointed
lawyers in the hands of county governments, not the local judges
who, Ellis said, often favor lawyers who speed cases along instead
of fighting tooth-and-nail for their client.
</P>
<P>
   That last proposal was vetoed by Bush because, Ellis said,
judges worried that it took away a piece of their patronage. Bush
said that power should be left to judges because they were better
qualified to select lawyers for defendants who need them.
</P>
<P>
   Texas courts are essentially a system of judicial apartheid,
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus tends to be on the law-and-order, lock-them-up,
throw-away- of-the-key stuff, and a refusal to look at the
inequities of the system,'' he said. ``Part of the problem is that
our governor and a number of my conservative colleagues somehow
have the view that if you show compassion, you can be perceived as
weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, maintains that all 131 inmates executed
while he has been governor were unquestionably guilty of murder and
had had appropriate access to the courts. And few legislators share
Ellis' view.
</P>
<P>
   ``People commit crimes because of bad values, not because of
their race or status,'' said state Sen. David Sibley, a Waco
Republican and Bush ally.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ellis may not be in sympathy with legislative leaders on
some things, he has still been quite effective on many issues,
including indigent health care and voter registration. He has
earned a place among the elite of the state's Senate, a place
where, Texas Monthly once said, ``toughness is good, shrillness and
criticism are not, and humor is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to put together coalitions,'' Sibley said, before
adding: ``I don't think he's one that says half a loaf is better
than none. He says, `I'll take half a loaf now, and come back for
the rest later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley and Ellis have already discussed legislation that would
make it easier for prisoners to obtain post-trial DNA testing that
might prove exculpatory. Without commenting on specifics, Sibley
said such legislation might stand a chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis already has some specifics in mind: Giving inmates the
right to get DNA testing of evidence from their case, requiring
that biological evidence be preserved, setting up a commission to
review and investigate cases of possible wrongful convictions, and
providing more compensation to people wrongfully imprisoned and
later exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, the son of a yardman, grew up in Houston, attended
college at Texas Southern University, and earned a law degree and a
master's degree in public affairs at the University of Texas in
Austin. After serving as Leland's chief of staff, he was elected to
the Houston City Council at the age of 29. He now works in the
Houston office of a New Orleans law firm, and is married with three
children.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush and Perry both expected to travel out of state at
times later this year, the final approval for executions could fall
to Ellis again. One inmate scheduled to die soon, Gary Graham, has
drawn a lot of support from those who insist he is innocent. What
would Ellis do if that case were left up to him? Not sure yet, he
said, ``but if I were a guessing man, I would guess the governor or
lieutenant governor will be in town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3357 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LAYOFFS-DOTCOM-SFCHRO     06-02 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFFS-DOTCOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DOT-COM WORKERS TAKE LAYOFFS IN STRIDE  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's been a tumultuous week for Paul Angeli.
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, the Fremont, Calif., resident went to his job as an
executive producer at Emeryville, Calif.'s Petstore.com and found
out he was being laid off _ the second time he has worked for a
dot-com that has axed staff. On Wednesday, he submitted his
graduate thesis, and Friday he signed up at the Fremont
unemployment office.
</P>
<P>
   But Angeli isn't a bit disheartened. After his Java programming
final Monday, he'll start hustling to form his own business _ on
the Internet, the same job market where he's already experienced
two rounds of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take that chance on myself,'' he said. ``The
Internet industry is just getting started. I'm inspired to stick
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Angeli is among a wave of dot-com workers who have been
deep-sixed recently as their employers confront financial reality.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike layoffs in the 1980s and '90s among steelworkers,
autoworkers and IBM blue suits, the current belt-tightening does
not forecast an economic slump, experts say. It simply means that
Internet companies have started ``running more reasonable
businesses, operating like they're trying to reach profitability,
instead of throwing around money like it's going out of style,''
said Rebecca Nidositko, a senior analyst with the Yankee Group in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``These layoffs aren't symptomatic of bad international trade or
plant closings,'' said Stephen Levy, director of the Center for
Continuing Study of the California Economy in Palo Alto, Calif.
``The market is sorting out which companies have the better
products or services. In any major niche, if you get several
companies trying to do the same thing, not all will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, at least 25 Internet companies _ many
with deep pockets and corporate backing _ have downsized, some into
oblivion. And the trend seems widespread in the Bay Area, where
Petstore.com, ThirdAge Media, TurboLinux, LinuxCare and BabyCenter
have all handed out pink slips in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   New Emphasis on Profits
</P>
<P>
   The downsized firms are e-tailers that sell pet supplies, toys
or other goods online; portals that try to be a favored cyberspace
destination; and companies supporting the Linux operating system.
The cutbacks show these firms' dawning awareness of a sterner
climate on Wall Street and among venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has fundamentally changed. Companies will have to
demonstrate profitability over the next 12 to 18 months or it will
be very difficult for them to be funded,'' said Jim Barnett, chief
executive of San Francisco's ThirdAge Media. After deciding it
needed a tighter focus, the baby-boomer portal this week shed about
35 people _ a quarter of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the downsizing dot-coms are small to begin with,
the numbers of workers laid off are small, too: perhaps a couple of
thousand people nationwide. By comparison, when Coca-Cola
restructured in January, it laid off 6,000 employees, a fifth of
its workforce.
</P>
<P>
   All the dot-com workers who've lost their jobs this year would
just fill a third of the bleacher seats at Pac Bell Park _ assuming
you could get them to assemble for a ballgame. Most are already
busy interviewing and fending off new job offers.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of Jobs Available
</P>
<P>
   Take Sherry Miller, who was an executive producer at
Petstore.com until May 26. She already has taken a consulting gig
while she mulls several offers. ``Everyone who worked with me who
got laid off can get another job in a week,'' she said. Wherever
she ends up, Miller said, she will miss the camaraderie at
Petstore, where employees routinely brought their dogs, rats,
snakes and other animal companions to work.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the overall U.S. economy slowed this month, the
nation _ and especially the computer sector _ continue to
experience unprecedented growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that adds 30,000 jobs a year in California
and a couple of hundred thousand jobs a year nationwide,'' Levy
said, adding that the layoffs ``don't represent an industry
downturn. E-tailing is growing by any set of statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Commerce Department this week released a report on
first-quarter e-tail sales that showed the sector growing. U.S.
retail sales over the Internet totaled $5.26 billion for January
through March, up from $5.2 billion in the fourth quarter of 1999.
While the increase sounds small, most retailers experience a
first-quarter dip after the frenetic holiday spending.
</P>
<P>
   Still, e-tail is a tiny fraction compared to the overall market:
Online sales were just 0.7 percent of total first-quarter sales. In
some markets, e-tail is a stronger force. A separate report this
week from market-research firm NPD Group showed that online
book-buying accounted for 5.4 percent of book sales in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Initial Shock
</P>
<P>
   The vibrant economy means that a layoff is an inconvenience,
rather than a life-shattering event. Still, employees may have a
visceral reaction to getting the heave-ho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with a dot-com (that was downsized) where people
would tell you in one breath they could get five jobs in Silicon
Valley, and in the next they'd sound like someone from a
one-factory town, as if, if they lose this job, they'll lose
everything,'' said Mitch Marks, an organizational psychologist who
works with firms in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who could give away their Porsches instead of
selling them. Despite objectively knowing that you're wealthy, that
you could find multiple jobs, psychologically, it's still a shock
when you lose your job involuntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a big surprise for Francine Schwartz when
Healthshop.com, a San Francisco purveyor of natural-health
products, fired her and 60 colleagues in April, effectively closing
the firm's e-tail activities. ``The handwriting was on the wall,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blessing in Disguise
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it ended up being a blessing in disguise,'' the
Novato, Calif., resident said. ``I ended up finding a job in Marin
(Marin County, Calif.) _ a more interesting position and a shorter
commute.'' She's now a senior writer for IC Planet, a site that
connects recruiters and consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Job hunters who have weathered an Internet firm meltdown may end
up having an advantage, Schwartz said. ``In the job market, people
are quite appreciative of the fact that you've come from a dot-com
that didn't work because they figure you'll be able to set up red
flags for them about things you've seen before that didn't work.
It's an added skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Angeli, who has been both working and going to school full-time
for the past two years, is looking forward to getting reacquainted
with his wife, he said. He hopes to leverage his passion for
children's education and his new master's in multimedia _ for his
thesis he created a 3-D virtual world populated with intelligent
agents _ into a business that ``bridges the gap between kids and
the Net for learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after what he calls ``the whole dot-com paranormal
experience,'' he's a true believer in the power of the Internet to
revolutionize the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
