<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-IMAGES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NASA LOOKS TO UPDATE ITS IMAGES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Seeking to put the entrepreneurial energy as
well as the financial muscle of Silicon Valley behind the space
program, NASA on Friday launched a new ``multimedia partnership''
with a Bay Area startup called Dreamtime Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, Dreamtime will develop and distribute
new multimedia products and programming based on the space agency's
vast archives of images, sound, video and film and on new programs
like the International Space Station, a joint effort of the United
States, Russia and 14 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Dreamtime, backed by undisclosed equity partners,
will invest more than $100 million to equip the space station,
shuttles and ground facilities with high-definition television
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the seven-year agreement, Dreamtime has committed to
converting the agency's archives into a multimedia database. It
will have its headquarters at NASA's Ames Research Center in
Mountain View, Calif., and additional facilities at the Johnson
Space Center in Houston and the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the material, including everything available to the
public today, will remain freely accessible, but the company will
have the right to sell high-resolution versions, according to
Dreamtime co-founder and CEO Bill Foster. Both Foster and his
co-founder and chief operating officer, Carleton Ruthling,
previously worked at ExciteAtHome, the Redwood City, Calif.,
Internet portal developer and high-speed service provider.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to marketing images and clips from the NASA
archives, Dreamtime plans to create a space-oriented site on the
Web. The company will also develop TV programming and documentary
films about the space program.
</P>
<P>
   Foster pledged that Dreamtime will give 5 percent of its equity
to a foundation that will in turn make donations to nonprofit
organizations. Just what that stake will be worth won't be known
until the company goes public, which Ruthling estimates could occur
in about two years.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamtime won out over 11 other companies that were vying for
the partnership. NASA began soliciting bidders for the role in
December in response to the 1998 Commercial Space Act, in which
Congress declared commercial utilization one of the primary goals
of the space station program.
</P>
<P>
   NASA yesterday brought a parade of luminaries, including its
administrator, Daniel Goldin, two assistant administrators and two
former astronauts, to endorse the deal at an elaborate news
conference at the Ames center.
</P>
<P>
   The event was presided over by Nancy Conrad, who is a member of
Dreamtime's board and the widow of astronaut Pete Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting also included several quick-cut video presentations
on the history of the space program, plus a phone call from
``Titanic'' director James Cameron and a speech by Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher, R-Huntington Beach (Orange County) and chairman of the
House Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics.
</P>
<P>
   Rohrabacher called the new partnership plan ``an idea that
couldn't have come out of the government bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy if they'd just painted a shuttle fuel
tank into a Coke bottle or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said the Dreamtime deal and other efforts to
commercialize low-Earth-orbit programs like the space station
project would enable the agency to focus more resources on
returning to the moon, then moving on to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   He said three hours of toasts with the Dreamtime team in a Palo
Alto, Calif., restaurant on Thursday evening had convinced him
``we're not dealing with a government bureaucracy here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the event wasn't completely free of
bureaucratic elements. Reporters were handed copies of a 49-page
agreement between the agency and Dreamtime, complete with six
annexes and certain passages blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning: The agreement binds the two
parties to negotiate ``an approved, detailed arrangement for
financial remuneration to NASA'' within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
