<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-THORN-NYT &LR;      06-02 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-THORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS OWNER SAYS THORN PERFECT FOR TEAM PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The last two weeks have been wondrous
for Lewis Katz, the principal owner of the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   First, Katz said received a last-minute phone call from his son,
Drew, encouraging him to change his mind about not attending the
NBA draft lottery and sitting on the dais. And sure enough, with
Katz representing them, the Nets received the first pick, defying
the off of 4 in 100.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Monday, Katz said he received a call from Rod Thorn,
the league's executive vice president of basketball operations.
Thorn, who Katz had attempted to woo into the organization last
summer, asked if the Nets had decided on a president. If they had
not, Thorn said, he wanted the job.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Thorn was announced as the Nets' president, reportedly
receiving about $12.5 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, still excited about the No. 1 pick, is floating. He said
he believes he has the best possible man in Thorn for the job of
president, and a franchise that is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major acquisition for us, akin to a first draft
choice,'' Katz said, linking his recent coups together. ``We have
Rod. We have the pick. We have Stephon Marbury. This is really not
going to be a lowly organization for too terribly long.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, the only player at the Nets' Champion Center for the
announcement, called it a ``plus with no negatives.'' Willis Reed,
the Nets' senior vice president, called it ``not a home run, but a
grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could have come away with a better person,''
Reed said. ``The first thing I asked Rod was, can he get us another
Michael Jordan?''
</P>
<P>
   Thorn, who drafted Jordan while serving as the Chicago Bulls
general manager in 1984, will continue in his duties with the NBA
for at least the next week, but he will represent the Nets at next
week's predraft camp in Chicago, where trade talk is always big.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn, who will head the business and basketball operations for
the franchise, said he is as excited as his new employers about
rejoining the Nets, whom he served as an assistant coach from
1973-1975 and from 1976-1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great challenge and opportunity,'' Thorn said.
``This franchise is not bereft of talent. It has some very talented
players here, and there is a tremendous opportunity here to get
better in a very, very quick time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Thorn has never run a franchise, he said his 14
years in the league office has more than prepared him for the
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being associated with the NBA office for the last 15 years is
like getting a doctorate in how to run a franchise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn, who has been an assistant coach, head coach, general
manager and league executive since his eight-year playing career
ended in 1971, will have the responsibility of rebuilding one of
the league's most dormant franchises. His first duties will be to
lead the Nets through the draft and to hire a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure we do the right thing with this great
asset we have in the No. 1 pick in the draft,'' Thorn said. ``We
have 26 days until the draft and we have to make sure we do the
right thing, whether it's who we draft or whether we trade it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorn said the search for a coach will be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm looking for is someone who's a teacher, someone who
has tremendous energy,'' Thorn said. ``It may be someone who's
experienced for a long time. It may be someone who's an assistant
coach. It may be someone who's a college coach. I don't want to
limit where we're looking for a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorn, who by virtue of his 37-years in the league has
connections to numerous coaches, said he has no candidates at this
point. He said he hopes to fill the position by the June 28 draft,
but acknowledged that it may take longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens, who has the most career NBA victories as a coach,
will almost certainly receive consideration. Thorn's first
assistant coaching job was under Wilkens in Seattle in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn also has a history with Eddie Jordan, a current Nets
assistant coach. Jordan played for the Nets when Thorn was an
assistant during the 1977-1978 season. Thorn will also decide
whether to retain General Manager John Nash. Thorn said he had not
yet decided, but it appears that Nash, who has one year left on his
contract, will remain with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known John a long time,'' Thorn said. ``John does a
really good job. But I'm going to evaluate our organization, our
strengths, weaknesses, what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of the Nets, and particularly Katz _ who said his
decision was a ``no-brainer'' after receiving Thorn's call _ they
got what they needed in Thorn.
</P>
</TEXT>
