<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA ACTION COULD SHUT DOWN ALASKA AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration threatened to shut down
Alaska Airlines' maintenance operation _ crippling its ability to
keep planes in the air _ unless the airline shows federal
inspectors by next Friday it is fixing maintenance practices.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency announced the highly unusual ultimatum
Friday. If carried out, it could slowly drain Alaska's fleet of
airworthy planes and force the SeaTac-based airline to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   But Alaska officials have confidence they can show the FAA they
have already addressed many of the problems and can convince the
agency to let them keep their authority to do heavy maintenance
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the FAA's oversight obligation, and we look
forward to demonstrating our continuing commitment to do everything
we can to assure the highest level of safety in the airline
business,'' said Alaska Chairman and CEO John Kelly at a brief news
conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Scrutiny of Alaska's operations heightened after a crash in
January took the lives of 88 people on a flight from Mexico to
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that the plane's jack screw _ a threaded
piece of metal that moved the horizontal section of the tail up and
down _ had been stripped. That focused renewed attention on
Alaska's maintenance practices, which had been the subject of a
federal grand jury investigation in Oakland, Calif., since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA Friday gave Alaska seven days to present an extensive
plan to fix problems its inspectors found, including improperly
documented maintenance work and ineffective ways to detect
maintenance problems.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said they did not discover that any unsafe planes
had been released for passenger service, but they were still
concerned by their findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aircraft accidents result from a series of small errors,''
said Nick Lacey, director of FAA Flight Standards Services.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA will review Alaska's plan, then issue an order and give
Alaska 30 days to comply. It could officially suspend Alaska's
maintenance authority, a measure Alaska could appeal, or it could
levy civil fines.
</P>
<P>
   During that month, Alaska must get FAA approval on heavy
maintenance work before it returns any planes to passenger service.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the deadly Jan. 31 crash of Alaska Flight 261, FAA
inspectors spent about two weeks in April scrutinizing maintenance
and operations in the airline's SeaTac and Oakland facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the audit, the agency found problems with the
paperwork documenting ``C'' check inspections on two aircraft.
Alaska quickly began reviewing the maintenance records of each
plane that had undergone a C check _ roughly 80 planes.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Lacey said the review found more than 150 instances in
which work scheduled in heavy maintenance inspections was not
documented.
</P>
<P>
   That means in roughly 267,000 pages of paperwork, said spokesman
Lou Cancelmi, some 150 glitches such as missing signatures turned
up.
</P>
<P>
   Inspection of the aircraft showed the work had been done, Lacey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had found maintenance that was not performed, or
sloppy... we would be taking a different course. We would not
hesitate to shut the airline down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the April FAA ``white glove'' inspection of Alaska raised
``serious concerns about critical processes,'' he said _ from
improper maintenance documentation to questionable management.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings, the FAA found that Alaska manuals did not
adequately define procedures for in-depth aircraft inspections, and
that Alaska's own audits failed to find and correct problems in
maintenance practices.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also reported that Alaska's procedures for releasing
planes after heavy maintenance did not properly ensure all the work
had been done and documented.
</P>
<P>
   And the agency said two Alaska officials shared the job of
maintenance director, a required position that needs to be held by
one person.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's threat of taking away Alaska's maintenance authority
is intended to spur the airline into correcting its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made great strides, (but) there's enough to be done
for us to propose this significant action,'' said FAA spokesman
Paul Takemoto.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's CEO emphasized the airline already has been working
closely with FAA inspectors and has made a range of improvements in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The airline put together its own team of aviation experts to
conduct an independent safety audit, recently filled the new
position of vice president of safety and hired 70 maintenance and
engineering workers.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska officials said they also have revamped the General
Maintenance Manual to ``assure clarity and consistency to
procedures and policies,'' and established weekly meetings between
FAA officials and Alaska management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to say that many if not all of the findings the
FAA outlined... were addressed by us over recent weeks, as soon as
they were raised by the FAA during its audit,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's announcement ``serves as formal notice to us to
institutionalize those changes during the next 30 days,'' Kelly
said. ``We're confident we'll be able to prove that we've done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Alaska's recent safety initiatives were prompted by the
complaints of 64 SeaTac-based mechanics, who said they'd been
pressured to cut corners on repairs. They sent a letter to company
executives in March.
</P>
<P>
   The manager has since been transferred and FAA officials have
interviewed each of the mechanics to assess their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FBI is taking a close look at the FAA, trying to
determine if it has sanctioned or ignored any improper maintenance
procedures at Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   If the FAA decides to strip Alaska of its authority to do heavy
maintenance, the effect could devastate the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six of Alaska's 89 planes are scheduled for heavy
maintenance each month. If the airline is not allowed to do that
work, those planes would be grounded and Alaska's fleet of
airworthy planes would begin to shrink.
</P>
<P>
   In that scenario, Takemoto said, Alaska would need to show it
has corrected all of the problems before doing heavy maintenance
work again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 68-year-old airline would not be allowed to let
contractors perform the maintenance work on its fleet, as it has
done in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is with process. Allowing someone else to do it is
skirting the issue,'' Takemoto said. ``It's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   CEO Kelly said he is confident, amid the airline's recent string
of troubles, the airline has kept ``a reservoir of good will with
the traveling public'' and will continue to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said we're not perfect,'' CEO Kelly said, ``but
we're never going to stop trying.''
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from P-I reporters Paul Nyhan
and James Wallace and from the Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
