<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-02 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A PICNIC, AND THEN THE BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  NEW YORK _ The New York Knicks had just finished a brisk morning
workout in preparation for yet another monumental Game 6 battle.
This was late Friday morning at the team's Purchase, N.Y., training
facility. I was rushing in from my daughter's talent show; Jeff Van
Gundy was rushing out to his daughter's pre-school picnic. We met
at a common intersection where priorities, often lost in the
pursuit of this trophy or that, are re-established.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Especially in New York, especially in the heat of a
nerve-fraying, back-and-forth battle with Indiana that boiled down
to a single question: Could Indiana win in New York? The answer
Friday night was a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   This whole round had been a series of mind games: Larry Bird
challenging, whipping his team, wondering _ out loud _ where the
Pacers' pride had gone. Where the warrior heart was. Friday night
he found it.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy had tried to paint a more heroic side of the Knicks.
Applauding effort despite sore knees, fractured toes, bad feet. For
despite all this, the Knicks had moved through fog and smoke; they
kept coming like the Mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, facing yet another day on the edge of elimination, Van
Gundy exhorted his team to keep the series alive, to force another
Game 7. The ultimate game.
</P>
<P>
   I reminded him what Cowboys running back Duane Thomas said
before one Super Bowl when asked about playing in what was
frequently described as the ultimate game. ``If it's the ultimate
game,'' he said, ``how come they're playing it again next year?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, how many ultimate games can you have?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you coach,'' Van Gundy said Friday afternoon as he
cleared off his desk. ``You try to get them to focus in on that one
game. Then you've got to try to come up with something for the next
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy gave his office a quick once-over, made certain, in
his haste to make his picnic date, that nothing was left behind. He
plucked a soft drink out of a refrigerator. ``I'm not into giving
them a reason to win other than winning is the reason,'' he said.
``I'm realistic: this is what I see, this is what we have to
correct, this is what I think is good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto series was framed by the news media as a battle
between the Knicks and a young Raptors star, Vince Carter; the
Miami series was cast as the Knicks against a granite Heat defense.
This Indiana series had become a massive exercise in
psychoanalysis, with the Knicks portrayed as being engaged in a
battle, mostly with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to make it a psychological thing instead of:
it's basketball. It's some skill. Some technique and some good
fortune,'' Van Gundy said. ``A lot of these games are decided on
who shoots the ball better that night. Same shots _ sometimes they
go in, sometimes they go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun to say: `The Knicks didn't guard Mark Jackson's
post-up well,' or, `What does Charlie Ward have to do, where does
the help have to come from?' That's not fun to write about, or fun
probably to read about. Because it's technical. But you have two
teams here who want it, who want the same thing. One doesn't want
it more. They both want it desperately.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy made his way down the steps, across a now-empty
practice floor. He conceded that after Wednesday's Game 5 loss,
when the Knicks squandered an 18-point lead in the second quarter
and eventually lost the game, he did some ego management.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take a hit the way we took a hit the other night, and
didn't respond because we didn't gather ourselves after they made a
run, we have to address that,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go to the whip every day and you can't try to
manufacture some psychological thing. But if you see something _
like in our last game, our bad offense, our struggles on offense,
sapped our energy defensively and with rebounding. That's something
that's real,'' Van Gundy said, emphasizing the last word. ``That's
real. See, that's not something that's manufactured. And so that's
what we addressed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys struggling with their offense, mainly because of
not feeling well, not shooting well, whatever, and it took away
from the other end of the floor and from the rebounding. You would
say that's psychological or mental games or mind games. And it is,
but it's more realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Van Gundy went to his car, headed for the temporary
sanctuary of a kinder, gentler world: a world of picnics and
balloons and children's games.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he would enter the cutthroat world of the NBA playoffs,
where, win or lose, life is never a picnic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
