<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-BEARS-575(2TAKES)-     06-02 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BEARS-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARS BECOME UNCOMFORTABLY CLOSE NEIGHBORS IN NORTHERN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Tips for dealing with bears are at end of article.)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STILLWATER, N.J. _ Danette Conroy was upstairs cleaning kitchen
cabinets and her year-old daughter Kayleigh was asleep when the
black bear somehow got into the ground floor of their new home.
They never heard a thing until the crash of breaking glass. The
bear, apparently startled by the arrival of Conroy's husband,
Chris, had plunged through a double-paned window and stumbled away
toward the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in Stillwater since I was age 4, and now I'm 41,''
said Chris Conroy, a hunter, recalling what happened last summer.
``I've never ever, even seen a bear until about five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, everybody in this township of 4,500 on the slopes of
the Kittatinny Mountains of northwestern New Jersey seems to know
somebody with a bear story. Charlie McMahon raised goats as a hobby
for 15 years until a bear killed two of them three years ago. Two
weeks ago, at a Boy Scout camp in nearby Allamuchy, a bear yanked a
sleeping bag _ with a teen-ager inside it _ off a bench; the youth,
who was uninjured, screamed and frightened off the bear.
</P>
<P>
   And last summer, a bear broke up Diane Apostola's backyard
barbecue for 20 relatives. ``He just came walking down like he was
coming to the party with us,'' Apostola said. ``We all ran into the
house, and he just left.''
</P>
<P>
   As the numbers of black bears and people have grown in forested
areas of the New York region, the bears _ once timid and content
with isolated lives in the woods _ are venturing more and more into
campgrounds, yards and even houses in search of food. The place
where their wanderings have caused the biggest stir is New Jersey;
the state Division of Fish and Wildlife said it received 1,659
complaints about bears last year, up from 285 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the complaints were about bears roaming in backyards and
getting into garbage and bird feeders, but 28 of them involved
bears killing livestock and 29 were about bears getting into homes.
Although none of the complaints involved bears attacking or
injuring people, the intrusions have imposed anxieties and
restrictions on life in this wooded corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Fish and Game Council will hold a public hearing
Tuesday on its proposal to allow bear hunting this fall for the
first time in 30 years. The council wants to reduce the state's
bear population, now estimated at 1,000, to between 250 and 330 in
the next three years in order to cut down on encounters between
people and bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a safety issue,'' said John W. Bradway,
chairman of the council. ``Some people fear for their children's
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunting proposal, made last March, is opposed by 22 animal
rights groups that want the state to do more to teach people to
coexist with bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no overpopulation problem,'' said Lynda Smith,
director of one such group, the Bear Education and Resource Group
of West Milford, N.J. ``If we cut off food in the neighborhoods,
the bears won't come in.''
</P>
<P>
   But the animals have a keen sense of smell that can penetrate
even the strongest barriers to food. Two summers ago, a black bear
broke into Carolyn and Michael Ganon's home here by yanking an
air-conditioner out of a window and crawling in through the hole _
apparently seeking an uncovered canister of chocolate-covered
toffee in the family room. Terrified, the couple's son, Leland, 13,
ran upstairs and called 911. The police found the animal sitting
near the Ganons' porch, calmly eating the candy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though the township of Stillwater is sparsely settled,
development has grown steadily in the last 20 years in sections of
Sussex, Passaic, Morris and Warren Counties that were once covered
with forests. The bears _ hearty eaters and intelligent, adaptable
animals _ have come to rely on people to broaden their diet of
berries, acorns, skunk cabbage, rabbits and other small mammals.
</P>
<P>
   Bears have long been meandering into settled areas, particularly
in the summer, as the young are rousted from their lairs to make
way for new offspring. But experts say the bears being spotted now
tend to be older and more brazen.
</P>
<P>
   As their numbers grow, they have migrated to more thickly
populated counties, including Bergen, Essex, Hunterdon and
Somerset.
</P>
<P>
   They are also showing up in other parts of the region. Bears
recently broke into a dozen homes in southeastern New York. One
tore cabinets off a kitchen wall and tipped over a refrigerator
looking for food in Olive, in Ulster County, said Dick Henry, a New
York state wildlife biologist.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, bear sightings and complaints tripled last year,
to about 300, and livestock killings, a rarity in the state, were
reported in the rural northwest, said Paul Rego, a state wildlife
biologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is habituation of bears to people and to
people's garbage,'' said Jon Rosenberg, superintendent of parks in
West Milford, a bear haven in northern Passaic County. He has
worked with New Jersey's bear research team since 1983. Female
bears teach their cubs about food sources both in deep woods and in
backyards, and the bears will return again and again for garbage,
bird seed and pet food at homes, and for morsels at campsites and
countryside picnics and cookouts, Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Black bears are easily intimidated if people yell, wave their
arms or bang pots and pans. But repeated, uncontested forays into
backyards can lessen the bears' natural shyness and wariness of
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Veronica Stevans moved to Stillwater 12 years ago, she
occasionally spotted a bear at night near her home. ``It's a whole
different world now,'' Stevans said. ``Now you see them at any time
of day. They're bolder.'' She added, ``They're not afraid of noise
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, she said, she felt at ease walking alone on country roads.
Now she brings along a 4-inch can of pepper spray and her dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear proofing'' has become a way of life here. People talk of
jogging and walking with whistles, air horns, firecrackers and
pepper spray. Shooting bears, however, is currently illegal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gay Quarty, who saw a bear near her barbecue grill last year,
takes walks with a golf-ball-size jingle bell attached to one of
her sneakers. ``It looks ugly and stupid, and I don't know if it
really works,'' she said, ``but it gives me peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people shut their windows and doors before they cook, and
many store garbage in their basements or sheds until pickup day.
Paul Klimek has installed electric wiring around his pigpen and
wraps bacon around the wires, guaranteeing a slight shock to any
bear biting the meat.
</P>
<P>
   At Swartswood State Park, a stuffed black bear stands on its
hind legs in the lobby, next to a picnic basket and a sign warning
campers to keep all coolers and baskets in their cars when they are
not being used. Campers face eviction and a $71 fine if they feed
bears, intentionally or accidentally, and if their car windows are
found open, even a crack, when food is stored inside. Rangers say
bears can rip the window out to get the food.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, rangers at Swartswood and other state parks in or
near the Kittatinny Mountains, including High Point, Stokes and
Worthington, have shot rubber buckshot and explosive noisemakers at
bears that linger around campsites or garbage bins. This tactic is
meant to stop bears from associating people with ``positive rewards
_ a snack or a meal,'' said Patrick Carr, principal wildlife
biologist for the Division of Fish and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   But more drastic measures are being taken. Four bears deemed
potentially dangerous were trapped and killed last year by New
Jersey animal control agents, including two that had broken into
homes in Sussex County. In March, the Fish and Game Council
proposed the resumption of bear hunting, which the state banned in
1970, when the bear population had been all but wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting would be limited to the northern half of the state;
bills to prohibit bear hunting have been introduced in the state
Legislature, but they are stalled in committees.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions here on the proposal are divided, even among those who
have had encounters with bears. The Township Council in West
Milford, where the animals are plentiful, says it opposes the hunt
because bears are attractive and symbolize the state's little
remaining wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   In Stillwater, Ed Szabo, a hunter, no longer hangs deer
carcasses in trees behind his house to dry because bears ate them
at night. He favors bear hunting, but says he has no interest in
taking part.
</P>
<P>
   In Green Township, Dede Esenlohr said she sleeps uneasily
because bears often come onto her deck at night. Last summer, she
watched two bears kill two fawns in her yard. But she favors a
sterilization program because, she says, too many bears will be
wounded and left to suffer or turn dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society of the United States, which opposes the hunt,
has asked the state to conduct a joint study into injecting 20
female bears with a vaccine that prevents conception. The state has
not responded, said Allen Rutberg, the society's senior wildlife
scientist. ``The bear problem in New Jersey is not a crisis, not
like the deer issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But bears inspire a fear that deer do not, especially after a
death last month in Gatlinburg, Tenn. On May 21, the body of Glenda
Ann Bradley, 50, of Cosby, Tenn., a teacher and experienced hiker,
was found partly eaten by two bears in the Great Smoky Mountains
National Park. An autopsy to determine if the bears had killed her
is not complete, said Nancy Gray, a park spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Rogers of Ely, Minn., an expert on black bears, said fatal
attacks by black bears are extremely rare _ only about 40 in North
America in this century. People face a greater chance of being
killed by dogs, lightning or bee stings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR DEALING WITH BEARS
</P>
<P>
   Blacks bears are intelligent and extremely strong and have keen
senses of smell and hearing. They are excellent swimmers and tree
climbers and can run up to 35 miles an hour. Adult males average
about 350 pounds, but can weigh as much as 600 pounds. Adult
females average about 200 pounds. Black bears are normally not
aggressive toward humans and will usually flee if people make a lot
of noise.
</P>
<P>
   When threatened, black bears may issue a warning by popping
their jaws, making huffing noises, swatting the ground or bluffing
a charge. If faced with a bear doing any of these things, people
should remain standing, avoid direct eye contact, back away slowly
and talk in a calm but assertive tone. Make sure the bear has an
escape route.
</P>
<P>
   AT HOME:
</P>
<P>
   _ Never feed or attempt to pet bears.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hang bird feeders at least 8 feet off the ground and take them
inside at night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take uneaten pet food inside at night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Store garbage in sheds and garages, away from doors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep barbecue grills clean of grease.
</P>
<P>
   AT CAMP:
</P>
<P>
   _ Never keep food, snacks, candy, gum or their wrappers inside
tents or shelters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a clean camp and minimize food odors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Store food in vehicles, with windows rolled up, or in
commercially sold, airtight bear-proof containers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash dishes immediately after using them and dump water away
from camp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put garbage and cooking grease in garbage bins or bear-proof
containers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash any food from your face and hands before going to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hang clothes with food or cooking grease on them beyond bear's
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: New Jersey Division of Fish and Wildlife; Lynn Rogers,
director, North American Bear Center, Ely, Minn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
