<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORZINE SPENDING $2 MILLION TO ENCOURAGE TURNOUT FOR NJ SENATE
PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Topping off a record-breaking Senate campaign
spending spree, Democratic candidate Jon Corzine is expected to
spend up to $2 million next week to encourage potential supporters
to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That amount approaches the get-out-the-vote budget in some past
presidential contests.
</P>
<P>
   Although Corzine campaign officials said they did not know how
much would be paid out between now and Tuesday's Democratic
primary, they said they had earmarked $1.5 million for workers
whose sole job will be to encourage likely Corzine supporters to go
to the polls. Several party officials said the spending could reach
$2 million.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Corzine's opponent in the primary, former Gov. Jim
Florio, had budgeted $2 million for his entire campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although the amount Corzine expects to dispense next week is a
fraction of the $35 million he has spent so far, Florio said that
such a large amount of money for election workers had the potential
to taint the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of Jon Corzine trying to buy to
election,'' Florio said. ``It's beyond the pale of anything anyone
has ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, most political campaigns rely on volunteers and party
loyalists for tasks that include passing out palm cards,
chauffeuring people to the polls and reminding potential supporters
to go vote. Better-financed candidates have been known to pay small
stipends _ generally around $25 _ to election day workers, but
party officials said they were authorized to give more than $100 to
those who will work on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine supporters said they hoped to employ as many as 3,000
people on Monday and Tuesday, although Steven Goldstein, a
spokesman for Corzine, said that 600 of them would be volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a very traditional volunteer get-out-the vote
operation, with people pounding the pavement and knocking on
doors,'' he said. ``Jim Florio has tried to make it into something
else because he does not have the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio, on learning that Sen. Charles Schumer of New York had
crossed the Hudson River Friday to endorse Corzine, told reporters
that he was stunned, because the senator had praised him in the
past for helping to enact tough gun control laws in New Jersey. In
contrast, Florio said, when Corzine was a co-chairman of Goldman
Sachs, the company was helping the parent company of Remington Arms
Co. in a merger deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer called that charge bogus, and he said of Florio: ``I
still consider him a friend. I think Jon Corzine would be a better
senator and more electable.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Zellner, the field coordinator for the Democratic Party
committee in Bergen County, said the extra money would make his
work easier by paying for literature to be mailed..
</P>
<P>
   Thomas P. Giblin, the chairman of Essex County's Democratic
Party, said he hoped to have an army of 1,100 people on Tuesday.
Some of the Corzine campaign money would help pay for 15 rented
vans to ferry voters to and from the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect people who are making $200 a day to take the
day off for $25,'' Giblin said. ``These are not glamorous jobs.''
But he and other party leaders said they were worried that such
large payments might be counter-productive in the long run. ``If
you give them steak one year, are they going to take bologna the
next?'' Giblin said.
</P>
<P>
   Zellner, for one, said he would not raise the daily stipend
above the usual $30. ``I don't want to offer something I can't
match next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Florio's supporters are making do with an
all-volunteer cadre of election day workers. A campaign spokesman,
Jim Lanard, said he expected to have 3,000 people making calls and
knocking on doors on Tuesday. ``Our workers are motivated by
loyalty, not by money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They may condemn Corzine's spending habits, but many of the
party leaders supporting Florio acknowledge that they wish they had
more cash. Gary Karr, the Burlington County Democratic Party
chairman, said he was frustrated by the profusion of Corzine signs.
``They're every six inches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said he was heartened that a few hundred people had
agreed to volunteer for Florio on Tuesday. ``They'll come because
they have a lot of admiration and respect for Governor Florio, not
because we can spit out cash at them,'' he said. ``These people are
used to burning down the old shoe leather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
