<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3467 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CIGNA-PULLOUT-LADN     06-02 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGNA-PULLOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIGNA TO PULL ITS MEDICARE HMO PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ Cigna Corp., the nation's sixth-largest health
maintenance organization, will stop offering a Medicare HMO plan to
almost 18,000 customers in Southern California on Jan. 1, a company
spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will affect 13,000 Cigna Medicare HMO members in
Los Angeles County, 3,000 members in Orange County, 1,300 members
in San Bernardino and 460 customers in Riverside counties.
</P>
<P>
   The company cited low government reimbursement rates and
competitive pressures in Southern California as reasons for the
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't continue to offer quality care and our wide range of
services at an attractive price to our customers,'' said Jim
Harris, a spokesman with Glendale-based Cigna Healthcare of
California.
</P>
<P>
   The company will continue to cover health care services through
the end of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna will assist its members in either signing up with another
HMO or returning to the traditional fee-for-service Medicare
program that currently does not include coverage for prescription
drugs. In Los Angeles, there are at least a dozen Medicare HMOs
available to help displaced Cigna customers, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Haines, a spokeswoman with Woodland Hills-based Foundation
Health Systems Inc., said the insurer offers a similar Medicare
plan to clients throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Cigna, however, Foundation Health will continue offering
seniors Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we do every year, we will look at all aspects of the
product we offer,'' Haines said. ``We don't expect any major
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Philadelphia, Cigna announced Friday that it is also
leaving Atlanta, Connecticut, Delaware, Houston, Baltimore,
Washington, D.C., northern Virginia, northern New Jersey, the New
York City area, Orlando, Tampa, Richmond, Va., Tennessee and
Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   About 104,000 members will be affected in those markets where
Cigna has decided to drop the Medicare program. According to
Harris, Cigna covers about 2.5 percent of seniors enrolled in
Medicare HMOs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna plans to continue offering its Medicare HMO in
Albuquerque, N.M., and the Phoenix area. Currently, Cigna insures
about 50,000 Medicare members in those markets.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said health plans are required to inform the Health Care
Financing Administration, the federal agency that regulates
Medicare, by July 3, which cities they plan to exit for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna is the first national HMO to announce what Medicare
markets it will leave next year. Aetna has announced that it will
leave some markets by Jan. 1, but has not specified which ones. And
industry experts predict that others will announce a reduction or
elimination of their Medicare involvement by the July 3 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 16 percent of Medicare beneficiaries, or 6.2
million seniors, are enrolled in HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna plan enrollees seeking information can call (800)
633-4227.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cigna also said it would sell its U.S. individual and
group life insurance operations for $170 million cash. The company
said it expects the sale to Life Reassurance Corp. of America to
result in an after-tax gain of $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Life Reassurance is a subsidiary of Switzerland's Swiss
Reinsurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``This divestiture further sharpens our focus on Cigna's
employee benefits business; employee health care, life and
disability benefits; and retirement and investment products and
services,'' said H. Edward Hanaway, Cigna's chief executive officer
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cigna gained $1.9375, or 2.2 percent, to close Friday
at $89.375 on volume of 750,200 shares traded on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
