<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP IDEA OF RENAMING THE STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY HEASTER, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There are a few billion reasons to leave
Ewing Kauffman's name on Kansas City's field of dreams. They're
called dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand the temptation to want to rename
Kauffman Stadium in return for the big bucks a corporation would
pay for the privilege. The extra revenue, after all, could buy the
talent needed to make the Royals a more competitive team. Moreover,
a really shrewd deal might be structured to shift the upkeep burden
to the enterprise with its name on the door.
</P>
<P>
   This would be good business, granted, but it wouldn't be the
right thing to do. There are some things that shouldn't be for
sale. Given everything Ewing Kauffman did for Kansas City, the name
on Kauffman Stadium is one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments against selling out Kauffman already have been
made with convincing eloquence. He not only restored major-league
baseball to Kansas City, but along the way spent considerable sums
of his own money to give fans a championship-caliber organization
of which they could be proud. This alone would be enough to justify
keeping his name on the stadium. But there's an even more
compelling reason to keep faith with his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, business and government leaders have gone to
great lengths to emphasize the economic benefit of having
big-league sports in Kansas City. The most recent number put on
this contribution has been well over a couple of hundred million
dollars a year in economic activity generated by the Royals and
Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Royals play many more games than the Chiefs, let's
assume for the sake of argument the two franchises contribute about
equally to Kansas City's economy. This would mean that over
Kauffman's stewardship tenure, he was probably responsible for at
least several billion dollars worth of economic oomph the area
wouldn't have otherwise enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   During his time as owner, Kauffman never threw his weight around
demanding onerous taxpayer-subsidized goodies in return for keeping
this tremendous economic asset in Kansas City. Quite the contrary.
He spent much of his personal fortune to improve the quality of his
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Even in death he left in place heroic measures to ensure the
continued presence of the Royals in Kansas City. It was an act of
love for his hometown that few, if any, Kansas City benefactors
have ever matched. Not only did Kauffman engineer the business and
financial details of this quest before dying, but he also entrusted
the task of saving the Royals for Kansas City to one of his most
able and trustworthy corporate lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all, Kauffman continued to build his Marion Labs
into a premier local company that also contributed much to the
Kansas City area economy apart from what Kauffman did in his more
visible role with the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   To betray such love and loyalty by selling Ewing Kauffman's name
off the stadium at which he accomplished so much for his community
would be a base and classless action unworthy of the fine people
who would be responsible for making this decision.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly fitting way to celebrate Kansas City's 150th
birthday, it seems, would be to drop this idea and pretend it never
existed in the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2334EDT &QL; 
