<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKER TELLS ANGELS HE'LL PLAY ANYWHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kevin Stocker hasn't taken a ground ball at
anywhere but shortstop all year, but the Anaheim Angels' newest
arrival won't complain if he and ``utility player'' are mentioned
in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they called to bring me in, I told them I'll fill
whatever role they want me to,'' said Stocker, who joined the team
for Friday's game against the Dodgers and figures to play in this
afternoon's game.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker, 30, has played shortstop for much of his six-year big-
league career and was the Tampa Bay Devil Rays' starter until his
release on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker should get plenty of opportunites to play shortstop with
injured Gary DiSarcina's transfer to the 60-day disabled list and
Benji Gil's struggles at the plate (.197).
</P>
<P>
   ``If that means playing every day, great. If it's every other
day, fine. I'm just happy to be here filling a spot. I'm not trying
to take anybody's job or anything,'' said Stocker, who hit .263 in
40 games for Tampa Bay. ``I'm grateful that they called me.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia is happy to have a versatile
veteran to call on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get a chance to play a lot of shortstop. I think
that will give Benji a little breather because he's been really
going hard and hasn't had a chance to get a lot of time off . . .
to get recharged,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stocker) gives us more depth to our club definitely. Plus he
has the ability to his second which gives us a good look to our
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Interleague not intermission: It won't ruin the season and it
probably won't determine whether or not an American League West
championship is won.
</P>
<P>
   But the first round of interleague play is a chance for the
Angels to improve the majors' second-worst record against the
National League sincethe crossover play began in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Friday's series opener against the Dodgers, the first
of nine consecutive interleague games, the Angels were 20-30
against NL competition. Only Tampa Bay (9-25) has been worse than
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won't consider series against the Dodgers, San
Francisco and Arizona as win-or-else, particularly when considering
the balance, if not mediocrity, of the Western Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of (interleague) problems last year,'' first
baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``We just have to go out, be ourselves and
play our game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bid adieu to Dodger Blue: Dodgers broadcaster Vin Scully's
famous voice was easily heard during Scioscia's chat with the media
Friday when the longtime Dodgers player and coach was asked about
managing against his old team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brings back memories . . . doesn't it?'' Scioscia asked,
referring to Scully.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the extent of Scioscia's nostalgia regarding the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus is on the 25 guys we have in our clubhouse,'' he
said. ``If I learned anything from my years (with the Dodgers). . .
. You've got to know your club and get your club ready to play. . .
. That's lesson No. 1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
