<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLMARK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLMARK SUES COMPETITOR OVER TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JENNIFER MANN, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hallmark Cards Inc. is suing competitor
American Greetings Corp., alleging that American Greetings' Web
site and two of its software products used technology owned by
Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark spokeswoman Julie Odell said the dispute centered on
technology that Hallmark acquired in September 1998 from Mary T.
Tackbary and Dan G. Friedrich.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is used on features such as address books,
personal reminders of important dates, and a history of what
products the person has bought. Both Hallmark's and American
Greetings' Web sites have such features.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark also alleges that American Greetings is illegally using
the same technology in its CreataCard and Personal Cardshop
software products.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Petit, vice president of communications for American
Greetings, said the Cleveland-based card maker had no knowledge of
the lawsuit, which was filed Thursday in federal court in the
Western District of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Tackbary met with American
Greetings' vice president of product management in 1994. At that
meeting, Tackbary demonstrated a prototype system and told company
officials she had filed for a patent application.
</P>
<P>
   Tackbary later met with other American Greetings executives,
including Morry Weiss, the chairman and chief executive officer at
the time. Again, Tackbary demonstrated her invention and told
company officials there was a patent pending.
</P>
<P>
   She then had a third meeting with American Greetings, the last
one with the vice president of interactive marketing. Ultimately,
American Greetings decided not to enter into a business
relationship with Tackbary.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark then acquired the technology in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City greeting card company is asking the court to:
</P>
<P>
   - Issue a permanent injunction to stop American Greetings and
entities it has relationships with from using the technology.
</P>
<P>
   - Award damages to Hallmark arising from American Greetings' use
of the technology, together with interest and costs.
</P>
<P>
   - Triple the amount of damages.
</P>
<P>
   - Make American Greetings pay Hallmark's attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   - Have the issues decided by a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that the two greeting card giants
have tangled over technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   Though the two never went to court, they tussled for several
years over technology used for interactive kiosks where consumers
can create personalized cards.
</P>
<P>
   That battle began in 1992 when American Greetings unveiled its
interactive kiosk with great fanfare at a media event in New York.
Hallmark fired back the next day, alleging those kiosks used
technology owned by Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of bickering the companies declared an
impasse, with each allowing the other to continue using the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Hallmark seems to be taking a firm stand on its ownership
issue this time around. Depending on how the lawsuit turns out,
Hallmark could pursue legal action against others, as many Web
sites and portals offer features similar to those offered on
American Greetings' Web site and in its software products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we won't pursue other legal action,'' Odell
said. ``I don't know that we've necessarily closed that door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
