<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S OK AT START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Coach Phil Jackson extended the suspense as
long as he could, but when tipoff came Friday night, Kobe Bryant
and his sore right foot were in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Exercising either gamesmanship or extreme caution, Jackson
declined right up until game time to reveal Bryant's status, saying
only that he would play. Of course, the Portland Trail Blazers
maintained all along that the Los Angeles Lakers were overplaying
Bryant's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant did skip two days of practice after spraining his foot in
Game 5 on Tuesday and he also skipped Friday's morning shootaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he can play, but he hasn't tested it,'' Jackson said
before the game. ``He's got to be the measure of what he can do and
can't do and has to let me know how he's doing out there. As far as
how he's playing, that's my decision as to whether he's playing
well enough to stay out on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's foot and his game were up to the challenge. He played
the entire first half without a breather.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bryant played 40 minutes or four, Jackson said the
Lakers would be comfortable adjusting. They played the first month
of the season without Bryant, while his broken hand healed, and
went 11-4. They also won at Phoenix on April 4, when Bryant was
serving a one-game suspension for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand how to play without him,'' Jackson said.
``They've done it this year often enough to know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Easygoing: Despite the uncertainty that surrounded Bryant's
status for the last three days, Derek Fisher said the Lakers
arrived in Portland much more relaxed than they had been earlier
this week. Fisher said the team was too tense for Game 5 in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much more relaxed at the shootaround today and that's a
positive sign,'' he said before the game. ``We all felt like we had
to win on Tuesday. We knew we were up 3-1 and we were at home. And
to lose an elimination game at home like that really bothered us.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Kupchak stays: The New Jersey Nets' hiring of Rod Thorn as
head of basketball operations on Friday means Mitch Kupchak will
remain a Laker for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak, the Lakers' general manager, was among the candidates
Nets ownership considered for their top personnel position.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of this point, nothing has transpired in the past few weeks
that would convince me that any other situation is better than the
situation I have with the Lakers,'' Kupchak said in a prepared
statement. He was not available for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers gave permission to the Nets to speak with Kupchak
about the position, but they would not confirm whether he had a
formal interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
