<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH FIRM TO BUY BUS COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- NATIONAL EXPRESS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY GENE MEYER, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Britain's largest long-distance
transportation group, National Express Plc, is buying the area's
School Services and Leasing Inc. for $205 million, the two
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The cash transaction, scheduled to be final in August,
represents part of the U.S. expansion by National Express into
operating fleets from California to Connecticut. School Services is
the United States' second-largest privately owned school bus fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction also represents a watershed for Kansas City
transportation executive and sports franchise owner Don Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   The company from which School Services was created is the same
bus company that Kincaid joined as a part-time driver in the
mid-1960s while attending the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
He bought the company in the mid-1970s with just $400 in the bank
and a Small Business Administration loan.
</P>
<P>
   Its growth, into an organization with 4,000 employees serving 40
school districts in eight states, is the engine that enabled
Kincaid to expand his portfolio with investments in other
regionally substantial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid is owner or a major investor in Kincaid Coach Lines, a
charter service; Midwest Bus Sales; Kincaid Leasing; a Leavenworth
auto dealership; and the Kansas City Attack soccer team. None of
those investments will be affected by the School Services sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``With consolidation and other trends in the industry, this is
the right time and the right thing to do for the company, our
employees and for National Express,'' Kincaid said Friday. ``But it
also is like watching my firstborn walk down the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   From National Express's perspective, ``the acquisition opens up
important new markets and consolidates our position in the
Midwest,'' said Larry Durham, chief executive of the company's
North American operations, which are based in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that when the acquisition was complete,
National Express' U.S. business volume would increase to more than
$500 million annually and include 9,000 vehicles and 16,000
employees in 20 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
