<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUSBAND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMEL MAN SENTENCED TO LIFE IN PRISON FOR KILING WIFE  
</HEADLINE>
 SENTENCED-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY TONY RIZZO, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An Overland Park, Kan., man who tape-recorded
the fatal shooting of his wife was sentenced Friday to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Romel Abufakher must serve 25 years before he can be considered
for parole. The 48-year-old real estate broker had nothing to say
before District Judge William Cleaver pronounced sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He testified at his trial in April that he accidentally shot his
wife, Carol Abufakher, on Sept. 21 while he was trying to leave
their house and she grabbed the gun he was holding.
</P>
<P>
   The voice-activated recorder in his pocket captured Abufakher
telling his wife, ``I'm going to kill you,'' seconds before the
sound of a shot. Police later confiscated the recorder.
</P>
<P>
   A Johnson County, Kan., District Court jury found Abufakher
guilty of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Abufakher's sister, Sharon Whitley, told the judge Friday
that her ``fun-loving and generous'' sister's death had devastated
their elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents loved Romel,'' she said. ``They took him into their
hearts and home, and he repaid their love by killing Carol.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred after several days of marital stress
prompted by Carol Abufakher's anger over her husband's relationship
with a female co-worker, according to trial testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the days before the shooting, Romel Abufakher called
police to the couple's house in the 9900 block of Metcalf Avenue.
One time she locked him out of the house and he called police so he
could go back in, get some belongings and leave.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the shooting he called police again, this time
seeking to have his wife committed for mental problems. Police said
they had no reason to take her.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day the couple went to a counselor, according to
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Romel Abufakher testified at trial that he put the tape-recorder
in his pocket that night to gather evidence that his wife was
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Carol Abufakher could be heard loudly demanding
that her husband tell her the truth. She repeatedly threatened to
reveal things the next morning that would get him in trouble if he
did not tell her the truth about the co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the tape changed abruptly when Carol Abufakher
shouted, ``He's got a gun!'' while speaking on the phone to her
husband's business partner.
</P>
<P>
   Rustling that suggested a struggle could be heard on the tape.
The last words spoken by Romel Abufakher were ``Don't open the
door,'' and then the shot was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Abufakher's brother, Fred Lamm, told the judge Friday that
he believed his sister was killed because of her threats to reveal
``the total truth'' about Romel Abufakher's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was a little money or a lot of money, my sister's
life was worth more than that,'' Lamm said.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Morrison had sought before the trial to
let the jury hear testimony about Abufakher's business dealings,
but the judge did not allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sentencing Friday, Cleaver denied a request by
defense attorney Tom Bath to throw out the verdict and order a new
trial. Bath said that the evidence ``at best'' supported a verdict
of second-degree murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-00 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
