<DOCNO> NYT20000602.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR THESE N.Y. FANS, IT IS OCTOBER IN JUNE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., S.C)  By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
ATLANTA _ Pat Riley would have strained his mousse. Reggie Miller
would have had conniptions. The Atlanta Braves prefer to think of
it as money in the bank.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All those ``NY'' caps strutting around the ballpark with large,
hard New York heads underneath were demographics on parade.
</P>
<P>
   There were transplanted New Yorkers, homesick New Yorkers,
lifetime New Yorkers, truculent New Yorkers, even some wannabe New
Yorkers, all of them wearing the dreaded dark-blue insignia that
has been branded into the troubled minds of Atlanta Braves fans
since the 1996 and 1999 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   There was a roar when Ricky Ledee lofted a three-run homer in
the fourth inning that helped the Yanks beat the Braves, 5-2. The
home fans cheered even louder when Andruw Jones made a running,
fully-extended catch to rob Paul O'Neill of extra bases in the
seventh, but there was not that great a disparity between the 90
percent Braves and the 10 percent Yankees in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand Yankees fans had come up with tickets for the
first interleague game of the season between the two World Series
teams of last year. How long ago that seems, back when John Rocker
was just a loutish relief pitcher with rabbit ears, before he
became a household name for his ugly comments about the diverse
types on the New York City streets and subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait for him to go to New York,'' said Steve Proper,
now from Buckhead, but originally from Meadville, Pa., who was
wearing his NY cap. ``It's going to be nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood was not nearly as intense as it was during last year's
World Series, when legions of Yankees fans marauded around Turner
Field, showing their Yankees emblems and their gall in equal
proportion. They were erstwhile Spike Lees, showing their stuff in
the rival arena, just as the Spikester does in his lightning raids
to Miami and to Indiana during the basketball playoffs, now ended
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By popping up like Bugs Bunny with orange Knicks paraphernalia
draped all over him, Spike has annoyed resident Elmer Fudds in
Miami and Indiana. Riley and Miller have urged local fans to show
patriotism and gobble up those tickets before ubiquitous New
Yorkers get their evil hands on them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is nothing new for New Yorkers to swarm to sports
events in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Knicks come down here, the crowd is half New
Yorkers,'' said Carl Liddelow, now working in Atlanta but
originally from Manhattan. ``The Giants play here this season. I
can hardly wait to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was born in Georgia and attended Morehouse College, has
returned for Knicks games, but the combined Braves-Hawks management
finally had to draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike called me before one game and said he needed to sit in
the front row,'' recalled Stan Kasten, the president of both clubs.
``I said it was not in my best interests to help him be in the
front row. So he found somebody and got in the second row.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball being a more democratic sport, it was much easier for
New York types to get into Turner Field Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on the phone the first day tickets went on sale,'' said
Phil Mentnech from Charleston, S.C., originally from the Catskills,
who was seated down the right-field line. ``This was the best I
could do after three hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees fans admitted they were not pummeled or taunted, the
way the occasional foolhardy Braves or Red Sox fan is bullied in
Shea or Yankee Stadium. But Kasten would not concede that New York
has a monopoly on viciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent of the fans are fine,'' Kasten said. ``But
you have to draw the line. There are things your neighbors and the
players have the right not to hear. There is a form of assault, not
battery, and we will throw people out if they cross that line.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was not making it up when he accused Shea Stadium fans of
shouting vile things at the Braves. His problem was that he made
some weird link between the small proportion of ugly Shea fans with
assorted ethnic and racial and social groups in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After his bigoted feelings hit print in Sports Illustrated
during the off-season, he was suspended for two weeks. The team was
barely putting up with him this spring even before his earned run
average soared to 4.41. Asked if Rocker was still his stopper,
Bobby Cox said slowly, ``Yeah, sure, I guess,'' which told it all.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night a feisty minority of New Yorkers reminded Rocker
there are more where they came from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
