<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-02 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-ELLIS-1STLD-WRI     06-02 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ELLIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SENATOR IS SAND IN THE GEARS OF TEXAS' DEATH ROW EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert quotation marks in sentence containing
`apartheid.')  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eleven years ago, when a plane carrying Rep.
Mickey Leland of Texas on a hunger relief mission crashed in
Ethiopia, Rodney Ellis, a young Democratic councilman in Houston,
was grief stricken and shaken.
</P>
<P>
   He had not only lost his mentor, but he was supposed to have
been on that plane and had even fumed at Leland for bumping him
from the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Urged by Leland's widow to run for his seat in Congress, Ellis
gave it some thought before deciding instead to seek the state
Senate seat that Leland had once held.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since then, Ellis has become perhaps the leading
political force behind the decidedly unpopular efforts in Texas to
slow the state's speedy executions and erase what he said are the
inequities that often keep black, Hispanic and indigent defendants
from a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem an unusual role for a man who, like almost every
influential Texas politician, said that he supports the death
penalty. But Ellis' deep reservations about the system, and his
occasional clashes with Gov. George W. Bush, earned him the
spotlight this week.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush's campaigning in California and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a
Republican, in Europe, Ellis, as the Senate president pro tem,
became the acting governor and was left to decide whether to grant
a reprieve for convicted murderer Ricky McGinn. Bush announced on
Thursday in Sacramento, Calif., that he had recommended a 30-day
reprieve, which Ellis had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, Ellis had mostly made up his mind five days
earlier, having conferred with his staff and read an order by a
state judge imploring an appeals court to postpone the execution to
allow DNA tests; defense lawyers said the tests might exonerate
McGinn of raping his 12-year-old stepdaughter. McGinn was convicted
of murdering the girl, but prosecutors could not have asked for a
death sentence without also getting the rape conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said that the case kept him awake until 3 a.m. Monday
night, thinking, ``What if I disagree with Governor Bush? How would
we resolve that?'' His wife told him to call Bush's aides first
thing on Tuesday, which he did, so Bush would have the chance to
return to Texas to make sure the execution was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But to his surprise, Ellis said, Bush's aides said they were
already seriously considering a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   To Ellis, a 46-year-old Democrat, McGinn's case highlights only
some of the state's criminal justice problems: Ellis said it is
outrageous that there was no process allowing the new DNA tests to
be conducted, as the state's highest criminal appeals court,
without explanation, refused to postpone the execution.
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, Ellis has advocated banning executions of
the mentally retarded; giving juries the option of sentencing
murderers to life without parole, thus making it easier for jurors
to forego the death penalty; and putting control of court-appointed
lawyers in the hands of county governments, not the local judges
who, Ellis said, often favor lawyers who speed cases along instead
of fighting tooth-and-nail for their client.
</P>
<P>
   That last proposal was vetoed by Bush because, Ellis said,
judges worried that it took away a piece of their patronage. Bush
said that power should be left to judges because they were better
qualified to select lawyers for defendants who need them.
</P>
<P>
   Texas courts are ``essentially a system of judicial apartheid,''
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus tends to be on the law-and-order, lock-them-up,
throw-away- of-the-key stuff, and a refusal to look at the
inequities of the system,'' he said. ``Part of the problem is that
our governor and a number of my conservative colleagues somehow
have the view that if you show compassion, you can be perceived as
weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, maintains that all 131 inmates executed
while he has been governor were unquestionably guilty of murder and
had had appropriate access to the courts. And few legislators share
Ellis' view.
</P>
<P>
   ``People commit crimes because of bad values, not because of
their race or status,'' said state Sen. David Sibley, a Waco
Republican and Bush ally.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ellis may not be in sympathy with legislative leaders on
some things, he has still been quite effective on many issues,
including indigent health care and voter registration. He has
earned a place among the elite of the state's Senate, a place
where, Texas Monthly once said, ``toughness is good, shrillness and
criticism are not, and humor is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to put together coalitions,'' Sibley said, before
adding: ``I don't think he's one that says half a loaf is better
than none. He says, `I'll take half a loaf now, and come back for
the rest later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley and Ellis have already discussed legislation that would
make it easier for prisoners to obtain post-trial DNA testing that
might prove exculpatory. Without commenting on specifics, Sibley
said such legislation might stand a chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis already has some specifics in mind: Giving inmates the
right to get DNA testing of evidence from their case, requiring
that biological evidence be preserved, setting up a commission to
review and investigate cases of possible wrongful convictions, and
providing more compensation to people wrongfully imprisoned and
later exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, the son of a yardman, grew up in Houston, attended
college at Texas Southern University, and earned a law degree and a
master's degree in public affairs at the University of Texas in
Austin. After serving as Leland's chief of staff, he was elected to
the Houston City Council at the age of 29. He now works in the
Houston office of a New Orleans law firm, and is married with three
children.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush and Perry both expected to travel out of state at
times later this year, the final approval for executions could fall
to Ellis again. One inmate scheduled to die soon, Gary Graham, has
drawn a lot of support from those who insist he is innocent. What
would Ellis do if that case were left up to him? Not sure yet, he
said, ``but if I were a guessing man, I would guess the governor or
lieutenant governor will be in town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
