r a BC-MURDERRULING-KAN &LR;      06-02 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH TWO FATHERS AWAIT JUDGE'S RULING ON RELEASE OF A MURDERER  
</HEADLINE>
 RULING-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JOE LAMBE KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Al Smith and Gary Rawlings Sr. sat on
opposite sides of a Jackson County courtroom again Friday. They've
done that many times in the 13 years since Rawlings' son murdered
Smith's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   They sat silently as a judge heard arguments that Rawlings' son,
Gary Rawlings Jr., 41, was fit to go free.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Gary Rawlings Jr. shot his girlfriend, Terri Smith, 23,
in the head while she slept. Smith, he said, had been trying to
kill him with microwaves. Doctors diagnosed him a paranoid
schizophrenic. In 1989, a judge found him not guilty by reason of
insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gary Rawlings Jr. is in a state mental hospital. Circuit
Judge Jay A. Daugherty heard arguments Friday on whether to release
him, and said he would rule on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the judge's decision, grief and horror have eaten away
at the two families. The murder made the elder Rawlings and Smith
advocates for opposite positions on the criminally insane.
</P>
<P>
   Both men spoke of it Friday, though not to each other.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gary Rawlings Sr., 67, of Kansas City, said
schizophrenia first hit his son at age 24, four years before the
murder. The disease helped break up his son's marriage and his own,
Rawlings said.
</P>
<P>
   His son was put on antipsychotic medication. He recovered, but
then stopped taking the medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary thought it was like a cold,'' Rawlings said. ``You just
took the medicine when you were sick. He understands now he has no
life without it.''
</P>
<P>
   His son stopped talking to him shortly before the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mad because I told him he needed to see a doctor _ he
was ill again,'' Rawlings said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Rawlings called Smith regularly to get news of his
son. She said she could handle him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so sweet and good to him,'' Rawlings said. ``She was
the last person who should have gotten hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   After the murder, Rawlings spoke to his son in prison as he was
starting to recover. His son told him that he wouldn't have hurt
Smith, that he loved her.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Then who did? ' I asked him,'' Rawlings said. ``His face got
real white and he left. He was sick again for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rawlings, a retired banker, supports the rights of the
mentally ill and easier release of criminally insane persons who
are controlled by medication.
</P>
<P>
   Al Smith has been active in legal changes that have made such
releases more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Murder has put them each in a place where they must be, Rawlings
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this wouldn't have happened, we would have become
friends,'' he said. ``Our kids loved each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 73, also of Kansas City, told the court about the impact
of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our other daughter, who was eight years older than Terri and
who was especially close to her sister, attempted suicide three
times. She felt guilty because she had introduced Rawlings to
Terri.''
</P>
<P>
   One son's wife of nine years left him ``because she could not
handle the cloud of death which hung over our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Another son, who was schizophrenic but stabilized by medication,
started drinking heavily after his sister's death and suffered a
relapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``His health took an extreme turn for the worse and he died last
fall as a result of contracting pneumonia while hospitalized for a
broken hip,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The family's problems forced Smith to retire early from his job
at Bendix and his wife to retire from her job as a psychiatric
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, our subsequent retirement income has been
severely reduced and we have had to change our standard of living
considerably,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gary Rawlings Jr., Smith told the judge he should not be
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has demonstrated he is dangerous and surely one murder
should be enough to convince the court that caution should be in
favor of public safety,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Smith said his daughter was about to leave Gary
Rawlings Jr. when he killed her. He also said there was no point in
talking to the elder Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on different sides,'' he said. ``There's no way around
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men listened Friday as lawyers argued points the men knew
by heart.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Rawlings Jr. won his first conditional release in 1990 and
successfully completed seven releases. Medical officials confined
him in 1997 after he didn't take his medication. At that time he
lived at a Kansas City group home.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is asking to be released again and to live in the same
group home. Two medical experts testified that Gary Rawlings Jr.
was not a danger to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors countered that he might kill again if he stopped
taking his medication.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, both fathers will learn Gary Rawlings Jr.'s future.
</P>
</TEXT>
